title: Avrora-consult.ru (fake)
description: This is supposedly the base of the debt collection agency Avrora-consult. But the source of the database is most likely different, perhaps compiled from other databases. The data contains names, dates of birth, cities and passport details. A total of 337 thousand lines.

title: RozaVam.ru
description: RozaVam is a Russian flower delivery service in Moscow. In February 2023, the site suffered a data breach. The published dump contained tables of users (142 thousand rows), orders (330 thousand rows) and personnel (700 rows). The data included names, emails, phone numbers of senders and recipients, order amounts, IP addresses and text comments, mostly declarations of love.

title: DOJO
description: Around February 2017, a mobile restaurant discovery app known as DOJO suffered a data breach that affected 761,000 users. The breach exposed email addresses, full names and passwords as MD5 and Bcrypt hashes. Please note that there are only about 300 thousand valid email addresses, the rest are automatically generated.

title: AlfaBank 2023 v2
description: In October 2023, it became known that Alfabank was hacked by the NLB hacker team. Later, two versions of this leak, slightly different in content, became publicly available. This is the second version containing about 450 million records. It was cleared of duplicates and intersections with the first version, which reduced its size by about 10 times.

title: Poolmark.mag
description: This leak came from the Ukrainian site aquamag.kiev.ua, which sells pond equipment. The data contains 14 thousand records with emails, names, IP addresses, phone numbers, bcrypt passwords and other data. The leak dates back to June 2023.

title: AdultFriendFinder 2016
description: In October 2016, adult entertainment company Friend Finder suffered a massive data breach. The exposed data included names, passwords in the form of SHA-1 hashes and 170 million unique emails. This company was previously hacked in May 2015, but then the leak contained only 4 million records.

title: 23 Million BTC Combos
description: In 2019, a list of emails and passwords in plain text was published online. This collection included 23 million records collected from cryptocurrency-related websites. This collection was used to hack accounts on crypto exchanges.

title: UltraTrade.ru
description: In February 2024, the Russian online hardware store UltraTrade suffered from a hack. Many data tables have been published containing users' orders, reviews, payments and other information. There are about 400 thousand records in total, including names, phone numbers, emails, IP addresses, comments on orders and passwords in plain text.

title: MinecraftDatabases
description: Since 2010, there have been more than 1,200 hacks of various MineCraft servers. All of these hacks were collected into large collections and distributed as a means of hacking player accounts in MineCraft. This collection contains emails, nicknames, passwords, IP addresses and other data from all these collections. There are about 57 million rows in total.

title: Sirena RZD 2003
description: In 2003, the largest airline ticket reservation system, developing systems for selling air tickets, checking in passengers and baggage, suffered a data leak of 24.8 million records, including passport data and full names, as well as departure and arrival stations.

title: Ozone Employees 2022
description: In 2022, a list of employees of the Ozone trading platform was leaked. The incident affected more than 47 thousand people. The data contained full names, phone numbers, emails, addresses, positions, departments, employment statuses and other information.

title: PSPISO
description: Around September 2015, the PlayStation PSP forum was hacked and nearly 1.3 million accounts were exposed. The data contained email addresses, IP addresses, and salted MD5 password hashes.

title: InterPals
description: At the end of 2015, the online dating site InterPals was hacked. 3.4 million accounts were exposed. These included email addresses, geographic locations, dates of birth, and salted password hashes.

title: SMS Interception 2015
description: In 2015, due to a vulnerability, attackers were able to intercept about 270 thousand SMS messages sent from Russian phones. The resulting database was later published; it contains phone numbers, dates of sending messages and their contents.

title: Tln.Spb.ru
description: On the website of the official representative of the franchise network of brands of clothing and accessories in St. Petersburg, in September 2024 there was a leak of data from the website TLN.SPB.ru, which talked more than 340 thousand users' entries, such as names, telephones, mail, nickelia and passwords inThe form of hash Bcrypt.

title: FD-telekom.ru
description: This company provides enterprise network development services for companies and call centers. It was hacked at the end of 2018. Information about employees was published: emails, telephone numbers, names, dates of birth, positions and work experience. There are 1220 entries in total.

title: Telecom.kz
description: This is a Kazakhstani Internet provider. At the beginning of 2024, a leak of its users containing 727 thousand records became publicly available. The data contains only the user name, city of residence, tariff description and device data.

title: Ubrru.ru
description: The website of the UBRD bank encountered an incident, as a result of which information about 77 thousand clients became publicly available. Phone numbers, emails, full names, and payment information were revealed.

title: Taringa
description: In September 2017, Taringa, known as the "Latin American Reddit", suffered a data breach. 28 million records were exposed, including names, email addresses and weak MD5 password hashes.

title: VMasshtabe.ru
description: In January 2023, a JSON file with data from users of the Russian engineering portal “V Masshtabe.ru” (vmasshtabe.ru) was posted on one of the forums. The file contains approximately 1.35 million lines. The data contains nicknames, names, emails, links to profiles on social networks and other data.

title: ForsCraft.net
description: This Russian Minecraft server was hacked in June 2024. Only the list of its users was affected, which included 44 thousand nicknames with data about the purchased privilege and server.

title: FNS 2008
description: This is a leak from the Russian Federal Tax Service that occurred in 2008. The data contains 1.6 million records with names, tax identification numbers, addresses, dates of birth and passport data.

title: M2Bomber.com
description: M2Bomber is a website with advertisements for the sale and rental of real estate, operating in Russia and Ukraine. In 2020, all advertisements from it were collected using parsing. About 14 million records were obtained with phone numbers and information about the objects being sold, including their addresses and photographs.

title: CondoCom
description: Around June 2019, condo buying and renting website Condo.com suffered a data breach that affected 1.5 million users. The breach resulted in the disclosure of data including full names, email addresses, phone numbers and locations.

title: PsWeb.ru
description: In 2017, data from the Russian programming forum PsWeb was obtained either through hacking or scraping. 1,700 users were affected; the data contains emails, nicknames and other information from profiles.

title: DeliveryClub
description: In May 2022, the Russian delivery service DeliveryClub reported a leak. Later, hackers published two files containing customer order data - names, phone numbers, emails, addresses and order contents. The total size of the leak is rumored to be 250 million records, but only 7.5 million orders are publicly available.

title: AtletasNow
description: In December 2021, the website of Brazilian sports authority AtletasNow suffered a data leak. The breach included email addresses, full names, phone numbers, physical addresses, dates of birth, gender and passwords stored as Wordpress hashes. In total, 62.8 thousand users were affected.

title: 3Snet
description: 3Snet is a site that offers to earn money for any actions related to casinos and sports betting, which is reminiscent of working with a drop. There are several leaks of this service online, but only one of them is not fake. This leak appeared in December 2023 and contains names, emails, phone numbers and 330 thousand records.

title: Labexch.ru
description: Labexch is a Russian labor exchange. On March 20, 2022, all resumes from this site were collected using scraping. A database of 35 thousand lines was obtained, containing telephone numbers, names, emails, desired salaries, positions and resumes of users.

title: Book24.ua
description: In August 2022, the Ukrainian book site BOOK24.UA subwisted hacking (do not confuse with the leakage of the site BOOK24.ru).The resulting base was a strongly littered SQL Damp, in which, among other things, there were names, mail and comments of customers.In total, about 10 thousand records.

title: D3Scene
description: In January 2016, a data leak occurred on the gaming website D3Scene. The compromised vBulletin forum discovered 569,000 email addresses, as well as IP addresses, usernames and passwords in the form of salted MD5 hashes.

title: Cherlock.ru
description: In September 2021, information appeared about a leak from the Russian service Cherlock.ru. This company provides legal advice. The leak contains two files. There are 82 thousand records in the customer file, and 950 thousand in the order file. Names, phone numbers, cities of residence, and reasons for contacting the service were compromised.

title: MC-magicstore.ru
description: MagicStore is a Russian server for the game MineCraft. Was hacked on January 11, 2018. The leak contains 102 thousand records, including nicknames, IP addresses and passwords in the form of AuthMe hashes.

title: Evite
description: In April 2019, social planning website Evite discovered a data breach from 2013. Among them were 101 million email addresses, as well as names, phone numbers, addresses and passwords in clear text.

title: Apoker.kz
description: This is a Kazakhstan site for playing poker. At the beginning of 2020, the database of its users became publicly available. It contains 23 thousand records with emails, nicknames, dates of birth and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes.

title: Alfagifts.ru
description: In September 2022, a vulnerability was discovered in the OpenCart system used for website development. This led to leaks from many sites using it, including Alfagifts, a gift-buying site in Moscow. The database contains 22 thousand records with emails, phone numbers and names.

title: Usurt.ru
description: In January 2022, the website of the Ural State Transport University Usurt.ru encountered an incident, as a result of which a database with information about 47 thousand users got into the network. Phone numbers, full names, emails and nicknames were revealed.

title: Aspkin
description: In September 2016, a data leak occurred on the Aspkins World marketing forum, which affected 68 thousand users. The breach exposed email addresses, usernames, IP addresses, dates of birth and passwords stored as vBulletin hashes.

title: Doctors List
description: In 2021, a list of all doctors living in the United States appeared on the Internet. Its date of receipt and source are unknown, but it is likely a scraping of public data. The file contained 726,000 records, which included names, telephone numbers, mails, addresses, and educational and medical practice information.

title: Uuu9
description: In September 2016, data from the Chinese website uuu9.com was published. They contained information about 7.5 million accounts, including email addresses and usernames.

title: Verified.cash
description: The Russian platform Verified, associated with financial transactions and cryptocurrencies, suffered from a leak in September 2019 that affected 24 thousand records, including logins, emails and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes.

title: Spektr
description: In June 2024, a file from the Spectrum database was made publicly available. This is a system for ensuring counteraction to insurance fraud of the Russian Union of Auto Insurers (RUA). The data contains names, dates of birth, information about the car, as well as information about the dates and circumstances of the accident in which it was involved. There are about 60 million records in total.

title: TochkaObmena.com
description: On May 7, 2023, a full dump database of Russian online exchange of electronic currencies and cryptocurrencies tochkaobmena was published on the shadow platform.SQL Dampus weighed almost 7GB, but there was almost no useful data in it.In total, about 10 thousand records containing mail, nicknames, hash passwords and IP addresses of users.

title: Nasha-pizza-cool
description: A Russian pizza delivery site was hacked in 2022. As a result, a database containing information about users, about 26 thousand records, and data about orders, more than 61 thousand records, got into the network. Phone numbers, addresses, full names and emails were released.

title: Afy.ru
description: In 2023, using parsing, data was collected about users of the Russian real estate portal Afy.ru. The database contains mainly realtor data - phone numbers, names, profile descriptions, regions of residence and links to the profile. A total of 120 thousand records.

title: BigMoneyJobs
description: In April 2014, job site bigmoneyjobs.com was hacked by an attacker known as "ProbablyOnion". The attack exposed more than 36,000 user accounts. The data included email addresses, usernames, and passwords, which were stored in plain text. Presumably, the attack was carried out using SQL injection.

title: JDBBX
description: In November 2016, a data leak occurred on the Chinese gaming site JDBBX. The breach included usernames, email addresses and passwords stored as MD5 hashes. In total, 4.8 million users were affected.

title: Kaixin001
description: Around October 2011, the Chinese social network Kaixin001 suffered a data breach that affected 8.2 million users. The breach included unencrypted email addresses, usernames and passwords. Kaixin001 concluded that the hacked credentials were obtained through brute force and not from a breach of their database.

title: Mappery
description: In December 2018, the mapping website Mappery suffered a data breach that exposed more than 205,000 unique email addresses. Usernames, geographic locations, and passwords were also published as unsalted SHA-1 hashes. There was no response from Mappery regarding the incident.

title: Forex 2023
description: In 2023, a database obtained from an online Forex exchange appeared online. The data contained names, phone numbers and emails of clients. In total there are more than 7 million records. The leak included users from a variety of countries, but the majority were from the UK and Germany.

title: Civil Online
description: In mid-2011, data from the Chinese engineering website Civil Online was published. They contained 7.8 million accounts, including email addresses, IP addresses, usernames and MD5 password hashes.

title: ZolotoDom.ru
description: In 2019, there was a large-scale data leak from the online jewelry store ZolotoDom.ru, specializing in the sale of jewelry made of precious metals. The information disclosed included records of 16 thousand customers, 48 ​​thousand orders and more than 137 thousand phone calls. Phone numbers, emails, full names, IP addresses, addresses and passport data have been compromised.

title: Driving Licenses 2018
description: Database of automobile licenses of Russian citizens obtained in 2018. Contains about a million people and information about their names, dates of birth, addresses and driver's licenses.

title: RunescapeBoards
description: In August 2013, the Runescape Forums website Runescape Boards suffered a data breach that affected 224 thousand users. The attack exposed usernames, email addresses, IP addresses and passwords as vBulletin hashes. The site no longer works.

title: FamilySpace.ru
description: In early March 2024, the Russian genealogy website FamilySpace suffered a hack, which led to a data leak. The leak contains 5.5 million records. Data includes full name, email, mother's maiden name and MD5 hashed password.

title: KushaiSushi.rf
description: In October 2023, another regional sushi and pizza delivery service was hacked and its customer data was put up for sale on the forum. This time the database of the delivery service “Eat Sushi and Pizza” was leaked. Later, the data became publicly available; it contained 660 thousand orders with names, phone numbers, IP addresses, delivery addresses and comments on the order.

title: Justiva.ru
description: Yustiva is a company providing fast legal assistance. It was hacked in 2019, which affected 117 thousand clients. The published data contains names, emails, addresses, phone numbers and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes.

title: Washington State Food Worker Course
description: Around November 2018, a food safety training program developed by the Tacoma-Pierce County Department of Health (Washington State Food Service Worker Course) inadvertently left a backup that contained the data of 2.1 million trainees unsecured. The leak revealed full names, postcodes, dates of birth and email addresses.

title: Tablepin.ru
description: In 2023, there was a leak on the restaurant booking site Tablepin. The published database contains about 60 thousand records with emails, names, phone numbers and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: LinkedIn Dump 119m
description: A large dump with emails and passwords from the social network LinkedIn appeared on a hacker forum in December 2022. The leak contained 119 million strings, of which only 33 million were unique. The database is a combination of data from other leaks.

title: AdultFriendFinder 2015
description: In May 2015, the adult dating site Adult FriendFinder was hacked. Almost 4 million records were made publicly available. The data dump included highly sensitive personal information about people, their relationship status and sexual preferences, combined with personally identifiable information.

title: WildStar
description: In July 2015, the IP.Board forum of the gaming website WildStar suffered a data leak that exposed more than 738,000 forum member accounts. The data was actively traded on underground forums and included email addresses, dates of birth and passwords.

title: makc.ru
description: In 2018, a leak occurred in the Russian car insurance service MAKS-M. The data includes names, phone numbers, addresses, SNI and passport data, dates of birth and other information. There are 3 million records in total. At the same time, the company's health insurance division was hacked.

title: Income 2016
description: A database with citizens’ incomes, which appeared in 2016. It is fake, although the data is real. In fact, this file was compiled from databases merged before 2010. Contains 1.6 million records - names, TIN, passports, dates of birth, addresses, citizenship, place of work and annual income.

title: ScanTour.ru
description: ScanTour is a Russian tour operator that suffered from a leak on 04/12/2024, as a result of which tables with customers, their orders, payment data and other information were published. The tables contain names, passport details, telephone numbers, dates of birth and other information. All tables have a total of about 800 thousand records.

title: Leomax.ru
description: Leomax is a Russian clothing and home goods store. It was hacked in September 2021. The leak includes names, addresses, phone numbers, order dates and amounts. A total of 112 thousand records.

title: Zfunds.in
description: These are Indian mutual fund platform. In May 2021, it suffered a leak that affected 134 thousand users. The database contains names, addresses, dates of birth, telephone numbers, emails and other data.

title: MobChasti.ru
description: The Russian online store MobChasti, offering services for the sale of mobile accessories and devices, became a victim of a data leak on February 9, 2024. A database was leaked online, affecting 22 thousand user records and 12 thousand of their orders, including mail, names, phone numbers, delivery addresses, IP addresses and text comments on orders.

title: PrivatBank 2014
description: In June 2014, it became known that personal data of users was stolen from the largest Ukrainian bank. The hacker group Green Dragon is behind the hack. The data contains names, telephone numbers, dates of birth, passport details and INN.

title: Freelance 2021
description: This is a database of freelancers collected in 2021 using parsing from the Russian site Fl.ru. The database contains data about freelancers from various fields, including names, phone numbers, emails, existing skills and links to social networks. There are about 110 thousand rows of data in total.

title: Learnable
description: In June 2020, SitePoint's learning platform Learnable suffered a data breach that affected 1 million users. The leak included email addresses, usernames, full names, IP addresses and passwords stored as bcrypt hashes.

title: Doxbin
description: In January 2022, a “doxing” website designed to expose the personal information of targeted individuals (“doxes”) suffered a data breach. The leak included 370 thousand unique email addresses, as well as usernames, password hashes and browser data. Personal information often included names, physical addresses, phone numbers and more.

title: Mprofiko
description: The Russian medical clinic Mfiko was hacked in January 2023. The leak contains names, dates of birth, phone numbers and emails of clients. A total of 267 thousand records.

title: Ulmon
description: In January 2020, travel app Ulmon suffered a data breach. The service had almost 1.3 million records with 777 thousand unique email addresses. The data also contained names, passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes, phone numbers and biographical information. The data was subsequently published on a popular hacker forum.

title: TheHalara.com
description: The American online women's clothing store Halara suffered a data leak, which was published on June 13, 2024 on a shadow forum. As a result of the incident, information about 900 thousand users became available, including full names, phone numbers, countries and addresses.

title: Puma.com
description: In February 2022, sportswear manufacturer Puma was hit by ransomware. The attackers managed to steal the data of 300 thousand company employees and their family members. Moreover, the theft was carried out through the Kronos cloud storage, which for many years was advertised as “the most secure and hack-proof.” Data published later included names, telephone numbers, mails, addresses and document numbers.

title: Animal-id
description: This is a Russian database of microchipped animals and their owners. It contains 117 thousand people and includes names, phone numbers and emails. The leak occurred in 2022.

title: MIX Database
description: In May 2022, a collection containing 464 million emails and plain text passwords obtained from various leaks appeared on a hacker forum.

title: Leddiretto.it
description: Spanish lighting website Leddiretto.it was hacked on November 22, 2022. Data about 72 thousand users has become publicly available. The leak included emails, names, IPs, dates of birth, gender and passwords as unsalted MD5 hashes.

title: TimeOClock.ru
description: In February 2023, a website selling watches, TimeOClock.ru, suffered a data leak. Information about 12 thousand users was publicly available, including nicknames, full names, emails and passwords in the form of an MD5 hash.

title: Wongnai
description: In October 2020, 17 previously unknown data breaches were put up for sale. Among them was a Thai restaurant and Wongnai sightseeing service. The leak revealed nearly 4 million unique customer records. They included emails, names, phone numbers, links to social networks and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes.

title: MPGH
description: In October 2015, the MPGH multiplayer game hacking website was hacked. The details of 3.1 million user accounts were exposed. The leak contained usernames, emails, IP addresses and passwords as salted MD5 hashes.

title: MatchUSA
description: In January 2018, the American dating service MatchUSA suffered a data leak that affected 208 thousand users. The leak exposed data including email addresses and passwords stored in plaintext.

title: TimeShop
description: In April 2020, a data leak occurred from the Ukrainian online watch store TimeShop.com.ua. Two tables containing data about 16 thousand users and 46 thousand orders were leaked online. Emails, full names, phone numbers, passwords, IP addresses and shipping addresses were exposed.

title: Edunetcafe.com
description: This is an Iranian forum devoted mainly to the interpretation of religious texts. It was hacked in November 2019. The published leak contains 85 thousand records with emails, nicknames, IP addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: Tangkaskita.net
description: On December 27, 2017, a data leak occurred from an online platform dedicated to the card game Bola Tangkas. It affected about 12 thousand records, including emails, nicknames, phone numbers, IP addresses, as well as bank account data.

title: DatPiff
description: At the end of 2021, 7.5 million plain text email addresses and passwords from the rap mixtape site DatPiff appeared for sale on a hacker forum. The data was later released free of charge.

title: Diet
description: In August 2014, a diet and nutrition website suffered a data breach that exposed 1.4 million unique user records dating back to 2004. The data contained email addresses, IP addresses, usernames, plain text passwords, and dietary information about site members, including eating habits, BMI and date of birth.

title: Libero
description: Around July 2016, the Italian email service Libero suffered a data breach that affected 701,000 users. The leak included full names, gender, physical addresses, email addresses and unencrypted passwords.

title: RussianDoska.ru
description: This is a Russian bulletin board with the sale of goods and services. Moreover, most of the advertisements are escort services. In November 2024, data from it was collected using parsing. About 70 thousand records with telephone numbers, addresses and other data from advertisements were received.

title: Weibo
description: In 2019, a leak occurred on the Chinese social network Weibo. 504 million rows of data were published that included a user ID and associated phone number.

title: DIT
description: In the spring of 2023, hackers hacked the Moscow Department of Information Technology (DIT) and for a long time pumped out all data from it. According to them, they were able to download 40 terabytes of data related to various services, including personal data of all posquitches and source codes of programs. The data includes telephone numbers (one or two), emails, names, passport details, dates of birth, addresses, medical policies and other information. In total there are about 12 million people.

title: Neposeda-Shoes.ru
description: The Russian online shoe store Neposeda-Shoes was hacked in April 2024, as a result of which access to the database was gained, affecting more than 25 thousand records. The data contained emails, names, telephone numbers, TIN and passwords in the form of MD5 and bcrypt hashes.

title: Dfb.de
description: Dfb.de is a German football website. In November 2016, information appeared that it had leaked 3.3 million users. Another 16 million users were published later. However, upon closer examination, it became clear that the leak did not originate from the Dfb.de website, but from somewhere else, so its source remains unknown. The leak contains only emails and passwords.

title: Ndv.ru
description: On February 10, 2023, the hacker group Cyber.Anarchy.Squad announced that it had hacked the Russian real estate agency Ndv.ru. They published a data dump of 8GB in size, which contains 156 thousand emails, almost 100,000 phones and many usernames of the resource.

title: Sport2000.fr
description: In March 2024, the French website Sport2000 suffered from a hack. More than 4 million records have been published, including names, phone numbers, emails, addresses, dates of birth and other information.

title: Collection of 7,651 databases
description: In December 2022, all databases from the hacker data trading site were made publicly available. A total of 7,651 leaks were published. The data contained only plaintext emails and passwords. A total of 493 million records in all databases.

title: DcEnergo.ru
description: In 2023, the database of a multidisciplinary clinic on the DcEnergo website became publicly available, affecting more than 38 thousand records, including emails, phone numbers and full names.

title: Factual
description: In March 2017, the Factual aggregator database was published. It contains 8 million records. The data contained 2.5 million unique email addresses as well as company names, addresses and phone numbers. Factual said the data was "publicly available information that Factual makes available on its website."

title: Facepunch
description: In June 2016, the game development studio Facepunch suffered a data leak that affected 343 thousand users. Emails, IP addresses, dates of birth and salted MD5 password hashes were exposed. Facepunch said they were aware of the incident and notified the affected people when it happened.

title: Xarakiri.ru
description: This is a Russian restaurant and sushi chain. The leak occurred in 2022 and contains phone numbers, emails, names, dates of birth and other information. A total of 85 thousand lines.

title: DIKIDI
description: In October 2023, the NLB hacker team published a leak of the Russian online recording service “DIKIDI” (dikidi.ru). The data includes names, phone numbers, emails and passwords in the form of SHA-256 hashes. A total of 100,000 rows were posted, but hackers claim that the full database contains 40 million entries.

title: AndroidLista
description: In July 2021, the Spanish Android phone app store Lista suffered a data breach that affected 6.6 million users. The breach resulted in the disclosure of usernames, email addresses, full names and passwords in the form of SHA-1 hashes. Few users set their own password due to the SSO system.

title: BioFam.ru
description: On February 5, 2024, it became known from a leak from the Russian health food store BioFam. A database was published containing 46 thousand users and 121 thousand of their orders. The data contains names, emails, phone numbers, passwords in the form of MD5 or bcrypt hashes, as well as addresses for delivery of orders and other data about them.

title: Sozar.ru
description: In 2023, there was a leak from the Union of Zoos and Aquariums of Russia, which affected 154 thousand users of the site. The data contains emails, nicknames, names and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes.

title: Uchi.ru
description: The Russian online educational platform Uchi.ru was hacked on November 9, 2019 by an unknown attacker, who later posted 50 thousand records of users of this platform. The data contains emails, names, phone numbers and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes.

title: IntimShop
description: In September 2022, a data leak occurred in the Russian sex toy store Intimshop. The leak exposed data including full names, phone numbers, email addresses and passwords stored as MD5 hashes. In total, 128 thousand users were affected.

title: GaPacc
description: In 2020, a set of decrypted databases containing 580 million emails and passwords was made publicly available. The data was obtained from 243 different leaks and contained only emails and unencrypted passwords.

title: Liker
description: In March 2021, the self-proclaimed "kinder, smarter social network" Liker suffered a data breach, allegedly in retaliation for Gab's data leak and data harvesting from Parler. The hack exposed 465,000 email addresses, as well as names, dates of birth, education levels, personal messages, plain text security questions and passwords stored as bcrypt hashes and other data.

title: Akson.ru
description: One of the largest Russian manufacturing and trading structures suffered a leak of confidential data in July 2021. 170 thousand records with personal information were compromised, including emails, names, addresses, phone numbers and tax identification numbers.

title: 247Hire
description: Around July 2022, an Offshore Hiring Solutions service called 247Hire suffered a data breach that affected 50,000 people. The breach exposed email addresses, locations, visa statuses, job titles and resumes.

title: Avvo
description: Around December 2019, the Avvo attorney directory data leak was posted on an online hacker forum. She was later used in an extortion scam. The data contained 4.1 million unique email addresses, as well as SHA-1 hashes that most likely represented user passwords. Several attempts to contact Avvo were unsuccessful.

title: EvoPlace.EvoBanco.com
description: In July 2024, the online service of the banking system EvoPlace.EvoBanco was hacked; as a result of the hacker attack, approximately 60 thousand user data was published on the network, including names, phone numbers, emails, residential addresses and other information.

title: AutoRia
description: Auto.ria.com is a Ukrainian website for selling or buying cars. There is a database of his clients online, containing 90 thousand rows. The data contains cities, names, phone numbers and vehicle information.

title: MindJolt
description: In March 2019, online gaming site MindJolt suffered a breach that exposed 28 million unique email addresses. Names and dates of birth were also affected, but not passwords.

title: Gravatar
description: In October 2020, a technique for extracting large amounts of data from Gravatar was published. This service provides common avatars for all sites. Using this method, 167 million usernames and MD5 hashes of their email addresses were collected. These hashes were used as a reference to user avatars. Many hashes were subsequently decrypted.

title: SberMarket.ru
description: SberMarket is a Russian online platform for ordering groceries and goods from supermarkets with home delivery. There is a publicly accessible database containing 115 thousand clients of this site - their phone numbers, names and addresses. The database dates back to 2020, however, there are rumors about the existence of a more complete leak, which already includes 12.5 million records.

title: Yota.ru
description: In 2013, there was a leak of data from all subscribers of the mobile operator Yota. The leak contains 1.8 million records with names, passports, tax identification numbers, passports, residential addresses and several phone numbers. The database also contained information about the purchased tariff and the IMSI code of the device.

title: Express-zakaz.ru
description: At the end of April 2024, the web store of dietary supplements and medical products Express-zakaz.ru became a victim of a data leak of more than 22 thousand customers, including their contact numbers, full names, addresses and emails.

title: LinkPass collection
description: In 2022, a combo player appeared on the Internet containing authorization data for various sites. It was obtained using viruses that steal saved login data in browsers. The leak contained approximately 150 million records. It indicated nicknames, emails and telephone numbers as logins and passwords in plain text, as well as the sites for which they were intended.

title: EpicBot 2016
description: In February 2016, RuneScape bot provider EpicBot suffered a data leak that affected 40.4 thousand users. The attack exposed usernames, email addresses, IP addresses, dates of birth and passwords as vBulletin hashes. EpicBot was hacked for the second time in 2019, affecting more than 800 thousand users.

title: Acikogretim.gen.tr
description: This is a Turkish educational site. It was hacked in November 2019. The published leak contains 210 thousand records with emails, nicknames, IP addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: FortnitePorn
description: Around January 2021, a porn and hentai site dedicated to the game “Fortnite” experienced a data leak that affected 76.4 thousand users. The breach included usernames, email addresses and passwords in MD5 hashes.

title: VerificationsIO
description: In February 2019, the email verification service Verifications.io was damaged. Data in MongoDB was left publicly accessible without a password, which exposed 763 million unique emails, phone numbers and IPs. Passwords were not included in the data.

title: 7k7k
description: Around 2011, Chinese gaming site 7k7k suffered a data breach that affected 9.1 million subscribers. The data contained usernames, email addresses, and passwords in plain text.

title: Russia Mobile Database
description: Allegedly in 2017, Russia Mobile created a dataset of Russian users, mainly from Moscow. Data includes emails, phone numbers, full names and dates of birth. Total 722 thousand.

title: TrudVsem.ru
description: This is the Russian federal base of vacancies and resume.In November 2024, the data of 10 million ads from this site were collected using parsing.The data obtained contained mail, 1-3 phone, name, region, work experience, education data and skills, as well as extensive information from the resume, including the presence of children and the level of ownership of a foreign language.

title: Zoloto585.ru
description: In April 2023, a hacker who had previously hacked the Zdravcity pharmacy and the Puma online store published information about hacking the database of the Russian jewelry store “Zoloto585”. The database, published later, contains about 10 million records with names, phone numbers, emails, addresses and passport details of buyers.

title: VbenterPriseTranslator.com
description: In April 2018, the VbenterPriseTranslator forum, dedicated to machine and manual translation, suffered from a hack. An SQL dump was published containing 1.2 million records, including nicknames, emails, passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt, and other information about users.

title: Pxel.ru
description: This is a Russian website for products for professional photography. In August 2020, a hacker was able to hack this site and download a complete data dump containing 10 thousand users and more than 100 thousand of their orders. The data includes emails, names, passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt and information about purchased goods and their delivery address.

title: SmsActivate
description: On July 20, 2021, it became known about a massive leak of data from users of the anonymous verification service sms-activate.ru. The leaked database contains data of 163 thousand users and includes emails, names, credit card numbers, their balances and IP addresses.

title: Dns-employers
description: In December 2022, it became known about the leak of personal data of employees of DNS, a Russian electronics store. The published file contains 150 thousand records, which include full names, corporate emails, dates of birth, work phone numbers and places of work of company employees.

title: WarandWork.net
description: In 2017, due to hacking, a database was obtained from the Minecraft server WarAndWork. In total, more than 77 thousand records were compromised, including emails, nicknames, IP addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes.

title: Sites.Reviews
description: On April 10, 2024, the Russian platform for discussing and rating websites Sites.Reviews suffered a data leak. There were more than 340 thousand records online containing emails, nicknames, full names, IP addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes.

title: FreeJob.ru
description: Job search platform FreeJob, offering services for posting vacancies and resumes. In 2021, resumes from the site were collected using parsing, which resulted in a database containing 45 thousand records, including emails, nicknames, phone numbers and dates of birth.

title: Reniec
description: This is the national register of Spanish citizens. In the spring of 2018, it suffered a leak that affected 3 million people. Published data includes names, addresses, dates of birth, parents' names and nationalities.

title: OMGPop
description: Around 2019, the multiplayer gaming website OMGPop (formerly known as "i'minlikewithyou") suffered a data breach affecting approximately 7 million users. The data dates back to 2013, but was leaked in 2019. The attack exposed email addresses and passwords in plaintext.

title: Hoster.by
description: In 2020, there was a data leak from the Belarusian cloud solutions platform Hoster.by, which provides services for business. As a result of the incident, more than 2 million records were made publicly available, including emails, nicknames and passwords in the form of MD5 and SHA1 hashes with salt.

title: DataKabel.ru
description: A Russian website selling cables and accessories for various needs was subject to a hacker attack in October 2020. As a result, 90 thousand records were published, including telephone and email addresses of users. There was no other information in the leak.

title: Beeline Employers
description: At the end of 2021, a database containing the data of all Beeline employees became publicly available. Including names, phone numbers, emails, logins and cities of residence. There are about 200 thousand records in total.

title: WorldOfTanks
description: WorldOfTanks is a multiplayer game on the computer. In June 2020, the data of all users of this game was collected by scraping from an online forum. The data contains about 230 thousand entries with nicknames and statistics from the forum.

title: Nulled.ch
description: In May 2020, the hacker forum Nulled.ch was hacked and its data was published on a rival hacker forum. More than 43 thousand accounts were compromised. The data included IP addresses, email addresses, usernames and passwords as salted MD5 hashes. The history of personal messages of the website administrator was also published.

title: GPSUnderground
description: In early 2017, GPS Underground was among many compromised vBulletin-based websites being sold online. The leak occurred in mid-2016 and included 670 thousand records of usernames, email addresses, IP addresses, dates of birth and passwords as salted MD5 hashes.

title: FMS Voronezh 2018
description: In 2018, the Russian Federal Migration Service database for the city of Voronezh became publicly available. The data contains 4.5 million records with names, addresses, dates of birth and passports of citizens.

title: DuelingNetwork
description: Dueling Network is a Flash game based on the card game Yu-Gi-Oh. In March 2017, it suffered a data breach. The site itself was taken offline in 2016, but the forum remained online for another year. The data breach exposed usernames, IP addresses, email addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes. The leak includes 2.5 million records.

title: CronOfHorse
description: In May 2020, a data leak occurred on the CronOfHorse website dedicated to horses and equestrian sports. The information of 1.4 million users was exposed, including nicknames, emails and IP addresses.

title: Bhinneka
description: In early 2020, Indonesian consumer electronics website Bhinneka suffered a data breach that exposed the records of nearly 1.3 million customers. The data included email and physical addresses, names, gender, dates of birth, phone numbers and password hashes.

title: PokerMagia.com
description: PokerMagia is an Italian online poker school. At the end of 2015, a leak occurred on this site, affecting 660 thousand users. The data includes emails, names and hashed passwords.

title: EmploymentCenter.ru
description: In August 2019, a Russian job search platform was hacked. As a result, 78 thousand user data was disclosed, including emails, phone names, dates of birth and information from resumes about skills, hobbies, education and relationship status.

title: Nic-Snail.ru
description: This is a Russian website for competitions and olympiads for children. In June 2020, it suffered a leak that affected 170 thousand users. The data contains emails, names, phone numbers, dates of birth, addresses, IP, places of work and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: Ostrov Chistoty
description: In October 2022, it became known about a data leak from the Belarusian store “Island of Purity and Taste.” This store sells household chemicals. The published data includes 148 thousand rows and contains names, emails, phone numbers, delivery addresses and other data.

title: DAI Ukraine
description: DAI - Road Automobile Inspectorate of Ukraine. In 2005, there was a leak in which the data of 9 million cars was published. The information contains license plates, car brands, serial numbers of their parts and engine size, as well as owner data - full name, date of birth and residential address.

title: Collection
description: In January 2019, a collection of 5 parts appeared on a hacker forum, representing a combination of data from different sites. The collection contained 108 thousand files with a total size of 870GB. These files contained 26 billion lines containing email and password. However, many values ​​were repeated many times, and there were only 4.3 billion unique pairs. And yet this collection is considered the biggest leak in history.

title: VK Phones 50k
description: As a result of parsing the social network VKontakte in 2024, about 57 thousand records containing only phone numbers and IDs got onto the Internet.

title: 8tracks
description: In June 2017, the online playlist service 8Tracks suffered a leak that affected 18 million accounts. Mail and salted SHA-1 password hashes for most users were made publicly available.

title: Eci-Spb.ru
description: In July 2023, the Eci-Spb.ru website, which provides engineering consulting services, suffered a data leak. The data of 9 thousand users and 8 thousand employees got into the network. Emails, full names, phone numbers and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes were exposed.

title: PromoFarma
description: In August 2019, a data leak occurred from the Spanish online pharmacy Promofarma. The data appeared for sale on the darknet trading platform. The leak contained more than 2.7 million records, including nearly 1.3 million unique customer email addresses. The data also contained the names of clients.

title: SuperArbalet.ru
description: This Russian store sells bows and crossbows, as well as accessories for them. It was hacked on November 26, 2021, resulting in 72 thousand entries being published. Data containing emails, names, logins and hashed passwords.

title: Twitter Active Users
description: In 2023, a database containing 880 thousand of the most active Twitter users appeared. It will include stars, politicians, athletes, journalists and other famous people. The database contains only emails and nothing else.

title: LyfApp
description: Around August 2021, the mental health app Lyf suffered a data breach. The breach included email addresses, names, countries, dates of birth and passwords stored as hashes of an unknown format. In total, 228 thousand users were affected.

title: Exploit.In
description: In late 2016, a huge list of email/password pairs appeared in the Exploit.In leak. The list contained 593 million unique email addresses and was used for “credential stuffing.”

title: EGRUL 2024
description: This data was collected in 2024 from the Russian register of legal entities. Using parsing, a database was obtained containing 26 million records, including emails, full names, INN and OGRNIP codes of organizations.

title: Tvoe.ru
description: Tvoe.ru is a Russian clothing store hacked by the NLB hacker team in May 2023. They made the database publicly available on June 8, 2023. The leak includes 2.2 million records. The data contains names, phone numbers and emails of clients.

title: OneLand.su
description: OneLand is a Russian Minecraft server that was hacked in March 2017. The leak included 340 thousand users and contained their nicknames, emails, IPs and parodies in the form of MD5x2 hashes. The data also contained information about the total playing time and the balance on the site.

title: Russian bus tickets 2021
description: This is a 2021 bus ticket database containing 2.5 million records. The leak includes names, passport details, travel routes, as well as bus models and numbers. The source of the leak is unknown.

title: DoSeng.org
description: In January 2022, the database of the DoSeng joke site was published on a hacker forum. The leak contains about half a million records with emails, names, IP addresses, regions of residence and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes.

title: Stalker.so
description: In 2020, a hacker hacked the official server of the multiplayer game “Stalker-Online” and gained access to the database of registered players. The publicly available database dump contains 1.3 million rows. The data includes names, emails, phone numbers and passwords, either in clear text or as salted SHA1 hashes.

title: Ukrainian voters 2019
description: This is a database of Ukrainian voters dating back to 2019. The data includes names, dates of birth, addresses and polling place numbers. A total of 32 million records.

title: LovePlanet
description: Around January 2015, the Russian dating site LovePlanet suffered a leak that affected 20 million users. The breach resulted in the disclosure of usernames, emails and passwords stored without encryption. The site was allegedly hacked by GnosticPlayers.

title: RecklessPk
description: Around April 2015, RecklessPk, the "Runescape Nr 1 launch server", suffered a data breach. The breach exposed email addresses, usernames, IP addresses and passwords as SMF hashes. In total, 82 thousand users were affected.

title: Kirov GIBDD
description: In 2006, there was a data leak from the traffic police database of the city of Kirov. As a result of the incident, 283 thousand records containing personal data of car owners, full names, tax identification numbers, vehicle numbers and models were leaked to the network.

title: Magti
description: Magti is a large Georgian mobile operator that suffered from a leak around 2020 (no exact date). The leak contains phone numbers, names and addresses. A total of 2.5 million records.

title: PassionsNetwork
description: Around January 2017, the dating site Passions Network suffered a data breach that affected the records of 833 thousand clients. The breach included usernames, email addresses and passwords in MD5 hashes.

title: 24samurai.ru
description: In March 2023, it became known about a data leak from the Russian sushi store “24 Samurai”. Phone numbers, emails, names, addresses and amounts of customer orders were published. The database contains 130 thousand orders from 30 thousand customers.

title: Warmane
description: Around December 2016, Warmane leaked. This is an online service for private World of Warcraft servers. 1.1 million records were published, including usernames, email addresses, dates of birth and salted MD5 password hashes.

title: Ingruz.ru
description: On October 19, 2023, a data leak occurred on the Ingruz platform, specializing in logistics and cargo transportation. It affected more than 12 thousand records containing telephone numbers, emails, names, cities of residence, tax identification number and place of work.

title: Vidita-sport.com.ua
description: In November 2022, a Ukrainian sporting goods website suffered a data breach. The published database contains 19 thousand records. Names, emails, phone numbers and addresses. For some reason, the database contained a lot of data in Chinese.

title: Trillian
description: In December 2015, instant messaging app Trillian suffered a data breach. 3.8 million users were affected. The hack became known in July 2016. The leak included names, email addresses and passwords as salted MD5 hashes. The full version of the leak is not publicly available; only a partial version is available, containing 79k lines.

title: Nbki.ru
description: In March 2024, a file was made publicly available, according to the hacker, taken from the National Bureau of Credit History database (nbki.ru). The hacker claimed that he had 200 million records, but only 500 thousand were posted. The data contains names, phone numbers, passport details, dates of birth, regions and debt amounts. Most likely the data was downloaded from some microfinance organization. The leak occurred on February 4, 2024.

title: ClashOfOlympus
description: In 2022, the MMO game Clash of Olympus suffered a leak that affected 1.5 million people. The data contains nicknames, emails, IP addresses, passwords in the form of MD5 hashes and other information.

title: Shadi
description: In July 2016, Muslim dating site Shadi.com suffered a data breach that exposed the email addresses of over 2 million members. The hack also exposed passwords stored as MD5 hashes, along with their text variants, and user registration dates.

title: GTA Gaming
description: In August 2016, the Grand Theft Auto forum was hacked and almost 200 thousand user posts were made publicly available. The vBulletin-based forum contained usernames, email addresses, and password hashes.

title: SushiKatana.ru
description: In January 2022, the food delivery website SushiKatana.ru was hacked. As a result, three tables were published containing information about 29 thousand customers, 35 thousand deliveries and 231 thousand orders. The tables contained phone numbers, nicknames, full names, emails and shipping addresses.

title: GlobalCatalog.com
description: A Canadian platform that helps companies find potential clients and partners suffered a data leak at the end of 2019. About 250 thousand records were leaked onto the Internet, including nicknames, phone numbers, emails and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes.

title: Freelance.ru
description: Freelance.ru is a Russian job search site. In 2015, it was hacked and the data of 180 thousand users became publicly available. The database contained emails, phone numbers, nicknames and names.

title: Qraved
description: In July 2021, Indonesian restaurant website Qraved suffered a data breach that affected 1 million users. The attack exposed full names, email addresses, dates of birth, phone numbers and passwords as MD5 hashes.

title: EmailMaker.ru
description: EmailMaker is an online email designer. At the end of 2021, it suffered from a leak that affected 4.4 million users. The data contains emails, names and other information.

title: Pochta.ru Сartoteka
description: In 2022, Ukrainian hackers made publicly available a database that, according to them, belongs to Russian Post and is called “Card Index”. Part of the database consisted of long-known leaks from the Compulsory Medical Insurance Fund, and part of it was new data. The database contained about 9 million users with information about their telephone numbers, addresses, dates of birth, passport data, TIN numbers and Snils. However, the data appears to be quite old.

title: Papiroska.rf
description: In September 2024, the website papiroska.rf, which sells electronic cigarettes in Russia, suffered from a hack. 836 thousand records containing names, emails and residential addresses of users were stolen from the site. In some cases there were also links to VK profiles. However, the leak is most likely not complete, since many user accounts are missing from the published database.

title: Parapa
description: In August 2016, the Russian gaming site parapa.mail.ru was hacked, along with a number of other mail.ru forums. The forum contained 49 million entries, including names, emails and passwords in the form of salted MD5 hashes.

title: ColorDating
description: The dating app "ColorDatingApp" allows you to search for people based on the color of their skin. In 2018, due to a hack, the data of 220 thousand users was stolen from this site. The leak contains emails, names, geolocation, age data and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes

title: Vedomosti.ru
description: In 2012, there was a leak from the Russian news site Vedomosti.ru. The emails, phone numbers, names and specializations of 217 thousand users were published.

title: ParagonServers
description: Paragon-Servers is a private World of Warcraft server. In August 2016, it suffered a data leak that affected 400 thousand users. The hack included usernames, email addresses, IP addresses and passwords in the form of SHA-1 hashes ($username.$pass).

title: United Kingdom Consumer Leads
description: More than 1 million records have been published in a massive data breach of UK citizens. The information disclosed included names, phone numbers, cities of residence and zip codes.

title: Navigator Children
description: This service is a system of educational programs and events for teachers, students and parents. In 2021, a database containing about 50 thousand unique records was downloaded from the service through an open endpoint. The data includes names, dates of birth, telephones, mails and in some cases SNILS numbers.

title: LovingFerrets.com
description: In March 2016, a data breach occurred from LovingFerrets.com, a site aimed at ferret owners. The database contained about 230 thousand user records, including IP addresses, emails, nicknames and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes.

title: 178 Million MIX Combolist
description: Collection published on a hacker forum in September 2022. Contained 178 million emails and passwords for them. But there were only 30 million unique pairs. The data likely came from many different leaks.

title: NumBuster 2018
description: NumBuster is an application for identifying the name of the phone owner. It collects data from users' phone books and provides searches for this data. In 2018, hackers were able to extract the API key from the application and used it to scrape the database. They managed to collect 102 million Russian phones. The database contains only numbers and names with which other people have recorded them in phone books.

title: iDTech
description: In January 2023, the American portal of children's summer programming training camps “iD Tech” was hacked. The leak contains about a million records with names, nicknames, dates of birth and passwords in plain text.

title: YoteprestoCom
description: In June 2020, the Mexican lending platform yotepresto.com was hacked. More than 1.4 million customers were affected by the breach, which exposed email addresses, IPs, usernames and passwords as bcrypt hashes.

title: NumBuster 09.2020
description: NumBuster is an application for determining the identity of the person calling. This database was obtained by scraping this application in September 2020. It contains half a million phone numbers and the names with which users of the application marked them in the contact book.

title: VezetVsem
description: “Everyone is lucky” is a Russian transportation service. In June 2022, it became known that the data of users of this service was made publicly available. The published table includes 1.6 million rows with phone numbers, emails, IP addresses, names and passwords in the form of md5crypt hashes.

title: MTSBank
description: On September 7, 2023, the database of MTS Bank clients was made publicly available. The hacking group claims to have 21 million records, but they have only made 1 million of them publicly available. The data contains names, phone numbers, emails, dates of birth, TIN and partial data of bank cards, as well as SHA1 card hashes, which can be used to recover full numbers using brute force.

title: WolfeEyeClinic
description: A leak occurred on the web resource of the American eye clinic wolfeeyeclinic.com, as a result of which the data of 70 thousand patients was published. The incident exposed clients' personal information, including full names, phone numbers, addresses, IPs, emails, and many other records. The attack also affected various medical health information.

title: Adidas
description: In December 2022, clothing and footwear manufacturer Adidas suffered from a data leak. The Adidas.co.ma website was hacked. Later, an SQL dump containing about 100 thousand user records, as well as emails, names, dates of birth, telephone numbers, addresses and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes, appeared in the public domain.

title: Adobe
description: In October 2013, 153 million Adobe accounts were hacked, containing names, emails, encrypted passwords and text hints. The cryptography of the passwords was terrible and they were quickly cracked.

title: MyPertamina
description: In November 2022, Indonesian oil and gas company Pertamina suffered a data breach on its MyPertamina service. The incident revealed 44 million records with 6 million unique email addresses, as well as names, dates of birth, gender, physical addresses and purchases.

title: Taobao
description: Around 2012, Chinese shopping site taobao.com suffered a data breach that affected more than 21 million subscribers. The data in the breach contains email addresses and passwords in plain text.

title: Aliexpress 2021
description: In 2021, Aliexpress marketplace data was collected using parsing. The resulting database contains 166 thousand records and includes emails, names, addresses and other information about customers.

title: Zaimer.kz
description: In March 2024, it became known that several microfinance organizations were hacked at once, including the Kazakh organization Zaimer.kz. Initially, only 500 thousand entries were published, but later a full version appeared, including more than 2 million unique users. The data contains names, telephone numbers (often several), addresses, passport details, dates of birth, contact details and other information.

title: Youla.ru
description: “Yula” is a Russian bulletin board. The data of its users was collected using parsing and made publicly available. They contain phone numbers, names, gender and addresses. The date of creation of the database is unknown.

title: GetPaidTo
description: In July 2019, GetPaidTo's Earn Money Online from Home website experienced a data breach. The breach included email addresses, usernames and passwords stored as vBulletin hashes. A total of 92.8 thousand users were affected.

title: SoarGames
description: Around December 2019, a data leak occurred on the gaming forum website SoarGames that affected 5 million users. The breach included emails, usernames, login IP addresses and passwords stored as MD5 hashes.

title: Mamba.ru
description: In 2015, there was a leak in the dating service Mamba.ru. 12.9 million records were compromised, but less than a million records were made public. These include emails, phone numbers and full usernames.

title: MegaMarket.ru
description: In 2023, on one of the largest online shopping platforms in Russia, MegaMarket.ru, there was a data leak from 42 thousand records, including emails, phone numbers, names, addresses and Taxpayer Identification Numbers.

title: PrizyvaNet.ru
description: PrizyvaNet.ru is a Russian site that helps avoid conscription into the army by searching for various diseases. At the beginning of 2020, 5 tables with data from this site were made publicly available. The data contains users, managers, payment data, a list of partners and a table of calls. The data includes telephone numbers, emails, names, dates of birth, passport details, addresses, links to social networks, bank card data and survey results, as well as a very detailed history of interactions with the client, often including several pages of text. The total number of rows in all tables exceeds 200 thousand, but there are no more than 50 thousand unique users.

title: Invest-Trades.ru
description: In August 2022, the now defunct investment site Invest-Trades.ru was hacked. Many tables containing names, emails, telephone numbers, addresses, company data and other information have become publicly available. There are about 600 thousand rows in total.

title: LadyCollection.com
description: LadyCollection is an online store selling fashion jewelry and accessories. It suffered from data breaches twice. In 2014, 140 thousand user records were stolen, and in 2015 - about 400 thousand. The data contains mails, addresses, dates of birth and names of clients.

title: Gamigo
description: In March 2012, German online game publisher Gamigo was hacked and more than 8 million accounts were exposed. The hack involved email addresses and passwords stored as unsalted MD5 hashes.

title: FoamStore.ru
description: This is a Russian online store specializing in the sale of goods made of polystyrene foam and polyurethane foam. Allegedly, on June 16, 2023, a leak occurred on it, which affected 1.5 million users, but the emails were not registered on the site itself, and therefore the real source of the leak is different. The data contains emails, phone numbers, names, passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt and links to VK pages.

title: LinuxForums
description: In May 2018, the Linux Forums website suffered a leak that exposed 276,000 unique email addresses. Names, IP addresses and password hashes with MD5 salt are also revealed.

title: UA Drivers License
description: In 2020, a database of driver’s licenses from Ukraine began to be distributed on Telegram channels. The database contains more than 21 million unique records and includes names in Russian and Ukrainian, dates of birth, place of birth, addresses, tax identification numbers, passports and driver's licenses.

title: Zoomcar
description: In July 2018, Indian self-driving car rental company Zoomcar suffered a data breach that was subsequently sold on the darknet market in 2020. The hack exposed 3.5 million records including names, email addresses, IP addresses, phone numbers and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes.

title: 966.ua
description: In 2021, the website of the Sushi and Lapsha restaurants, popular in the cities of Kharkov, the Dnieper and Odessa, lost the personal data of his customers.The public domain was a file containing detailed information about 8 thousand customer orders from these cities.The leak included names, phones, addresses and mail.

title: Atomcraft.ru
description: In December 2017, the AtomCraft minecraft server database became available online. About 415 thousand lines with nicknames, emails, IP addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes were compromised.

title: Disk54.ru
description: Disk54 is a Russian auto store. In 2023, it suffered from a data breach of 78 thousand users. The data contains names, phone numbers, emails and addresses of clients.

title: MTS
description: On September 7, 2023, it became known about the leak of MTS Bank customer data. The hacker group claimed to have 21 million records, but they were only made publicly available at the end of the year, with several different versions published. The data contains names, phone numbers, emails, dates of birth, TIN and partial data of bank cards, as well as SHA1 card hashes, which can be used to recover full numbers using brute force. There were several phones per person, and therefore their total number exceeded 70 million.

title: Best2Pay
description: On January 31, 2023, the NLB hacker group published part of the data from the Best2Pay payment service. The leak contains more than a million records. Compromised data includes emails, phone numbers, location data, and transaction and bank card information.

title: StripChat
description: In November 2021, the live sex cam and adult chat site Stripchat left several databases open and unprotected. The following June, more than 10 million Stripchat posts appeared on the popular hacker forum. The exposed data included usernames, email addresses and IP addresses.

title: SimpleMinecraft
description: The server for the Minecraft game SimpleMinecraft was hacked. The date of the leak is unknown, but as a result, the accounts of 500 thousand players were compromised. The data includes nicknames, emails and passwords in the form of double MD5 hashes.

title: Kickstarter
description: In February 2014, the crowdfunding platform Kickstarter announced a data leak. The later published database contained nearly 5.2 million unique email addresses, as well as usernames and salted SHA1 password hashes.

title: vBulletin
description: In November 2015, forum software maker vBulletin suffered a major data breach. The attack resulted in the release of nearly 519,000 forum user and client accounts. The breach included email addresses, dates of birth, security questions and answers for clients, and password hashes for both sources.

title: CoinPayex.ltd
description: The cryptocurrency transaction service CoinPayex suffered a leak in July 2021 that affected more than 620 thousand records, namely emails and passwords.

title: Minted
description: In May 2020, online marketplace for independent artists Minted was hit by a data breach that exposed 4.4 million unique customer records. They were subsequently sold on a darknet marketplace. The exposed data also included names, physical addresses, phone numbers and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes.

title: JoyGames 2020
description: In 2020, there was a data leak from the JoyGames online platform dedicated to multiplayer browser games. About 980 thousand entries were published containing nicknames, emails, IP addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: AlexHost
description: Around May 2022, hosting provider AlexHost accidentally copied all of its users into an email, allowing anyone who received the email to see other people. The leak included email addresses and full names. In total, information was disclosed to 1.5 thousand clients.

title: Uvi.ru
description: In November 2022, a leak occurred on the website of the Russian jewelry store Uvi. The database includes 53 thousand clients and contains emails, phone numbers and names.

title: Eprice
description: Eprice.com.tw is a Taiwanese e-commerce website. In January 2021, it was hacked and 460 thousand records were made public. The data contained emails, phone numbers, names, residential addresses, dates of birth, IP, security questions and answers to them in clear form, as well as passwords in plain text.

title: Elections.istra-da.ru
description: This is a Russian website with information about all parliamentary elections in Russia. In 2020, all publicly available information from it was collected using parsing. The resulting database contains about a million records with the names and dates of birth of candidates, as well as information about the elections in which they participated.

title: Tele2
description: Around June 2022, the Russian company Tele2 suffered a data leak. She revealed email addresses, full names, phone numbers and gender. In total, 7.5 million users were affected.

title: AvtoStrast.ru
description: A leak occurred on the official website of the Krasnodar service station Auto Passion in July 2019. It contained more than 80 thousand records, such as names, emails, passwords in the form of SHA256 hashes.

title: Lenwood.ru
description: In August 2021, the Lenwood website, which sells lumber, was hacked. About 2 thousand users were affected. The data contained emails, names, phone numbers, addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: CapitalGames
description: In September 2019, a data leak occurred on the CapitalGames gaming forum, which affected 645 thousand customers. The breach included email addresses, usernames, IP addresses and passwords stored as MD5 hashes. The site was hacked using the ForumRunner vulnerability. In total, 645 thousand users were affected.

title: VkusnyeSushi
description: On February 26, 2022, a leak occurred on the Russian sushi delivery service vkusnyesushi.ru. 847 thousand users were affected. The leak contained names, phone numbers, addresses, IP, email, shopping lists, payment amounts and other data.

title: Olx.kz
description: In the fall of 2023, scraping from the Kazakh message board Olx appeared on the network. The file contained 390 thousand entries with telephone numbers, names and cities of residence of users.

title: LifeBoat
description: In January 2016, the Lifeboat community dedicated to the game MineCraft was hacked. More than 7 million user accounts have been leaked. The owners of the service knew about the incident three months before the hack became known to the public, but decided not to tell customers anything. The data leak included usernames, emails and passwords as unsalted MD5 hashes.

title: SynergyRegions.ru
description: In November 2019, the Synergy online university suffered from a hack. 450 thousand records with names, phone numbers, emails, residential addresses and information about places of work were made publicly available. There is also a more complete version that also contains passwords, positions and other information removed from the first version.

title: RootKit
description: In February 2011, the hacker forum Rootkit.com was hacked. As a result, about 80 thousand records containing emails, nicknames, full names, IP addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes were leaked into the network.

title: Photographer.ru
description: Photographer is a website dedicated to world photography. It was hacked in 2021, which led to the publication of data on 55 thousand users. The database contains emails, phone numbers, names, addresses, dates of birth, IP and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes.

title: RedDoorz
description: In September 2020, booking platform RedDoorz suffered a data breach. Data from 5.8 million user accounts were exposed. The hacked data included names, email addresses, phone numbers, gender, dates of birth and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes.

title: Promo
description: In July 2020, self-proclaimed "World's No. 1 Marketing Video Producer" Promo suffered a data breach. The incident revealed 22 million records containing nearly 15 million unique email addresses. The database also contained IP addresses, gender, names and SHA-256 password hashes.

title: DeriveSystems.com
description: This company specializes in software development for the automotive industry. At the end of 2020, it suffered a leak that affected 350 thousand users. Emails, IPs, nicknames, dates of birth and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes were compromised.

title: Collection 3
description: In January 2019, 5 collections appeared on a popular hacker forum, representing a combination of data from many other leaks. The third collection was the smallest of all. It contained 20 thousand files with a total size of 37 GB. These files contained about a billion lines with emails, passwords, nicknames and IP addresses. Some of the passwords were hashed. There were only 300 million unique strings.

title: OASISGAMES
description: Around September 2020, OASIS GAMES, "the world's leading game publisher", suffered a data breach. The breach exposed email addresses and passwords stored as MD5 hashes with the static salt “@legend.” In total, 471 thousand users were affected.

title: Larix
description: Larix is ​​a Russian information system containing data of Moscow residents. It has been leaked many times. This database dates back to 2013 and contains 7.3 million people. It includes names, dates of birth, gender and addresses of citizens.

title: Flipkart
description: Around September 2022, Indian shopping site Flipkart experienced a data breach that affected 3.8 million users. The leak revealed full names, email addresses (552 thousand in total), phone numbers and physical addresses.

title: Sjovt.com
description: The website sjovt.com is a platform focused on entertainment and communication. It offers various services, including competitions and communication between users. In 2016, there was a leak that affected half a million users. Nicknames, emails, IP addresses and passwords were published in the form of MD5 hashes.

title: Nvidia
description: In February 2022, chip company NVIDIA suffered a data breach. As a result, employee credentials and proprietary code were exposed. The affected data included more than 70,000 employee email addresses and NTLM password hashes, many of which were subsequently hacked and distributed to the hacker community.

title: MoDaCo
description: Around January 2016, the UK Android MoDaCo community suffered a data breach. As a result, the identities of 880,000 subscribers were revealed. The data included email addresses, IP addresses, usernames and passwords as salted MD5 hashes.

title: VTB
description: In May 2022, information appeared about the leak of phone numbers of users of the Russian VTB bank. The published file contained 17.6 million phones, including 9 million unique ones. There was no other data in the database. Representatives of the bank stated that there was no leak, and the data was collected from a third-party service.

title: ShopBack
description: In September 2020, the ShopBack cashback program suffered a data breach. As a result, more than 20 million unique email addresses were exposed, as well as names, phone numbers, countries of residence and passwords in the form of salted SHA-1 hashes.

title: Miltor
description: Miltor.ru is a Russian bulletin board for the purchase and sale of goods and services. This site was hacked in April 2022. All of its data, including the source code, were made publicly available. 3.7 million users were affected, and the leaked data included emails, phone numbers, names and addresses of users, as well as descriptions of their products.

title: NextGenUpdate
description: In early 2014, video game website NextGenUpdate suffered a data breach that exposed nearly 1.2 million accounts. Among the published data were usernames, email addresses, IP addresses, and passwords in the form of salted hashes.

title: Enbek.kz
description: This is an information portal about employment and employment in Kazakhstan. At the end of 2022, it suffered a leak that affected 2.5 million people. Data published later includes names, emails, telephone numbers, residential addresses, document numbers and job information.

title: Tamodo
description: In February 2020, the Tamodo affiliate marketing network suffered a data leak that was subsequently published on a popular hacker forum. The incident revealed almost 500 thousand accounts including names, email addresses, dates of birth and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes. Tamodo has not responded to multiple attempts to report the hack through its published communication channels.

title: 700k+ Amazon, Paypal, Spotify + more
description: Kombalist, collected from various sites and published in 2022. Contains only emails and passwords. A total of 700,000 lines.

title: Tiktopers.ru
description: In September 2021, the database of the Russian service Tiktopers.ru became publicly available. It provides boost for tiktok and instagram accounts. The database contains 5 thousand records with emails, phone numbers and passwords in the form of SHA-512 hashes with salt.

title: Naumen.ru
description: In 2022, a data leak occurred at the Russian software developer Naumen. Data includes emails and usernames.

title: SportFood40.ru
