description: In July 2023, it became known about a leak of orders from the health food store “SportFood40.ru”. The data contains 77.8 thousand records and includes names, phone numbers, mails, delivery addresses, contents and delivery costs, as well as order dates (from 02/19/2015 to 06/26/2022).

title: FinFive
description: In September 2022, it became known that the Russian microcredit organization FinFive had been hacked. The data contains about 200 thousand records and includes names, phone numbers, emails, dates of birth, passport details, addresses and other information.

title: GamerzPlanet
description: Around October 2015, the online gaming forum Gamerzplanet was hacked. 1.2 million accounts were exposed to public access. The data included emails, IP addresses and passwords in the form of salted MD5 hashes. A weak implementation was used that allowed many passwords to be cracked quickly.

title: 2019 Databases Collection  110 DBS
description: In 2019, a collection of 110 previously hacked sites was published. In total it contains more than 10 million lines. Entries include emails and passwords in plain text.

title: Oschadbank.ua
description: In September 2023, the Ukrainian bank Oschadbank was subject to a hacker attack. As a result, the data of approximately 5 million people became publicly available. They include names, telephone numbers, emails, passport details, places of residence and other information.

title: TheWarinc
description: In mid-2012, the real-time strategy game War Inc suffered a data leak. More than 1 million accounts containing usernames, email addresses, and salted MD5 password hashes were affected. The original leak has disappeared from the public domain and now only 875 lines of emails and decrypted passwords are publicly available.

title: INTERWEBZ
description: In June 2015, the CSGO cheat website INTERWEBZ suffered a data leak that affected 5.2 thousand users. The breach exposed usernames, email addresses, IP addresses and passwords stored as IPB hashes.

title: Artnow.ru
description: In August 2022, a leak occurred on the Russian website for artists “Artnow.ru”. The data of 100 thousand users was made publicly available, including emails, phone numbers, names, cities of residence and passwords in plain text.

title: Rusnod.ru 2022
description: In August 2022, a database dump of the website of the Russian political association rusnod.ru was made publicly available. It contains 200 thousand lines with names, emails, phone numbers, dates of birth and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes without salt. This is the third time this site has been hacked. The past ones occurred in 2016 and 2021.

title: Stoneworks
description: In April 2022, a data leak occurred on the Minecraft Stoneworks server, which affected 63.5 thousand users. The leak revealed UUIDs, usernames and IP addresses.

title: MSPAForums
description: In March 2016, the MSPA Forums webcomic suffered a data leak. The breach included usernames, email addresses, IP addresses and passwords in the form of vBulletin hashes. In total, 180 thousand users were affected.

title: Disqus
description: In October 2017, blog commenting service Disqus announced a leak. The violation dates back to July 2012 but was not detected earlier. The leak contained 17.5 million emails and usernames.

title: SpacetimeStudios
description: In November 2020, a data leak occurred at the Forum of the gaming company Spacetime Studios, affecting 181 thousand participants. The breach included usernames, email addresses and passwords stored as vBulletin hashes. The website was hacked by donjuji. Shortly thereafter, Spacetime Studios filed a report with the FBI and local law enforcement.

title: DNS (2022)
description: On September 19, 2022, a leak occurred on the website dns-shop.ru, affecting 16 million users. It is alleged that it was hacked by the pro-Ukrainian NLB team. Emails, full names and telephone numbers were revealed.

title: DRFO 2018
description: DRFO is the state register of all individuals in Ukraine. In 2018, the registry suffered a leak that exposed 52.7 million entries. The leak includes names, dates of birth and addresses of citizens.

title: BoAtLifestyleIndia
description: BoAt is a large company in India that sells audio-centric electronic gadgets such as wireless speakers, wired and wireless headphones, home audio equipment, cables and a range of other technology accessories. In March 2024, a hacker announced that boAt Lifestyle data had been hacked. The attacker leaked data hack files with access to clients' personal information, which contained 7.5 million records. The data includes emails, names, phone numbers, physical addresses, purchases, and website activity.

title: RosZdravNadzor.gov.ru
description: In 2016, there was a data leak from the Federal Service for Surveillance in Healthcare RosZdravNadzor.gov.ru, affecting more than 475 thousand records. The database contained full names, addresses, mails, tax identification numbers, telephone numbers and passport details.

title: PrivatBank v2
description: In February 2021, it became known about a leak from PrivatBank, the largest bank in Ukraine. Over time, quite a few versions of this leak appeared, differing in content and processing method (the data was initially very littered). This is one such version of the leak, containing about 30 million records.

title: Bonobos
description: In August 2020, clothing store Bonobos suffered a data breach that exposed nearly 70 GB of data containing 2.8 million unique email addresses. The hack also exposed names, physical and IP addresses, phone numbers, order histories, and salted SHA1 hashes of passwords. The hack also exposed partial credit card data, including the card type, name on the card, expiration date and the last 4 digits of the card.

title: Moscow GIBDD 2019
description: In October 2021, a Moscow traffic police database with information about drivers and cars from 2006 to 2019 appeared for sale on the darknet. The leak included about 50 million records containing data on cars - state. number, VIN, make, color, body number, engine number and other data. There was also information about the owner - name, address, passport, date of birth and other data.

title: Chistovie
description: The Russian store chistovie.ru sells disposable consumables for the beauty industry and medicine. In 2022, a database of its users began to spread across the network. It includes 104 thousand entries and contains full names, emails, phone numbers and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: AtlasRSPS
description: Sometime in 2019 or 2020, Runescape Private Server Atlas suffered a data breach that affected 12.9 thousand users. The breach included usernames, email addresses, IP addresses and passwords stored as bcrypt hashes. The site no longer exists and the domain belongs to someone else.

title: DarkPro.net
description: The DarkPro forum used to discuss topics related to carding, cybercrime and hacking, leaked data in March 2023.The incident affected 5 thousand users.Of the useful data in the dump there were only mail and nicknames.

title: SvenskaMagic
description: Sometime in 2015, the Swedish magic website SvenskaMagic was leaked, revealing over 30,000 entries. These included names, email addresses and MD5 password hashes. The public version of the leak does not include usernames.

title: Pochta.02
description: At the end of 2022, Ukrainian hackers hacked Russian mail. Later they published several parts of this leak, this is the second part. It contains 140 thousand lines with names, addresses, telephone numbers, emails and passport data. Some fields also contain SNILS and TIN.

title: Evgexacraft.ru
description: At the beginning of 2016, the then popular Minecraft server EvgexaСraft was hacked. The published database contains emails, names, nicknames, IPs and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes. A total of 338 thousand accounts. Most of the passwords (297 thousand) were immediately hacked and also made publicly available

title: 4cheat.ru
description: 4cheat is a Russian forum dedicated to cheats for games. It was hacked in April 2022. The emails and nicknames of users, as well as their time zones and the number of messages, were made publicly available. A total of 216 thousand records. This site was previously leaked in 2018.

title: 5120.ru
description: In October 2022, the Russian website 5120.ru, which sells electronics parts, was hacked. More than 30 thousand customer records were published, including phone numbers, names, nicknames, emails (one or two), addresses, order amounts and delivery information.

title: El-dent.ru
description: In mid-2024, hackers broke into the dental online store El-dent.ru. The resulting data contained almost 200 thousand rows, including names, phone numbers and addresses.

title: Xbox-scene
description: Around February 2015, the Xbox-Scene forum was hacked, exposing over 432,000 accounts. The forum included emails, names, IP addresses and passwords in the form of salted hashes.

title: HolodForum.ru
description: In 2020, a leak occurred on the Russian refrigerator forum HolodForum, which affected more than 70 thousand users. The leak includes names, emails, IP addresses and passwords as salted MD5 hashes.

title: Osk-Ins.ru
description: In October 2023, the hacker group UHG announced that they had obtained data from the Russian insurance company OSK. The dumps published later contained phone numbers, emails, passport details, dates of birth and car details, as well as passwords in the form of MD5 hashes. In total there are more than a million unique users.

title: Pron
description: Around June 2011, the now-defunct pornography site Pron suffered a data breach. The site was hacked by the hacker collective "LulzSec" as part of the "50 Days of Lulz". The breach included unencrypted email addresses and passwords. Total 25.9 thousand records.

title: BookCrossing
description: In August 2022, the free book club BookCrossing suffered a data breach that affected 1.5 million members. The breach exposed email addresses, usernames, full names, dates of birth, IP addresses and passwords in clear text. The breach occurred because BookCrossing exposed a database backup that was almost 9 years old (January 13, 2013).

title: Mastoner.com
description: Due to a data leak from the Mastoner.com trading platform, which sells components for office equipment, the personal information of more than 33 thousand customers was leaked online. The compromised information included emails, full names, phone numbers, and bcrypt hashed passwords.

title: MuscleNutrition
description: Around September 2022, the Italian online store Muscle Nutrition experienced a data leak that affected 138 thousand users. The breach exposed email addresses, full names, phone numbers, physical addresses and passwords stored as MD5 or Bcrypt hashes. The website was hacked by stdpwn due to incorrect server configuration.

title: Mir-eks.ru
description: In May 2023, the Russian travel agency World of Excursions suffered from a hack. A very large SQL dump was published, in which there were only 800 users. The data contains emails, names, phone numbers, places of work and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: CrackedTO
description: In July 2019, hacker website Cracked.to suffered a data breach. The forum had 749 thousand unique email addresses registered among 321 thousand users. The data also included IP addresses, passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes, personal messages, usernames and other data. A rival hacking website claimed responsibility for the hack.

title: Aipai
description: In September 2016, Chinese gaming website Aipai.com leaked data online. They contained 6.5 million accounts. The data in the breach contains email addresses and MD5 password hashes.

title: Destructoid.com
description: In July 2015, the popular gaming portal Destructoid was hacked. As a result, data about 72 thousand users, including nicknames, emails, IP addresses and passwords in the form of an MD5 hash with salt, became available on the network.

title: MeetMindful
description: At the beginning of 2020, the online dating service MeetMindful suffered from a data leak. 1.4 million unique customer emails were exposed. The data included a vast array of personal information used to find romantic partners. It included address, physical characteristics, alcohol, drug and cigarette use, marital status, dates of birth, gender, IP and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes.

title: VeganAllSorts.com
description: An online store specializing in the sale of vegan sweets suffered a data leak in March 2021. It affected about 100 thousand records, including emails, names, phone numbers and delivery addresses.

title: Adamas
description: In November 2022, a data leak occurred from the Russian jewelry store Adamas. The data included about a million records containing information about 320 thousand customers. Data includes names, dates of birth, emails, phone numbers and order details.

title: Instagram 14.01.2021
description: At the beginning of 2021, the French agency Influentia.fr collected data from Instagram users using parsing. The resulting database contains almost 50 million records and includes all public information from accounts - names, bios, age, language, number of followers and other data.

title: MemeChat
description: In June 2022, the meme-sharing app MemeChat suffered a data breach. The leak only affected usernames and email addresses. In total, 7.4 million users were affected. MemeChat was hacked because they left their ElasticSearch server open to everyone. They've done this several times in the past.

title: Catho
description: Around March 2020, the Brazilian recruitment website Catho was compromised and subsequently appeared along with 20 other hacked websites on the darknet market. The leak included almost 1.1 million records. Plain text usernames and passwords were also exposed.

title: FOMS Sahalin
description: In 2018, information about 360 thousand insured persons was leaked from the database of the Compulsory Health Insurance Fund of the Sakhalin Region. The compromised data contained names, phone numbers, addresses, telephone numbers, dates of birth, medical policy numbers and information about places of work.

title: HelloTravel.com
description: In August 2020, there was a data leak from the website HelloTravel.com, which deals with travel services. Data about 105 thousand users was leaked into the network, including emails, phone numbers, passwords, nicknames and addresses.

title: 8fit
description: In July 2018, the 8fit health and fitness service suffered a leak. The data became available for sale on the darknet market in February 2019. The leak included 15 million unique emails, as well as names, gender, IP and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes.

title: Teespring
description: In April 2020, custom printed clothing website Teespring suffered a data breach. 8.2 million customer records were exposed, including email addresses, names, locations and social media handles.

title: TicketIQ
description: Around March 2016, the TicketIQ website experienced a data breach. The breach exposed email addresses, locations and IP addresses. In total, 15.4 thousand users were affected.

title: Soderganki.ru
description: In October 2024, parsing of the Soderganki.ru resource was released to the public domain. The data contains 70 thousand records with emails, links to profiles and text descriptions.

title: WhatsApp
description: Due to the Facebook hack in 2019, the WhatsApp messenger was also affected. As a result, the phone numbers of all messenger users were published, broken down by country. The leak included more than 500 million records, but after removing duplicates, only 367 million remained.

title: Passat-club.ru
description: This is a Russian club for fans and owners of the Volkswagen Passat. The date of the leak is unknown. The database contains emails, names, IP addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt. A total of 75 thousand records.

title: TalantGold.ru
description: Talant is an online jewelry store specializing in the sale of jewelry from gold and silver.In November 2024, the data of about a thousand customers of this store entered the open score.The leak contains mail, phones, names, customer residence addresses and passwords in the form of Bcrypt Hashi.

title: ExileMod
description: Around August 2016, a data leak occurred on the Exile Mod gaming forum, which affected 80.5 thousand users. The breach included email addresses, usernames, IP addresses and passwords stored as bcrypt and Wordpress hashes.

title: Mamba.ru 8M
description: In 2015, a leak occurred in the dating service Mamba.ru, affecting 12.5 million users. This file is likely only part of the leak, as it includes 8 million records with emails, phone numbers and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes.

title: FaweMC
description: In 2023, a data leak occurred from FaweMC, a Minecraft game server. Information about 50 thousand users was publicly available, including nicknames, IP addresses and passwords in the form of an AuthMe hash.

title: Tcb.com.ua
description: In December 2022, the website providing bus tour services Tcb.com.ua suffered an SQL dump. As a result, about 86 thousand records were made public, including email, full names and phone numbers.

title: Perm-rabota.ru
description: This is a site for finding work in Perm. In 2013, data from it was collected using parsing. A total of 5,400 resumes with phone numbers, names, education data, skills and vacancies for which users submitted resumes.

title: Neznaika.info
description: "Dunno" is a Russian service for preparing for exams. In 2023, it suffered a hack that affected more than two million users. The data includes emails, phone numbers, names, regions, IP, VK pages and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes.

title: OGUsers2021
description: In April 2021, an account hacking and SIM swap forum suffered a data leak. This is already the fourth (!!!) leak on this service since December 2018. The database was subsequently sold on a competing hacker forum and contained usernames, email addresses, IP addresses and passwords as salted MD5 or argon2 hashes. As a result of the hack, 348 thousand unique emails were published.

title: Indian Combolist
description: A combination of data from several leaks that occurred in India. It was published in April 2022 and contains 13 million emails and unencrypted passwords.

title: Atmeltomo.com
description: Atmeltomo is a Japanese site for dating and discussing computer technology. The site suffered a leak in early 2021 that exposed 1.5 million records from its database. The leak contained 580 thousand unique emails and 317 thousand nicknames, as well as passwords in the form of MD5 hashes, IP addresses and other information.

title: JobInMoscow.ru
description: JobInMoscow is a Russian site for finding jobs in Moscow. On October 25, 2022, 170 thousand records were collected from it using parsing. The data included emails, phone numbers, names, ages, and relationship status. This site was previously assembled using parsing at the end of 2019.

title: IP Index
description: This is an inverse index created in April 2024. It allows you to search for all emails and phone numbers associated with a particular IP address. It contains 880 million emails, 200 million phones and 420 million unique IPs. Keep in mind that most IP addresses are dynamic and constantly change from one user to another. To get more information, enter the received emails or phone numbers into the search.

title: Sythe.org
description: An American website that provides services for the exchange of virtual goods and services in online games suffered a data leak in November 2014. As a result, 260 thousand records were published, including nicknames, emails, IP addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: Biletik.Aero
description: A database of the air ticket booking service Biletik.aero was discovered on the Internet, including more than 215 thousand user records. The leak contained full names, email addresses, phone numbers, nicknames and passwords in the form of a salted MD5 hash.

title: 28 600 000 Dump Mail-Pass
description: This is a combination of emails and passwords from various leaks, published in December 2022 on a hacker forum. Contains 28.6 million rows.

title: BreachedForum Combolists
description: Breached.vc is the most famous site for publishing various leaks. This database contains all files from the “Combolists” section, downloaded on 02/22/2023. This section had 2200 databases containing 170GB of data (5 billion rows). After deduplication and removal of rows from the collections, only 770 million remained. The data contains only emails and passwords.

title: Xat
description: In November 2015, the xat.com online chat was hacked. Data from 6 million user accounts were exposed. The leaked data included usernames, email addresses, IP addresses and passwords in the form of digital hashes with an unknown algorithm.

title: Spidermetrix
description: Sometime in 2017, an online survey website known as Spidermetrix suffered a data breach that affected 693 thousand users. The breach included usernames, email addresses and passwords stored unencrypted. This file was originally posted by user "gr4c3ann" on RaidForums. The exact date of the hack is unknown.

title: BabyNames
description: Around 2008, babynames.com, a website that helps parents name their babies, suffered a data breach. 846 thousand email addresses and passwords were published, stored as salted MD5 hashes. The leak became known in October 2018. Baby Names reported that "the hack occurred at least ten years ago" and that members were notified at that time.

title: Undora.ru
description: Undora is a sanatorium in the Ulyanovsk region. In February 2020, I suffered from a hack that affected applications for receiving callbacks on the site. The data contains telephone numbers, specified names and type of contact. There are 4400 records in total.

title: Declaration.com.ua
description: In October 2022, a database obtained from a government website on which declarations of civil servants are published began to be published on hacker forums. However, this is not a leak, since anyone can download this data from the site. The database contains 5.3 million rows, but in fact there are fewer people, since each person has several declarations for different years. The database contains names, region and place of work, as well as a list of relatives. Search by relatives is also available.

title: HKGolden
description: In August 2019, a data leak occurred on the Chinese computer hardware and software forum HKGolden (高登讨论区), which affected 297 thousand users. The attack resulted in the disclosure of data including email addresses, usernames, phone numbers, IP addresses, gender, dates of birth and plain text passwords.

title: Cizimokulu.com
description: A website dedicated to teaching and sharing software experiences, Cizimokulu.com suffered a data breach in early 2021. As a result of the leak, about 319 thousand records containing personal data such as nicknames, passwords, logins and emails were compromised.

title: RealDudesInc
description: This platform resells cheats for various games and suffered a data leak in 2022. The published database contained more than 100 thousand entries, including emails, nicknames and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes.

title: Azino777
description: Azino777 is a Russian casino, remembered for its annoying advertising on the Internet. The date of its hack is unknown, but there is a database of its users online containing 250 thousand entries. This leak includes emails, names and phone numbers of casino clients.

title: DaFont
description: In May 2017, DaFont, a font sharing site, suffered a data leak. This event resulted in the disclosure of 637,000 records. Presumably the hack occurred due to a vulnerability to SQL injections. The exposed data included usernames, email addresses and passwords in unsalted MD5 format.

title: DecoratingTheHouse
description: In March 2020, Korean interior decoration website Decorating the House was affected. The data leak affected almost 1.3 million users. Public data includes email addresses, usernames and phone numbers. The database was subsequently widely distributed among online hacker communities.

title: AtlasQuantum
description: In August 2018, there was a data leak on the Atlas Quantum cryptocurrency investment platform. The hack exposed the personal information of 261,000 investors on the platform, including their names, phone numbers, email addresses and account balances.

title: Ostrov-Shop.by
description: As a result of a network leak of the Belarusian online store “Island of Purity and Taste,” the data of more than 660 thousand users and about 800 thousand order records were compromised, namely full names, phone numbers, emails, addresses, geolocation and passwords in the form of a bcrypt hash.

title: DawnOfTheDragons
description: In July 2016, a data leak occurred on the Dawn of the Dragons forums, affecting 293 thousand participants. The breach exposed usernames, email addresses, IP addresses, dates of birth and passwords as vBulletin hashes. The game was owned by 5th Planet Games and has since been closed.

title: Fotostrana
description: On October 10, 2021, a data leak occurred on the Russian dating site fotostrana.ru. As a result, the data of about 800 thousand users was freely available.  The leak included emails, usernames, hashes, IP and other data.

title: Damoda24.by
description: Damoda24 is a Belarusian clothing store. Suffered from a leak in March 2021, 14 thousand records became publicly available. The data contains emails, names, phone numbers and passwords in the form of SHA1 hashes with salt.

title: SGB.net
description: This is an online store specializing in the sale of building materials. In 2021, a database containing more than 9 million emails and passwords from this site became publicly available. Passwords were in plain text.

title: Cloudata
description: Large collection of email-pass data. The database was collected from many files on May 18, 2023. Initially, all databases weighed 338 GB (11 billion rows). After removing duplicates and data from the collections, about 2 billion remained.

title: TheGymkc.com
description: The website of the fitness club TheGymkc.com suffered from a data leak in 2021, affecting 35 thousand clients. The compromised records contained emails, full names, phone numbers and addresses.

title: AnimeForum.ru
description: In December 2017, a data leak occurred on the Russian anime forum AnimeForum, which affected 132 thousand users. The database included dates of birth, email addresses, IP addresses, languages ​​spoken, usernames, website activity, and MD5 hashed passwords.

title: Pochta.ru
description: In July 2022, the Russian Post database was posted on a hacker forum. It contained 10 million delivery records. They included the names of senders and recipients, addresses, telephone numbers, delivery statuses, package weights and technical data. Campaign representatives denied the leak.

title: Fin-ra.ru
description: In July 2023, the database of the Fin-ra website, which provides investment training, became publicly available. The leak contains more than 300 thousand records with emails, phone numbers, names, information about purchased courses and payment methods.

title: KinoKong
description: In March 2021, there was a data leak on the pirate website KinoKong. The leak exposed data including usernames, email addresses and passwords in the form of Bitrix hashes. In total, 824 thousand users were affected. The vast majority of entries in the database were bots due to the fact that KinoKong does not use captcha on its website.

title: VK 2024
description: This is a parsing of the VKontakte social network made in the summer of 2024. The data contains links to profiles, names, gender and links to user avatars. A total of 390 million records.

title: SofaScore
description: Around July 2021, the football website SofaScore suffered a data leak that affected 262 thousand users. The leak exposed data including email addresses, full names and passwords stored in an unknown format.

title: cBANK
description: In 2022, a private combo player containing 400 million emails and passwords was sold online. There were 260 million unique lines. The Kombolist was sold for $650, but now it is available to everyone. To increase the uniqueness of the data, sellers changed the case of some passwords and diluted the data with generated strings. Despite the title, this collection is not related to the March 2022 central bank leak.

title: Blogigo.com
description: In December 2020, the blogging platform Blogigo suffered a leak. Names, emails, addresses, dates of birth and passwords were published in the form of MD5 hashes without salt. A total of 850 thousand users.

title: GrandExchangeTracker
description: In May 2017, the GE-Tracker.com swiping tool suffered a data leak that affected 42.2 thousand users. The breach exposed usernames, email addresses, phone numbers, Paypal email addresses, and passwords stored as Bcrypt hashes.

title: Quidd
description: Quidd is an online marketplace for trading stickers, cards, toys and other collectibles. In 2019, there was a data leak on it. The hack exposed email addresses, usernames and passwords as bcrypt hashes. Almost 4 million users contributed. The data was subsequently sold and then widely distributed through hacker forums.

title: 8minecraft.ru
description: In November 2013, there was a leak from the Russian Minecraft site 8minecraft. The site had 54 thousand users. The leak affected nicknames, emails, regions of residence, IP addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes without salt.

title: MacForums
description: In July 2016, the self-proclaimed Mac Forums website suffered a data breach. The database contained more than 326 thousand usernames, email addresses, IP addresses, dates of birth and passwords in the form of salted MD5 hashes. It was later discovered that the data was being traded on a popular hacker forum. The forum owners did not respond to the message about the incident.

title: Neo24.pl
description: Neo24 is a Polish online store of household appliances. At the end of 2017, there was a leak on it, affecting 700 thousand users. The published data contains email names, phone numbers and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: Malakye
description: In January 2022, a job seekers website known as Malakye suffered a data breach. The violation included email addresses, full names, phone numbers, physical addresses and professions. In total, 232 thousand users were affected.

title: Bns-club.ru
description: In May 2022, it became known about a leak from the website bns-club.ru, which resells clothing. The database contains 67 thousand users. The data includes phone numbers, emails, names and passwords in the form of sha512crypt hashes.

title: Lenta
description: In February 2020, the Russian hypermarket chain Lenta suffered from a leak. 90 thousand records with personal data of clients, mainly from the Moscow region, were made publicly available. The leak included full names and phone numbers.

title: HeadHunter
description: Around 2018, the Russian job site HeadHunter suffered a data leak that affected 827 thousand users. The violation included professions, salaries, phone numbers, email addresses, Skype usernames, full names and locations.

title: VipOferta.bg
description: In April 2021, it became known that one of the largest Bulgarian tour operators, VIPoferta, had been hacked. Hackers published data of about 350 thousand clients, including Email, phone numbers, names, IP addresses and passwords in the form of an MD5 hash.

title: Pharmaceutics 2023
description: In 2023, there was a leak from an unknown Russian pharmaceutical company. As a result, several dozen client files containing names, phone numbers, regions of residence and passport information became publicly available. There are 3.6 million rows in total, but the actual number of people in the leak is less because there were multiple entries per person in different files.

title: FSSP 2020 (100M)
description: One of the biggest leaks from the Federal Bailiff Service. Dating back to 2020, it contains approximately 100 million records. Also this year there was a more modest leak - 17 million lines. The data contains names, addresses, INN, amount of debt, information about collectors and other information.

title: Tout.com
description: On September 11, 2014, the Tout.com website, which provides “mobile video recorder” services for journalists, was hacked. The stolen database contains emails, phone numbers, IP addresses and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes. A total of 790 thousand records.

title: JapanCar.ru
description: This is a board of ads for the sale of cars and spare parts for them.In November 2024, data from it were collected using Parsing.About 50 thousand ads were collected, the data contain the names of sellers, the name of the goods and from 1 to 4 Nomers of Teleffons.

title: ABFRL
description: In December 2021, Indian retailer Aditya Birla Fashion and Retail Ltd was hacked and offered a ransom. The ransom demand was rejected and the data was released the following month. They contained 5.4 million customer and employee records, including names, phone numbers, physical addresses, dates of birth, order histories and MD5 hashed passwords.

title: Zaymer.ru
description: This is one of many Russian microfinance organizations. In March 2024, it became known that several of them were hacked at once. 16.8 million user records were stolen from this particular site. The data contains names, telephone numbers, addresses, passport details, dates of birth, tax identification number and other information. The hackers tried to get a ransom from the company, but after being refused, they made all the data publicly available.

title: AgusiQTorrents
description: In September 2019, a data leak occurred on the Polish torrent site AgusiQ-Torrents.pl. The incident revealed records of 90,000 participants, which included email addresses and IP addresses, usernames and passwords stored as MD5 hashes.

title: CallOfGods 2017
description: The gaming community CallOfGods was the victim of a hacker attack in 2017. As a result, more than 640 thousand accounts were exposed, including nicknames, emails, IP addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: Pik-arenda.ru
description: In September 2022, a leak occurred in the Russian real estate agency Pik-arenda. The data contains 150 thousand records and includes telephone numbers, emails, names, dates of birth, addresses, apartment data, payment information, IP addresses, INN, passport data and other information.

title: 1cont.ru
description: At the beginning of 2020, the Aktion counterparty verification service (1cont.ru) suffered from a hack. A database containing data of 1.5 million people was published. The database contains names, emails, addresses, company names and from one to five telephone numbers for each user.

title: HonestinSite.com
description: In July 2020, a database of the Honest Insite web resource dedicated to marketing topics was published. It contains about 150 thousand records, including full names, emails, telephone numbers, residential addresses, data on relationship status, presence of children and income, as well as passwords in plain text.

title: BlankMediaGames
description: In December 2018, the Town of Salem website created by BlankMediaGames suffered a data breach. The data contained 7.6 million unique email addresses. Also in the leak were names, IP addresses, purchase histories and passwords in the form of phpass hashes. BlankMediaGames has not responded to multiple attempts to contact regarding the incident.

title: Akc.org
description: The canine portal American Kennel Club, which publishes materials about dog breeds, their education and participation in exhibitions, leaked a user database with information about 595 thousand community members in 2016. The data included emails, registration dates, and last activity dates. There was no other information in the leak.

title: Turniketov.net
description: On June 16, 2022, a leak occurred from the Russian website “Day Without Turnstiles” (turniketov.net). The published site included names, phone numbers, emails, dates of birth, passport details and places of work/study. In total, the database contains 146 thousand rows.

title: Job.Ws
description: In April 2022, the domain rental website Job.ws was hacked. As a result, information about 204 thousand users, including emails and passwords, got into the network.

title: 8teenxxx.com
description: At the end of 2020, the website 8teenxxx.com, which provides access to adult content, suffered a data leak. The data of 68 thousand users was made publicly available. The data only includes emails and passwords in plain text.

title: SilkRoadOnline.net
description: In 2012, the online empire-building game Silkroad Online was hacked, affecting approximately 4 million users. Please note that the files contain 11 million lines, this is due to the fact that a new line was created every time the user played on a new server. The data contains usernames, email addresses, game information and passwords in plain text.

title: SonicBids
description: In December 2019, booking site Sonicbids suffered a data breach that they attributed to “third-party cloud hosting services.” The breach contained 752 thousand user records that included names, email addresses and passwords in the form of PBKDF2 hashes.

title: AppleInsider
description: In 2021, a partial data dump from an online publication about Apple products, AppleInsider, was made publicly available. The leak affected 890 thousand registered users. The database contained data such as emails, full names, nicknames, IP addresses, as well as passwords in the form of MD5 hashes and text comments from clients.

title: Pay System
description: Around May 2022, the Russian payment system PaySystem suffered a data leak that affected 16.1 million users. The attack resulted in the disclosure of email addresses and payment information.

title: OnlineTours.ru
description: In August 2021, a CSV file with personal data of clients of the online travel store onlinetours.ru became publicly available. The data contains 85 thousand rows. Records include name, date of birth, passport details, mail, phone numbers and details of purchased trips.

title: RaidForum
description: RaidForum is the largest hacker forum, operating since 2015, where leaks and hacking methods were traded and exchanged. This forum was closed on April 12, 2022 after the arrest of its creator. Shortly before this, the data of all forum users was collected using parsing. The resulting file includes 572,000 people and contains nicknames, titles, number of posts and other public information.

title: Rttax.com
description: In June 2021, there was a leak on the Rttax website, which provides legal advice on taxes. The leak contains 2.6 million records with phone numbers, names, emails and other data.

title: Exactis
description: In June 2018, marketing firm Exactis accidentally published 340 million personal data records. The leak contains several terabytes spread across hundreds of individual fields and contains 132 million emails.

title: GemplexTV
description: In February 2021, Indian streaming platform Gemplex suffered a data breach that affected 4.6 million users. The breach exposed full names, phone numbers, email addresses, devices, dates of birth and passwords in the form of Bcrypt hashes.

title: VapePartsMart
description: In June 2022, the online vape store VapePartsMart suffered a data leak that affected 140 thousand users. The breach included full names, usernames, email addresses, physical addresses, IP addresses, phone numbers, and MD5 hashed passwords (Wordpress).

title: NL International
description: At the end of 2022, the database of the network marketing company NL International became publicly available. The published files contained data on 13 million users. The data dump was received on October 31, 2022. The leak contained emails, full names, addresses, dates of birth, education, passport information, places of work and passwords. Some passwords are in plain text. Some are in the form of SHA-1 hashes.

title: Poshmark
description: In mid-2018, social commerce marketplace Poshmark suffered a data breach that exposed the accounts of 36 million users. The data included email addresses, usernames, gender, location, and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes.

title: Live4fun.ru
description: Live4fun is a Russian entertainment site. At the beginning of 2021, it suffered from a leak that affected more than 300 thousand users. The data includes nicknames, emails, balance data and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes.

title: KillBillet.com
description: A forum dedicated to car culture and Rat Rods modifications was the victim of a hack in July 2020. As a result, a database with data of 120 thousand users became available, including nicknames, emails, IP addresses, profile information and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: Kassy.ru
description: On April 10, 2023, hackers put the Kassy.ru user database up for sale. This is a Russian aggregator of tickets for various events. After this, the site was temporarily closed to fix the vulnerability. The leak contains 16 million rows in the user and order tables. They include nicknames, full names, phones, cities, emails, dates of birth and MD5 password hashes.

title: Acne.org
description: This is a site dedicated to skin problems. It was hacked at the end of 2014. About 700 thousand records with emails, nicknames, IPs, dates of birth and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt were made publicly available.

title: Mintrud.gov.ru
description: In February 2023, the database of employees of the Ministry of Labor of the Russian Federation became publicly available. The leak contains emails, names, phone numbers, addresses, positions and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt. A Ukrainian hacker group was behind the hack.

title: WeHeartIt
description: In November 2013, the image-based social network We Heart It suffered a data breach. The incident was not discovered until October 2017. The leak contains 8.6 million user records. The data contained usernames, email addresses, and password hashes, 80% of which were SHA-256 with a salt, and the rest were MD5 without a salt.

title: DariPoluchayBot
description: “Dari Receive” is a telegram bot, which is a regular financial pyramid. In 2023, all data of its users became publicly available. The published file contains telephone numbers, names, nicknames and IDs of telegram accounts. A total of 555 thousand people.

title: Nostroy.ru
description: This is the Russian national register of specialists in the field of construction. It was hacked in February 2020, which led to data leakage of 315 thousand users. Phone numbers, names, addresses, positions, insurance information and tax identification numbers were compromised.

title: Foms Rostov 2008
description: MHIF - Compulsory Health Insurance Fund. It has suffered from leaks dozens of times and there are many databases on the network obtained from this service. Most often they are broken down by city, for example, this leak occurred in Rostov in 2008. The data contains names, addresses, dates of birth and passport details of city residents. There are 3 million records in total.

title: FreeGen.pw
description: FreeGen is a now-defunct service that used to allow you to create premium accounts on various sites such as Netflix, Spotify, PornHub and others. In fact, the site simply resold other people's previously hacked accounts to its customers. But in May 2020, he himself suffered from a hack. The data of 7 thousand users was published - emails, nicknames, IP addresses and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes, as well as authorization data of all accounts for sale in the form of emails and passwords in clear text. There are about 330 thousand such records in total.

title: NeoPets
description: In May 2016, a dataset from virtual pet website Neopets leaked online. The data contains dates of birth, IP, gender and names, as well as almost 27 million emails. Passwords were stored in plain text.

title: BBNT.ru
description: In March 2023, bbnt.ru BBNT business social network was hacked.80 thousand users were injured, names, mail, telephones, companies and passwords in the form of Hashi MD5 with salt were published.

title: SumoTorrent
description: In April 2016, the SumoTorrent platform, designed for sharing torrent files and downloading content via P2P networks, became a victim of hacking. As a result, 293 thousand records were compromised, namely emails, nicknames, IP addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes. The site was previously hacked in the summer of 2014, when 285 thousand accounts were affected.

title: DontCraft
description: This Minecraft server was hacked at the end of 2016. 240 thousand records were made publicly available, including nicknames, IP addresses and passwords in the form of AuthMe hashes.

title: ATT
description: AT&T is the largest American telecommunications company. In 2021, their services were hacked, but the database became publicly available only in March 2024. The leak contains more than 70 million records and includes the emails, names, phone numbers, addresses and insurance numbers of all customers.

title: Rybak96.com
description: The Russian fishing online store Rybak96 was hacked in March 2023. As a result, 208 thousand records were made publicly available, including data such as names, emails, telephone numbers, addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes.

title: Jusan.kz
description: One of the largest banks in Kazakhstan recorded a data leak in 2023. As a result, more than 30 thousand records appeared on the Internet, including full names, addresses, dates of birth and telephone numbers.

title: FSSP 2022 (small base)
description: In Russia there is the “Federal Bailiff Service” (FSSP). It suffered two leaks in 2022, the smaller of which contained 8.4 million records relating to legal entities. They include names, addresses, INN, amount of debt, information about collectors and other data. Earlier, in 2021, this service also suffered from a major leak of 87 million records. In total, 5 leaks from the FSSP service are known.

title: Flado.ru
description: In November 2024, the Russian pretext of advertising Flado was subjected to Parsing.About 50 thousand entries with names, phones and information from ads were collected.

title: EngrenagemVirtual
description: In July 2020, the Brazilian marketing agency Engrenagem Virtual suffered a data leak that affected 430 thousand records. The leak revealed email addresses, full names, dates of birth, gender, marital status and phone numbers. After the hack, the website was taken down.

title: QuickJump
description: In July 2016, a data leak occurred on the gaming news forum QuickJump (QJ.net). The breach exposed email addresses, usernames, dates of birth, IP addresses and passwords stored as vBulletin hashes. In total, 334 thousand users were affected.

title: K9irk.ru
description: At the beginning of 2024, an SQL dump appeared in the public domain, allegedly obtained from the website of the K-9 dog kennel, located in Irkutsk. The data contains 18.4 thousand records with emails, nicknames, dates of birth, places of work and passwords in the form of hashes with salt.

title: DateHotBrunettes
description: DateHotBrunettes is a dating network for fantasy brunettes. Around January 2021, it suffered a data breach that affected more than a million users. The hack data contains email addresses, usernames, full names, IP addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes.

title: Otzyvy.pro
description: In January 2022, the review publishing site Otzyvy.pro suffered a data leak. Records of 338 thousand users were leaked into the network, including emails, full names, phone numbers, IP addresses, nicknames and passwords in the form of an MD5 hash.

title: Pokemon Negro
description: Around October 2016, the Spanish pokemon website "Pokemon Negro" suffered a data breach. As a result of the attack, 830,000 accounts were exposed. Data includes email addresses, IP addresses and unencrypted passwords. Pokemon Negro did not respond to the message about the hack.

title: FlexBooker
description: In December 2021, the online booking service FlexBooker suffered a leak that exposed 37 million accounts - emails, names, phone numbers, password hashes and credit card details.

title: CityMobil drivers
description: In 2022, there was a data leak from the Russian taxi ordering service Citymobil. The leak affected 3.9 million service clients and 83 thousand drivers. This database contains drivers' telephone numbers. There is also a separate database in which photographs of passports and IDs of service workers were published.

title: Xsplit
description: In November 2013, the creators of the game streaming and recording software XSplit were compromised in an online attack. The data breach exposed nearly 3 million names, email addresses and hashed passwords.

title: m-vanna.ru
description: In September 2021, a Russian website selling bathtubs was hacked. The leak contains 11 thousand users and 11 thousand of their orders. The data includes phone numbers, names, emails, addresses, IPs, passwords in the form of MD5 hashes, and the user's shopping list.

title: Exotiks.ru
description: Exotiks is a Russian store of carnivorous plants. It suffered a hack at the end of February 2023. 7.6 thousand users and 16.7 thousand of their orders were published. The data contains phones, names, emails, IP and passwords in the form of SHA1+Salt hashes, as well as all information about customer purchases.

title: DeliveryClub Couriers
description: In 2022, the database of all couriers leaked from the food delivery service DeliveryClub. The published database contained 520 thousand rows, but only 140 thousand of them were unique. The data contained the names, emails and telephone numbers of couriers.

title: Shein
description: In June 2018, the online fashion store SHEIN suffered a data leak. The company reported the leak 3 months later. As a result of the hack, hackers obtained 39 million unique email addresses and MD5 password hashes. 29 million emails and decrypted passwords to them were made publicly available.

title: Warframe
description: In November 2014, the online game Warframe was hacked and 819 thousand users were compromised. Presumably, the hack was committed through SQL injection. The attack exposed usernames, email addresses, and data in the "pass" column, which matches the salted SHA12 password hashing pattern used by Drupal 7. However, Warframe developers claim that salted hashes represent "aliases" and not passwords.

title: Wendy
description: In March 2018, Wendy's, a fast food restaurant chain in the Philippines, suffered a data breach. This affected more than 52,000 clients and job seekers. The hack exposed extensive personal information including names, email addresses, IP addresses, physical addresses, phone numbers and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes.

title: ElvineLoL
description: In February 2016, a data leak occurred on the Elvinelol forum dedicated to WoW, as a result of which 10.7 thousand members were affected. The breach exposed email addresses, IP addresses, usernames and passwords as vBulletin hashes.

title: Nafham
description: Around November 2021, Egyptian learning platform Nafham Education suffered a data breach that affected 416 thousand users. The breach included email addresses, full names and passwords as bcrypt hashes.

title: Libex.ru
description: In April 2024, tables with data from users and their orders obtained from the Libex website, an online store for buying and selling books, became publicly available. The data contains 117 thousand users and 830 thousand of their orders, including names, phone numbers, mails, residential addresses, IP, payment data and other information.

title: AptekaNevis.ru
description: On August 25, 2024, this Russian pharmacy chain was hacked. As a result, the tables of users (82 thousand records) and orders (143 thousand records) became publicly available. The data includes telephone numbers, mails, cities of residence and addresses of pharmacies used by clients.

title: LifeOfPix.com
description: A website that provides free photos for commercial and non-commercial use, LifeOfPix.com, has suffered a data breach. It affected about 175 thousand records, including emails, passwords and nicknames.

title: Wm-help.net
description: The site “To Help the Webmaster” contains articles about programming and marketing, as well as a service board. In early 2024, data from this service board was collected using scraping. The published database contains telephone numbers, addresses and names of companies/websites. There are 135 thousand records in total, each of them contains from 1-3 phone numbers, and therefore the number of numbers exceeds 200 thousand.

title: TvoyDom
description: On June 6, 2023, the hacker group NLB published the database of the Russian hypermarket “Your House”. The database includes 675 thousand records containing emails, names, phone numbers, passwords, addresses, dates of birth and other customer data. Passwords are stored as salted MD5 hashes.

title: Filmai.in
description: Around 2019 or 2020, Lithuanian movie streaming service Filmai.in suffered a data breach that exposed 645,000 email addresses, usernames and text passwords.

title: Oriflame.ru
description: Around September 2021, a data leak occurred at the cosmetics company Oriflame.ru. The data of Russian users was made publicly available, and a total of 5.5 million people were affected. The data included emails, names, phone numbers, addresses, dates of birth, PIN codes and credit card limits and other data. The company was fined 30 thousand rubles.

title: Cristalix.ru
description: At the end of 2016, a server for the game MineCraft called Cristalix.ru was hacked. The leak contained 72,800 records, including emails, nicknames and salted SHA1 passwords. Later, in 2019, another leak occurred, but this time on the mobile version of this server.

title: BTC-Alpha
description: In November 2021, the BTC-Alpha crypto exchange platform suffered a data leak as a result of a ransomware attack, after which customer data was published. The data included 362 thousand email and IP addresses, as well as usernames and passwords in the form of PBKDF2 hashes.

title: K7Maths
description: In October 2019, Australian maths education service K7Maths suffered a data breach that affected approximately one million users. The breach exposed full names, email addresses, educational institutions and passwords stored as Bcrypt hashes.

title: TorrentLeech
description: In November 2020, a data leak occurred on the TorrentLeech torrent platform, which affected 555 thousand participants. The attack exposed email addresses (encrypted and unreadable), usernames, and IP addresses. The data also contains "PassKeys", which are similar to MD5 hashes, but are not passwords.

title: 3 000 000 Usa Dump
description: This is a combination of emails and passwords from leaks in the United States, published in December 2022 on a hacker forum. Contains 3 million lines.

title: DashHacks.com
description: In May 2016, the DashHacks website, which published news about games and their modifications, suffered a data leak in 2016. A database containing more than 450 thousand records, including emails, nicknames, IP addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes, was leaked online.

title: Thanhhoafc.vn
description: This is a Vietnamese bookmaker site. It was hacked in November 2019. The published leak contains 340 thousand records with emails, nicknames, IP addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: Acuity
description: In 2019, the insurance company Acuity suffered a data breach. Because of it, the data of 242 million users was exposed. The data was published on raid forums by Crazyoldfart in 2021. The database contains household information and personal information about US citizens. Including full names, addresses, phone numbers, occupation, ethnicity and more. The leak did not contain any emails.

title: Gosuslugi 2021
description: This is a major leak of a Russian government services website that occurred in 2021. It affected more than 7 million people. The data includes telephone numbers, names, mails, addresses, passport data, SNIS data and INN.

title: E-mail base for free MIX
description: A set of several dozen databases published in one of the telegram channels one at a time throughout 2022. Contains 62 million mails. Approximately 5 million of them are accompanied by simple text passwords.

title: Superhry
description: In December 2021, the Czech Gaming Superhry website suffered a data breach that affected 528 thousand users. The breach exposed usernames, email addresses, IP addresses, gender and passwords stored in plain text.

title: RusDosug
description: This is a Russian escort site. In 2021, profile data from this site was collected using parsing. A total of 8600 entries with phone numbers, nicknames, addresses and other data.

title: AshleyMadison
description: In July 2015, adultery website Ashley Madison suffered a major data breach. The attackers threatened the site with complete disclosure of the database if the service was not closed. The database contained over 30 million unique email addresses and detailed user data. However, in the public domain there is only a greatly reduced version of the database, containing only names and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes.

title: Tyaga.com.ua
description: This is a Ukrainian site that sells various radio-controlled toys. At the end of 2024, the site was hacked and a database of 6 thousand orders containing phone numbers, emails and purchase amounts was made publicly available. The site was previously hacked in February 2023.

title: CallOfGods 2016
description: At the end of 2016, the forum of the gaming site Call of Gods suffered from a data leak that affected 640 thousand participants. The leak exposed email addresses, usernames, IP addresses and passwords stored as vBulletin hashes.

title: Aerobus
description: Aerobus.rf is a Russian website that sells bus tickets to and from the airport. In May 2024, there was a leak on it, due to which data about 3,000 users and 60 thousand of their orders were published. The data contains names, phone numbers, emails, IP, passwords in the form of SHA1 hashes with salt and information about payment methods.

title: Resh.Edu
description: In June 2023, the database of users of the educational platform “Russian Electronic School” (resh.edu.ru) became publicly available. The published file contains 9.1 million records, including emails, names, phone numbers and passwords in the form of hashes, information about the educational institution and other information. The data was likely received in December 2022.

title: Westwing.ru
description: In November 2019, a dump of the online store “Westwing”, which sells designer items, appeared for sale on shadow forums. The published database contains information about clients, including emails, names, phone numbers, addresses, passwords in the form of MD5 hashes and Facebook accounts. There are only 1.5 million unique clients, but due to the fact that there are several tables in the database, the total number of rows exceeds 3.3 million.

title: Epik
description: In September 2021, domain registrar and web hosting company Epik suffered a data breach, allegedly in retaliation for hosting alt-right websites. The leak exposed a huge amount of data not only from Epik customers, but also exposed WHOIS records belonging to individuals and organizations that were not Epik customers. The data contained 15 million email addresses, names, phone numbers, physical addresses, purchases and passwords in various formats.

title: MobileLegends
description: In May 2022, a data leak occurred on the Mobile Legends: Bang Bang gaming forum. The attack exposed usernames, email addresses, gender and IP addresses. In total, 289 thousand users were affected.

title: AlpineReplay
description: In August 2019, AlpineReplay, a sports tracking app available on Android and iOS, suffered a data breach that affected 988,000 user records. The breach included usernames, full names, email addresses, gender, dates of birth, favorite sport information and passwords stored as bcrypt hashes.

title: UTair
description: At the end of March 2019, the Russian airline UTair suffered a data leak that affected 519 thousand passengers. The leak revealed full names, email addresses, phone numbers, dates of birth and physical addresses.

title: PharmaCosmetica
description: In October 2023, it became known about a leak from the Russian cosmetics store PharmaCosmetica. The data of 800 thousand customers and 1.8 million orders made by them were published. The data contains names, emails, phone numbers, addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes without salt. The orders table also contains delivery addresses and lists of purchased goods. This site had already been hacked a year before. There are less than 100 thousand records in the public domain.

title: HongFire
description: In March 2015, the anime and manga forum HongFire suffered a data leak. The hack resulted in the exposure of 1 million accounts along with email addresses, IP addresses, usernames, dates of birth and salted MD5 passwords.

title: urok.1c.ru
description: At the beginning of 2023, the Russian website with educational materials urok.1c suffered from hacking. 190 thousand users were affected. The data contains emails, names, phone numbers and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes.

title: IndoMoneyTalk.com
description: The now defunct Indonesian business forum IndoMoneyTalk was hacked in November 2019. 23 thousand users were affected. IP addresses, email addresses, usernames and passwords were published as salted MD5 hashes.

title: TrueFire
description: In February 2020, the guitar training website TrueFire suffered a data breach. It affected 600,000 participants. The hack exposed extensive personal information including names, email addresses, physical addresses, account balances and unsalted MD5 password hashes.

title: Asdap.ru
description: This is a Russian cargo transportation portal. Using parsing, 67 thousand records were collected from it. Data includes names, phone numbers, job titles and company names.

title: Design2u.ru
description: The website Design2u.ru, dedicated to design and creative services, suffered from a data leak in early 2021. Information about 41 thousand users was compromised, including emails, full names, phone numbers, nicknames and passwords in the form of an MD5 hash with salt.

title: StarTribune
description: In October 2019, Minnesota-based news service StarTribune leaked data that was subsequently sold on the dark web. The hack exposed the data of more than 2 million people. These included emails, names, physical addresses, dates of birth, gender, and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes.

title: CafeMom
description: In 2014, CafeMom, a social network for mothers, suffered a data leak. The data appeared along with a number of other leaks and contained 2.6 million email addresses and passwords in plain text.

title: Twitter 200M
description: In January 2022, a vulnerability in the Twitter platform allowed a hacker to create a database of emails and phone numbers of 200 million users of the social platform. In August 2022, Twitter reported that the vulnerability was related to a bug introduced in June 2021. The data included emails, phone numbers, username, biography, location and profile photo.

title: CitiLab
description: At the end of spring 2023, it became known that data from the CITILAB clinical diagnostic laboratories had been leaked. Many documents and analysis results were published, as well as a complete user database dated 09/11/2023. It contains 350 thousand records with names, phone numbers, emails, addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes.

title: 404035.ru
description: 404035 - delivery service in Almetyevsk. On September 27, 2021, it suffered from a data leak. 14 thousand user records and 100 thousand of their orders were published. The database contains names, phone numbers, delivery addresses and comments on orders.

title: Sony
description: In 2011, Sony suffered from multiple cybersecurity breaches. Using SQL injection on the website sonypictures.com, 37 thousand accounts on various systems were hacked. Data included dates of birth, email addresses, gender, names, passwords, phone numbers, physical addresses, and usernames.

title: Klub31.ru
description: Klub31 is a Russian service for renting establishments. In 2023, 767 thousand records with data from its users appeared in the public domain. The database included only emails and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes. The date of the leak is unknown.

title: Brazzers
description: In April 2013, the adult site known as Brazzers was hacked and the data of 790 thousand accounts became public. The records contained usernames, email addresses and passwords in plain text. The hack was discovered in September 2016.

title: GreenLoft.ru
description: In September 2022, the Russian online store for home goods Greenloft was hacked. 83 thousand records containing names, surnames, emails and phone numbers of clients were made available to the public.

title: Bitmax
description: In November 2018, Bitmax.io, BTMX's own trading platform, suffered a data breach that compromised the personal information of 160,000 of its users. Data included first names, last names, email addresses, IP addresses, ID/passport numbers, and geographic locations.

title: MySpace
description: Around 2008, MySpace suffered a data breach that exposed nearly 360 million accounts. In May 2016, the data was offered for sale on the dark market website "Real Deal" and included email addresses, usernames, and SHA1 hashes of the first 10 characters of the password, converted to lowercase and stored without salt. The exact date of the hack is unknown.

title: Knuddels
description: In September 2018, the German social network Knuddels was leaked. 808 thousand unique emails were identified, as well as nicknames, real names, the person’s city and password in plain text.

title: WineLab
description: In July 2024, the WineLab alcohol market was hacked, causing more than 400 thousand user records to become publicly available. The data contains phone numbers, names, emails and other data.

title: Peatix
description: In January 2019, event management platform Peatix suffered a data breach. As a result of the incident, 4.2 million email addresses, names and salted password hashes were exposed.

title: Justdial
description: In April 2019, the Indian search engine JustDial compromised the information of more than 100 million people due to a serious security breach. Usernames, emails, phone numbers, gender, addresses, photographs, job information, occupation, and search query history were available from the search engine database via a URL. According to researchers, the vulnerability has existed since mid-2015.

title: Ixigo
description: In January 2019, the travel and hotel booking website ixigo suffered a leak. The data appeared for sale on the darknet market the following month and included more than 17 million unique email addresses. They also contained names, gender, telephone numbers, connections to Facebook profiles and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes.

title: Mknc.ru
description: In July 2023, the Moscow Clinical Research Center, on whose website you can make an appointment with a doctor, suffered from a data leak. The leak contains 240 thousand records with names, phone numbers, emails, addresses, dates of birth and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes.

title: Xbox360 ISO
description: Around September 2015, the XBOX360 ISO forum was hacked and 1.2 million accounts were exposed. Email addresses, IP addresses, and salted MD5 password hashes were compromised.

title: Trello
description: Trello is a cloud service for managing teams and projects. At the beginning of 2024, a database of this service containing more than 15 million users was posted on one of the forums. The data includes full name, email, nicknames of users and links to their profiles. The data was probably obtained through scraping.

title: ProSushi.ru
description: On March 25, 2023, hackers from the Ukrainian Hacker Group hacked a large Japanese restaurant, ProSushi.ru. The leak contains 165 thousand records of clients and 260 thousand records of their orders. Names, phone numbers, dates of birth, delivery addresses, IP addresses, comments on orders, and passwords in the form of BCrypt hashes were compromised.

title: Art-talant.org
description: On September 15, 2024, the Art-Talent website, where users can participate in various competitions, festivals, and other cultural projects aimed at developing creative abilities, was hacked. The database contains 480 thousand unique lines with emails, names, places of work and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt. The site had previously been hacked in November 2022, but then the amount of data affected was much higher.

title: Voen-torg.ru
description: At the end of 2022, a list of buyers and orders from the Russian online store “Ataka” (voen-torg.ru), which sells military goods, became publicly available. The data contains 36 thousand users and 55 thousand orders. Names, phone numbers, emails, addresses and passwords in the form of bcrypt and MD5 hashes with salt.

title: DealMed.ru
description: At the beginning of June 2024, the database of the Russian medical store DealMed became publicly available. The data contains 81 thousand records with names, phone numbers, addresses of client organizations, emails and other information.

title: Facebook
description: In April 2021, data on more than 500 million Facebook users became available for free download. The data was obtained by exploiting a vulnerability fixed in August 2019. Every entry included a telephone, but only 2.5 million contained email. The records also contained names, gender, dates of birth, location, relationship status and employer.

title: CallCenter OTP Bank
description: In 2014, OTP Bank was hacked. Among other data, a history of calls to their clients with an offer to issue a credit card was published. This database contains names, addresses, 2-3 phone numbers and call results. In total, the database contains 260 thousand rows.

title: SkyEng
description: In June 2020, the data of 5 million students of the SkyEng foreign language school appeared for sale on the darknet. The base was sold for 40 thousand rubles. Data included emails, telephone numbers, full names, gender, dates of birth and regions of residence. A few years later, the database became publicly available.

title: CDEK
description: At the beginning of 2022, the “IT Army” group, whose stated goal is to “de-anonymize Russian users,” posted more than 30 GB of data from the Russian courier service SDEK, including mail and telephone numbers.

title: BotofLegends.com
description: In November 2014, a data leak occurred on the Bot of Legends forum. The IP.Board forum contained 238 thousand accounts, including usernames, emails, IP addresses and passwords, stored as salted MD5 hashes.

title: Domain Index
description: This is an inverse index created in April 2024. It allows you to search for all emails that have a specific domain. This index contains 96 million unique domains and 500 million emails for which they were used. There are no domains in the index that appeared more than 200 times. Enter the received emails into the search to get more information.

title: PoliceOne
description: In February 2017, the law enforcement website PoliceOne was hacked, they confirmed the data leak of 700,000 accounts, including email addresses, IPs, usernames and salted MD5 password hashes.

title: HomeChef
description: In early 2020, food delivery service Home Chef suffered a leak and was subsequently sold online. The hack exposed the information of 9 million customers, including names, IPs, zip codes, last 4 digits of credit cards and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes.

title: Aternos
description: In December 2015, the Aternos service, which allows you to create and run free Minecraft servers, suffered a data leak that affected 1.4 million subscribers. The data included usernames, email addresses, IP addresses and also hashed and salted passwords. The non-standard formula MD5(SHA1(SALT)MD5(PLAIN)) was used.

title: Snail
description: In March 2015, the gaming website Snail suffered a data breach. It affected 1.4 million subscribers. The data included usernames, IP addresses, email addresses, and passwords as unsalted MD5 hashes.

title: CdekMarket
description: In August 2022, Ukrainian hackers posted a continuation of the sensational leaks of SDEKA, a Russian delivery service. They published data from the CDEK.Shopping and CDEK.Market services, containing names, phone numbers, dates of birth and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt. The leaked CDEK.Market contains 87 thousand users, and CDEK.Shopping - 20 thousand.

title: SpkNano.ru
description: In May 2022, the Spknano website, which assesses the qualifications of workers, was hacked. The data contains about two thousand records with emails, names, nicknames, place of work and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: Audi
description: In August 2019, Audi suffered a data breach after the manufacturer left data unprotected and posted it online. The data contained 2.7 million unique email addresses, names, phone numbers, physical addresses and vehicle information including VIN. Some customers' driver's licenses, dates of birth, Social Security numbers and other personal information were exposed.

title: Beer Of Siberia
description: A site dedicated to beer produced in Siberia. It suffered a data leak containing 56 thousand users. Full names, phone numbers and dates of birth were compromised.

title: OnRPG
description: In July 2016, online video game discussion platform OnRPG suffered a data breach. The breach included usernames, email addresses, IP addresses and passwords stored as vBulletin hashes. In total, 1 million users were affected.

title: Phoenix-plus.ru
description: At the beginning of 2023, the Russian stationery store Phoenix Plus suffered from a data leak. 2300 users were affected. The data contains emails, phone numbers, names, number of orders and their amount.

title: Maxxi-cafe.ru
description: Maxxi-cafe - pizza and rolls delivery service in Kursk. The leak occurred on April 24, 2022. The data contains 62 thousand records - phone numbers, names, addresses, IP and delivery comments.

title: CashCrate
description: In June 2017, it became known that the CashCrate survey site was leaked and 68 million records were exposed. Names, physical addresses, emails and passwords stored in clear text or MD5 have been disclosed.

title: CurteaVeche.ro
description: CurteaVeche is a Romanian publishing house that produces books and magazines. In March 2021, their website was attacked, which led to the leak of 120 thousand user records. The data contained emails, names, IP addresses, phone numbers and passwords in the form of SHA1 hashes with salt.

title: PatrolPolice.ua
description: This is a database of calls to hotline 102 in Ukraine. Contains data from 2014-2016, about 6 million hits in total. The data includes phone numbers, names, dates of birth, dates of contact and police departments that received the call.

title: Utmagazine.ru
description: UtMagazine is a Russian investment platform. It was hacked in April 2019. Emails, phone numbers, names, addresses and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes were made publicly available. A total of 28 thousand users.

title: Coinmine
description: In July 2022, the newsletter of a cryptocurrency mining company known as Coinmine suffered a data breach. The violation included email addresses, phone numbers, full names and physical addresses. In total, 7.6 thousand users were affected.

title: Ddo.com
description: In April 2013, the interactive video game Dungeons Dragons Online suffered a data breach that exposed the data of nearly 1.6 million players. The data was actively traded on underground forums and included birthdate email addresses and password hashes.

title: SwordFantasy
description: In January 2017, the online MMO and role-playing game SwordFantasy suffered a data breach that affected 3.2 million users. The breach included usernames, email addresses, IP addresses and passwords stored as salted MD5 hashes.

title: GamesBox
description: In March 2021, the (now defunct) gaming website GamesBox suffered a data breach that affected 1.5 million users. The breach included usernames, email addresses and unencrypted passwords.

title: ReallyWorld.ru
description: In June 2020, a leak occurred from the Russian minecraft server ReallyWorld. 673 thousand users were affected. Nicknames, IP addresses and passwords in the form of AuthMe hashes were made publicly available.

title: BurgerHeroes.ru
description: A website dedicated to the fast food restaurant chain BurgerHeroes.ru suffered a data leak in January 2024. As a result, information about 76 thousand users was exposed, including phone numbers, emails, full names, dates of birth, and passwords in the form of an MD5 hash.

title: Astrovolga
description: In August 2023, information appeared about a leak from the Russian insurance company Astro-Volga. The leak contained personal data of clients - telephone numbers, email addresses, addresses, passport data and information about cars. A total of 1.3 million unique entries.

title: Fotolog
description: In December 2018, a leak occurred on the photo-sharing social network Fotolog. As a result, 16.7 million unique email addresses, usernames and unsalted SHA-256 password hashes were made publicly available. The following year the site was closed.

title: DBForums
description: In July 2016, a data leak occurred on the DBForums forum, which affected 363 thousand customers. The breach included usernames, email addresses, IP addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes.

title: Pokebip
description: In July 2015, a French Pokemon website suffered a data breach that exposed the identities of 657,000 subscribers. The data included email addresses, IP addresses, usernames and passwords as unsalted MD5 hashes.

title: InfoUrok.ru
description: InfoUrok is a Russian website that aggregates educational materials and data about teachers. In August 2024, the list of site users was collected using scraping. The data contains names, dates of birth, information about specialty and place of work, region of residence and a link to the user’s avatar.

title: Digimon
description: In September 2016, over 16 GB of logs were retrieved from the digimon.co.in service. The logs contained 77 million unique emails, email server IPs, email subjects, and information about email openings and clicks.

title: Zivame.com
