description: Zivame is an Indian website that sells bras. In May 2023, its database of 1.5 million users began to be sold online for $500. The data contains telephone numbers, names, emails and residential addresses. Most of the users are women.

title: Infobiz.ru
description: This is an information platform for teaching methods of making money on the Internet. It was hacked at the end of 2022. 672 thousand user records, including names, phone numbers and emails, were leaked into the public domain.

title: HoundDawgs
description: In December 2017, the Danish torrent tracker HoundDawgs was damaged. Over 55GB of data was released and contained over 45,000 unique email addresses, as well as extensive logs of torrent activity, IP addresses and salted SHA256 hashes of passwords. In rare cases, the SHA1 hash was used.

title: Dominos
description: In June 2014, Dominos Pizza in France and Belgium was hacked by a group called "Rex Mundi" and their customer data was held for ransom. Dominos refused to pay the ransom, and six months later the attackers published the data along with a database of hacked accounts. Client data included emails, phone numbers, addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes without salt.

title: WiredBucks
description: In July 2022, the online money making website WiredBucks suffered a data breach that affected 920,000 users. The breach exposed full names, email addresses, IP addresses, physical addresses and plain text passwords.

title: Heroes of Newerth
description: In December 2012, an online multiplayer game known as Heroes of Newerth was hacked. More than 8 million accounts were extracted from the system. The data included usernames, email addresses and passwords, but no publicly available passwords currently exist.

title: LiveJournal
description: In mid-2019, news emerged about an alleged LiveJournal data leak. The breach allegedly occurred in 2017 and contained 26 million unique usernames and email addresses, as well as plain-text passwords. The data archive was published on a hacker forum in May 2020.

title: V3rmillion
description: In August 2014, a data leak occurred on the Roblox V3rmillion hacker forum, which affected 8 thousand participants. The breach included usernames, email addresses, IP addresses, dates of birth and passwords stored as MD5 hashes (MyBB).

title: JD.com
description: In 2013 (the exact date is unknown), a leak occurred in the Chinese e-commerce service JD, revealing 13 GB of data containing 77 million unique emails and extensive user data.

title: iDressUp
description: In June 2016, the social network for teenagers “i-Dressup” was hacked. More than 2 million user accounts were exposed. The hack was based on a SQL injection vulnerability that had remained unpatched for a long time. A total of 5.5 million accounts were exposed. The hack included email addresses and passwords stored in plain text.

title: Lifebear
description: In early 2019, a leaked Japanese scheduling app called Lifebear appeared for sale on the darknet market. The hack revealed almost 3.7 million unique email addresses, as well as usernames and passwords in MD5 format.

title: PartSelect.ru
description: As a result of a hacker attack on October 22, 2019, on an online store of spare parts for household appliances, a database containing 15 thousand user records and 10 thousand orders was published. The data contained emails, names, phone numbers, delivery addresses, order amounts and text comments on them.

title: BattleRoyaleForums
description: Sometime in 2019, a data leak occurred on the gaming forum Battle Royale Forums, which affected 51.7 thousand users. The breach exposed usernames, email addresses and passwords stored as bcrypt hashes. The website was hacked by donjuji by decrypting the admin hash obtained from another leak.

title: Totaljerkface
description: In August 2010, the gaming website Totaljerkface suffered a data leak that affected the records of 188 thousand customers. The breach included email addresses, usernames, IP addresses, locations, user websites, and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes. It was later discovered that this leak was fabricated and came from another database.

title: My.mail.ru
description: In April 2021, the My.mail.ru mail service database appeared online. The database, 1.6 million rows in size, contained emails, names, dates of birth and regions of residence of users. The data was collected using scraping. Later, another database from this service appeared, but with 1 million rows and a large number of columns.

title: Velnet.ru
description: In October 2021, a leak occurred on the website of the Russian Internet provider Velnet, which affected about 10 thousand users. The data contains emails, names, addresses, information about connected tariffs, several telephone numbers for each user and passwords, mostly automatically generated.

title: Start.ru
description: In August 2022, it became known about an attack on the Russian streaming service START. The incident revealed 44 million records containing 7.4 million unique emails, as well as the country and md5crypt password hash. Most of the records contained only the password, service information and device data.

title: AtlasBus.ru
description: In August 2023, the Russian ticket purchasing and booking service AtlasBus suffered from a data leak. The stolen database is rumored to contain data on 100 million tickets sold, but only a user table containing approximately 1.3 million people is publicly available. The data only includes emails, phone numbers and names.

title: go-gl.com
description: The go-gl.com link shortening service was hacked in October 2023. The data of 5.5 thousand users was made publicly available. Records include emails, nicknames and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes.

title: UKScrappers
description: In January 2021, UKScrappers, a forum dedicated to scrapbooking in the UK, suffered a data leak that affected 50.4 thousand users. The breach included email addresses, usernames, IP addresses and passwords stored as vBulletin hashes.

title: Thingiverse
description: In October 2021, a database backup from the 3D model sharing service "Thingiverse" began to circulate widely in the hacker community. The 36GB file contained 228,000 unique email addresses, mostly along with comments left on the 3D models. The data also included usernames, IP addresses, full names, physical addresses, and passwords stored as unsalted SHA-1 hashes or bcrypt.

title: Acxiom
description: In 2020, a dataset containing nearly a quarter of a billion records, covering more than 400 different areas, came online. It was originally incorrectly attributed to database marketing company Acxiom. The data contained nearly 52 million unique email addresses.

title: AidLegal.ru
description: In March 2023, the Aidlegal Legal Consultation website was hacked.The resulting leak contains about 280 thousand records with names, phones, IP addresses and comments.The data were unloading from the feedback system through which customers asked them to call back.

title: LeroyMerlin
description: LeroyMerlin is an international company selling furniture and renovation tools. On June 8, 2023, the NLB hacker group published the database of the Russian branch of this company. The leak contains 4.7 million records. Data includes names, addresses, emails and phone numbers of customers. The leak occurred in May 2023.

title: FpTaxi
description: On July 29, 2024, there was a data leak from the Portuguese taxi fleet, which connects drivers to Yandex Taxi, Food, Courier and other services. About 15 thousand records appeared on the Internet, including full names, emails, phone numbers, passwords, dates of birth and passport details of users.

title: Zeeroq
description: Around 2019, about 250 combo players were found in the open directory on the demo.zeeroq.com domain. The number of entries was more than 200 million. The leak contained emails and passwords in plain text.

title: BEUTiFi
description: In September 2022, the beauty salon website BEUTiFi suffered a data leak that affected 126 thousand users. The breach included email addresses, countries, and passwords as salted SHA-1 hashes. The site closed after being hacked and is no longer operational.

title: Devil-Torrents
description: This is a pirate resource specializing in the distribution of unlicensed content. In January 2021, Devil-Torrents user data was compromised and made public. The leak included information about 160 thousand users. It contained nicknames, email addresses, passwords in the form of MD5 hashes, IP addresses and other personal information.

title: Luyentoeicvn.com
description: The now defunct site Luyentoeicvn was hacked in November 2019. 27 thousand users were affected. IP addresses, email addresses, usernames and passwords were published as salted MD5 hashes.

title: 51.com
description: In August 2019, one of the main social networking sites in China suffered a data leak affecting 4.2 million posts. The leak included emails, nicknames, full names and IP addresses.

title: Eroticy
description: In mid-2016, the adult site Eroticy was hacked. 1.4 million accounts were exposed to public access. They contained a wealth of personal information, from email addresses and phone numbers to passwords in plain text.

title: PirogiDomoy.ru
description: PirogiDomoy.ru is a Russian pies delivery service. On July 14, 2022, there was a data leak. It included names, addresses, telephone numbers and order amounts of customers. A total of 223 thousand records.

title: Tunngle
description: Sometime in 2016, the (now defunct) virtual gaming network Tunngle suffered a data leak. The leak resulted in the disclosure of data including usernames, email addresses, IP addresses and passwords in the form of IPB hashes. In total, 8.1 million users were affected.

title: GSkill.com
description: In January 2023, G.Skill was compromised via a vulnerable database service. In April of the same year, their database was deleted and they were served with extortion demands, which they could not agree on, which is why the data was published. The database contains RMA information, user information including email addresses, full addresses and hashed passwords. In total there are more than 50 thousand records.

title: Ecapper.net
description: This is a now defunct American sports betting site. Around 2021, it suffered a leak that affected 22 thousand users. Names, emails, phone numbers, addresses and passwords were published in plain text.

title: DayCrafts.ru
description: The Minecraft game server DayCrafts.ru was hacked at the end of 2016. A database containing more than 50 thousand records, including IP addresses, emails, nicknames and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes, has leaked online.

title: Epal
description: Around October 2022, a gaming buddy meeting website known as E-Pal suffered a data breach affecting 108,000 members. The leak exposed data including usernames, email addresses and purchases.

title: PowerBuy.co.th
description: In May 2023, it became known that the Thai service PowerBuy, which sells consumer electronics, was hacked. The leak affected 200 thousand records and included mail, phone numbers, addresses, names and purchase amounts.

title: PlayThePlanet.org
description: In May 2020, the information portal PlayThePlanet, covering topics such as auto, business, health, technology and other areas, suffered a leak that affected more than 123 thousand users. The data contained emails, nicknames and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: HauteLook
description: In mid-2018, the fashion shopping website HauteLook was hacked. The data includes more than 28 million email addresses, as well as names, genders, dates of birth and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes.

title: Comelec Philippines Voters
description: In March 2016, the Philippine Elections Commission (COMELEC) website was attacked and defaced, allegedly by Anonymous Philippines. Soon after, data on 55 million Filipino voters was made public and included sensitive information such as gender, marital status, height and weight, and fingerprint biometrics.

title: Stickam
description: Stickam was a video streaming website launched in 2005. On February 1, 2013, Stikam announced its closure a month later. It is unknown when it was hacked, but it is believed to have happened in 2012. The leak contains 530 thousand records and includes usernames, emails and passwords.

title: Photigy.com
description: At the end of 2022, a database of the Photigy.com website dedicated to photographers appeared on the Internet. It contains data from 23 thousand users, including nicknames, emails and full names.

title: Cheryomushki.ru
description: Data from the Cheryomushki company, one of the largest Russian manufacturers of lingerie, was leaked online in January 2021. The data of about 3 thousand orders and 27 thousand users with full names, emails, phone numbers, customer delivery addresses and passwords in the form of SHA1 hashes with salt was compromised.

title: SolidWorks
description: In January 2022, a file with data from the official client forum of the CAD software manufacturer SolidWorks was made publicly available. The file contains 238 thousand entries, including names, emails and passwords in the form of hashes. The leak dates back to March 2021.

title: MeFeedia
description: Around September 2019, now-defunct video search platform MeFeedia suffered a data breach that affected 1.6 million users. The breach exposed usernames, email addresses, IP addresses, physical addresses and passwords as MD5 hashes. The website was hacked by GnosticPlayers.

title: Game-Shop.com.ua
description: On February 10, 2023, a data leak from the Ukrainian online store Game-shop.com.ua, specializing in the sale of game consoles, accessories and video games.As a result of the incident, more than 45 thousand users, including their mail and passwords, got into the network.

title: SportVokrug.ru
description: SportVokrug is a Russian website for organizing sporting events. In 2023, it suffered a leak that affected more than a million users. The published SQL dump contained a lot of tables and a lot of garbage, but the important data included emails, names, phone numbers and information about events.

title: Doxbin.com
description: At the beginning of 2022, a data leak occurred from the Doxbin.com resource, a popular site for exchanging information about people (deanonymization). The database was leaked by the former owner, and it contains about 50 thousand records with data of registered users, including logins, email addresses, hashed passwords, profile descriptions and account creation dates.;📩 Email: 51,244; 🔑 Password (clear text): 6,396

title: Rossko.ru
description: In November 2024, a leakage of a partial database of orders of the Rossko.ru online store, a large Russian auto parts and accessories store, took place.She affected 7.6 million records containing names, phones and addresses.

title: Moscow Drivers licenses 2016
description: This is a leak of drivers from Moscow and the Moscow region, dated 2016. The data contains names, driver's license numbers, residence addresses, dates of birth and passport details, as well as information about driver's license categories. A total of 750 thousand records.

title: Vedantu
description: In mid-2019, Indian interactive online learning platform Vedantu suffered a data breach that exposed the personal information of 687,000 users. The JSON database dump contained extensive personal information including email addresses, IP addresses, names, phone numbers, gender, and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes.

title: Vkusno i tochka
description: The Russian fast food chain Vkusno i tochka (renamed McDonald's) suffered from a data leak that occurred on May 25, 2023. A Ukrainian hacker group was behind the hack. As a result, the details of all people who applied for work in this establishment were published. The leak contains about 300 thousand records. Including names, phone numbers, addresses, ages and job application information.

title: Pogranec.tar
description: On April 19, 2024, a hacker attack occurred on the official news website of the border guards, due to which about 120 thousand records were obtained, such as nicknames, IP addresses, emails and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: ProgrammingForums
description: In late 2015, the programming forum programmingforums.org suffered a data breach that exposed 707,000 unique users. The data contained email addresses, IP addresses, usernames and passwords as salted MD5 hashes.

title: Calls Ambulance Samara
description: This database contains a list of ambulance calls in Samara. There are about a million records in total with names, phone numbers, addresses and information about who called the ambulance.

title: GiantTiger
description: In 2024, the Canadian GiantTiger store suffered a hack. The data published on the hacker forum contains names, emails, addresses and phone numbers of clients. A total of 2.8 million records.

title: NterOne
description: Around September 2021, online IT training site NterOne was hacked. The breach affected 203K users and included email addresses, full names, IP addresses, phone numbers, company names, locations and passwords stored as bcrypt hashes ($2).

title: StockX
description: In July 2019, fashion and sneaker trading platform StockX suffered a data breach that was subsequently sold on a darknet marketplace. The data included 6.8 million unique email addresses, as well as names, physical purchase addresses, and salted MD5 hashes of passwords.

title: HeyPlay.games
description: In 2021, online gaming website HeyPlay.games experienced a data leak. It contains about 60 thousand records, including Email, full names, nicknames, IP addresses and passwords in the form of a bcrypt hash.

title: Georgia 4.9kk
description: Database of Georgian residents containing 4.9 million records. The data contains names, phone numbers, addresses and dates of birth. The origin of the base is unknown.

title: SportMaster
description: In early January 2023, the NLB hacker team published part of the database of the Russian sports store Sportmaster. The leak contains 100 million store customers, but hackers claim that the full database contains more than 400 million rows. The published data contains 17 million emails, as well as telephone numbers, names, gender, dates of birth and residential addresses of users.

title: Znanium.ru
description: This is a leak of a catalog of electronic libraries for Russian universities. The data dates from 2011-2018. The files contain emails, names, passwords and some other personal data.

title: RocketWash.me
description: At the end of 2019, a freely available Elasticsearch server for the RocketWash car wash management service was discovered. Soon the data from this server was downloaded and posted on one of the forums. The leak contains names, phone numbers, dates of birth and car numbers of customers. There are about 170 thousand records in total.

title: Youku
description: At the end of 2016, the Chinese online video server Youku suffered a data leak. As a result, 92 million unique user accounts and their corresponding MD5 password hashes were exposed.

title: Gai UA 2023
description: In 2023, there was a data leak from the Ukrainian traffic police service. The database included information about registered cars without reference to their owners. The data contains vehicle numbers, VIN, makes, years of manufacture, engine power and other data. In total, the database contains 17.3 million unique cars.

title: DreamShirts.ru
description: In September 2022, the online t-shirt store DreamShirts suffered from a hack. There were 16.5 thousand registered users on the site, whose emails, names, IP and purchase data were made publicly available.

title: ClickASnap
description: Around September 2022, image-sharing website ClickASnap suffered a data breach that affected 3.3 million users. The breach included full names, email addresses, social media profiles, physical addresses, orders made, and passwords stored as SHA512 or Bcrypt hashes. The website was hacked due to leaked Amazon RDS credentials.

title: Fira.ru
description: Fira is a Russian rating agency that provides data on various companies. At the end of 2023, a table containing companies collected by this agency appeared in the public domain. It contains the name, phone number and email of the manager, as well as information about the company - occupation, address, registration date, Taxpayer Identification Number and other information. There are 76 thousand companies in total.

title: DemonForums
description: In February 2019, the hacker forum Demon Forums suffered a data breach. The hack exposed 52,000 unique email addresses, as well as salted MD5 hashes of usernames and passwords.

title: CalcioShop
description: In 2021, Calcioshop, an online store dedicated to football in Italy, suffered a data leak. Several tables were leaked online, including 366 thousand customer records and 360 thousand order records. Data such as names, phone numbers, emails and shipping addresses were exposed.

title: ExVagos
description: In July 2022, the Latin data sharing service ExVagos suffered a data leak. As a result, 2.1 million participants were affected. The leak included usernames, email addresses, dates of birth, IP addresses and passwords as salted MD5 hashes.

title: Whoosh-bike
description: In November 2022, the Russian scooter rental service Whoosh suffered from a data leak. The published database contains 7.23 million records, including emails, phone numbers and usernames. The leak also contained information about the presence/absence of a bank card.

title: DavitaMebel
description: In February 2024, a partial dump of the furniture online store davitamebel appeared in the public domain. This dump contains only names, phone numbers and emails left through the feedback form. There are about 30 thousand unique entries in total. There is also probably a full version of the leak, containing almost half a million records, including addresses and passwords, but it is not publicly available.

title: Dave
description: In June 2020, digital banking app Dave suffered a data breach that exposed 7.5 million rows of data. The leak exposed extensive personal information, including nearly 3 million unique email addresses, as well as names, dates of birth, encrypted social security numbers and passwords in bcrypt hashes.

title: NTV Sputnik
description: "NTV" is a Russian satellite television channel. The service was hacked in March 2017. The leak contains 270 thousand records, including telephone numbers, names and cities of residence.

title: FreeOnesForum
description: Somewhere in early 2018, a data leak occurred on the forum of the erotic website FreeOnes, which affected 963 thousand users. The breach included usernames, email addresses and passwords as vBulletin hashes (the salt was in hexadecimal encoding).

title: Nitro
description: In September 2020, the Nitro PDF service suffered a massive data breach. More than 70 million unique email addresses, names, bcrypt passwords, and converted file headers were exposed.

title: PeepMyPorn
description: In July 2022, the porn site Peep My Porn suffered a data leak. The breach included usernames, email addresses and passwords in SHA-1 hashes. In total, 261 thousand users were affected.

title: Randizzon.hu
description: Randizzon is a Hungarian dating site. It suffered a hack in July 2013 that resulted in the publication of nearly two million user records that included emails, names, hometowns, dates of birth and passwords in plain text.

title: TikTop-free.com
description: TikTop-free is a Russian website for gaining free followers on TikTok. It was hacked on December 1, 2022. The data of two million users, containing emails and passwords in plain text, was released to the public.

title: Payad.me
description: Payad is a service for advertisers that allows them to search for clients. In 2018, there was a leak that affected emails and passwords. There are about 100 thousand records in total.

title: Yatra
description: In September 2013, Indian booking website Yatra suffered a breach affecting 5 million users. The data contained email addresses, physical addresses, dates of birth, phone numbers, PIN codes and passwords in plain text.

title: Tns-e.ru
description: In July 2022, hackers hacked the energy company TNS Energo and demanded a ransom from it. After refusing to pay it, the hackers published all user data, divided by region, in several passes. The data contains mainly emails without other data, but the database also contains names, phone numbers and bcrypt passwords.

title: YouHack.ru
description: On May 29, 2013, a data leak occurred from the hacker forum YouHack.ru. About 1.1 million records were made publicly available, containing nicknames, emails, IP addresses and passwords in the form of salted hashes.

title: JamesDelivery
description: In June 2020, 14 previously unknown data breaches went on sale. Among them was the Brazilian delivery service James. The breach occurred in March 2020 and exposed 1.5 million unique email addresses, as well as customer locations and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes.

title: Eatigo
description: In October 2018, restaurant reservation service Eatigo suffered a data breach that exposed 2.8 million accounts. The data included email addresses, names, phone numbers, social media profiles, gender, and passwords as unsalted MD5 hashes.

title: OrderSnapp
description: In June 2020, restaurant solutions provider OrderSnapp suffered a data breach that exposed 1.3 million unique email addresses. The data also included names, phone numbers, dates of birth and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes.

title: MortalOnline
description: In June 2018, a data leak occurred in the massively multiplayer online role-playing game (MMORPG) Mortal Online. The file contained 570,000 email addresses and hacked passwords. A larger, more complete file was later published containing 607,000 email addresses with their original unsalted MD5 password hashes, usernames, and physical addresses.

title: Kadrovichka.ru
description: In April 2020, the Russian job search site Kadrovichka suffered from a hack. 156 thousand client records containing names, phone numbers, emails, dates of birth and cities of residence were made publicly available. The hack was caused by SQL injection.

title: Chess.com
description: In November 2023, the database of the chess website Chess.com became publicly available. The database contains 1.2 million users. The data includes emails, nicknames, names and profile data - country, registration date, link to avatar, level, rating and donation status.

title: AptekiPlus.ru
description: In August 2024, the Russian pharmacy chain AptekiPlus was hacked. The published data contains telephone numbers, mails, names and regions of residence in the form of their numbers. A total of 4.5 million records.

title: Rptour.ru
description: The Russian travel agency Romantika Travel was hacked in June 2022. 11.2 thousand clients were affected. Only their emails and the dates when they left them on the site in the feedback form were compromised.

title: Kz.M2bomber
description: Data from the Kazakh website for searching and renting real estate Kz.M2bomber was collected using parsing in 2024. The network leaked information from 1.8 million users, including phone numbers, addresses and descriptions of real estate properties.

title: opt-opt-opt.ru
description: opt-opt-opt - Novosibirsk shoe store. In August 2022, it suffered from a hack that affected 11.4 thousand users. The leak contains emails, names, phone numbers, addresses, places of work and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: Vostruha.ru
description: In 2024, a dump appeared, allegedly obtained in February from the Russian recipe site Vostruha, but the data in the leak itself dates back to June 2011. The database contains 20 thousand entries with emails, nicknames and hashed passwords.

title: JustClick
description: JustClick, an online platform for creating and managing sales funnels, marketing automation and sales of services, suffered a data leak. As a result, data about 322 thousand users was published, including their emails, nicknames and lists of purchased products.

title: SuperJob
description: In 2016-2017, a leak occurred in the company SuperJob, which provides a search for high-paying vacancies. However, until 2020 nothing was known about the leak. When it was published, it contained 5 million users and information about their emails, phone numbers, names, cities of residence and dates of birth.

title: Cheerleading
description: Around January 2021, the online store Cheerleading.com experienced a data breach that affected 66.5 thousand members. The attack exposed email addresses, full names and passwords stored as SHA512 hashes. The initial attack vector was a rogue mysql administrator.

title: CrimeAgency
description: In January 2016, a large number of vBulletin forums were compromised by an entity known as CrimeAgency. In total, data from 140 forums were extracted and then disseminated. The data included usernames, email addresses, and passwords, most commonly hashed using salted MD5.

title: Pixlr
description: In October 2020, online photo editing app Pixlr suffered a data breach that affected 1.9 million subscribers. The data included names, email addresses, social media profiles, country of origin of the company and passwords stored as SHA-512 hashes.

title: Helix.ru
description: In July 2023, hackers hacked the Russian medical laboratory Helix and published a database of its clients. The leak contains 7.3 million records with names, phone numbers, dates of birth, SNI and medical insurance data. Hackers also threaten to publish tests and other sensitive information.

title: NordicGames
description: In March 2016, European game publisher Nordic Games experienced a data leak that affected 157 thousand users. The breach included usernames, email addresses, IP addresses and passwords stored as vBulletin hashes. Shortly after the hack, Nordic Games was renamed THQ Nordic.

title: JustPex
description: This Minecraft server was hacked in July 2021. 8 thousand players were affected. Nicknames, IPs and passwords were published in the form of AuthMe hashes.

title: TGBUS
description: Around 2017, Chinese gaming site TGBUS suffered a data breach that affected more than 10 million unique users. The data contains usernames, email addresses, and salted MD5 password hashes.

title: Lbb.in
description: In August 2022, customer data of Indian shopping website LBB (Little Black Book) was posted on a popular hacker forum. The data contained more than 3 million records with 39,000 unique email addresses, as well as IP and physical addresses, names and device information, with the most recent data going back to early 2019. they retain their customers, it has also been enriched with additional data attributes.

title: Apteka ANC
description: On June 6, 2023, the pro-Russian hacker group XakNet Team announced the hacking of the Ukrainian “Low Price Pharmacy” (anc.ua) and published a database with user purchases. The file included data from 100 thousand customers and a list of goods they purchased, trimmed to the first 3-4 items. A total of 250 thousand purchase records. The data also included names, telephone numbers, addresses of pharmacies, medical policies and purchase amounts in rubles.

title: Villavu
description: In 2014, the runescape bot/script web forum Villavu (also known as the SRL Resource Library) suffered a data breach that affected 137,000 members. The breach included usernames, email addresses, IP addresses and passwords in the form of vBulletin hashes.

title: COMB+12billion
description: Two huge combo players called CompilationOfManyBreaches and 12Billion special appeared in February 2021 and September 2022, respectively. Each of them contained more than 3 billion unique emails and passwords. Most of the data was taken from collections 1-5 and combo player Ga$$Pacc, leaving only 211 million rows after removing them.

title: msp.gov.ua
description: In October 2022, a Russian hacker group published the database of the Ministry of Social Policy of Ukraine. The database contains complaints from 20 thousand Ukrainians. The data includes names, emails, telephone numbers, addresses, age and text of the appeal.

title: Benchmark
description: In November 2019, Serbian technology news website Benchmark had its forum hacked, exposing the records of 93,000 customers. The hack exposed IP and email addresses, usernames and passwords as salted MD5 hashes. The breach occurred because the forum was previously running on an outdated instance of vBulletin.

title: InnoGames
description: Around June 2016, a data leak occurred on the gaming forum InnoGames, which affected 652 thousand customer records. The breach included usernames, email addresses, IP addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes.

title: Russian Motor Insurers
description: "Russian Union of Auto Insurers" (RUA) is an association of companies involved in car insurance. In March 2023, there was a breach that affected their clients' data for the last four years. It contains 68 million people and 5 million companies. Data includes names, dates of birth, regions, company INNs and vehicle information. The surnames were closed with asterisks, but 90% of them were deciphered.

title: SuperPnevmat.ru
description: The Russian online store SuperPnevmat, which sells air and air guns, became the victim of a data leak in May 2017. The data of more than 600 users and 33 thousand of their orders, including phone numbers, names, emails, cities of residence and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes, were made publicly available.

title: TNAFlix
description: In June 2022, the porn site TNAFlix suffered a data leak that affected 1.3 million users. The breach included email addresses, usernames, IP addresses, and plain text passwords (note that for some reason the IP addresses were stored without dots).

title: New Post Offise
description: On February 5, 2018, it became known about a huge leak from the Ukrainian service “Nova Poshta” (NovaPoshta.ua). The database put up for sale included full names, emails, telephone numbers, residential addresses and delivery addresses. The leak contains approximately 8 million users. There is also information about passport data in the leak, but the public version of the database does not contain it.

title: Love.mail.ru
description: In February 2021, one of the mail.ru services (presumably the dating service Love.mail.ru) suffered from a vulnerability. This vulnerability allowed, using parsing, to collect data on 10 million users, including emails, names, residential addresses and dates of birth.

title: Wikkeo
description: In 2022, the Wikkeo marketplace suffered from a data leak. 66 thousand customer records were made publicly available. Data includes telephones, mails, names and addresses.

title: MascotApp
description: Around June 2022, the role-playing game app Mascot experienced a data breach. The attack resulted in the disclosure of data including usernames, full names, IP addresses, gender, phone numbers and dates of birth. In total, 85.7 thousand users were affected.

title: IceCreamForum
description: Around May 2021, the ice cream discussion forum Ice Cream Forum experienced a data leak that affected 1,000 members. The breach included email addresses, usernames, dates of birth, IP addresses and passwords stored as vBulletin hashes.

title: 17Media
description: In April 2016, customer data obtained from the streaming app 17 was put up for sale on the Tor marketplace. The data contained more than 4 million unique email addresses, as well as IP addresses, usernames and passwords in the form of unsalted MD5 hashes.

title: BitcoinTalk
description: In May 2015, the cryptocurrency forum Bitcoin Talk was hacked. More than 500 thousand users were affected. The attack exposed personal data including names, email addresses, IP addresses, gender, dates of birth, security questions and MD5 hashes of their answers, as well as hashes of the passwords themselves.

title: LeaderID
description: These data were obtained at the end of 2022 from the Russian website leader-id.ru, intended for conducting training events. Using parsing, information was collected about 1.5 million users, including their emails, phone numbers, cities of residence, names, dates of birth and work information.

title: Artek
description: On July 5, 2023, two files containing data from the Artek children’s camp were made publicly available. The leak contains data of children and parents including full names, mails, addresses, telephone numbers, SNILS, passport number and place of study, as well as other data. A total of 1.5 million records.

title: Powerbot
description: Around September 2014, Powerbot, a site that provides bot services for the game RuneScape, suffered a data breach. More than half a million unique user records were exposed. The data contained email addresses, IP addresses, usernames, and MD5-salted password hashes. It was previously reported that the site was compromised at Vigilante.pw using a database directory hack.

title: LavaGuden.ru
description: This Minecraft server was hacked in early 2019. The leak contains nicknames, emails, IPs and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt. There are 7 thousand records in total.

title: SunDays.by
description: In February 2020, a data leak occurred on the SunDays trading platform. Information about more than 20 thousand clients was made publicly available, including full names, nicknames, phone numbers, emails and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes.

title: Dukcapil
description: In 2023, it became known about a data leak from Dukcapil, a government service for document management in Indonesia. According to experts, more than 337 million records were stolen, but only 24 million of them were publicly available. The data contains telephone numbers, names, dates of birth, addresses and NIK numbers, which are used in the ID card.

title: Ast
description: On June 9, 2023, the NLB hacker group published data from the Russian publishing group Eksmo-AST. The base consists of two parts - Eksmo and Ast. The Ast file contains 87 thousand records, including information about users - emails, names, addresses and passwords in the form of bcrypt and md5 hashes with salt.

title: Contest.co.nz
description: This is a New Zealand forum for competitions. It was hacked in November 2019. The published leak contains 160 thousand records with emails, nicknames, IP addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: ChinaEKO
description: In January 2017, a data leak occurred on the Chinese design website China EKO. The breach exposed usernames, email addresses and passwords in the form of VBulletin md5(md5($pass)$salt) hashes. In total, 348 thousand users were affected.

title: Buslik.by
description: In June 2023, it became known about a data leak from the Belarusian online store for children “Buslik”. As a result of the leak, approximately 223 thousand records were published containing names, phone numbers, emails and passwords in the form of an MD5 hash with salt.

title: RocketText
description: Around January 2020, customer engagement tool RocketText experienced a data breach. The violation included email addresses, home addresses, IP addresses, gender, ethnicity, and telephone numbers (including the operator of the number listed). In total, 32 million records were affected. Rocket Text now operates under the name "LaunchSMS" and was previously known as ApexSMS.

title: Otpravkin.ru
description: In August 2023, a database appeared of emails and decrypted passwords taken from the website Otpravkin.ru, which sells tours. The database contains 6000 unique emails and passwords in plain text.

title: AnimeGame
description: In February 2020, the gaming website AnimeGame suffered a data leak. The incident affected 1.4 million subscribers and exposed email addresses, names and passwords as salted MD5 hashes.

title: Hiretale.com
description: In 2022, job search platform Hiretal.com suffered a data breach. A database with information about 170 thousand users, which included nicknames, full names, phone numbers and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes, was leaked online.

title: Slivup.net
description: In October 2022, there was a data leak from the Russian forum Slivup, dedicated to the exchange of private courses on earnings, business and much more. As a result, data about 124 thousand users was publicly available, including emails, full names, nicknames, IP addresses and passwords in the form of an MD5 hash with salt.

title: Lyrics Mania
description: In December 2017, the lyrics website Lyrics Mania suffered a data breach. As a result of the hack, 109 thousand usernames, email addresses and passwords were published without encryption. The Lyrics Mania website did not provide any answers to questions about the hack.

title: Hcs.land
description: At the beginning of 2017, the game website Hcs.land suffered from hacking. A user dump containing 370 thousand entries was published. The data includes emails, names, nicknames, IP addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes.

title: MobiFriends
description: In January 2020, Barcelona-based dating app MobiFriends suffered a data breach. As a result, 3.5 million unique email addresses were exposed. The data also included usernames, gender, dates of birth and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes.

title: Scardio.ru
description: In May 2024, data from the Russian cardiological society SCARDIO leaked. The data of 90 thousand employees was compromised, including full names, emails, addresses, phone numbers, as well as passwords in the form of MD5 hashes.

title: Deltel.ru
description: In August 2022, the website of the Delta Electronics store, which sells radio components and computer spare parts, was hacked. The published SQL dump contains 8.1 thousand users and includes emails, addresses, INN dates of birth and from one to three telephone numbers for each client.

title: 10 000 000 Dump Mail-Pass
description: This is a combination of emails and passwords from various leaks, published in November 2022 on a hacker forum. Contains 10 million rows.

title: Instagram Parsing
description: In 2022, the Instagram user base, collected through parsing, began to spread in Telegram channels. The date of data collection is unknown, but the database contains 17 million records, including names, emails, phone numbers, nicknames and addresses.

title: Jassume
description: In May 2020, the French dating site J'assume suffered a data breach. The breach resulted in the disclosure of data including usernames, email addresses, dates of birth and plain text passwords. In total, 792 thousand users were affected.

title: KudaNaMore.ru
description: KudaNaMore is a Russian bulletin board for renting houses on the seashore. In October 2024, data from all advertisements on this site was collected using scraping. In total there were about 20 thousand records with telephone numbers, names, a small number of emails and text descriptions of rental properties.

title: GrailsForum.co.uk
description: This is a UK programming forum. It was hacked in November 2019. The published leak contains 88 thousand records with emails, nicknames, IP addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: GreenСoffee
description: The company GreenCoffee, which produces green coffee for weight loss, suffered a data leak in 2016. The leak affected 160 thousand records, but there is also a more complete version of the database containing more than 600 thousand users. The table included telephone numbers, full names and addresses.

title: V3toys.ru
description: In 2023, a leak occurred in the Russian toy store V3toys. It affected 267 thousand users and included phone numbers, emails and names.

title: Russian Crime Reports
description: This is a database of criminal reports from Russia. It contains information about crimes that have occurred over the past 30 years. In total, the database contains about 50 million records. The data contains names, dates of birth and case descriptions in free format. The database became publicly available in 2018.

title: Kvadroom.ru
description: In April 2021, the Kvadroom database began to be publicly distributed. This is a Russian real estate website. The leak contains 225 thousand records and includes phone numbers, names, emails, balance data and PIN codes.

title: PlayStationUniverse
description: In September 2016, the Forum for the Playstation News PlayStation Universe website suffered a data leak that affected 226 thousand users. The leak exposed usernames, email addresses, dates of birth, IP addresses and passwords stored as vBulletin hashes.

title: Residents of Russia 2016
description: This database contains about 8 million Russian citizens. The source of the leak is unknown, but the database was obtained in 2016 and contains about 4 million people. The data includes names, telephone numbers, passport data, addresses, SNILS data and TIN.

title: TextRu
description: In March 2022, the Russian website text.ru, which rewrites and checks texts for uniqueness, suffered from a data leak. A hacker under the pseudonym “Neuron” published the data of 3.5 million users. The data included emails, names, IP, balance level on the site and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes without salt. When the site learned of the leak, it forcibly reset all users' passwords.

title: BlackSpigot
description: In July 2019, a hacker hacked the database of the minecraft BlackSpigot forum, where paid resources were leaked. The dump, 140 thousand lines in size, contained nicknames, emails, IPs and bcrypt passwords of forum users.

title: Yandex Practikum
description: In June 2023, a hacker group made the database of the Yandex.Practicum service publicly available. The leak contains 300 thousand records with the names, nicknames, emails and telephone numbers of clients of this educational service.

title: Yandex Go
description: In 2019, the Russian company Yandex suffered from a hacking of one of its shuffling services. Due to the hack, the data of all taxi drivers registered in the aggregator became publicly available. A total of 24 thousand records, including telephone numbers, names, numbers and models of cars and city of residence (mainly Moscow).

title: KyrgyzstanResidents
description: In 2020, a government website in Kyrgyzstan was hacked. On October 5-6, during the riots, several computers of employees of the Jogorku Kenesh apparatus were stolen. Using one of them, the hacker group The Black Pirate gained access to a database of citizens' personal data. Presumably this is the same file. It contains 880 thousand records with names, personal identification numbers (PIN) and residential addresses.

title: 1Win
description: In November 2024, a huge data leak from the 1Win bookmaker appeared in the public domain. 96 million users were affected, mainly from India (26 million), Russia (19 million) and Brazil (17 million). The data contained emails, phone numbers, names, IP addresses, passwords in the form of SHA-256 hashes and dates of birth in encrypted form. Many entries were accounts of bots and autoregisters. Also in the leak was a separate partner table containing 570 thousand records with referral data.

title: Solobi.ru
description: The educational website Solobi.ru was hacked in April 2024. Several tables containing users, their orders, call histories and other information have become publicly available. In total, all tables contain more than 6 million rows, but these are mostly call histories and the number of unique users is much lower.

title: CellulariShop
description: Cellularishop.com is an online store that sells electronics. On February 1, 2023, a database of this store was published containing information about 110,000 customers. The data included names, emails, dates of birth and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes.

title: KupiVip
description: Around 2019, clothing clearance platform KupiVip suffered a data breach. Customer data including 4.2 million records was made publicly available. Including email, last name, first name, city and in some cases mobile phone.

title: LeagueOfLegendsHentai
description: Around January 2021, the League of Legends Hentai website suffered a data breach that affected 84.6 thousand members. The breach exposed data including usernames, email addresses and passwords stored as MD5 hashes.

title: Psx-scene.com
description: Around February 2015, a Sony Playstation forum known as PSX-Scene was hacked and over 340 thousand accounts were exposed. On the vBulletin forum, IP addresses and passwords were stored as salted hashes using a weak implementation that allowed many of them to be quickly cracked.

title: Kari Club
description: Kari is a Russian online store of shoes and accessories. In July 2022, it suffered a leak containing 1.3 million rows. The store's bonus program service was hacked. The data included names, telephone numbers, emails, dates of birth and addresses. But only names and phone numbers are publicly available.

title: Telegram 2020
description: In 2020, a base of almost 40 million Telegram users leaked onto the Internet. The file contained user account IDs and their phone numbers, as well as the specified first and last names and usernames. 70% of users in the database are from Iran, and 30% are from Russia. Representatives of the messenger stated that the information was collected through the contact import function.

title: ExtremStyle.ua
description: In January 2023, the Ukrainian online sports goods store ExtremStyle suffered from a leak. A database of 128 thousand lines was published, which contains emails, phone numbers and client names.

title: TaiLieu
description: In November 2019, Vietnamese education website TaiLieu suffered a data breach, exposing the records of 7.3 million customers. The data included nicknames, usernames, emails, dates of birth, gender, and passwords in the form of unsalted MD5 hashes. TaiLieu did not respond to a message about the incident.

title: IDC Games
description: In March 2021, 4 million entries obtained from IDC Games were posted on a public hacker forum. The data included usernames, email addresses, and passwords as salted MD5 hashes.

title: FL.ru
description: Database of freelancers from the Russian exchange FL.ru. The leak occurred in 2015. The data contains emails, passwords, names, emails and phone numbers.

title: Litres
description: On August 4, 2023, the NLB hacker group published the Litres bookstore database. The leak contains 3 million records, but hackers claim that this is only part of the leak and there are 97 million users in the full version. The data contains names, emails and passwords as SHA1 hashes. In most lines, names and emails were not filled in.

title: Ancestry
description: In November 2015, Ancestry, also known as RootsWeb, suffered a data breach. The breach was not discovered until late 2017, when a file containing nearly 300,000 email addresses and unencrypted passwords was discovered.

title: Dota 2
description: In July 2016, the Dota 2 gaming website suffered a data breach that affected 1.9 million users. The breach included email addresses, IP addresses, usernames and passwords. 1.4 million passwords are in clear text, and the rest are in the form of vBulletin hashes.

title: Comcast
description: In November 2015, the American cable and Internet television provider Comcast suffered from a data leak. 590,000 customer email addresses and unencrypted account passwords were exposed. Another 27,000 accounts contained home addresses. The entire data set was sold on underground forums.

title: Teh-fed.ru
description: This is a telephone directory, the data of which became publicly available in 2014. The leak contains 632 thousand records with names, phone numbers, addresses and dates of birth of Russian residents.

title: Ykt.Ru
description: On May 11, 2022, a leak from the Russian information portal Ykt.Ru became publicly available. The data included emails, names, gender, IP, dates of birth, phone numbers and passwords in the form of SHA1 hashes with salt.

title: Ska.ru
description: On August 20, 2020, the database of the official website of the SKA St. Petersburg hockey club was published, as a result of which about 130 thousand user records were published. The data contained names, emails and, in rare cases, telephone numbers.

title: SpiritFit.ru
description: In February 2024, the SpiritFit network of Russian fitness clubs suffered from a hack. 150 thousand user records were published, including phone numbers, names and emails.

title: gPotato
description: In July 2007, the multiplayer gaming portal gPotato suffered from a data leak. More than 2 million user accounts were exposed. The site was later merged into Webzen, where the original accounts still exist. The exposed data included usernames, email and IP addresses, passwords in MD5 hashes, and personal information such as gender, date of birth, physical address, security questions and answers in plain text.

title: P.ua
description: In November 2022, the Ukrainian printing supplies store P.ua was hacked. 174 thousand customers were affected. The leak contains names, phone numbers, emails and cities of residence.

title: LinkedIn Scraped Data
description: During the first half of 2021, LinkedIn became a target for attackers who extracted data from hundreds of millions of profiles and then sold it online. This was not a leak and only publicly available information was collected. The 1.5 terabyte file contained 400 million records and 100 million unique emails, as well as the names, locations, gender and positions of users.

title: ProfMagazin.ru
description: ProfMagazin is a Russian online store of hair cosmetics. On March 17, 2024, its user data was leaked, which contains 138 thousand users and 235 thousand orders. The data includes names, emails, phone numbers, addresses, order amounts and passwords in the form of salted MD5 hashes.

title: ThisHabboForum (part)
description: In 2014, the ThisHabbo forum (a fan site of the Finnish social network Habbo.com) appeared on the list of compromised sites. While the actual date of the hack is unclear, the stolen data includes usernames, email addresses, IP addresses and password hashes. The published file contained only 27 thousand records. Another 584 thousand records were discovered in October 2016, but they are still not publicly available.

title: Kdl.ru
description: The KDL laboratory network is part of the Medscan group of companies. This is a large company in the non-state healthcare sector in Russia. On July 28, 2023, their servers were hacked, as a result of which about 70 thousand lines of information about users were published. The data was heavily littered, but it contained phone numbers, emails, names, addresses, dates of birth and, in some cases, INN of clients.

title: HH.ru 12.2022
description: At the end of 2022, data with HeadHunter - the Russian site for searching for work - were collected using parsing.The base for a long time was in private, but in November 2024 it was discovered.There were approximately 3.4 million records with names, phones, posts and information from user resumes.

title: AgeOfWushu
description: In March 2015, the free-to-play 3D combat game MMORPG Age of Wushu suffered a data leak that affected 90.3 thousand users. The attack exposed email addresses, IP addresses and passwords stored as MD5 hashes.

title: Gemini
description: At the end of 2022, data likely taken from the Gemini crypto exchange was posted on a hacker forum. The data consisted of email addresses and phone numbers that Gemini later attributed to an incident at a third-party vendor. The numbers were in the format 123-XXX-7890. They are partial numbers and do not include the middle 3 digits. In total, 5.7 million users were affected.

title: FxCash.net
description: On December 21, 2021, a data leak occurred on the website of the affiliate program for Forex traders FxCash, which compromised more than 37 thousand records containing names, addresses, telephone numbers, balance data and passwords in the form of SHA1 hashes.

title: Brutalica.ru
description: In April 2020, there was a data leak from the Brutalica.ru online store, specializing in the sale of knives and related products. Several tables were leaked online, including almost 100 thousand records of orders and more than 22 thousand records of users. Names, emails, phone numbers, IP addresses, passwords in the form of SHA1 hashes with salt, as well as payment and delivery information were exposed.

title: rg.ru
description: In March 2023, Ukrainian hackers announced the hacking of two subsections of the Rossiyskaya Gazeta: pravo.rg.ru and works.rg.ru. They managed to obtain a user database, which, however, was heavily littered. The data contains 68 thousand records with emails, names, dates of birth and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes.

title: Out1k-1-irr
description: A database obtained by parsing from the site irr.ru, which sells apartments. A total of 2380 lines with telephone numbers, addresses and information about objects.

title: Ozon
description: In November 2018, the Russian online store Ozon was hacked. 450,000 accounts were affected, which became known only after 7 months. It turned out that the company stored passwords in clear text and only after this leak began hashing them. Only passwords and emails were made publicly available.

title: DailyMotion
description: In October 2016, video sharing platform Dailymotion suffered a data breach. The attack exposed 85 million user accounts and included email addresses, names and bcrypt password hashes.

title: Famm
description: At the end of 2020, Japanese family photo site Famm suffered a data breach. 1.3 million customer records were exposed, including 535,000 unique email addresses. The data also contained names, dates of birth, gender and passwords in the form of SHA-256 hashes.

title: Xyya.net
description: In February 2023, the Russian site for publishing photo jokes, HuYandex, was hacked. A data dump containing 432 thousand users was published. Emails, nicknames, IP addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes.

title: Icigarette.ru
description: This Russian e-cigarette store was hacked on March 30, 2021. Data of 130 thousand users was published, which contains emails, phone numbers, names, dates of birth and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes without salt.

title: Lamoda
description: In February 2020, rumors appeared about a leak from the Russian clothing and accessories store Lamoda. The company itself claimed that the leak was not related to its customers and was received from another location. The leak contained data from 880 thousand records, including phone numbers, emails and full names of clients.

title: CigReviews
description: Sometime in 2021, the now-defunct smoking forum CigReviews suffered a data breach. The breach included usernames, email addresses, IP addresses, dates of birth and passwords stored as vBulletin hashes. In total, 154 thousand users were affected.

title: Philips.ru
description: In 2021, a leak from the online store of Philips equipment began to actively spread. The date of the leak is unknown. The data contains only emails and names, a total of 300 thousand users.

title: Asi.ru
description: On August 14, 2022, a leak occurred from the Russian Agency for Strategic Initiatives. Interestingly, this hack was likely carried out by two people independently, and therefore there are two leaks in the public domain. The first contains 45 thousand lines, and the second - 570 thousand. The data includes names, emails, phone numbers, addresses, places of work and passwords in the form of salted MD5 hashes.

title: Clash of Kings
description: In July 2016, the Clash of Kings forum suffered a leak that affected 1.6 million subscribers. The data included usernames, IP addresses, email addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes.

title: GameGrin
description: In October 2018, a data leak occurred on the gaming website GameGrin, which affected 90.4 thousand users. The breach included email addresses, usernames, IP addresses and passwords stored as MD5 hashes.

title: MirTesen
description: On July 1, 2022, part of the database of the Russian social network “Mir Tesen” became publicly available. The leak contains 17 million records, including names and emails in the form of MD5 hashes, which are fairly easy to decrypt. There are also phone data in a separate file.

title: GAMEVIL
description: In May 2020, the now-defunct gaming forum GAMEVIL suffered a data leak that affected 769,000 members. The breach included usernames, email addresses, dates of birth, IP addresses and passwords in MD5 (vBulletin) hashes. Most of the accounts were created by bots due to the fact that GAMEVIL does not have a captcha.

title: Konfiskat.ua
description: In mid-May 2022, the database of the Ukrainian online clothing store Konfiskat.ua became publicly available. The database contains 130 thousand records with emails, names, phone numbers and passwords in the form of hashes.

title: Beeline 2019
description: In October 2019, information appeared about a data leak of 8 million clients of the Russian mobile operator Beeline. The data contains information for 2017. The leak includes the full names, phone numbers, emails, addresses and connected services of people who installed wired Internet.

title: Traders-union.ru
description: In 2012, there was a data leak on the website dedicated to the association of traders and the exchange of information about financial markets Traders-union.ru. About 54 thousand records, including emails, full names, phone numbers, nicknames and dates of birth, were publicly available.

title: Relationship
description: This is a database of family ties of Russian citizens. It contains 235 million records. The number of unique people in it exceeds 100 million. For each person, full name, date of birth, residential address and a list of relatives with names and dates of birth are provided. The data was obtained in 2022 by the “Eye of God” from the housing register and later became publicly available. The database contains people living in the same apartment. Most often these are relatives.

title: KreditPlus
description: In June 2020, Indonesian credit service Kreditplus suffered a data breach that exposed 896,000 user records. As a result of the leak, extensive personal information was revealed including emails, names, family composition, information about spouses, income and expenses. religion and employment information. Data provided by HIBP https://breachbase.pw/ breachbase.pw.

title: Evermotion
description: In May 2015, Polish 3D modeling website Evermotion was leaked, revealing 435,000 unique entries. The data contained addresses, emails, names, dates of birth and salted MD5 passwords.

title: ScufGaming
description: In June 2015, the gaming company ScufGaming suffered a data leak that affected 129 thousand participants. The attack exposed email addresses, usernames, full names and passwords stored as Wordpress hashes.

title: MigosMc
description: In June 2018, a SQL dump of the Minecraft server MigosMc was published, containing about 55 thousand players, including nicknames, IP addresses and passwords in the form of SHA-256 hashes.

title: Chainlink
description: In 2022, crypto company Chainlink experienced a data breach that affected 6 thousand people who pre-ordered it. The attack exposed email addresses, ETH addresses, and ETH balances.

title: Fksr
description: This is the website of the Russian Equestrian Federation. 42 thousand user records were stolen from it, including names, phone numbers, emails and dates of birth. The date of the leak is unknown.

title: RecruitMilitary
description: In June 2017, RecruitMilitary, a website designed to help veterans find jobs, suffered a data breach. The violation included full names, email addresses and phone numbers. In total, 850 thousand users were affected.

title: Gfuel
description: Gfuel is an energy drink for gaming and e-sports. In 2015, using the method of social engineering, the customer base of this company was obtained. The data was directly exported through the Shopify admin panel. The leak contains first names, last names, email addresses, physical addresses and phone numbers. A total of 160 thousand records.

title: Cristalix.pe
description: At the end of 2019, the server for the mobile game MineCraft called Cristalix.pe was hacked. The leak contained 561,000 records in the form of two SQL dumps. The databases included emails, nicknames and MD5 passwords without salt. Earlier, in 2016, another leak occurred, but this time on the computer version of this server.

title: RussianСrime
description: This database contains the names of all convicted criminals in Russia, as well as their dates of birth, regions and articles of the sentence. Data refer to 2020. Most likely, the database was obtained by parsing government websites.

title: Sirena 2019
description: Sirena Travel is the largest air ticket booking system. It suffered leaks in 2003, 2005, 2006, 2016 and 2019. This is the latest leak, affecting 6.4 million users and publishing data from 16.3 million flights. The leak included names, dates of birth, passport details and flight routes.

title: Serasa Experian
description: At the end of 2020, data from a Brazilian credit analysis company known as Serasa Experian was leaked online. The violation included CPF numbers, full names, gender and dates of birth. In total, 223 million users were affected. The file was originally published by a hacker known as JBR.

title: Pipl
description: In June 2019, Pipl, "the world's leading provider of identity services for professional investigations and identity verification applications," suffered a breach that affected 49.5 million records. The leak included names, emails, cars, phone numbers and home addresses. The data was likely purchased from Pipl & LexisNexis and then provided to one of their clients.

title: Appen
description: In June 2020, an AI training company called "Appen" suffered a data breach. The data of 5.9 million users was exposed and subsequently sold online. The data included email addresses and passwords as bcrypt hashes. Some records also contained employers' phone numbers and IP addresses.

title: BellTreeForums
description: In January 2016, a data leak occurred on the Animal Crossing gaming forum BellTreeForums. The breach included email addresses, usernames and passwords stored as vBulletin hashes. In total, 97.6 thousand users were affected.

title: AnabelLee
description: Around January 2022, online clothing store Anabel-Lee suffered a data breach. The breach included email addresses, usernames, physical addresses, phone numbers and passwords in Wordpress hashes. In total, 20.5 thousand clients were affected.

title: Vniirapsa.ru
description: At the beginning of 2023, the database of the Lipetsk Research Institute was posted on a hacker forum. The file contains 26 thousand lines and nicknames, emails and passwords in the form of hashes.

title: KFC
description: In May 2022, a leak from the Chinese branch of the fast food chain K.F.C. appeared online. The leak contains 5.2 million records and includes phone numbers, emails, names, addresses and gender of users who ordered home delivery.

title: Alfabank
description: In October 2023, it became known that Alfabank was hacked by the NLB hacker team. They published only 650 thousand records with names, phone numbers and emails, but they claim that the full database contains more than 20 million records.

title: Glofox
description: In March 2020, Irish gym management software company Glofox suffered a data breach. 2.3 million membership records were exposed. The data included email addresses, names, phone numbers, gender, dates of birth, and passwords in the form of unsalted MD5 hashes.

title: ZdravCity
description: In February 2022, information appeared about a possible hack of the Russian online pharmacy Zdravcity.ru. The company strongly denied this leak. Later, when the leaked file was published, it contained more than 10 million records. The leak contains names, phone numbers, emails, dates of birth and addresses of pharmacies used by customers.

title: Beeline 2017
description: Russian mobile operator Beeline was leaked in 2015, 2017, 2018, 2019 and twice in 2021. This leak occurred in 2017. The database contains names, addresses, information about connected Internet tariffs and one or two phone numbers. In total there are about 5.5 million people.

In late 2011, a series of data breaches in China affected up to 100 million users, including 7.5 million from the gaming site 17173. The data in the breach contained usernames, emails and passwords in plain text.

title: GamesOfDesire
description: In December 2021, the adult gaming site Games of Desire suffered a data breach that affected 313 thousand members. The breach exposed usernames, email addresses, gender and passwords in plain text.

title: DivXSubTitles.com
description: Around 2010, the now-defunct DivX SubTitles website suffered a data breach that exposed 783,000 user account details, including email addresses, usernames and text passwords.

title: Krasnodar residents 2016
description: In 2016, a list of residents of the Krasnodar region in Russia was obtained from an unknown source. The database contains the name, date and place of birth, as well as the date of death, if present.

title: Rainbow Gmail Combolist
description: This is a collection of Gmail emails and passwords obtained from various leaks. It was published in August 2022 on a hacker forum and contained 283 thousand lines.

title: Sirena 2005
description: Sirena Travel is the largest air ticket booking system. Around 2005, it suffered a passenger data breach that affected 3 million customers. The published database included full names and passport details.

title: RusProfile.ru
description: This Russian service allows you to check companies and legal entities, as well as to comply with the Inn search.In 2024, the data of this site was collected using parsing, which was convinced to get 3.6 million records.The base contains a phone, name, address, Inn, type of activity, income given about the authorized balance sheet and other information.

title: Iran Telegram
description: In the spring of 2022, a database of Telegram users from Iran appeared online. It contained 42 million unique entries, likely obtained through scraping. Data dates back to early 2020. The database contains telephone numbers, telegram IDs, specified names, surnames and usernames, as well as the dates of collection of this information.

title: CafePress
description: In February 2019, custom goods retailer CafePress suffered a leak. 23 million emails revealed. Some records contain names, physical addresses, phone numbers, and passwords as SHA-1 hashes.

title: GetСontact
description: In 2021, a database containing 50 million Russian and 9 million Ukrainian phones became publicly available. Each telephone number was accompanied by names under which it was stored in telephone books. The source is unknown, but most likely this is a partial leak of GetContact, a service that allows you to find out what names you are listed under in other people's phone books.

title: DragonNest
description: Around August 2013, the fantasy MMORPG DragonNest suffered a data leak. The breach included bios, email addresses, gender, geographic location, IP addresses, usernames and passwords stored as plaintext hashes. In total, 3.1 million users were affected.

title: VK.com 2012
description: One of the biggest leaks from the VKontakte social network. It happened in 2012, but the leak became known much later. The database, distributed in several different variations, contains more than 100 million accounts and information about names, emails, phone numbers and other profile data.

title: Weee
description: In February 2023, data belonging to the Weee service, which delivers Asian and Latin American food, appeared on a hacker forum. Data going back to mid-2022 included 1.1 million unique email addresses from 11 million order lines containing names, phone numbers and shipping instructions.

title: Preen.me
description: In May 2020, social media marketing company Preen.Me suffered a ransom attack that resulted in its database being made public. The attack exposed more than 236,000 unique email addresses, along with usernames and links to social media profiles.

title: DoomWorld
description: In October 2022, the DoomWorld foursome suffered a data leak that exposed the records of 34,000 members. The data included email and IP addresses, usernames, and bcrypt password hashes.

title: BloomsToday.com
description: In April 2024, a database of clients of the American flower and gift delivery service “Blooms Today” was made publicly available. The leak contains 15 million records with names, phone numbers, emails, addresses and payment card data. A few days before publication, the base was sold for 5 thousand dollars.

title: Opdex.ru
description: In March 2020, the now defunct Minecraft server OpDex was hacked. The data contains IP addresses, nicknames and passwords in plain text. A total of 83 thousand records.

title: LevelTravel
description: The online service level.travel, which aggregates data from tour operators, was hacked in December 2022 by the NLB hacker team. The data of 900 thousand customers and 400 thousand orders became publicly available. Including emails, names, phone numbers, passport details and bcrypt passwords.

title: Universarium
description: Around November 2019, a leak occurred in the Russian “Distance Preparatory Faculty of IT Specialties” Universarium. 565 thousand emails, addresses and passwords without hashes were revealed.

title: DengiSrazy.ru
description: In March 2023, it became known that one of the largest Russian credit history bureaus, nbki.ru, had been hacked. Initially, only half a million records were published, but very soon the full version of the database, 46 million rows in size, also became publicly available. True, this database appeared as belonging to the Dengi Immediate MFO, and therefore the exact origin of the leak is unknown.

title: Hub4Tech
description: Around 2017, Indian training and assessment service Hub4Tech suffered a data breach due to SQL injection. injection attack. The incident revealed nearly 37 thousand unique email addresses and passwords in the form of unsalted MD5 hashes. No response was received from Hub4Tech.

title: Short Edition
description: In June 2021, French short fiction publisher ShortEdition suffered a data breach. As a result, 505 thousand records were disclosed. Affected data included email addresses, physical addresses, usernames, phone numbers, dates of birth, gender, and passwords in the form of salted SHA-1 or SHA-512 hashes.

title: Dostaevsky.ru
description: Dostaevsky is a Russian food delivery service. In January 2024, information began to spread that the database of users of this service was made publicly available last summer. The data contains about 3 million phone numbers, as well as emails, addresses, order data and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes without salt.

title: Users Online Casino
description: There is a publicly accessible database associated with an unknown online casino. The file contains information about 150 thousand users; the data contains only emails and names in English.

title: SemHora
description: In August 2016, the Brazilian concert site SemHora suffered a data leak that affected 206 thousand members. The breach exposed full names, email addresses, dates of birth, gender and orders. Now this site no longer exists.

title: Yandex Parsing 2022
description: In 2022, using parsing, user data was collected from the Yandex reviews website. About 5 million records with phone numbers, nicknames and profile links were received.

title: Contact-Center.su
description: In 2019, a website that offers call center services for businesses suffered a data leak. The leak affected about 80 thousand records, including emails, names and passwords in the form of SHA-256 hashes.

title: SandPex
description: In July 2021, the Minecraft server SandPex suffered from a leak that affected 340 thousand players. The data included nicknames, IP addresses and passwords in the form of AuthMe hashes. The server was previously hacked at the beginning of 2020.

title: RuZakaz
description: In May 2017, a leak occurred on the RuZakaz website. This is a search and information system that made it possible to obtain information about tenders, government procurement and auctions, as well as about the companies participating in them. The leak contains 240 thousand records. Data includes names, telephones, mails, addresses and company names, INN and other information.

title: Kvartelia.ru
description: Kvartelia is a Russian portal for advertisements about the sale and rental of real estate. In 2023, using parsing, about 10 million records with names, phone numbers, cities of residence and links to profiles were collected from it.

title: Chegg
description: In April 2018, textbook rental service Chegg suffered a leak that affected 40 million subscribers. The data included email, usernames, and passwords in the form of unsalted MD5 hashes.

title: LottedDreamTogether.com
description: The website LottedDreamTogether.com, dedicated to the educational Olympics, suffered from a data leak in April 2021, information about 19 thousand users was leaked to the network. Emails, phone numbers, addresses, full names, IP addresses and MD5 hashed passwords were exposed.

title: MoonMc.ru
description: In 2019, the MoonMc website of the MineСraft game server suffered from a data leak and a database containing 90 thousand users was leaked onto the network. It included nicknames, IP addresses, server names and passwords in the form of AuthMe hashes.

title: naz.api
description: This database was created by extracting data from stealer logs. It contains data about saved logins and passwords in users' browsers. It contains 270 million unique records.

title: DangDang
description: In 2011, Chinese e-commerce site Dangdang suffered a data breach. The incident revealed 4.8 million unique email addresses that were subsequently sold online several years later.

title: FinCup.ru
description: Fincup.ru company is a credit broker that provides online lending services. She was the victim of a data breach in 2019. The database included names, email addresses and phone numbers of users. The leak occurred due to unauthorized access to the company's database.

title: BehForum.com
description: This is an Iranian forum dedicated to music. It was hacked in November 2019. The published leak contains 260 thousand records with emails, nicknames, IP addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: Experian 24M
description: In August 2020, credit bureau Experian leaked consumer data. However, the incident was not related to hacking. Instead, the scammer posed as one of Experian's customers, and the credit bureau employee willingly handed over the data to him. The leak included 24 million records and contained emails, phone numbers, names and addresses of users.

title: School Bars Group
