description: In 2022, there was a major leak from a Russian website for maintaining electronic diaries and journals for schoolchildren. The names, telephone numbers, emails, addresses, passport details and social security data of students and staff were published. The leak contains 7 million records, of which a little more than three million are unique people.

title: Unistroy
description: Unistroy is a Russian construction company. Its hacking became known in March 2023. The leak contains 50 thousand records with emails, phone numbers and client names.

title: 2GIS 2020
description: This is a parsing of 2GIS online maps containing the company data indicated on it. Was collected and published between 2019 and 2020. The data contains contact telephone numbers and emails of companies, as well as their addresses, names and categories to which they belong.

title: Avito 2014
description: In 2014, more than 6 million ads were collected from the Russian Avito marketplace using parsing. The data includes names, phone numbers, addresses, and items for sale.

title: VivaAir Columbia
description: In March 2022, the now-defunct Colombian airline Viva Air suffered a data breach and subsequent ransomware attack. Among many other data obtained through the hack, the incident revealed a log of 2.6 million transactions with 932 thousand unique email addresses, physical and IP addresses, names, phone numbers and partial credit card information (last 4 digits).

title: Okru.ru
description: User data from the Okru.ru message board, published in early 2022. Includes 200 thousand records with emails, logins, names, phone numbers and passwords. Origin unknown.

title: Sprashivai.ru
description: In May 2015, Sprashivay.ru reported that 6.7 million user data had been exposed. The site, created for the expression of anonymous opinions, contained emails, dates of birth and other personal information.

title: Tramontana.ru
description: This is a tourist equipment store in St. Petersburg. In 2024, a leak from this site containing emails, names and phone numbers of clients was publicly available. A total of 32 thousand records.

title: MrExcel
description: In December 2016, the Microsoft Excel forum suffered a data leak. The hack resulted in the disclosure of more than 366,000 accounts, as well as email and IP addresses, dates of birth and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes.

title: Zakupki.prom.uz
description: In January 2023, the website for government procurement of Uzbekistan suffered from a leak. Data on 36 thousand users was exposed, including emails, phone numbers, full names, nicknames, addresses and salted MD5 hashed passwords.

title: TrueCaller India
description: In February 2019, the "world's best caller ID and spam blocking app" Truecaller suffered a data breach affecting 286 million Indian users. Phone numbers, phone operators, full names, genders, locations, job titles, company names, emails, websites, Facebook handles, and Twitter usernames were revealed.

title: MelonCraft
description: In 2019, the Minecraft server MelonCraft was hacked. The leak contains 660 thousand player nicknames, as well as their IP addresses and passwords in the form of AuthMe hashes.

title: Diva Chix
description: Around February 2022, the online fashion game Diva Chix suffered a data leak. The violation included ages, biographies, email addresses, geographic locations, IP addresses, names, social media profiles, usernames and passwords as unsalted MD5 hashes. In total, 376 thousand users were affected.

title: AvtoShina24.ru
description: In January 2024, AvtoShina24, a website selling car tires, suffered from a leak. Information about 32 thousand users was exposed, including full names, phone numbers, emails and addresses.

title: Oxfam.org.au
description: In January 2021, Oxfam Australia was the victim of a data breach that exposed 1.8 million unique email addresses of the charity's supporters. The data was put up for sale on a popular hacker forum and also included names, phone numbers, addresses, gender and dates of birth. In some cases, partial credit card and other banking information was exposed. The data was later made publicly available on a hacker forum.

title: Artsy
description: In April 2018, the online art database Artsy suffered a data breach that was subsequently put up for sale on the darknet market. More than 1 million accounts were affected, including IP addresses, email addresses, names and passwords in the form of hashes with SHA-512 salt.

title: Nadpo.ru
description: On May 15, 2022, the National Academy of Continuing Professional Education was hacked. The leak contains 57 thousand applications that contain names, phone numbers and cities of users.

title: BreachForums.to
description: In the fall of 2022, on the popular BreachForums Darknet-resource, data leaks occurred, which led to the disclosure of 212 thousand records containing user names, mail, date of birth, as well as passwords in the form of hash.

title: ChqBook
description: In September 2020, Indian banking website ChqBook suffered a data breach, affecting 4.8 million users. The leak included home addresses, email addresses, full names, phone numbers and passwords as bcrypt hashes.

title: Dobigpgt.com
description: Leak from Indian digital agency Dobigpgt. Occurred in January 2023. Contains 125 thousand records with emails, phone numbers, names, company names, positions and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: Habibs
description: In August 2021, a well-known food delivery app and restaurant known as "Habib's Food Restaurant" suffered a data breach. The violation included full names, dates of birth, email addresses, CPF numbers and IP addresses. In total, 3.6 million users were affected.

title: ForumCommunity
description: On an unknown date around 2017, Indian training and assessment service Hub4Tech suffered a data breach due to SQL injection. The incident revealed almost 37 thousand unique email addresses and passwords stored as unsalted MD5 hashes. No response was received from Hub4Tech.

title: Xploder.net
description: The platform that provides gamers with tools for cheats and modifications in video games, Xploder, suffered a data leak in late 2014. A database containing about 109 thousand records was made publicly available, including emails, nicknames, IP addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: Kwork
description: In March 2022, user data of the Kwork freelance services exchange occurred. 166 thousand emails, usernames and passwords were published in the form of MD5 hashes.

title: MoneyVeo.ua
description: In 2017, there was a data leak from the Ukrainian online loan service Moneyveo.ua. The database contained 256 thousand customer records, including full names, dates of birth, phone numbers, email and passport information.

title: Zvonili
description: Zvonili.com is a Russian site for aggregating reviews of phone numbers, mainly related to spam and scams. On April 20, 2023, all available information was collected from it, including 228 thousand telephone numbers, 367 thousand comments to them and 251 thousand nicknames of the authors of these comments. The database also contains the rating and classification of telephone numbers.

title: Avito 2020
description: In May 2020, the Russian advertising website Avito suffered a data leak that affected 9.2 million users. The violation included names, phone numbers, addresses, names and messages. Most likely the database was obtained through parsing.

title: 5turistov (part)
description: 5turistov.ru - hotel booking service for destinations in the Krasnodar region. In 2022, there was a leak on it, during which 280 thousand accounts were compromised. The data included telephone numbers, emails, names and dates of birth.

title: Duolingo
description: This is one of the most famous sites for learning foreign languages. In January 2023, through a vulnerability in the site's API, the data of 2.6 million users was downloaded from it. During the “hacking,” the hacker simply went through various emails and obtained logins, user names, registration dates, countries of residence, studied and native languages. The leak was published in August 2023.

title: BearBike.ru
description: This is a Russian bicycle store. The leak contains 10,000 records with emails, names, phone numbers, quantity and amount of orders. The date of the leak is unknown.

title: Imgur
description: In September 2013, the online image sharing community imgur suffered a data breach. In November 2017, a data set containing 1.7 million email addresses and passwords was published. The original hashes were cracked and the passwords were in clear text. imgur reports that they switched to bcrypt hashes in 2016.

title: Zunal.com
description: In 2019, about half a million user entries were published, obtained from the website Zunal.com, which provides online erudition quests. The data contains emails, names, dates of birth and passwords in plain text.

title: UkrSotsBank 2017
description: In 2017, there was a leak from a large Ukrainian bank, affecting 1.5 million people. The data contains names, phone numbers, emails and TIN numbers.

title: NeedMine
description: At the end of 2017, NeedMine, a server for the game MineCraft, was hacked. 600 thousand entries were published with player nicknames, their IP addresses, a small number of emails and passwords in the form of AuthMe hashes.

title: Boesner
description: In March 2019, the French arts and crafts store Boesner suffered a data leak that affected 78.5 thousand users. The leak exposed full names, dates of birth, email addresses, physical addresses and passwords stored as unsalted MD5 hashes.

title: Parfems.sk
description: The online store from Slovakia, specializing in the sale of perfumes and cosmetics of famous brands, in 2020, leaked data, which affected more than 231 thousand users.Their mail, names and passwords in the form of a hash Sha1 got into the network.

title: Battlefy
description: In January 2016, there was a data leak on the esports website Battlefy. 83,000 customer records were exposed. The data included email addresses, usernames, and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes.

title: Albaset.com
description: On November 17, 2020, a leak occurred on the airline ticket website albaset.com. In total, 2.2 million users were affected, but only 10% of this data was made publicly available. Published data includes emails, nicknames, IPs and MD5 passwords with salt.

title: Mathway
description: In January 2020, math problem-solving website Mathway suffered a data breach. As a result, more than 25 million records were exposed. The data was subsequently sold on the darknet market and included names, Google and Facebook IDs, email addresses, and base64-encoded salted MD5 password hashes.

title: USA Voters
description: This collection of files contains voter databases for 27 US states. Much of this data was purchased by Omnipotent for RaidForums in 2018 (most states charge money to download voter data). The databases contain full names, addresses, telephones, emails and parties selected during voting.

title: MamCupy.com
description: In August 2023, the clothing and souvenir website MamCupy was hacked. About 140 thousand lines were published with names, emails, phone numbers, addresses, work data and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: SamuTech
description: SamuTech is an application for identifying spammers' phones. In 2023, a database of this service appeared on the network, obtained through parsing. It contains phones, numbers and spam rating as a number from 0 to 5, where 0 means no spam was detected, and 5 means there is a lot of spam from this phone. The database contains 5.7 million phones.

title: NumPass 80M
description: In August 2023, a fresh collection of Russian phone numbers and passwords appeared online, which were used by their owners on various websites. The database contains 80 million records and is a combination of leaks and stealer data.

title: USA Consumer Optin 28 million
description: In early 2023, a database called “USA Consumer Optin” began to circulate online. It contained the data of 28 million US citizens and was positioned as a spam database. Despite the fact that it can be easily downloaded for free, it is actively sold on the Internet for hundreds of dollars. The database contains emails, phone numbers, names, addresses and other data obtained from various sources.

title: EpicBot
description: In September 2019, EpicBot, the bot provider for the game RuneScape, suffered a data breach that affected 817,000 subscribers. The leak data was subsequently published on a popular hacker forum and included usernames, email addresses, IP addresses and passwords in the form of salted MD5 or bcrypt hashes. EpicBot never responded to questions about the incident. The site was previously hacked in 2016.

title: Medi-center.ru
description: In April 2024, a leak from a Russian medical center was published. The data contains 380 thousand rows with names, emails, telephone numbers and information about health complaints.

title: Geniusu.com
description: In November 2020, a collection of data leaks was made public that contained, among other things, the GeniusU “Entrepreneur Success Platform.” The data included 1.3 million names, email addresses and IP addresses, as well as gender, links to social media profiles and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes.

title: Venmo
description: In June 2019, data on transactions of users of the Venmo application became publicly available. This is a social payments service that is used to make payments and transfer funds to friends and relatives. 7 million records were published containing names, phone numbers, emails and payment information.

title: SpecialKSpamList
description: At the end of 2015, a spam list known as the “Special K Data Feed” was discovered on the Internet, containing almost 31 million entries. Data includes names, physical and IP addresses, gender, dates of birth and telephone numbers.

title: Russian pensioners
description: In April 2022, data on Russian pensioners, mainly from Moscow, was published on a hacker forum. The data included names, dates of birth, telephone numbers, mail, region of residence and desired salary. Total 250,000 people.

title: MGTS
description: Moscow City Telephone Network (MGTS) is a Russian telecommunications company affiliated with MTS. In 2002, data from 4 million people was collected from it. The database contains names, phone numbers and passport numbers.

title: Imavex
description: In August 2021, website development company Imavex suffered a data breach. As a result, 878 thousand unique email addresses were published. The data also included usernames, passwords, gender and partial credit card information. Hundreds of thousands of forms and orders through Imavex clients were also exposed and contained additional personal information of the senders.

title: VK 2017
description: In 2017, the data of some users of the Russian social network VKontakte was made publicly available. The published file contained 27.1 million records that contained emails, names and phone numbers of users.

title: Wanelo
description: Around December 2018, the Wanelo digital shopping mall experienced a leak. A total of 23 million unique emails were included in the hack, along with passwords in the form of MD5 or bcrypt hashes.

title: Zhilischnik.ru
description: The Russian State Budgetary Institution “Zhilishchnik” is engaged in the management and maintenance of apartment buildings. In 2021, data from this service for the last 6 years became publicly available. They contain people's names, residential addresses and from one to three telephone numbers. A total of 4.5 million entries, mostly from Moscow.

title: Kesko
description: Kesko Oyj is a Finnish holding company. At the beginning of 2018, a file containing Russian users of this company appeared on the Internet. The data includes names, phone numbers, emails, dates of birth and other information. A total of 65 thousand records.

title: 3M Combolist Russia
description: A combination of leaks from unknown Russian sites. Appeared on a hacker forum on July 5, 2022. Contains 3 million records.

title: Uznia.es
description: As a result of a data leak on the website Uznia.es, which provides educational services, a database with records of 228 thousand users appeared on the Internet. Information about full names and nicknames has been published.

title: RZD Orders
description: In April 2022, data from the website rzd.ru about train tickets was leaked online. The table contained 636 thousand records with personal information of passengers, including full names, passport details and Taxpayer Identification Number. The data also included train numbers and travel routes.

title: SexyAndFuny.com
description: SexyAndFuny.com - erotic webcam site. In January 2020, a complete dump of this site was made publicly available. The leak affected 700k users; emails, nicknames, IP addresses, dates of birth and passwords were compromised in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: Modern Business Solutions
description: In October 2016, a large Mongo database file containing tens of millions of accounts was published by Twitter. The database contained more than 58 million unique emails, as well as IP addresses, names, home addresses, gender, positions, dates of birth and telephone numbers. The data is attributed to Modern Business Solutions, a company that provides data storage and database hosting solutions.

title: Shebinchim.ru
description: In September 2022, the database of the Shebekinskaya Industrial Chemistry company became publicly available. The data contains advertising mailing data - mail, phone numbers, names, messages sent and customer responses. There are 2100 entries in total.

title: Brizol.net
description: In 2019, the database of tender participants www.brizol.net, dated 2018, began to be freely distributed online. The data contains the names of companies, their addresses and contact details - name, email and telephone. A total of 700 thousand records.

title: Att.com
description: AT&T is the largest American telecommunications company. In 2021, their services were hacked, but the database became publicly available only in March 2024. The leak contains more than 70 million records and includes the emails, names, phone numbers, addresses and insurance numbers of all customers. There are two versions of this database online with slightly different data, probably due to different processing. This is the second version, which has significantly more phones and some other fields.

title: PlutoTV
description: In October 2018, the Internet television service Pluto TV suffered a breach, which was then widely distributed in hacker communities. Pluto TV "decided not to inform users in advance about the hack." The leak contained 3.2 million unique email addresses. The data also included IP addresses, usernames, gender, dates of birth and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes.

title: SC Daily Phone Spam List
description: At the beginning of 2015, a spam list appeared, called SC Daily Phone. It contained almost 33 million records. Data included emails, names, physical and IP addresses, gender, dates of birth and telephone numbers.

title: ShareThis
description: In July 2018, social bookmarking service ShareThis suffered a data leak. The incident exposed 41 million unique email addresses, as well as names and, in some cases, dates of birth and password hashes.

title: KomInfo Indonesia
description: Since 2017, Indonesia has had a regulation that requires all SIM card holders to register their phone number with a proof of identity (KTP). In August 2022, a hacker under the pseudonym Bjorka, who became famous after the largest hacker attacks in Indonesia, reported that he had managed to steal the database of this registry with the data of all mobile phones (1.3 billion rows). The data includes telephone number, provider name, registration date and user document number.

title: Moscow Residents 2011
description: This is a list of Moscow citizens collected in 2011 from an unknown source. The data contains names, addresses, INNs, passport details, dates of birth and driver's license numbers.

title: VSantechnike.ru
description: On January 21, 2024, the online store VSantechnike.ru, specializing in the sale of plumbing equipment, was hacked, and a database containing 20 thousand user records and 11 thousand of their orders was leaked into the network. The leak contained emails, names, phone numbers, nicknames and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes, as well as information about addresses for delivery of purchases.

title: IHEC
description: In February 2019, Iraq's Independent High Electoral Commission (IHEC) suffered a data breach that affected 24.3 million voters. The attack exposed full names, dates of birth, national identification cards, document numbers, location and voting information. Initially, this data could only be read through a special program.

title: NetProspex
description: In 2016, a list of more than 33 million people received from NetProspex was leaked online. They contained personal and corporate information, including names, emails, positions and general employer information.

title: Turkey GSM Database 2023
description: In June 2023, a database of all Turkish phone numbers stolen from providers was published on a hacker forum. The data contains only a telephone number and an identification number, which plays the role of a passport in Turkey. Data dates back to 2022. A total of 116 million records.

title: Hurb
description: Around March 2019, a Brazilian travel agency suffered a data breach. The data subsequently appeared online and included more than 20 million customer records. The database contained emails, IPs, names, dates of birth, phone numbers and passwords in the form of unsalted MD5 hashes.

title: SberSpasibo (part 2)
description: On March 9, 2023, the NLB hacker group published a leak from the SberSpasibo service, the Sberbank bonus program. The published database includes emails, telephone numbers, dates of birth and information about the availability of credit cards. A total of 48.3 million records. On March 22, they published the second part of this leak, containing another 4.5 million records, which is what you see.

title: Auto-Azimut.ru
description: In March 2023, data from the Russian website Auto-Azimut.ru, which sells cars, was published. The leak affected about 23 thousand records containing user data, including full names, phone numbers, and IP addresses.

title: Clearbit
description: In April 2022, B2B data platform Clearbit suffered a data breach that affected 918 thousand records. The leak revealed email addresses, full names and social media profiles.

title: Platan.ru
description: Platan is a Russian store of components and materials for electronics production. On August 15, 2024, the site was hacked and 165 thousand users and 415 thousand of their orders were exposed to public access. The data contains names, telephone numbers, mail, delivery addresses and company names, as well as information about payment methods.

title: ShakerAndSpoon
description: Around March 2022, online drinks retailer Shaker & Spoon suffered a data breach that affected 169,000 users. The attack exposed email addresses, full names, physical addresses, phone numbers, payment methods and incomplete card information (last 4 digits and expiration year).

title: Chrono77.com
description: The Indonesian online store Chrono77.com was attacked by hackers at the end of 2019. As a result of the hack, they gained access to a database containing 300 thousand records, including emails, nicknames, IP addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes.

title: DetMir.ru
description: In October 2024, the data of 1.2 million customers of the Detsky Mir store became publicly available. The leak included both users of mobile applications for Android and iOS, as well as the website. The database contains names, phone numbers, emails, dates of purchases and bonus card numbers. The data dates back to August 2024.

title: ForeverMoto.it
description: On May 12, 2023, the database of the Italian motorcycle goods store ForeverMoto was published. The leak contains about 6 thousand users. Including full names, emails, dates of birth and passwords in the form of bcrypt or md5 hashes.

title: 000webhost
description: Around March 2015, free web hosting provider 000webhost suffered a data breach. Almost 15 million customer records were exposed. The data was sold many times and became public in October. The leak included names, email addresses and passwords in plain text.

title: rt-internet.ru
description: On September 11, 2023, applications for Internet connections were made publicly available. It was stated that they were obtained from the Rostelecom website, but most likely they were collected by a third-party aggregator. The data contains names, telephone numbers, emails and residential addresses. There are only 190 thousand unique telephone numbers, but the records themselves are much larger.

title: Inhabitants Ukraine 2022
description: A database of Ukrainian residents received at the end of 2022 from an unknown source. Contains more than 5 million records with names, dates of birth, residential addresses and TIN data of citizens.

title: BestMebelShop.ru
description: In August 2024, an SQL dump of a furniture online store website was published on one of the shadow forums, containing data from more than 100 thousand registered users, including names, addresses, emails, phone numbers and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: Magic-Custom.com
description: There was a data leak on the website Magic-Custom.com, which sells customized goods. The data of 56 thousand users was compromised, including emails, full names and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes.

title: ClubFoto.ru
description: In July 2023, a leak occurred on the Russian photo sharing site ClubFoto. The database contains 615 thousand lines and includes user names, nicknames, emails, dates of birth, IP and passwords.

title: Rydo.ru
description: In November 2024, data from the Russian Board of Ads of Rydo.ru were collected using Parsing.In total, 7 thousand records were received.The table has sellers, links to ads, prices and descriptions of goods and services.

title: FSSP 2022
description: In Russia there is the “Federal Bailiff Service” (FSSP). In 2022, it experienced two major leaks. The first resulted in 8.4 million posts being published, and the second resulted in about 100 million. Data includes names, INN addresses, and collector data. Earlier, in 2021, this service also suffered from a major leak of 87 million records.

title: ElevenTickets
description: In January 2022, the Brazilian ticket website Eleven Tickets suffered a data breach. The attack exposed email addresses, full names, phone numbers, CPF numbers and physical addresses. In total, 196 thousand users were affected.

title: JobStreet
description: In October 2017, Malaysian website lowyat.net published an article about a huge set of hacked data affecting millions of Malaysians after someone posted it for sale on forums. The data covers several leaks, including job site JobStreet. It occurred in March 2012 and affected 4 million users. Data includes emails, names, gender, dates of birth, phone numbers, addresses and passwords.

title: GameSalad
description: In February 2019, education and game creation site Game Salad suffered a data breach. The incident affected 1.5 million accounts and exposed email addresses, usernames, IP addresses and passwords in the form of SHA-256 hashes.

title: GoNinja
description: Around December 2019, gaming website GoNinja suffered a data breach that affected 5.2 million users. The breach included email addresses, IP addresses, usernames and passwords stored as Vbulletin hashes.

title: Catalyst.bigline.kharkov.ua
description: In June 2023, it became known that a large Ukrainian Internet provider had been hacked. Data from 380 thousand users was published. The leak contains emails, names, addresses and passwords in plain text.

title: Bust.net.ua
description: The Ukrainian website Bust.net.ua sells women's underwear. It suffered a hack in November 2022. 57 thousand entries were published with posts, nicknames and passwords in plain text.

title: Gaadi
description: In May 2015, there was a leak on the Indian automobile website Gaadi. 4.3 million records were found in it. The data contained usernames, email addresses, IP addresses, gender, city, and passwords stored in both plain text and MD5 hashes.

title: SKTorrent
description: In February 2016, the Slovak torrent tracking site SkTorrent was hacked and more than 117 thousand records were leaked. The data dump included usernames, email addresses and passwords stored in plain text.

title: Gainful
description: In October 2020, New York-based dietary supplement company Gainful suffered a data breach that affected 102,000 users and 305,000 orders. The breach exposed email addresses, order numbers, payment methods, and the last 4 digits of credit/debit cards (if used). Gainful never notified affected users of the threat.

title: Spim.ru
description: On October 10, 2024, on a shadow forum, a user under the nickname Shadow published a database of the online store of sleep products spim.ru. The leak included about 160 thousand customer contact records, about 400 thousand user data records and a telephone directory with about 176 thousand records. Among the compromised information were full names, phone numbers, emails, residential addresses, IP addresses, TIN/KPP of organizations, comments and customer contact history.

title: BeepXtra.com
description: In February 2015, the BeepXtra.com website, which is a cloud service for storing loyalty cards from different clubs, suffered from a hack. An SQL dump was published containing names, emails, nicknames, IP addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt. A total of 760 thousand records in several tables.

title: PrivatBank
description: In February 2021, it became known about a leak from PrivatBank, the largest bank in Ukraine. A database containing more than 40 million records was put up for sale. It contained names, dates of birth, tax identification number, telephone numbers and passport details. Later the database was published in the public domain.

title: SpaceTime
description: In November 2020, a data leak occurred on the forum of the gaming company Spacetime Studios, which affected 181 thousand participants. The breach included usernames, email addresses and passwords stored as vBulletin hashes. Shortly after, Spacetime Studios released a statement: "The Spacetime Studios team took immediate action to secure the site, address its vulnerabilities, and file a report with the FBI and our local law enforcement agencies."

title: LastCraft.net
description: The Russian minecraft server LastCraft was hacked on May 28, 2017. The data contains 166 thousand users and includes nicknames, IPs and passwords in the form of AuthMe hashes.

title: VK 2012
description: In 2012, the Russian social networking site VKontakte was hacked. 100 million accounts were exposed. The data leaked online in June 2016 and included names, phone numbers, emails and passwords in clear text.

title: AntiChat.ru
description: In August 2010, the forum of the Russian hacker community Antichat.ru suffered an information leak. The incident affected more than 40 thousand participants. The data included nicknames, emails and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes.

title: Inturist.ru
description: In July 2023, it became known that pro-Ukrainian hackers had hacked the Russian tour operator Intourist. A file containing 5.5 million lines was published. The leak contains names, phone numbers, addresses, dates of birth, passport details, citizenship and date of tourist trip. The data was heavily littered.

title: SirHurt
description: SirHurt is a site for cheaters in the Roblox game. In April 2021, it suffered a data breach that exposed the records of more than 90,000 customers. The data included email addresses, IP addresses, usernames and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes.

title: PapaJohns.ru
description: In 2015, the Russian pizza delivery service PapaJohns was hacked. Later, data from all clients containing 1.2 million records became publicly available. The leak included emails, names, phone numbers and dates of birth.

title: Neverendless-WoW
description: Somewhere in 2017-2018, a data leak occurred on the Neverendless-WoW private server, which affected 341 thousand users. The attack exposed email addresses, usernames, IP addresses and passwords as SHA-1 hashes.

title: D-apteka.ru
description: On August 19, 2024, the D-apteka online store, which delivers medicines in the Arkhangelsk region, became a victim of a data leak of 120 thousand users. The published files contained information about the full names, phone numbers and emails of clients, as well as reviews and comments with which people contacted technical support.

title: Makaan.com
description: It is an Indian online real estate portal. In March 2015, it suffered a leak that affected more than 2 million people. Emails, phone numbers and names of portal users were published.

title: Coinmama
description: In August 2017, cryptocurrency brokerage service Coinmama suffered a data breach that affected 479,000 subscribers. The leak was discovered in February 2019. Data included email addresses, usernames and passwords were stored as WordPress MD5 hashes.

title: 9lives
description: In October 2014, the (now defunct) gaming news forum 9lives.be suffered a data leak that affected 109 thousand users. The leak exposed usernames, email addresses and passwords stored as vBulletin hashes.

title: Russian Military 2021
description: On February 28, 2022, the Ukrainian organization Center for Defense Strategies published a database of Russian military personnel collected in 2021. The published file contained 120 thousand records with names, military units, personnel numbers and military ranks of soldiers. The data was a PDF document of 6616 pages. Later, this document was actively sent by mail in the form of spam.

title: Russian Driver Licenses
description: This is a database of Russian driver's licenses. It contains 12 million driver records. The data includes name, date of birth, telephone number, residential address, ID number and passport number. The leak appeared online in 2023.

title: DaniWeb
description: At the end of 2015, a data leak occurred on the technology and social site DaniWeb. The attack exposed 1.1 million accounts. Data including email and IP addresses which were also accompanied by salted MD5 password hashes. However, DaniWeb reported that "the broken password hashes and salts are incorrect" and that they have since moved to new infrastructure and software.

title: Mimisi.ru
description: The MiMiSi.ru online store sells professional hairdressing tools, accessories and hair cosmetics. In October 2019, it was hacked by a hacker, which led to the leak of 18 thousand user records and 64 thousand of their orders. The data contains telephone numbers, names, emails, passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt, as well as addresses, IP, order amounts and comments to them.

title: Ru.Tixuz.com
description: In 2016, there was an information leak on a Russian classifieds website. The breach affected about 237 thousand records, including phone numbers and regions.

title: NatoSchool
description: On December 1, 2023, a hacker group published a file containing data of 12 thousand users from the website elearning.natoschool.nato.int. This is the electronic platform of the NATO training center in Oberammergau (Bavaria). Data for each user contains name, rank, place of service, country, telephone, email and nickname. The leak likely occurred in May 2023.

title: Dunzoin
description: Around June 2019, Indian delivery service Dunzo suffered a data breach. 35 million unique email addresses were discovered, as well as names, phone numbers and IP addresses.

title: BurgerKing.ru
description: In October 2024, a hacker put up for sale on one of the forums the database of Russian clients of the Burger King mobile application. The leak, leaked on August 5, 2024, contains names, phone numbers, emails, names, dates of birth and information about orders and dishes. Only 5 million users.

title: R2Games 2015
description: In late 2015, gaming website R2Games was hacked, exposing the data of more than 22 million users. The leak contains email addresses, IP addresses, logins and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt. The site was later hacked again in 2016 and 2017.

title: Fsfera.ru
description: In October 2021, a leak affected the Russian photo service Fsfera. A total of 240 thousand records with names, emails, telephone numbers, dates of birth and IP addresses.

title: ExcaliburCraft.ru
description: ExcaliburCraft is a Russian server for the game MineCraft with mods. In early 2018, his forum was hacked and the data of 737,000 users was published. They included emails, nicknames, IP addresses, balance on the site, the number of votes for the site in the top and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes without salt. Three months later, the site administration reset all passwords.

title: Ok.ru 2024
description: In October 2024, data from users of the Odnoklassniki social network was collected by parsing the account recovery form. When parsing, the site provides the phone number, age, region of residence in clear text, as well as email and name, partially covered with asterisks. Data from 320 million previously leaked phones was collected. In 100 million cases, accounts were found registered to these phones. Based on data from other leaks, it was possible to decrypt many emails, and also add dates of birth to the database if they matched the age in the profile.

title: Bi.zone
description: "BI.ZONE" is a digital risk management company. In April 2023, 7 thousand records were hacked and published, containing emails, names, phone numbers and information about the place of work of users.

title: Gsm-Opt.ru
description: At the beginning of 2020, hackers hacked into an online store selling spare parts for GSM-OPT mobile devices. The database contains about 87 thousand user records, including full names, phone numbers, emails, and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes.

title: Rostelecom Employees
description: In June 2022, a list of all employees of the Internet provider Rostelecom, received at the beginning of 2021, became publicly available. The data contains 109 thousand records. The table contains the name, email in the rt.ru domain, position, several telephone numbers and other information.

title: Adengi.ru
description: In March 2024, it became known that several microfinance organizations had been hacked at once. 6.8 million customer records were stolen from Adengi. The data contains names, phone numbers, emails, cities of residence, dates of birth and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes.

title: Svyaznoy.ru
description: The Russian online electronics store Svyaznoy experienced a hack that affected about 10 thousand customers. The stolen data included full names, phone numbers, addresses and credit card information. The date of the leak is unknown.

title: Osp.ru
description: In March 2023, a database dump of the website of the IT publishing house Open Systems was put up for sale on a shadow forum. The database, published later, contained 120 thousand records with names, emails, telephone numbers and places of work of users.

title: MGM Resorts
description: In July 2019, MGM Resorts (a chain of resorts and casinos) discovered a data leak in one of its cloud services. The leaks included email and physical addresses, names, phone numbers and dates of birth. Initially, only part of the database was published, but later all 50 million records were made publicly available. The data includes dates of birth, email addresses, names, phone numbers and physical addresses.

title: K-vrachu.ru
description: In 2016, a leak occurred on the Russian medical portal “To the Doctor.” The data contains names, dates of birth, emails and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes. A total of 463 thousand records.

title: Rtmis.ru
description: Rtmis is a Russian company that is engaged in the digitalization of healthcare. In November 2023, this company suffered from a hack. As a result, a database was published that contains 13 million records, including 2.3 million unique ones. True, there were several different lines per person, and therefore there were only 120 thousand unique users. The data contains names, phone numbers and dates of birth, as well as SNIs and medical policy numbers.

title: Opentable
description: The leak occurred on the website opentable.com, which specializes in selecting and ordering tables in restaurants. The leak occurred in 2020 and contained 12 million email addresses and passwords.

title: MechoDownload
description: In October 2013, the now defunct download website "Mecho Download" suffered a data leak. Because of it, 438 thousand records were disclosed. The data included email addresses, IP addresses, usernames and passwords as salted MD5 hashes.

title: Kasla.ru
description: In March 2024, the online store Kasla.ru, specializing in the sale of phones, suffered from a hack. The administration simply left the database available to everyone. At this point, an embarrassing 7 months after this was discovered, the vulnerability is still not fixed. Thus, a SQL dump containing a huge amount of mostly useless information was leaked onto the network. But it contained a table containing data from 42 thousand users. Phone numbers, full names, emails, nicknames, and bcrypt hashed passwords were compromised.

title: CaseTime.pro
description: CaseTime.pro, a website for purchasing and opening cases with prizes for Minecraft servers, suffered from a leak in 2019 that affected the data of 18 thousand users, including emails, nicknames and account balances.

title: DNR Border
description: In 2023, a database of citizens who crossed the border of the Donetsk People's Republic (DPR) began to be distributed online. The data contains about a million records and includes names, addresses, dates of birth and passport data, as well as information about the car: number, VIN, model, year of manufacture and other data.

title: Gfan
description: In October 2016, data obtained from the Chinese website GFAN surfaced containing 22.5 million accounts. The data contains email addresses, IP addresses, usernames, and salted and hashed passwords.

title: TicketCounter.nl
description: In August 2020, Dutch ticketing service TicketCounter accidentally released a database backup to a public location, where it was then found and uploaded in February 2021. The data contained 1.9 million unique email addresses that were put up for sale on a hacker forum, as well as names, physical and IP addresses, gender, dates of birth, payment history and, in some cases, bank account numbers. The data was later made publicly available.

title: CDProjektRed
description: In March 2016, Polish game developer CD Projekt RED, known for creating The Witcher and Cyberpunk games, suffered a data leak. The hack of their forum led to the disclosure of 19 million accounts, names, emails and salted MD5 passwords.

title: Sosedi.by
description: In July 2022, it became known about a leak on the Belarusian website Sosedi.by. The data of users who have a “Kupilka” loyalty card was published. In total, 634 thousand people were affected. Their emails, phone numbers, cities of residence and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt got into the network.

title: ShotBow
description: In May 2016, the Minecraft multiplayer server suffered from a leak. The incident resulted in the exposure of over 1 million unique email usernames and SHA-256 salted password hashes.

title: Pemiblanc
description: In April 2018, a Pemiblanc list containing 111 million emails and passwords was discovered on a French server. The data was collected as a result of various leaks from other services.

About 40 thousand entries were published with phone numbers and dates of logins to the site, as well as 3.4 thousand reviews of doctors indicating the patient’s name, phone number and text of the review.

title: Mr-Morgan.ru
description: This is a Russian site for men's accessories and jewelry. In early 2022, it was leaked containing 1,000 users and 10,000 of their orders. The data includes phones, names, emails, IPs, passwords in the form of SHA1 hashes with salt, delivery addresses and information about the payment method and amount.

title: YandexMaps
description: In 2022, building data on Yandex online maps was collected using parsing. A total of 1.36 million records. The data includes company names, addresses, coordinates and specified contact telephone numbers and emails, as well as some other data.

title: Vivo
description: Vivo Participacoes S.A. (Vivo) is a Brazilian telecommunications company. At the beginning of 2023, this company's database containing 28 million records appeared online. The data contains emails, phone numbers and residential addresses of users.

title: Synergy.ru
description: Synergy.ru is the official website of Synergy University, one of the largest private educational institutions in Russia. In 2023, there was a leak on it, due to which a user base containing about 700 thousand lines was published. However, there were less than 400 thousand unique entries. The data includes telephone numbers, names, emails and a small number of bank cards.

title: Eliti.ru
description: In 2020, Eliti.ru, a website selling health products, suffered from a data leak. As a result, data on 6 thousand users was exposed, including emails, full names, phone numbers and addresses.

title: R2Games 2017

title: Mirbis.ru
description: "Moscow International Higher School of Business" is one of the largest higher educational institutions in Moscow for training management personnel in the Russian business community. There is a database on the network obtained from the CRM system of this educational institution at the end of 2023. The data contains emails, phone numbers, names and a large amount of service information. A total of 55 thousand users.

title: GGCorp
description: In August 2022, the MMORPG website GGCorp suffered a data breach that exposed nearly 2.4 million unique email addresses. The breach included usernames, email addresses, IP addresses and passwords in the form of salted MD5 hashes.

title: Sirena 2006
description: Sirena Travel is the largest air ticket booking system. In 2006, it suffered a passenger data breach that affected 13 million customers. The published database included full names and passport details.

title: VK 1.2023

title: MisterCrab.ru
description: MisterCrab is a Russian store selling seafood for grilling. On April 23, 2024, a leak occurred on it, affecting 2,700 users and 7,400 of their orders. The data contains phone numbers, names, emails, IPs, passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt, and payment information.

title: AhoyGame
description: Around 2017, the gaming website AhoyGame suffered a data breach that affected 191 thousand users. The breach involved email addresses and passwords stored as Vbulletin hashes.

title: Gameturk
description: Around November 2015, the (now defunct) Turkish online gaming portal GameTurk suffered a data breach that affected 712 thousand users. The attack exposed email addresses, usernames, IP addresses, dates of birth and passwords as salted MD5 hashes (vBulletin).

title: Mnogo.uz
description: In January 2016, there was a data leak from the Uzbek entertainment portal Mnogo.uz. Information about 103 thousand users was disclosed, including emails, nicknames, IP addresses and passwords in the form of an MD5 hash with salt.

title: FlashFlashRevolution 2016
description: In February 2016, the music rhythm game Flash Flash Revolution was hacked. 1.8 million accounts were exposed. Along with email addresses and IP addresses, salted MD5 password hashes were also discovered on the vBulletin forum.

title: RealGM
description: In June 2015, a data leak occurred on the forums of the sports website RealGM, which affected 170 thousand users. The hack included usernames, email addresses, IP addresses and passwords stored as PHPass or Bcrypt hashes.

title: Avito.ma
description: Around September 2022, the advertising website Avito.ma suffered a data leak that affected 2.7 million users. The breach resulted in the disclosure of data including full names, email addresses, phone numbers, regions and IP addresses. The site was hacked through the admin panel.

title: Laguna-club.by
description: This is a Belarusian club of lovers, owners and those who are not indifferent to the Renault Laguna car. In 2022, it became known about a leak from their website, which affected 160 thousand users. The data includes emails, names, dates of birth, IP addresses and passwords in the form of salted MD5 hashes.

title: NewseaSIMS 2018

It contains 41 thousand records with names, phone numbers, emails, job and specialization data, as well as passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: Rekrute.com
description: Rekrute is a platform for finding jobs in Morocco and North Africa. In 2017, there was a leak containing 700 thousand records with personal data of users. The leak contains emails, phone numbers, names, addresses, dates of birth and passwords in plain text.

The published file included extensive information about the debtors, including their telephone numbers, full names, residential addresses, passport details and dates of birth. There were also comments in the database that clarified the nature of the debt. A total of 20 million records.

The data contains 35 million records, including names and addresses of owners, as well as vehicle data - make, model, color, year of manufacture, VIN, as well as BPKB and NIK numbers, which are used in documents as identification information.

The leak exposed usernames, email addresses, IP addresses, dates of birth and passwords stored as MyBB hashes. In total, 29.1 thousand users were affected.

title: Armenia Abonents 2007

title: OnlineTrade

title: Mira1.ru
description: Mira1.ru is a Russian museum center on Peace Square in Krasnoyarsk. In early 2023, their website suffered a leak. Because of this, 500 thousand users were compromised. The database included emails, telephone numbers, names and dates of registration in UNIX format.

description: In October 2022, it became known that the online flooring store Remontnick.ru had taken over. The data of 63 thousand clients was made publicly available. The leak includes names, emails and phone numbers.

The database contains 70 million records and includes names, date of birth, description of offenses, date of arrest and release, as well as information about appearance - skin color, hair color, presence of scars and tattoos, etc.

Twitter said the vulnerability stems from a bug introduced in June 2021. The data included publicly available information: username, display name, biography, location, and profile photo. 6.7 million email addresses were affected.

title: MangaFox

The compromised data included emails, nicknames and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes. There are about 180 thousand unique users in total, although some sources claim that there are about 300 thousand unique people in all tables.

In February 2021, 281 million records were leaked, but only 68 million records are now publicly available. The data contains names, wealth information and CPF code (Brazilian taxpayer number).

title: VeryBerrylab.ru

title: Printi.com.br
description: This is a Brazilian online service for printing materials. The date of the leak is unknown, but the dump available online contains the names, emails, phone numbers and document numbers of 600 thousand of the company’s clients.

title: Anilibria.tv

title: Nihonomaru

The data consists of 250 thousand files in xml format, containing more than 200 million users. Parsing includes names, phone numbers, addresses, statuses, education, hobbies, religion, avatars and other information specified in profiles.

The data contains phone numbers, names, emails, addresses, order amount and comments on it. Only 10 thousand orders. The exact date of the hack is unknown.

Later it turned out that this database was simply collected by parsing the bot’s eye and is not the base of its users.

title: xfit.ru

The attack resulted in the disclosure of data including full names, physical addresses, mobile phone serial numbers, Pakistani CNIC ID number, phone IMEI details and phone numbers.

title: MoniDays

title: Redem
description: In April 2022, a gift card selling and purchasing website known as Redem suffered a data breach affecting 23.6 thousand members. The leak exposed email addresses, full names, usernames, phone numbers and passwords stored as Bcrypt hashes.

title: Microsoft
description: In June 2022, a list of emails and passwords of Microsoft users was published using a hacker formula. This list contained 54 million rows and was obtained by combining data from many other leaks.

A company specializing in software development, supply of office equipment and IT business support leaked personal data, including phone numbers, full names and emails.

title: NapsGear

The data includes email addresses, names, addresses, phone numbers, purchase histories and passwords in the form of salted MD5 hashes.

title: RuniquePS

title: GitHub
description: In 2016, GitHub, the largest site for developing and publishing software, was scraped. About two million records were collected with emails, nicknames, names, and other publicly available information about users.

title: BourseDesVols
description: Around January 2021, French flight booking site Bourse des Vols (bdv.fr) suffered a data breach that affected 1.4 million subscribers. The leaked items included IP addresses, email addresses, physical addresses, phone numbers, flights booked, flights taken, purchase logs, dates of birth, payment methods used and partial credit card information.

title: Corbina.net
description: In September 2021, subscriber data of the Ukrainian provider corbina.ua (owned by Beeline) was made publicly available. A total of 1.4 million records. The data contains names, dates of birth, addresses and passport details.

title: Convex
description: Convex is a Russian telecommunications service. At the beginning of 2023, it suffered from a data leak, during which a complete dump of its server (119Gb of data) was published. As a result of the leak, 80 thousand users were affected. Emails, phones, addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes were compromised.

title: HomeRefill
description: In April 2020, Brazilian shopping site HomeRefill suffered a data breach that affected 194 thousand users. The attack exposed email addresses, full names, phone numbers, dates of birth and passwords in the form of SHA512 hashes. The hack was caused by an incorrectly configured aws s3 bucket.

title: 500px

title: Zarina.ru
description: This is a Russian clothing store. In September 2023, the database of this site was posted on the Telegram channel of a hacker group. Entries contain names, emails and telephone numbers. A total of 932 thousand people.

title: QuestApp

The leak includes about 700 thousand users, contains 522 thousand unique email addresses, dates of birth, gender, marital status, names, phone numbers and passwords, saved as MD5 and bcrypt hashes.

title: Uralchem
description: Uralchem ​​plant employee base. Was received in September 2022, contains 5.5 thousand people. Names, phone numbers, emails, addresses and positions.

title: Ajarn.com

In February 2018, a huge collection of nearly 3,000 suspected data breaches was discovered online. Each file contained an email address and text passwords.

title: VK 2013
description: In 2013, data from the Russian social network VKontakte was collected using scraping. A SQL dump with this data was later published. It included names, phone numbers, dates of birth, marital status and links to avatars. A total of 16.1 million rows.

title: Vietloan.vn
description: This is a large Vietnamese microfinance organization that was hacked in early 2024. As a result of this incident, more than 2 million records with names, emails, phone numbers, dates of birth and insurance information were published. All data was made publicly available along with several other leaks from microfinance organizations.

title: NNM-club.ru
description: This is one of the most popular Russian torrent trackers. It was hacked in September 2013, affecting nearly 3.5 million users. Emails, nicknames, IP addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes were made publicly available.

title: Suppliers
description: This database contains a list of product suppliers obtained from an unknown source. The data contains 460 thousand lines and includes names, company names, addresses, mails, telephone numbers and TIN of organizations.

title: Metro-cc.ru
description: Some sources claim that in 2017, the Metro-cc.ru website suffered from a data leak. The names of the companies, the names of their directors, addresses and telephone numbers were published. However, almost all entries in the database overlap with the subscriber database, and therefore the leak seems very doubtful. The database contains about 70 thousand rows.

title: GameTuts
description: Apparently in early 2015, video game site GameTuts suffered a data breach that exposed over 2 million user accounts. The exposed data included usernames, email addresses and IP addresses, as well as salted MD5 hashes of passwords.

title: YoudaGames.com

title: VolgoFarm.ru
description: On May 16, 2023, it became known about a data leak from the Russian pharmacy VolgoFarm.ru. The published database contained 75 thousand records about clients, but there is also a private database with 220 thousand records. The leak included phone numbers, emails, names, order dates and payment amounts.

title: FoxyBingo
description: In April 2007, the online gambling site Foxy Bingo was hacked and hackers obtained 252,000 accounts. The data was subsequently sold and included plain text passwords, dates of birth and home addresses.

title: CrossFire
description: In August 2016, the Russian gaming forum Cross Fire was hacked, along with a number of other mail.ru forums. The vBulletin forum contained 128 million names, email addresses and passwords in the form of salted MD5 hashes.

This is the second collection, it was the largest of all and contained 20 thousand files with a total size of 526 GB. These files contained 15.8 billion lines with emails and passwords, but there were only 3.2 billion unique pairs.

title: BSI Bank

title: Houzz

title: makcm.ru
description: In 2018, a leak occurred in the Russian health insurance service MAKS-M. The data includes names, phone numbers, addresses, SNI, passport and medical insurance data, dates of birth and other information. There are 10 million entries in total, but the actual number of people is much lower since there are multiple entries per person.

title: JahForum.org
description: The website for the sale of prohibited substances JahForum.org suffered a cyber attack in May 2024, as a result of which the data of more than 100 thousand users was obtained. The compromised information included emails, addresses, nicknames and IP addresses.

title: AmplitudeStudios

title: 1 1111.com.tw

title: 100k Private Combos - Chinese Porn
description: Kombolist, collected from Chinese erotic sites and published in 2022. Contains only emails and passwords. Total 100,000 lines.

title: BukalaPak

The incident exposed approximately 13 million unique email addresses, as well as IP addresses, names and passwords in bcrypt and SHA hashes. 512 with salt.

title: Rambler

title: RailYatri

title: GamingMonk
description: In December 2020, there was a data leak in the Indian esports community GamingMonk. The breach included usernames, full names, email addresses, dates of birth and passwords stored as bcrypt hashes. A total of 609 thousand users were affected.

title: DeviousPk
description: In September 2014, a data leak occurred on the RuneScape DeviousPk server (now defunct), affecting 5.7 thousand participants. The breach included usernames, email addresses, IP addresses and passwords stored as vBulletin hashes.

title: ActMobile
description: In October 2021, an open database was discovered, which was later linked to ActMobile, an American VPN service. Most of the data was auto-generated data, but the database contained 1.6 million unique email addresses, as well as IP addresses and password hashes. All this data was subsequently leaked to a hacker forum.

title: BTC-E
description: In October 2014, the Bitcoin exchange BTC-E was hacked and 568 thousand accounts were compromised. The data included email addresses, IP addresses, wallet balance and hashed passwords.

title: PipingRock.com
description: In April 2024, the website PipingRock.com, which sells dubious dietary supplements in the United States, was hacked. As a result, about two million user records with emails, names, telephone numbers, residential addresses and other information were published.

title: Rostelecom
description: Around December 2021, a data leak occurred in the Russian Smart Home service owned by the Internet provider Rostelecom. The leak exposed email addresses, full names, phone numbers, IP addresses and passwords as Bcrypt hashes. In total, 712 thousand users were affected.

title: PlayTech
description: In January 2014, game provider PlayTech suffered a data breach that affected 761 thousand users. The violation included email addresses, usernames, phone numbers and physical addresses.

title: ProPostuplenie.ru
description: In March 2023, the Russian forum for university applicants propostuplenie.ru suffered from a data leak. 520,000 records were made publicly available, including names, emails, phone numbers, classes and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes. Data included students, teachers, and parents.

title: GfinityeSports.com
description: In January 2016, the database of GfinityeSports, a news resource dedicated to games, became publicly available. The data contains emails, names, dates of birth, hashed passwords and other data about users of this site.

title: Akgalleria.com
description: Akgalleria is a Pakistani clothing store. Was hacked in August 2021. The leak contains 12 thousand records and includes names, emails, phone numbers, addresses and order amounts

title: Ngs.ru
description: In March 2022, the Russian news site Ngs.ru was subjected to a large-scale DDOS attack for several days. At the same time, news appeared about a vulnerability found by attackers. Using it, they downloaded and then published the data of 18 million users. The leak included emails, names, IP addresses and passwords as MD5 hashes with a static salt.

title: Ukraine Wanted 07.2020
description: This is a list of all Ukrainian citizens who are on the wanted list due to disappearance or criminal prosecution. Was received in July 2020 and contains 54 thousand records. Records include names, emails, phone numbers, dates of birth, regions of last location, dates of disappearance and reasons for the search.

title: MemoryBreak
description: In November 2020, the Turkish game automation tool MemoryBreak suffered a data leak. The breach resulted in the disclosure of data including usernames, email addresses and passwords stored as MD5 hashes. In total, 40.7 thousand users were affected.

title: UnixForums
description: In May 2021, a data leak occurred on the unix.com forum. The hack included usernames, email addresses, IP addresses, dates of birth and passwords stored as vBulletin hashes. In total, 169 thousand users were affected.

title: BaseusRussia.ru
description: The Baseus accessories store in Russia suffered a hacker attack in 2022. The result was a data leak of 8 thousand records. It included information such as phone numbers, names, emails, nicknames, addresses and passwords, hashed using bcrypt and MD5.

title: Eldorado
description: In 2017, there was a data leak from the Eldorado electronics store. The data contains 4 tables with user data and their orders. In total there are about 8 million records containing names, phone numbers, emails, addresses, dates of birth, passport data and bonus card numbers. The leak appeared in the public domain only at the end of 2023.

title: USA Hige Leak
description: A huge database of US residents, which was originally leaked by pompompurin on the now defunct RaidForum. The source is unknown, but data from more than 250 million American citizens can be found in this database. The data contains names, addresses, telephone numbers, geolocation, home and income information, nationality, date of birth. It also contained more than 100 million emails.

title: Mover24.ru
description: On January 23, 2020, the Devicelock Data Breach Intelligence service discovered an open Elasticsearch server with the data of the Mover freight taxi selection system.The leak contained several tables with information about more than 50 thousand records containing names, telephones and addresses.

title: YouPorn
description: In February 2012, the adult site YouPorn exposed its user accounts in a hack. 1.3 million people were affected. The publicly released data included email addresses and passwords in plain text.

title: SberbankPremier
description: In March 2021, SberPremier, a premium service of Sberbank, suffered from a leak. The leak is likely related to other Sberbank hacks that occurred at the same time. The database published later contains emails, phone numbers, names, dates of birth and names of banks used by clients. There are 270 thousand records in total, but there is information about larger versions of this leak.

title: PhoneRadar
description: This is a Russian site containing reviews of fraudulent numbers. In April 2024, all data from it was collected using parsing. The resulting database contains 57 thousand phones with reviews about them and the nicknames of the authors of these reviews.

title: 1spotbet.com
description: In January 2024, the bookmaker 1spotbet suffered from a leak. 28 thousand user records were published, including their names, emails, balance data and passwords in plain text.

title: SberBank 2021
description: In 2021, there was a leak from the Sberbank user base. The published database contains 18 million records, including customer phone numbers and emails. Most likely, this database was collected from different sources.

title: Msp29.ru
description: The My Business service center provides assistance to the self-employed and entrepreneurs. It was hacked in February 2023. The leak contains 119 thousand records with names, emails, phone numbers and dates of birth of clients.

title: Anime Planet
description: Around 2016, anime website Anime-Planet suffered a data breach that affected 369 thousand subscribers. The leak contains usernames, IP addresses, email addresses, dates of birth and unsalted MD5 passwords, and for newer accounts, bcrypt hashes.

title: FSSP 2020
description: In Russia there is the “Federal Bailiff Service” (FSSP). It experienced leaks in 2020, 2021, 2022 and 2023. This is the first leak containing data from 2018 to 2020. A total of 17.8 million records. The data contains names, addresses, dates of birth and nature of debt.

title: GoHome.by
description: The Belarusian real estate portal Gohome, which helps users buy, sell and rent residential and commercial real estate, has become a victim of data leakage.As a result of this, information about more than 87 thousand records, including mail, telephones, IP addresses, nicknames, activity dates, balances, discounts and names of companies, got into the network.

title: St.Petersburg 2021
description: In 2021, there was a leak from the St. Petersburg police base. The leak contains 12 million records including names, addresses, dates of birth and passport details of city residents.

title: Steehold.com
description: In 2023, the agency that installed the Steehold security control system suffered a data leak, as a result of which about 90 thousand records were published, including names, dates of birth, document numbers, as well as information about place of work and the presence of relatives.

title: BookvoEd
description: On June 8, 2023, the NLB hacker group reported that the database of the Russian book house Bukvoed had been hacked. They published a database containing 3.5 million records. Data includes names, emails and phone numbers of buyers. The hack itself occurred in May 2023.

title: Zacks
description: In December 2022, investment research firm Zacks announced a data breach. And in June 2023, a dataset containing nearly 9 million Zacks customers became publicly available. The data includes names, emails, physical addresses, phone numbers and passwords stored as SIC hashes.

title: Filmhot.us
description: This is a Thai movie streaming site. It was hacked in November 2019. The published leak contains 36 thousand records with emails, nicknames, IP addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: Ubu.ru
description: In August 2024, the charity website Ubu.ru suffered a data leak. It was previously hacked in 2021, but this time much more data was leaked - 770 thousand records with emails, phone numbers, names, addresses, dates of birth, INN and links to social networks.

title: Altenen.st
description: A forum dedicated to carding and illegal activities suffered a data leak in June 2022. More than 56 thousand users were affected; the data included emails, nicknames and passwords in the form of a bcrypt hash.

title: Wakanim
description: In August 2022, the European streaming service Wakanim experienced a data leak that was subsequently advertised and sold on a popular hacker forum. The hack exposed 6.7 million customer records, including email, IP addresses, physical addresses, nicknames and usernames.

title: Russian America
description: Around 2017, a website for Russian-speaking Americans known as russianamerica suffered a data breach. As a result of the incident, 183 thousand unique records were exposed, including names, email addresses, phone numbers and passwords stored either in plain text or as MD5 hashes.

title: WayDate
description: In June 2016, the free dating site WayDate suffered a data leak. The breach exposed gender, IP addresses, email addresses, full names, locations, dates of birth and passwords stored in plaintext. In total, 120 thousand users were affected.

title: Collection 4
description: In January 2019, 5 collections appeared on a popular hacker forum, representing a combination of data from many other leaks. This is the fourth collection, one of the largest. It contained 40 thousand files with a total size of 178 GB. These files contained 5.4 billion lines with emails and passwords, but there were only 1.9 billion unique pairs.

title: ECCIE
description: Around January 2021, there was a data leak on the ECCIE pornography forum. The leak included email addresses, usernames, IP addresses and passwords hashed as MD5 hashes. In total, 547 thousand users were affected.

title: OrgPage.ru
description: OrgPage - directory of Russian organizations. In October 2024, the data of all companies published on this site was collected using scraping. The result was 750 thousand records with telephone numbers, company names, their descriptions and addresses.

title: Forex4you.com
description: In February 2020, the Forex4you user database became publicly available. This is a mobile application for trading on the market. The database contains 114 thousand records and includes names, regions, emails and telephone numbers. The leak is old and occurred back in 2013, but it became known only now.

title: ProShkolu.ru
description: In 2013, there was a leak of users of the Russian educational portal proshkolu.ru. The data of one million people was made publicly available. The leak included emails, phone numbers and full usernames.

title: Naykalab.ru
description: In June 2023, Ukrainian hackers hacked the Russian network of medical centers MK Nauka. They stole the data of 116 thousand users, as well as information about their appointments and list of reviews. The data contains names, emails, phone numbers, dates of birth and passwords in plain text.

title: Perevozka24.ru
description: In October 2024, ad data from the Russian website Perevozka24 was collected using scraping. The database contains 50 thousand records with names, phone numbers, emails, personal identification numbers, information about advertisements and other open information from profiles, as well as 470 thousand advertisements.

title: HSYS
description: In November 2022, Turkey's citizen health database Halk Sağlığı Yönetim Sistemi suffered a data breach that affected more than 100 million people (including living and dead). The attack exposed full names, dates of birth, general location (city and county), parents' names, and parent ID numbers.

title: Mimigram.ru
description: In July 2023, the Mimigram.ru service, which created photo books, collages and souvenirs from photographs, suffered a large-scale leak. The Internet contained a database of 52 thousand accounts, 24 thousand delivery addresses and 3 thousand customer reviews. The data included full names, emails, social network IDs, addresses and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes.

title: Checko.ru
description: Checko is a Russian website for checking companies and legal entities. In 2024, about a million company records were collected from it using parsing. The data contains several emails and telephone numbers, addresses, company names, names of directors and founders, type of activity, number of employees, income and other data.

title: BleachAnime
description: In January 2015, the now-defunct anime forum Bleach suffered a data leak that affected 145 thousand users. The leak included usernames, email addresses and passwords as salted MD5 hashes.

title: AllWomensTalk
description: Around January 2016, AllWomensTalk, a website created for women to discuss various topics, suffered a data breach. The breach included usernames, email addresses and passwords in the form of phpBB hashes. In total, 200 thousand users were affected.

title: Alnassrah.com
description: This is an Iranian news site. It was hacked in November 2019. The published leak contains 80 thousand records with emails, nicknames, IP addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: Markets.com
description: In April 2023, information was leaked from the financial trading platform Markets.com. As a result of the incident, the data of 33 thousand users was compromised, including their emails, names and phone numbers.

title: HgClub.ru
description: HgClub is a Russian restaurant delivery service. It was hacked on 05/02/2022, as a result of which 106 thousand rows with order data were made publicly available. They included addresses, prices of goods, bonus card numbers and customer data - names, phone numbers and email addresses.

title: Knoppix.net
description: In June 2019, the Knoppix.net forum dedicated to the Linux OS was hacked. The leak contains 30 thousand records with emails, nicknames, IP addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: Auto-club42.ru
description: This is an online auto parts store in Kemerovo. The database of its users was made publicly available on May 15, 2022. The leak contains more than 8 thousand records with names, emails, phone numbers, cities and passwords in the form of salted MD5 hashes.

title: Eurasia.expert
description: In August 2019, the news website eurasia.expert was subject to a hacker attack, as a result of which 5 thousand records were obtained, namely full names, email addresses and cities of residence.

title: NetEase
description: In October 2015, the Chinese website NetEase, located at 163.com, was the victim of a data breach that affected 234 million subscribers. The data contains emails and passwords in plain text.

title: Trackitt.com
description: In July 2022, Trackitt's immigration status service suffered a data breach that affected 421,000 users. The breach included usernames, email addresses, IP addresses and passwords in the form of SHA1 hashes. The breach occurred because Trackitt left open the directory where they intended to upload backups.

title: Telefon-treff.de
description: In July 2020, the German forum dedicated to mobile phones and telecommunications, Telefon-treff.de, leaked data about 222 thousand users. Emails, nicknames and passwords were compromised in the form of an MD5 hash with salt.

title: Sib3ka.ru
description: The Russian minibus "Sibirskaya Troika" suffered from a hack on November 14, 2022. Hackers published a database containing 16 thousand entries. It contains phone numbers, names, dates of birth, passwords in the form of MD5 hashes and a small number of emails.

title: RUSSIA KnowEveryone
description: In June 2023, a database called “RUSSIA we know everyone” began to spread in telegram channels. Its origin is unknown, but it contains data about individual entrepreneurs and their companies. The leak size is 2.5 million rows.

title: Verified
description: In January 2014, one of the largest cybercriminal communities in Eastern Europe known as “Verified” was hacked. As a result of the hack, almost 17,000 forum users were exposed. The leak included their private messages and other potentially personally identifiable information.

title: Wahana Express
description: Wahana is a large Indonesian transport company. At the beginning of 2022, about 17 million records of deliveries by this service were publicly available. The data contains names, addresses, data about parcels and their costs, as well as one or two phone numbers.

title: Vapstore.de
description: In August 2021, a data leak occurred at the vaporizer and e-cigarette store VAPSTORE. The violation included email addresses, full names, physical addresses, phone numbers and dates of birth. In total, 253 thousand users were affected. Please note that most email addresses are anonymous versions due to people ordering through Amazon.

title: AuphanOnline
description: In August 2017, the computer hardware verification platform Auphan Online (now defunct) suffered a data leak that affected 46.9 thousand users. The leak exposed email addresses, usernames and passwords stored as unsalted MD5 hashes.

title: FreeNavalny
description: Hackers leaked the database of those who signed up for the rally for Navalny on the website Free.navalny.com. A total of 530,000 people registered from March 23 to April 1, 2021. The hack was carried out using the API key of an ex-FBK employee, with the help of which data was pumped out from the notification distribution service.

title: UnrealEngine
description: In August 2016, the UnrealEngine forum suffered a data breach, allegedly due to a SQL injection vulnerability in vBulletin. 530,000 accounts were exposed: names, emails and password hashes with MD5 salt.

title: AmericanBeauty.club
description: In September 2022, the AmericanBeauty website, which sells American cosmetics, was hacked. The leak contains 13 thousand records with phone numbers, names, emails and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: StreetEasy
