description: Around June 2016, the real estate website StreetEasy experienced a data breach. A total of 988,000 unique email addresses were included in the leak, along with usernames and SHA-1 hashes of passwords. All data was put up for sale on the darknet trading platform in February 2019.

title: Eisz.kz
description: In October 2023, a large Kazakh government registry, Eisz, was allegedly leaked. The leak most likely occurred on the website dmed.kz. As a result of this, the hacker managed to obtain more than 28 million records with names, dates of birth, telephone numbers, addresses and passport data of citizens of Kazakhstan. However, only a portion of this leak is publicly available, containing approximately 2.3 million unique people. However, some data indicates that the leak was generated and the data is not real.

title: Poradnikzdrowie.pl
description: This is a Polish news site that publishes articles about health. It was hacked in 2019. The published leak contains 44 thousand records with emails, nicknames, IP addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: Amfr.ru
description: The Amfr.ru auto forum suffered a cyber attack in June 2023. As a result of the incident, the personal information of 30 thousand community members was disclosed. The stolen data included full names, emails, addresses, phone numbers and passwords in the form of salted MD5 hashes.

title: FaceIt
description: Sometime in 2017, the esports platform FACEIT suffered a data leak that affected 230 thousand participants. The breach included plain text email addresses and passwords. It is unknown how and by whom the site was hacked.

title: StForex.ru
description: In 2022, there was a data leak from the brokerage company StForex.ru. The database published later contained 400 thousand records with names, phone numbers and emails of clients.

title: SushiMaster.ru
description: In September 2022, a database of the Russian sushi restaurant “SushiMaster” appeared on a hacker forum. The dump contains 2.8 million records and includes emails, phone numbers, names and other customer data.

title: Voronezh-org.ru
description: In November 2024, this Russian message board was collected using scraping. 25 thousand records were received with telephone numbers, emails, names and data on goods sold.

title: OnlineGibdd
description: In June 2022, a database of the Russian service for checking fines, vehicles and drivers - OnlineGibdd - appeared for sale on one of the forums. They also sold access to their server. The leak contains 490 thousand records and includes names, phone numbers, emails, regions, double MD5 passwords and social network IDs.

title: Ragazzos
description: Around August 2021, Brazilian fast food franchise Ragazzo's Food Restaurant experienced a data breach. The information compromised included full names, dates of birth, email addresses, CPF numbers and IP addresses. A total of 936 thousand users were affected.

title: Comodo
description: In September 2019, a data leak occurred on the forums of the cybersecurity company Comodo, which affected 173 thousand participants. The breach included email addresses, usernames, IP addresses and passwords stored as MD5 hashes.

title: NexusMods
description: In December 2015, game modding site Nexus Mods released a statement notifying users that they had been hacked. They subsequently dated the hack to July 2013, although there is evidence that the data was sold several months earlier. The hack contained usernames, email addresses and passwords as salted hashes.

title: Dkwizard.ru
description: The Dkwizard.ru website was hacked in September 2022. The data contains emails, names, telephone numbers, cities of residence, work and family information. There are about 4 thousand records in total.

title: Moya-Mebel.ru
description: This is a Moscow online furniture store. In September 2022, the databases of users (2000 lines) and orders (6400 lines) were stolen from it. The data contains phone numbers, names, emails, passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt and detailed information about orders.

title: NeedSpec.ru
description: This is a Russian site to search for tutors in Moscow.In November 2024, with the help of steaming, about 400 thousand entries with these profiles were collected from this site.The base contains names, description of services, prices, links to photographs of the tutor and other information.

title: Mashable.com
description: Around mid-2020, Mashable experienced a data breach that subsequently became public in November 2020. The data included 1.4 million unique email addresses, as well as names, gender, expired authentication tokens, physical locations, links to social media profiles, and birthdays and months.

title: BigLeak Germany
description: A combination of leaks from unknown sites in Germany. Appeared on a hacker forum on May 29, 2022. Contains 33 million records.

title: LEOTVHD
description: Around January 2017, the LEOTVHD movie website suffered a data breach that affected 128 thousand members. The leak exposed data including email addresses and passwords stored as MD5 hashes.

title: Kazakhstan 2020
description: Around 2020, a leak occurred on a large government website of Kazakhstan, eGov.kz. The user data of 36 million citizens was stolen from the site, including full names, dates of birth, telephone numbers, emails, passport details and residential addresses. There are relatively few emails and telephone numbers in the database.

title: Vietnam 2019
description: In 2019, a leak occurred from the public registry of the city of Hanoi in Vietnam. The database contains about a million records with names, dates of birth, telephone numbers and emails of city residents.

title: Sogaz
description: In April 2023, an SQL dump of the Russian insurance company SOGAZ (sogaz-life.ru) appeared in the public domain. The published database contained 8.3 million rows. The records included full names, dates of birth, nicknames, telephone numbers, emails, places of work and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt. Data current as of October 21, 2022.

title: ProsapHotel
description: The hotel business automation service ProsapHotel experienced a database leak that affected more than 280 thousand accounts. The compromised information included nicknames, emails, IP addresses and MD5 hashed passwords.

title: ProCapital.ru
description: On the Russian trading and investment forum ProCapital.ru, where strategies and market analysis are discussed, in October 2017 there was a leak containing 120 thousand user records. The compromised information included nicknames, emails, IP addresses, as well as passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: diia.gov.ua
description: In February 2023, a database of the Ukrainian state system, stolen from the website diia.gov.ua, appeared for sale. The data contains 2.6 million records and includes names, phone numbers, emails, addresses, passport details and other information.

title: Pally.live
description: The online communication site Pally.live has been hacked. As a result, information about 624 thousand users became publicly available, including their nicknames, full names, emails and countries of residence.

title: ParkBench.com
description: In 2024, the American network of hyperlocal sites Parkbench became a victim of black hat hackers. As a result of the leak, 620 thousand records containing information about full usernames, emails and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes were leaked to the network.

title: ForodelGuardiaCivil
description: In September 2022, a data leak occurred on the Spanish forum Foro del Guardia Civil, affecting 233 thousand users. The leak exposed usernames, email addresses, dates of birth, IP addresses and passwords stored as vBulletin hashes. Due to the website not using captcha, there are many bot entries.

title: Pampling
description: In January 2020, online T-shirt website Pampling suffered a data breach that affected 383,000 users. The leak exposed email addresses, full names, usernames and passwords as MD5 hashes.

title: Tianya
description: In December 2011, China's largest online forum, Tianya, was hacked and the attacker gained access to tens of millions of accounts. The leak included usernames and email addresses.

title: Vk.pay
description: In 2022, data from users of the Russian payment system Vk.pay was collected using parsing. The file contains 164 thousand phone numbers and names, which are displayed when you try to translate them.

title: HTC Mania
description: In January 2020, the Spanish mobile phone forum HTC Mania suffered a data breach. Due to the incident, 1.5 million email addresses of participants were exposed, as well as usernames, IP addresses, dates of birth, salted MD5 password hashes and password histories. The leak data was subsequently distributed on popular hacker sites.

title: Funimation
description: In July 2016, Funimation's anime website suffered a data breach that affected 2.5 million accounts. The data contained usernames, emails, dates of birth and passwords in the form of SHA-1 hashes with a salt.

title: MyPirata
description: In December 2019, the now-defunct anime forum MyPirata suffered a data leak that affected 503,000 members. The breach included usernames, email addresses, IP addresses and passwords stored as MD5 hashes.

title: TopBanki.ru
description: In July 2022, a complete dump of the TopBanki website appeared in the public domain, which aggregates information about offers from different banks. The data contains about 60 thousand reviews, including emails, names, IP addresses and comment texts.

title: Pikabu
description: In February 2022, the database of the entertainment website Pikabu became publicly available. Initially, it contained 4 million encrypted data, 1 million of which were decrypted and published. Contains nicknames, emails and phone numbers.

title: Walmart
description: Walmart is a wholesale and retail chain. At the end of 2018, a data leak of its users of unknown origin appeared on the network. The leak contains 3.2 million emails and their passwords in clear text.

title: Social-apteka.ru
description: On August 29, 2023, the Social Pharmacies network suffered from a data leak. Files with data from 140 thousand users and 330 thousand of their orders were published. The data includes phone numbers, emails, names, dates of birth, passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes, pharmacy addresses and comments on orders.

title: Sapato.ru
description: Sapato is a Russian spare parts store. There is a leak on the Internet from this site dating back to 2014 and containing more than a million lines with names, emails and addresses of clients.

title: BestHack
description: In December 2016, a data leak occurred on the Russian hacker forum Best-Hack, which affected 70 thousand users. The breach included usernames, email addresses and passwords in the form of vBulletin hashes.

title: MFO Application
description: In early 2024, a database of users of an unknown microfinance application, presumably OneClickMoney, appeared online, the site of which was hacked around the same time. The data contains about 13 million records, although the number of unique users is noticeably lower. The data includes names, emails, passport details, addresses, information about work, income, loan amount and insurance. Also, up to 4 phone numbers were known for each user.

title: YandexFood
description: In February 2022, the Russian food delivery service Yandex Food suffered a data leak that affected 49.4 million orders. The leak revealed emails, phone numbers, full names, physical addresses, delivery instructions and spending amounts. A class action lawsuit was filed against the company, as a result of which Yandex paid a fine of 60,000 rubles ($500 at that time). One cent per 1000 entries.

title: RaidForums.com
description: RaidForums is the most famous hacker forum, active since 2015. It was closed on April 12, 2022 after its creator was arrested. Later, on May 30, 2023, the database of its participants, collected on September 24, 2020 as a result of hacking, was made publicly available. The database contains 478 thousand entries and includes names, emails, IPs and passwords in the form of hashes with salt.

title: MMM 2011-2012
description: MMM is the largest financial pyramid in Russian history, operating in 2011-2012. A few years after its ruin, a database of users who invested money in it appeared on the Internet. The records contain customer emails and names. The base includes 1 million people.

title: 3g-mag.com.ua
description: On September 26, 2022, the Ukrainian online electronics store 3g-mag.com.ua collided with a data leak that affected more than 100 thousand users.Published records contained mail, numbers, IP addresses, names, addresses, as well as passwords in the form of a hash MD5 with salt.

title: Renault.ru
description: In September 2021, the official dealer of Renault cars in Russia suffered from a leak. 850 thousand records containing names, phone numbers and emails of clients were made publicly available.

title: Career.habr.com
description: A popular Russian platform for finding jobs in IT, created on the basis of the Habr portal. It helps employers and job seekers find each other in various IT areas, offering vacancies for programmers, developers and analysts. In 2020, platform data was collected using scraping. The resulting database contains 165 thousand profiles containing names, phone numbers, emails, links to avatars and other information.

title: Collection 1
description: In January 2019, 5 collections appeared on a popular hacker forum, representing a combination of data from many other leaks. This is the first collection found. It contained 12,300 files with a total size of 87 GB. The collection contains more than 2.5 billion lines with emails and passwords for them. There were only 1.25 billion unique rows. For many strings, the site where the leak occurred was indicated.

title: ApexSMS
description: Around April 2019, the cloud-based SMS platform ApexSMS (also known as "MobileDrip") suffered a data breach. Because of her, 88 million posts were published. The violation included full names, email addresses, physical addresses, IP addresses and phone numbers.

title: Telderi
description: In March 2022, the Russian exchange for trading domains and social network accounts Telderi.ru suffered from a data leak. Emails, telephone numbers, WebMoney wallet numbers and passwords in the form of MD5 or bcrypt hashes were made publicly available. In total, 250 thousand users were affected.

title: Articoolo.com
description: On November 1, 2021, a data leak from the Israeli service Articoolo was published in Telegram channels, which uses artificial intelligence to create unique articles.The leak affected about 340 thousand records containing mail, nicknames, regions, IP addresses and passwords in the form of hash BCRYPT.

title: Minehut
description: Minehut is a server for the game Minecraft. In May 2019, its website suffered a data breach. The company said that a database backup had been obtained and that all affected users had been notified. 397 thousand email addresses were published. Passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes have also been compromised, but currently do not exist in the public domain.

title: Nival
description: In February 2016, the Russian gaming company Nival became the target of a hacker attack. Nival was one of several Russian websites hacked as a protest against "Russian foreign policy towards Ukraine." More than 1.5 million accounts were made public, including dates of birth, email addresses, gender, names, languages ​​spoken and usernames.

title: Fyrfyr.ru
description: On October 10, 2021, a leak occurred in the Russian sweets store FyrFyr. The data contains emails, phone numbers and customer names. A total of 16.5 thousand records.

title: Raychat
description: In January 2021, the now-defunct Iranian social media platform Raychat suffered a data breach. 939 thousand unique email addresses were published. The data included names, IP addresses, browser data and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes.

title: Russkoe-slovo.ru
description: In the summer of 2022, the logs of the publishing house and the online store “Russian Word” were made publicly available, from which about 1,000 records with names, phone numbers, emails and addresses can be extracted.

title: Overblog
description: Around April 2019, the blogging service Overblog suffered a data breach that affected 2.1 million members. The data included email addresses, usernames, IP addresses, device information, and passwords stored as SHA1 hashes.

title: Patreon
description: In October 2015, the crowdfunding site Patreon was hacked. The published dump included almost 14 GB of records from the database. Including 2.3 million unique email addresses, millions of private messages and passwords stored as bcrypt hashes.

title: Upstox
description: In April 2021, Indian brokerage firm Upstox suffered a data breach. The incident exposed extensive personal information about more than 100,000 customers, including names, gender, dates of birth, physical addresses, banking information and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes. Extensive know-your-customer information was also revealed, including scans of bank statements, checks and identity documents with Aadhaar numbers.

title: School.mos.ru
description: In December 2022, hackers hacked the Moscow Electronic School website and published the data of more than 17 million students. The data included emails, names, telephone numbers, dates of birth, citizenship and SNILS data.

title: Basarab.ru
description: In February 2024, the Russian online clothing store Basarab suffered from a hack. Soon a database was published containing tables with users (60 thousand records), their orders (166 thousand), reviews and other information. In total, more than 600 thousand records, including names, emails, phone numbers, addresses, payment information and passwords in the form of SHA1 hashes with salt.

title: KrasotkaMarket.ru
description: "Krasotka Market" is a Russian clothing and shoe store. In 2023, a file with emails and names of the company’s clients began to spread online, containing 138 thousand entries. The data source is probably site scraping.

title: Abt.ru
description: In the spring of 2023, information about site users was published for the provision, implementation and maintenance of VLSI Abt.ru software. The data included names, emails, phone numbers and company names. In total, approximately 56 thousand records appeared on the network.

title: 2krossovka.ru
description: In February 2023, the Russian online shoe store 2krossovka was hacked. The leak contains about 30 thousand records with phone numbers, IP addresses, emails, names and other data about clients.

title: Originalam.net
description: In July 2022, a leak occurred in the Originalam.net printer equipment and supplies store. The database contains 193 thousand records, which include names, dates of birth, emails, telephone numbers and passwords without hashes.

title: Carsok.ru
description: The Russian car sales website Carsok was attacked on June 8, 2023; hackers hacked a database that contained approximately 9 thousand user records and 19 thousand order records. The data included phone numbers, full names, IP addresses, as well as information about purchases and prices.

title: Romwe
description: In mid-2018, Hong Kong retailer Romwe was hacked. 20 million customers were affected. The data includes names, phone numbers, emails, IPs, geographic locations, and passwords as salted SHA-1 hashes.

title: KyivStar.ua
description: In June 2022, the database of KyivStar, the largest Ukrainian mobile operator, was posted on one of the hacker forums. The published database contained 15 million records. They included telephone numbers, full names, residential addresses, passport details, INN and dates of birth. The data was most likely obtained as a result of a leak from a private bank.

title: Mywed.com
description: In August 2023, an incident occurred with the Mywed.com portal, a platform for wedding photographers. The data of 13 thousand users was made publicly available, including their full names, phone numbers, nicknames and cities of residence.

title: HiAPK
description: It is alleged that around 2014 there was a leak in the Chinese Android store known as HIAPK. It affected 13.8 million subscribers and revealed emails, names and passwords in the form of salted MD5 hashes.

title: kr.gov.ua
description: In August 2022, a Russian hacker group posted a file containing a database of the official website of the Krivoy Rog administration. The database contains 242 thousand lines, including the names and telephone numbers of Ukrainian citizens.

title: 2berega.ru
description: In March 2022, a leak occurred from the Russian food delivery service “Two Banks”. The leak contained 10.4 million rows and over a million clients. The data included telephone numbers, names and residential addresses of users.

title: VipFish.ru
description: VipFish is a Russian restaurant selling fish and seafood dishes. In 2023, a parsing of his clients appeared on the network, containing 13 thousand records. The database contains only phone numbers and names of clients.

title: UnionePro
description: UnionePro is an educational platform of the Russian University Innopolis. In October 2022, it suffered from a hack. Data of 112 thousand users was published, including telephone numbers, names, emails, dates of birth, INN, snils, passport data and passwords in the form of SHA256 hashes

title: 1xbet
description: At the end of 2023, a list of 75 thousand emails and passwords in clear text appeared online. It is alleged that this is data from the bookmaker site 1xbet. The data was likely obtained through stealers or phishing and is not a leak from the site itself.

title: Weltrade.ru
description: The leak is likely from the financial site Weltrade. Contains 13 thousand user records - names, cities, telephones, emails, account name and balance. The database was published in December 2023, but the exact date of the leak is unknown.

title: Yam
description: In June 2013, the Taiwanese website Yam.com suffered a data breach, which was published on a popular hacker forum in 2021. The data included 13 million unique email addresses, usernames, phone numbers, physical addresses, dates of birth, and unsalted MD5 password hashes.

title: Abonents 2015
description: In 2015, a hodgepodge was created from many leaks called “subscribers”.The database contains about 40 million people, including phones, names, addressing addresses, date of birth, passport data, and in some cases IMEI and IMSI codes from devices.

title: Tsum.ru
description: In May 2024, the database of the online store TSUM, one of the largest department stores in Russia, became publicly available. The published files contained about 30 thousand records, including full names, phone numbers, and information about customer preferences by brand.

title: GamePlanet.com
description: In April 2023, the video game website Gameplanet suffered a data breach that affected more than 1.7 million of the site's users. The compromised data included more than 1.7 million unique email addresses, dates of birth, names, phone numbers and passwords in the form of Vbulletin hashes.

title: BioFarm.ru
description: In February 2024, a data leak occurred on a Russian website that sells medications and dietary supplements, BioFarm.ru. Two tables containing 112 thousand records of orders and more than 40 thousand records of users were leaked online. Emails, full names, phone numbers, addresses, IP addresses and salted MD5 hashed passwords were compromised.

title: VimeWorld
description: VimeWorld is one of the most popular Russian servers for the game MineCraft. It was hacked in July 2018, leaving the data of 5.6 million users compromised. Emails, passwords, nicknames, IP addresses and balance data were made publicly available. 90% of the passwords were in the form of MD5 hashes and the rest were in the form of bcrypt hashes.

title: Russian Job Seekers
description: In 2020, a database of Russians looking for work, collected from an unknown site, appeared on the Internet. The data contains names, phone numbers, emails, addresses, dates of birth and other information. There are 300 thousand records in the database. The date of the leak and the origin are unknown.

title: GeekBrains
description: In May 2022, a leak occurred on the GeekBrains website. The site confirmed it on June 1. The hacker claimed to have 6 million records, but only 213 thousand emails, names and phone numbers are publicly available.

title: GreenMarathon.Sberbank.ru
description: In 2015, the all-Russian run “Green Marathon 2015” from Sberbank was announced, and in December 2023, the personal data of the participants of this marathon was made publicly available. A total of 59 thousand records, including the names of participants and their children, emails, telephone numbers, cities of residence and links to social networks.

title: Pizap
description: Around December 2017, there was a leak on the online photo editing site PiZap. It contained 42 million unique records, including emails, names, genders and passwords in the form of SHA-1 hashes.

title: EmuParadise
description: In April 2018, the self-proclaimed "world's largest retro gaming website" Emuparadise suffered a data breach. 1.1 million email addresses, IP addresses, usernames and passwords were discovered as salted MD5 hashes.

title: Animoto
description: In July 2018, the cloud video creation service Animoto suffered a data leak. As a result of the leak, 22 million email accounts were affected. In addition, the data included names, dates of birth, country of origin, and salted SHA256 password hashes.

title: Rabota v Sochi
description: In 2013, data from the labor exchange in the city of Sochi was collected using parsing. The published file includes the names, phone numbers and resumes of 15 thousand people.

title: Leet
description: In August 2016, the Leet service, designed to create and run Minecraft Pocket Edition servers, suffered from a leak. It affected 6 million subscribers. The data included usernames, email addresses, IP addresses, and SHA512 password hashes.

title: AdoptMeTradingValues
description: In July 2022, the Roblox tool for the game Adopt Me, known as Adopt Me Trading Values, suffered a data breach that affected 104 thousand participants. The leak exposed email addresses, IP addresses, usernames, Roblox usernames, and passwords stored as bcrypt hashes. The website was hacked by user tilly.

title: Forento.ru
description: Forento is a Russian hotel booking service. In September 2023, a hacker group published his database containing names, dates of birth, phone numbers, emails and passwords in plain text. In total there are more than 300 thousand users.

title: Gubernia.ru
description: In November 2017, there was a data leak from the website Gubernia.ru, which was previously an online platform for posting free advertisements in the Arkhangelsk region. 96 thousand records containing emails, phone numbers and full user names were leaked into the network.

title: ChatBooks
description: In March 2020, photo printing service ChatBooks suffered a data leak. The leak contained records of 1.5 million users with 2.5 million unique email addresses and SHA-512 passwords.

title: Skolkovo
description: On May 17, 2022, information about a leak from the Skolkovo business school appeared in telegram channels. The published data contains names, telephone numbers, dates of birth, places of work and positions, as well as passwords in the form of PBKDF2 hashes. In total, the leak contained more than a million records.

title: Digido.ph
description: In March 2024, data from the Philippine microfinance organization Digido became publicly available. The data contains more than 5 million records of Filipinos' emails, phone numbers, names, dates of birth, addresses and ID numbers.

title: MCResolver
description: In December 2015, the popular Minecraft Resolver website (mcresolver.pw) suffered a data breach that exposed over 13 million usernames and IP addresses.

title: Auto.ru
description: In 2014, a Russian car sales website suffered from a hack. The leak compromised the data of 517 thousand users. The data contains names, phone numbers, cities and extensive information about the vehicles being sold.

title: DoctorNaUchebe.ru
description: On March 29, 2024, a data leak occurred on the Doctornauchebe platform, which provides medical consultations and educational materials for doctors and patients. The incident affected about 30 thousand users. The published information contains full names, emails, passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt, and data on place of residence.

title: ScentBird
description: In June 2020, online fragrance service Scentbird suffered a data breach. Because of it, the personal information of more than 58 million customers was disclosed. Personal information including names, email addresses, gender, dates of birth, passwords as bcrypt hashes and password strength indicators.

title: Armenia 2010
description: In 2010, a data leak occurred on one of the Armenian websites, allegedly associated with the traffic police, affecting information about vehicles. In total there are about 240 thousand records with names, phone numbers, addresses and data about cars, including their numbers and models.

title: Buffet24
description: This is a food delivery service in Krasnoyarsk. The hack occurred in February 2022 and affected more than 80 thousand order records. The records contain phone numbers, names, addresses, amounts and contents of orders, as well as the last 4 digits of the credit card.

title: BinWeevils 2017
description: In 2017, there was a data leak in the online game Bin Weevils. The leak included usernames, email addresses, IP addresses and passwords as PeopleSoft hashes (UIDs). In total, 6.9 million users were affected. This game previously suffered from a leak in 2014.

title: Eksmo
description: On June 9, 2023, the NLB hacker group published data from the Russian publishing group Eksmo-AST. The base consists of two parts - Eksmo and Ast. The Eksmo file contains 433 thousand records, including information about users - emails, names, phone numbers, addresses and passwords in the form of bcrypt and md5 hashes with salt.

title: Obmen4you.com
description: This is an online electronic money exchanger. The leak occurred in April 2022 and affected 22 thousand users. Emails, nicknames, IPs and passwords were published in the form of hashed passwords.

title: DigitalBankingReport
description: In early 2022, DigitalBankingReport was hacked due to password reuse in their cPanel accounts. This site was hacked by Captain_Blackbeard. The leak contains usernames, email addresses and passwords. There are 3300 entries in total.

title: ColorDatingApp.com
description: In September 2018, the dating site ColorDatingApp suffered an information leak. Data about 221 thousand users was leaked into the network, including emails, full names, location data and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes.

title: Kopirka.ru
description: Kopirka.ru is a Russian network service in the field of printing photographs and documents. In 2022, Ukrainian hackers hacked it and posted user data on Telegram channels. The database contained 266 thousand users, although there were much more records of orders.

title: Nzvsmst.ru
description: In June 2024, the automobile website Nzvsmst.ru was hacked. A dump of about 7 thousand lines was made publicly available. The data includes names, phone numbers, IP addresses and order data, as well as text reviews.

title: TheWarZ
description: In December 2012, the now-defunct zombie apocalyptic MMO game TheWarZ suffered a data breach that affected 320,000 users. The leak exposed usernames, email addresses, IP addresses, dates of birth and passwords stored as vBulletin hashes.

title: MasedWorld
description: Around April 2018, the Russian Minecraft server "MasedWorld" suffered a data leak that affected 1.6 million players. The breach included usernames, IP addresses, email addresses and passwords in the form of SHA256 (AuthMe) hashes.

title: AndroidForums.com
description: In October 2011, the computer site Android Forums was hacked, and subsequently 745 thousand user accounts were exposed to public access. The compromised data included users' email addresses, dates of birth, and passwords, stored as a salted MD5 hash.

title: ConceptArt.org
description: A community and resource for artists and designers. It was hacked in 2015, resulting in the publication of almost half a million records. The data contains names, emails, dates of birth and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: ShadowCraft.ru
description: In the fall of 2016, the Russian MineCraft server “ShadowCraft” suffered from two consecutive hacks. The databases of the server itself (200 thousand entries) and its forum (150 thousand entries) were published. The leak includes nicknames, emails and passwords in the form of MD5x2 or MD5+Salt hashes.

title: MoviStar
description: It is a mobile operator in Spain. In 2022, it suffered from a leak that affected approximately 13 million users. The data contains names, telephone numbers, emails, passport details, dates of birth, cities of residence and other information.

title: TigTag
description: Around May 2021, the Chinese website TigTag experienced a data breach, affecting 1.6 million users. The breach included email addresses, IP addresses, usernames and passwords stored as MD5 hashes.

title: NewseaSIMS 2016
description: In June 2016, SIM-based avatar website NewseaSIMS suffered a data breach that affected 109,000 users. The breach included usernames, email addresses, locations, full names, dates of birth and passwords stored as MD5 hashes.

title: Zolniva.ru
description: Zolotaya Niva is a Russian agro-industrial company. In May 2022, their website suffered a hack. An SQL dump containing emails, phone numbers, nicknames, IP addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes has become publicly available. There are 17.6 thousand records in total, but sometimes there were several lines per person, and therefore the number of unique people is lower.

title: Petitions.by
description: In May 2021, 208 thousand records from the leak of the Belarusian platform for online petitions “Convenient City” (petitions.by) were made publicly available. The data contains names, mails, telephones and home addresses. The full version allegedly contains 600 thousand records, and the hack itself occurred in March 2021.

title: Bell2017
description: In May 2017, the Canadian telecommunications company Bell suffered a data breach that exposed millions of customer records. The data was subsequently leaked online with a message from the attacker saying they were "exposing a significant portion of Bell.cas data due to their failure to cooperate with us" and threatening to leak more data. The affected data included more than 2 million unique email addresses and 153,000 survey results dating back to 2011 and 2012.

title: ActionNetwork
description: Around December 2019, the betting and sports news site ActionNetwork suffered a data breach that affected 693,000 users. The hack included email addresses, full names, phone numbers, usernames and passwords stored as bcrypt hashes.

title: Vodafone 2020
description: This database of the Ukrainian telephone operator appeared in June 2022. Most likely, the source of the leak was actually Privat Bank. The data in the file contains 9 million records including names, dates of birth, telephone numbers, addresses and passport details.

title: CrackingItaly
description: In January 2017, CrackingItaly suffered a data breach in which 18 thousand user posts were leaked from their forums. Passwords were in the form of bcrypt hashes.

title: PrimalCarnageForums.com
description: The PrimalCarnageForums forum dedicated to the game Primal Carnage was hacked in November 2019. 20 thousand users were affected. IP addresses, email addresses, usernames and passwords were published as salted MD5 hashes.

title: RobinHood
description: In November 2021, online trading platform Robinhood suffered a data breach. Hackers used social engineering on a customer service representative. The incident exposed more than 5 million email addresses and 2 million customer names.

title: DrPepper
description: At the beginning of 2023, the website of this detergent suffered from hacking. The database, published later, contains 16 thousand records and includes emails, phone numbers and client names.

title: TechnoLove.ru
description: In January 2024, the Russian website TechnoLove, which sells Apple equipment, was hacked. 86 thousand records about users and 62 thousand of their orders were published. The data contains names, phone numbers, emails, delivery addresses, hashed passwords and other data.

title: FSSP 2021
description: In Russia there is the “Federal Bailiff Service” (FSSP). In 2021, it suffered a leak during which 87 million records were published. They include names, INN addresses, SNIs data, passport details, dates of birth and residential addresses. This leak is different from the 2020 and 2022 leaks.

title: Mail.ru 3mln
description: On January 13, 2023, the NLB hacker group announced that they were able to hack the Russian mail service Mail.ru. They claimed that they were able to steal 2 billion records, but they only made 3.5 million of them publicly available. The leak contains emails, names and nicknames of users. Representatives of mail.ru stated that the hackers have no other records other than those published.

title: QZaem sample
description: In September 2023, a data leak occurred from the Russian microcredit organization Qzaem. Hackers made 500 thousand records publicly available and began selling the full version, containing 9.2 million lines. The data contains emails, phone numbers, names, nicknames, addresses, dates of birth, tax identification numbers, passports and credit card information. The organization never closed the vulnerability, which is why a second leak later occurred, which was made publicly available.

title: SberLogistica
description: In February 2023, the NLB hacker group hacked several services of the largest Russian bank SberBank.ru. Almost immediately they published data from the SberLogistics delivery service. The leak contains 1.3 million lines, including 680 thousand unique phone numbers, 137 thousand unique emails, full names and passwords in the form of SHA512 hashes with salt.

title: Shisha-net.de
description: The German hookah sales website Shisha-net.de was hacked in 2021, resulting in the data of 50 thousand users being compromised, including emails, names and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes.

title: ICrafts.su
description: In February 2015, there was a data leak from the Minecraft server ICrafts.su. As a result, user data was exposed, including email addresses, nicknames and hashed passwords. There are about 300 thousand records in total.

title: Alfa Bank Ukraine 2019
description: In November 2019, it became known about a possible data leak from the Russian bank Alfabank. The company confirmed the leak of data of only 15 users, but later a file containing 1.4 million records appeared on the network. The data included names, phone numbers, emails and addresses of users from Ukraine.

title: SMineCraft.com
description: In early 2017, the now defunct Minecraft server SMineCraft was hacked. The data of 200 thousand users with nicknames, emails, IP addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes was made publicly available.

title: Eye4Fraud
description: In June 2022, Eye4Fraud, a fraud protection system for merchants, suffered a data breach. The breach exposed full names, email addresses, phone numbers, physical addresses and payment methods. In total, 532 thousand users were affected. It appears that online retailers were warned about this event in advance.

title: Alpmarathon
description: In October 2022, the website Alpmarathon.ru, dedicated to organizing sports events, suffered from a leak. The data of 13 thousand users was publicly available, including phone numbers, full names, emails, nicknames and passwords.

title: Cit0Day
description: Cit0day is a now defunct service for searching emails among various leaks. After its closure in November 2020, a collection of more than 23,000 hacked sites became publicly available. The data was sorted into several dozen categories and contained more than 226 million emails and passwords. Some passwords were protected using hashes.

title: Btech.com
description: On 02/23/2023, a leak occurred on the Arabic website Btech.com, which sells electronics. The data contains 200 thousand records with names, phone numbers and emails of users.

title: Gamevn
description: In May 2016, a data leak occurred on the GameVN gaming forum. The breach included email addresses, usernames and passwords stored as MD5 hashes. In total, 1.3 million users were affected.

title: Hopzone.net
description: On the platform for promoting online game servers Hopzone, a data leak occurred in May 2020, as a result of which about 200 thousand records were leaked to the network, including emails, nicknames and passwords in the form of an MD5 hash with salt.

title: Millennium-Platform.ru
description: In August 2022, the database of the automated cloud travel booking service “Millennium” became publicly available. Tables of users and passengers were published containing names, telephone numbers, emails, dates of birth and document data. In total there are more than half a million entries.

title: Badoo
description: In June 2016, a leak occurred from the Badoo website. The data contained 112 million unique email addresses with personal data including names, dates of birth and passwords stored as MD5 hashes.

title: Fun88
description: In July 2021, the “Best Sports Betting Website in India and Asia” Fun88 suffered a data breach affecting 403 thousand members. The breach exposed full names, phone numbers, usernames and email addresses.

title: Duowan
description: Around 2011, data was released from Chinese gaming website Duowan.com that contained 2.6 million accounts. The data in the breach contains email addresses, usernames and passwords in plain text.

title: Kirov GIBDD 2006
description: In 2006, the Kirov Region State Traffic Safety Inspectorate website suffered a data leak that affected about 400 thousand records, including information about cars, full names and addresses.

title: McSkill.ru
description: In September 2024, data from the McSkill server forum was collected using scraping. The data contains nicknames, profile information and links to Instagram and VK, if they were present. A total of 31 thousand records.

title: Stronghold Kingdoms
description: In July 2018, the online multiplayer game Stronghold Kingdoms suffered a data leak. The incident affected almost 5.2 million accounts. This resulted in the disclosure of email addresses, usernames and passwords in the form of salted SHA-1 hashes.

title: Zdclinic.ru
description: The Russian Railways Medicine medical center in Vladivostok was subject to a hacker attack by the UHG group in 2023. As a result, the personal data of 50 thousand patients became publicly available. The attackers took full names, passport information, information about medical policies and SNILS, as well as phone numbers, passwords and nicknames.

title: YahooVoices
description: In July 2012, Yahoo! their online publishing service "Voices" was compromised via an SQL injection attack. The hack exposed nearly half a million usernames and passwords stored in clear text. The breach found that 59% of people who also had accounts in the Sony leak reused their passwords on both services. In 2012, such analytics were still relatively new.

title: EpicNPC
description: In January 2016, account reseller EpicNPC suffered a data breach that affected 409,000 subscribers. The data included usernames, IP addresses, email addresses and passwords in the form of salted MD5 hashes.

title: Excurspb.ru
description: In September 2020, there was a data leak from the Russian tour operator Excurspb. 63 thousand lines were published with emails, telephone numbers, names, dates of birth, addresses and passport details.

title: Mmdm.ru
description: In July 2020, the Moscow International House of Music suffered from a data leak. The data of 388 thousand users was compromised. The published data contains emails, names, one or two phone numbers and passwords in the form of scrypt hashes.

title: Xiaomi
description: In August 2012, the Chinese Xiaomi user forum website suffered a data leak. In total, 7 million email addresses were exposed as a result of the hack. A significant portion of them were numeric aliases in the bbs_ml_as_uid.xiaomi.com domain. Usernames, IP addresses and passwords were also exposed in the form of salted MD5 hashes.

title: JobAndTalent
description: Around February 2018, job site Jobandtalent suffered a data breach, which then went on sale along with other leaks a year later. The incident affected 11 million subscribers and exposed their names, email addresses, IP addresses and passwords as salted SHA-1 hashes.

title: KirMarket.ru
description: The Russian supermarket chain Kirovsky suffered a data leak in February 2023. Several tables were leaked online, including about 20 thousand user records. Data such as names, emails, telephone numbers, IP addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes, as well as reviews and order information, were leaked.

title: Abandonia 2015
description: In November 2015, the gaming website dedicated to classic DOS games Abandonia suffered a data breach that exposed 776,000 unique user entries. The data contained email and IP addresses, usernames, and MD5 password hashes.

title: Kixify
description: It is an international online platform for buying and selling sneakers and sports shoes. It was hacked in 2022, which led to the leak of 3 million records with emails, names and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes without salt. The site was later hacked again in September 2023, causing another 800 thousand records to leak.

title: Jobinruregion.ru
description: Jobinruregion - Russian catalog of vacancies and resumes. On May 9, 2022, data from all reviews from it was collected using parsing. The table includes names, phone numbers, emails, desired income and schedule, as well as user specialization. There are about 100 thousand records in total.

title: LeakBase Collection
description: Leakbase.cc is one of the sites that publish various leaks. This database contains all leaks from the “Mixed Database” section on this site, containing emails and passwords. There were 50GB of files (1.5 billion rows) in this partition. After deduplication and removal of rows from the collections, only 210 million remained. The data was downloaded in early 2023.

title: Tfsource.com
description: The American online store Tfsource, specializing in Transformers collectible toys and action figures, became the victim of a data leak in 2016. As a result, about 50 thousand user records were affected, including names, emails, IP addresses and passwords.

title: Sad-i-Ogorod
description: In 2021, the Russian online store of seedlings “Garden and Vegetable Garden” suffered from a hack. The leak contains about half a million records with names, phone numbers, emails, addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: Read Novel
description: In May 2019, Chinese literature website Read Novel suffered a data breach that exposed 22 million unique email addresses. The data also included usernames, gender, phone numbers and passwords in the form of salted MD5 hashes.

title: KinoPlan.ru
description: In May 2022, a dump of orders of the filmcass ticket system from the developer for cinemas for cinemas of Kinoplanic Plane got into open access.Four JSON files as a whole contain information about approximately 6 million orders with posts, phone numbers, payment data and other information.

title: Mir-Aromata.ru
description: In 2022, there was a data leak from the online store of fragrances and perfumes Mir-Aromata, amounting to about 20 thousand customer records containing names, phone numbers, as well as order and review data.

title: MyRepoSpace
description: In July 2015, a Cydia repository known as myRepoSpace was hacked and user data became public. Cydia is designed to make it easier to install apps on jailbroken iOS devices. The repository service was allegedly hacked in retaliation for the service's refusal to remove pirated tweaks.

title: FSSP 2023
description: In Russia there is the “Federal Bailiff Service” (FSSP). It has one or two leaks every year. In 2023, there were two leaks totaling 64 million rows. The data contains names, addresses, INN, amount of debt, information about collectors and other information.

title: Luxottica
description: Sometime in November 2022, the “leader” in premium, luxury and sports eyewear with over 7,400 stores in North America suffered a data breach. This revealed email addresses, phone numbers, dates of birth, home addresses and full names of customers of the Luxottica brand. The leak occurred due to a third party exposing data through a publicly accessible storage container.

title: Editus.ru
description: At the beginning of 2024, it became known that the database of the book publishing house Edistus had been leaked. The leak dates back to February 2022. The data contains emails, names, phone numbers and passwords in the form of SHA1 hashes. In total there are about 12 thousand customer records.

title: Mail.ru
description: In September 2014, several account dumps appeared on the Russian Security Forum, including one with almost 5 million email addresses and passwords mainly for the mail.ru domain.

title: StrikePlanet.ru
description: StrikePlanet is a Russian online store with airsoft products. It was hacked in January 2021. More than 40 thousand records with customer data were made publicly available. The database contains emails, phone numbers, names, dates of birth and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: Terrasoft.ua
description: In July 2022, data from the Terrasoft company, which develops programs for managing corporate processes, became publicly available. The data contains 17,700 companies and 26,400 users. Records contain names, emails, telephone numbers, addresses, tax identification numbers and other information.

title: GOBPO
description: In August 2017, the now-defunct GOBPO brokerage website suffered a data breach. The breach included email addresses, usernames and passwords stored in plaintext. In total, 23.9 thousand users were affected.

title: SberPravo
description: In February 2023, the NLB hacker group hacked several services of the largest Russian bank SberBank.ru. In March, they published data from the SberPravo legal assistance platform. The leak contained information about 116 thousand users, including their full names, emails, phone numbers and dates of birth.

title: RuSalut.ru
description: The site for the sale of pyrotechnics RuSalut.ru suffered from a leak in October 2022. As a result, information about 22 thousand users became publicly available. The data included phone numbers, full names, emails, cities of residence, and credit card information.

title: Roscadastre.ru
description: In October 2024, data from the website of the professional association Roscadastre.ru was collected using parsing. Information was obtained from the profiles of 9 thousand cadastral engineers. The data contains telephone numbers, full names, tax identification numbers and addresses.

title: Tokensoft
description: In November 2022, crypto platform Tokensoft purposefully blocked 4.4 thousand users of its platform because they were “bad actors”, which led to the publication of their data. The leak resulted in the disclosure of data including email addresses, IP addresses, crypto addresses, full names, locations and usernames.

title: Onliner Spambot
description: In August 2017, a spam bot called "Onliner Spambot" was identified by security researcher Benkow mokueq. The malware contained a server component located on an IP address in the Netherlands, which exposed a large number of files containing personal information. It contained 711 million unique emails, many of which also included passwords.

title: Leonardo.ru
description: Leonardo is a Russian hypermarket selling tools and materials for needlework. In 2020, it suffered from a leak that affected more than 300 thousand users. The published data contains names, phone numbers, dates of birth, emails, addresses and passwords in the form of salted MD5 hashes.

title: Askona.ru
description: On June 7, 2023, the NLB hacker group made the database of the Russian mattress manufacturer askona.ru publicly available. The database contains almost 2 million rows containing emails, phone numbers, names and other customer data. The leak occurred on April 20, 2023.

title: LucasForums
description: In May 2016, the now-defunct Star Wars fan forum known as LucasForums suffered a data breach that affected 154,000 users. The leak exposed usernames, email addresses, IP addresses and passwords as vBulletin hashes.

title: Seochat
description: In July 2016, a website dedicated to the exchange of knowledge and tools in the field of SEO “Seochat” suffered a data leak. The compromised information affected about 300 thousand users, including their emails, logins, IP addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes.

title: Pm.ru
description: In July 2023, the First Furniture store suffered from a data leak. The database published later contains 8,600 records with information about orders. Data includes names, phone numbers, emails, addresses and purchase information.

title: GSM Saltwort
description: GSM-hodgepodge is a very common base for breaking through data. It was created in 2022 from various sources. Contains names, phone numbers, dates of birth and mail. There are 11 million records in total.

title: SeenSMS.uz
description: On May 30, 2024, a leak occurred on the Uzbek website of SeenSMS virtual numbers. The data contains about 900 thousand records with phone numbers, balances and in some cases usernames.

title: NumBuster MSK 2023
description: This database is a parsing of the NumBuster call detection service for 2023. The collected numbers are mainly from Moscow. The database consists of three parts and contains telephone numbers, names, emails, company names, addresses and dates of birth. There are only 1.3 million phones, but all other fields are not always filled out. The data largely overlaps with the database about the Russia Mobile company, and therefore remains questionable.

title: BrandNewTube
description: In August 2022, the streaming site Brand New Tube suffered a data leak that exposed the personal information of nearly 350,000 subscribers. The affected data included email addresses, IP addresses, usernames, private messages, gender, and passwords in the form of unsalted SHA-1 hashes.

title: MC.GamesMadeInPola.com
description: The web resource for hosting various servers mc.gamesmadeinpola.com was hacked in January 2021, as a result of which the data of 55 thousand users was published online, containing names, passwords in the form of SHA256 hashes, IP addresses and Email.

title: 4KMILES
description: Founded in 2018, 4K Miles, an official Amazon Partner, is a SAAS platform that provides a one-stop sales operations management solution for all Amazon sellers. In October 2019, a data breach occurred that affected 9.4 million Amazon customers. The attack exposed full names and physical addresses. There were also emails in the database, but they were generated randomly.

title: MediBank
description: In October 2022, Australian health insurance provider Medibank was hit by a ransomware attack. All data of 10 million of the company's customers was compromised. Including mail, telephone, name, address, date of birth, health complaints, geolocation, insurance data and other information. The company paid for the re-issuance of documents for affected clients.

title: BlueOceanGaming
description: In February 2021, the BlueOcean Gaming casino gaming platform suffered a data breach that affected 1 million members. The attack exposed full names, usernames, email addresses, phone numbers and deposited amounts.

title: ChessPlayers 2021
description: This is a list of Russian chess players for 2021, obtained from official ranking tables. The data contains names, numbers of regions of residence, identification codes, year of birth and level of play on the Elo scale.

title: Himera
description: Himera is a well-known bot for punching information. In 2024, a small part of its database containing 120 thousand users became publicly available. Data included names, telephone numbers, dates of birth and addresses. At the same time, the full version of the database, 91 million rows in size, began to be sold. Later, this full version also became publicly available and turned out to be an absolute fake, so the data from this fragment of the database should not be taken seriously either.

title: Zoon
description: In September 2023, hackers announced that they had managed to hack the Zoon.ru service, which allows you to leave reviews about various companies. Hackers claim that there are 1.3 million records in the complete leak, but only 117 thousand of them are publicly available. The data contains emails, phone numbers, names, places of work and text descriptions of a person’s specialty.

title: go2pub.com
description: go2pub - service for digital marketing (spamming). This site was hacked in March 2023. 2.3 million emails through which they sent mailings, as well as some IP addresses, were made available to the public.

title: Crossout
description: Crossout is a multiplayer game on the computer. In June 2020, the data of all users of this game was collected by scraping an online forum. The data contains about 70 thousand entries with nicknames and statistics from the forum.

title: SavePechora.ru
description: The Pechora Rescue Committee is a non-governmental organization working in the Pechora River basin and dealing with environmental issues. This site suffered a hack in February 2023. The data of 230 thousand users was published, which includes emails, names, IP addresses and hashed passwords.

title: Wattpad
description: In June 2020, user story site Wattpad suffered a leak that exposed 270 million records. Personal information was exposed: names, emails, IP, gender, dates of birth and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes.

title: CraftRise
description: In May 2023, news emerged of a data breach of a Turkish Minecraft server known as CraftRise. The data of more than 2.5 million users was subsequently published on a popular hacker forum and included email addresses, usernames, geographic locations and passwords in plain text. The latest records indicate that the data was received in March 2022.

title: USA Fresh Dump
description: A combination of many hacks from the USA, collected in 2022. Contains 25 million emails along with their passwords.

title: ILikeCheats
description: In October 2014, the gaming cheat site ILikeCheats suffered a data leak. Because of it, 189 thousand accounts were exposed. Usernames, IP addresses and email addresses, as well as MD5 password hashes, were published.

title: Daily Quiz
description: In January 2021, a quiz website suffered a data breach that exposed over 8 million unique email addresses. The data also included usernames, IP addresses, and passwords in plain text.

title: Romantino.ru
description: In September 2022, the database of Romantino, a Russian online cosmetics store, was made publicly available. The data contains 8 thousand users and 48 thousand orders. Emails, names, phone numbers, IP, passwords in the form of SHA1 hashes with salt and lists of purchased goods.

title: FarmaCent
description: In October 2023, a Russian website selling sports nutrition, FarmaCent.ru, was hacked. As a result, data on 23 thousand orders was exposed, including emails, full names, phone numbers, addresses and IP addresses.

title: SfGuard
description: At the beginning of 2021, a leak occurred in the SfGuard system, which implements a user authorization system in applications. As a result, the data of 2.5 million users was published, including emails, names and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: I-GIS
description: In August 2022, a database dump of the “Unified Dispatch Service of the Lipetsk Region” (l-gis.ru) became publicly available. The data contains 395 thousand lines with names, phone numbers, addresses and information about the reasons for contacting the dispatch service.

title: Pacific-Coast.ru
description: In May 2017, the SAMP server “Pacific Coast Project” of the GTA San Andreas game suffered a data leak. About 8 thousand user records containing nicknames, emails and passwords were leaked online.

title: Yapdomik.ru
description: On October 17, 2022, the Japanese House sushi bar chain was hacked. The data contains 988 thousand records with phone numbers, names, delivery addresses and customer comments.

title: Cutout.pro
description: Cutout is a website for photo editing using artificial intelligence. In February 2024, the site suffered a hack that resulted in the publication of data on 22 million users. The information includes names, emails, IP addresses and passwords in the form of salted MD5 hashes.

title: Ticketfly
description: In May 2018, the website of the ticket distribution service was damaged. The data included more than 26 million unique email addresses, as well as names, physical addresses and phone numbers. There are only 6 million records in the public domain.

title: WifeLovers
description: In October 2018, a site dedicated to posting nude photos of married women suffered a data leak. The database was later published as part of a collection containing a total of 8 different adult websites. In total, 1.2 million unique email addresses were compromised. Wife Lovers admitted the violation. The leak affected usernames, email addresses, IP addresses and passwords in the form of rather weak DEScrypt hashes.

title: Kaspersky
description: In 2024, as a result of the hacking of the Kaspersky fan club forum, a database containing more than 56 thousand entries was leaked online. IP addresses, emails, nicknames and passwords have become available in the form of MD5 hashes.

title: AspProekt.ru
description: This Russian company is engaged in the automation of electronic equipment. There is a file on the Internet containing telephone names and messages from advertising mailings related to this company. Total 2000 lines.

title: Aptoide
description: In April 2020, the independent Android app store Aptoide suffered a data leak. 20 million customer records were exposed. The data included email addresses, IP addresses, names and passwords as unsalted SHA-1 hashes.

title: Animeify
description: In October 2021, anime translation website Animeify suffered a data breach that affected 838 thousand user records. The violation included usernames, full names, email addresses, gender, and passwords stored in plain text.

title: OpenRaid.org
description: The database of the OpenRaid website, which allowed World of Warcraft gamers to coordinate group tasks and communicate, became publicly available in 2015. The file contained emails, nicknames and password hashes of more than 344 thousand users.

title: Dobro.ru
description: On April 11, 2022, a data leak occurred on the Russian volunteer website dobro.ru. The incident revealed 590 thousand telephone numbers, 648 thousand emails, names, date of birth, part of the address (subject of the Russian Federation) and a short biography.

title: NiceMc.ru
description: In January 2017, the Minecraft game server NiceMc leaked a database of about 51 thousand gamers, which contained nicknames, emails, IP addresses and passwords in the form of an MD5 hash.

title: IndiHome
description: In August 2022, Indonesian television and communications company Telkom Indonesia IndiHome suffered a data breach. The data included names, @telkom.net emails, gender, IP addresses and websites visited. A total of 26 million records. The leak caused a huge public outcry in Indonesia and became the most popular on the hacker forum where it was first published.

title: GoldSilver
description: In October 2018, a data leak occurred on the GoldSilver website dedicated to dealer training and services, as a result of which the data of 243 thousand subscribers was published. A large amount of personal information about clients was obtained. It included names, addresses, phone numbers, purchases and passwords, as well as answers to security questions in the form of MD5 hashes. A small number of passports, insurance and credit cards were also disclosed.

title: CityMobil.ru
description: In 2022, there was a data leak from the Russian taxi ordering service Citymobil. The leak affected 3.9 million service clients. The leak contains customer phone numbers, the number of orders and trips, and the date of the last order.

title: ZenMobile
description: ZenMobile is a French mobile advertising agency. Presumably in early 2023, it suffered a leak that affected 3 million users. The data included names, phone numbers, mails, addresses and other details.

title: Miit.ru
description: At the beginning of 2024, a file with data from the University of the Ministry of Transport of the Russian Federation became publicly available. The leak contains 480 thousand records and includes the full name, date of birth, faculty and direction, as well as phone number and link to the avatar.

title: Jili-Bili.ru
description: In 2016, the Russian Jili-Bili toy and children's goods store was hacked.The leak contained names, mail, addresses, customer comments and from one to three phones.In total, about 400 thousand records.

title: KrasnoeBeloe
description: In June 2019, a file containing the data of all buyers of the Russian alcohol market “Red and White” appeared on the Internet for the first time. Initially, the leak included only 100,000 records, but it was regularly replenished by people who hacked it. At the moment, this database contains 17 million records with names, phone numbers and dates of birth of customers.

title: FestivalScope.com
description: In 2020, the database of the online platform for organizing festivals FestivalScope.com, containing about 109 thousand user records, became publicly available. The compromised information included full names, emails, and passwords in the form of SHA1 hashes with salt.

title: 5 Rabota5ka.ru
description: In August 2022, a file with vacancies for the Russian store Pyaterochka became publicly available. The data contains 177 thousand records, including names, dates of birth, telephone numbers, cities and the position for which the applicant responded.

title: Rustirka.ru
description: This is a Russian online store of household appliances.The site was hacking, which touched 25 thousand customers.Phones, names, delivery addresses and information and payment amount and type of payment.The exact hacking date is unknown, but presumably 2024.

title: AntiPub by Nik_Tesla
description: So-called “Anti-Public” lists are used by hackers to analyze new leaks for the presence of unique entries. They usually contain emails and passwords collected from various leaks. This particular list was published in March 2020 and included 3.2 billion rows. After removing duplicate records from collections, there were 252 million rows left.

title: MonopolyStar.ru
description: In 2023, the site dedicated to board games MonopolyStar suffered from a leak, as a result of which personal data and profile information of 155 thousand users were published, including emails, nicknames, full names, regions of residence, IP addresses and passwords in the form of hashes MD5.

title: Kkm.ru
description: In March 2023, the First Bit website, which provides services and equipment for trade automation, product labeling and anti-theft systems, was hacked, as a result of which data from several related sites, including Kkm.ru, was published. 70 thousand records were published that contained phone numbers, emails, names, addresses and TIN of clients.

title: NeimanMarcus
description: In May 2024, the American retailer of the luxury objects Neiman Marcus suffered from a data leak, which was later published at a popular hacker forum.The data included 31 million unique email addresses, names, phone numbers, birth dates, physical addresses and partial data of credit cards.The leak was monitored to a series of attacks on the cloud service of Snowflake, which affected 165 organizations around the world.

title: Volia.com
description: In 2018, the website providing the services of the Internet provider Volia.com was hacked. As a result, information about 89 thousand users was exposed, including full names, emails, phone numbers and addresses.

title: 2035school
description: This is a Russian educational platform for schoolchildren. In 2023, there was a leak affecting 657 thousand people. Data includes names, phone numbers and emails.

title: Azur.ru
description: In April 2024, information from the database of the Russian tourism portal Azur.ru became publicly available. The dump contains online booking data for hotels/resorts in the Krasnodar Territory, Crimea and Abkhazia. The data contains having, mail, phone, city of residence, IP address and booking information. In total there are more than half a million entries.

title: MCBans
description: In October 2016, a Minecraft blocking service called MCBans suffered a data breach. This resulted in the exposure of 120,000 unique user records. The data contained email addresses, IP addresses, usernames and password hashes in an unknown format resembling SHA256.

title: MyDocuments36.ru
description: In June 2022, the database of the center for the provision of state and municipal services “My Documents” of the Voronezh region (mydocuments36.ru) was posted on the English-language shadow forum. The data contains names, emails and passwords as bcrypt hashes. A total of 25 thousand records.

title: Telegram 13.5kk
description: Telegram user base obtained in 2022 by parsing various sources. It indicates the telegram ID, first and last names of users, as well as their telephone numbers and the dates of the last message at the time of data collection. There are 13.5 million lines in total.

title: Xfirm.ru
description: Xfirm is a Russian site for checking counterparties by full name or tax identification number. In early 2024, data from this site was collected using scraping. The published file contains 568 thousand records and includes the names of entrepreneurs, the names of their companies, addresses, INN and the type of activity of these companies.

title: RockYou 2024
description: In the summer of 2024, a new version of the RockYou database was made publicly available; previously similar databases were published in 2021 and 2009. The database is simply a compilation of passwords that have ever been publicly available.  It contains about 10 billion records. There is no other data in the leak, but it can still be used to check the strength of passwords, as well as to decrypt hashes from leaks.

title: Nordski.ru
description: In May 2023, the online sportswear store Nordski suffered from a hack. Tables of users (7200 rows) and their orders (3500 rows) were published. The data contains emails, phone numbers, names and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes.

title: Taklope
description: Around January 2022, an online store owned by the French e-cigarette and vaping company Taklope suffered a data breach. The attack exposed full names, email addresses, dates of birth and passwords stored as MD5 hashes ($salt.$pass) with a static salt. In total, 269 thousand users were affected.

title: Hhide
description: On September 29, 2020, the Hhide.org hacker forum was hacked. Within a few weeks, the database, along with the source codes, was made publicly available. The leak contains about 57 thousand records, including nicknames, emails, dates of birth and passwords in the form of hashes in an unknown format.

title: AsianDate.kr
description: AsianDate is an Android application for finding Asian girls. At the beginning of 2024, a SQL dump with a database of its users appeared on the network. The leak contains about 600 thousand records with nicknames, emails, IP addresses and other data.

title: YouNow
description: In February 2019, data from the YouNow live streaming service appeared for sale on the darknet. The affected data included 18 million unique email addresses, as well as IP addresses, usernames and links to social media profiles. Since authentication is done through social networks, there were no passwords.

title: KM.RU
description: In February 2016, the Russian portal and mail service KM.RU came under attack. KM.RU was one of several Russian sites that were hacked. Almost 1.5 million accounts were affected, including dates of birth, emails, gender, location, security questions with answers and usernames.

title: Moneycontrol
description: In April 2021, hackers put data from the Indian online financial platform Moneycontrol up for sale. This data included 763,000 unique email addresses (allegedly part of a hack of 40 million accounts) as well as geographic location, phone numbers, gender, dates of birth and unencrypted passwords. The date of the initial hack is unclear, but is believed to be September 2017.

title: CDEK (14.07.2022)
description: This CDEK courier service leak was made public on July 14, 2022. This is the second leak of this service in 2022, the first occurred in February. The new leak contains 121 million records, including 17.6 million unique emails, as well as names, addresses, phone numbers and postal codes of customers.

title: Infagard
description: This is a non-profit organization for interaction between American companies and the FBI. At the beginning of 2022, a hacker gained access to the data of 80 thousand users of this platform and sold it for 50 thousand dollars. The leak was later made public. The data contains names, nicknames, state and region, company name and position, and in some cases a text description.

title: BBGpoint
description: In October 2014, the website BBGpoint.com, which provides various online games, leaked the data of about 1.3 million users, including nicknames, emails, social networks and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes.

title: EplDiamond.ru
description: EplDiamond is a Russian jewelry store. It was hacked on April 2, 2023. The leak included emails, phone numbers, names, addresses and dates of birth of buyers. There are about 380 thousand records in total.

title: BitTorrent
description: In January 2016, the forum of the popular torrent program BitTorrent was hacked. The IP.Board-based forum stored passwords as weak SHA1 hashes with a salt. The hacked data also included usernames, email addresses and IP addresses.

title: Pryanikov38.ru
description: On November 17, 2022, a large Irkutsk food delivery restaurant “Pryanikov 38” (pryanikov38.ru) was hacked. The database contained 1.2 million records and included customer names, phone numbers, mail, delivery addresses, IP addresses, order comments and other data.

title: Smogon
description: In April 2018, the Pokemon website smogon.com announced a data breach. The leak occurred in September 2017 and affected their XenForo-based forum. The exposed data included usernames, email addresses, gender, and bcrypt and MD5 password hashes.

title: USA Social Security Death Master
description: This is the official American Social Security death file, dated October 2011, originally contributed by "crazyoldfart" from the now defunct RaidForums. It contains Social Security numbers, full names, and dates of death and birth. A total of 85 million records.

title: EyeEm
description: In February 2018, photography website EyeEm suffered a data breach. The database was later discovered among many other major incidents and contained almost 20 million unique email addresses, as well as usernames, biographies and password hashes.

title: FIFA 2018
description: The 2018 FIFA World Cup was attended by 1.7 million people. Later, the data of all visitors was stolen and became publicly available. The leak includes the name, phone number, email, date of birth and ID number for each person.

title: Buy-Xbox-Live.com
description: This is a store for games and promotional codes for XBox. At the end of 2022, it suffered from a leak that affected 41 thousand users. The published database contains posts, names, phone numbers, IPs and passwords in the form of SHA1 hashes with salt.

title: MinstroyRF.gov.ru
description: In the winter of 2023, hackers from the DumpForums group announced that the resources of the Russian Ministry of Construction had been hacked. As a result of the leak, more than 83 thousand citizens' appeals to the Ministry of Construction were published. The data included full names, email addresses, residential addresses and telephone numbers.

title: Onverse
description: In January 2016, the online virtual world onverse.com was hacked. 800,000 accounts were exposed. Emails, IP addresses, addresses and salted MD5 password hashes were compromised.

title: BitRewards
description: In April 2020, the e-commerce platform BitRewards was hacked. 420 thousand users were affected. The stolen data includes passwords, email addresses and additional personal information. Passwords were in the form of bcrypt hashes.

title: IndiaMART
description: In August 2021, 38 million entries from Indian e-commerce site IndiaMART were discovered on a popular hacking forum. The data included more than 20 million unique emails, as well as names, phone numbers and physical addresses. It is unclear whether IndiaMART intentionally disclosed data attributes or whether the data was obtained by exploiting a vulnerability.

title: 126.com
description: Around 2012, the Chinese email service 126.com suffered a data breach that affected 6.4 million subscribers. The data contained 64 million email addresses and passwords in plain text.

title: MtGox
description: In June 2011, there was a data leak on the MtGox Bitcoin exchange. The attack exposed usernames, email addresses and passwords stored as md5crypt hashes. In total, 61 thousand users were affected.

title: Bitrix24
description: On October 19, 2022, a message appeared on a hacker forum about the sale of data from users of the Russian service Bitrix24, which helps in doing business. The seller provided a sample of their 177 thousand lines and sold the full leak of 4 million lines for $6,000. Later, the full leak became publicly available. The data contains email, balance, MD5 passwords and other information.

title: Collection 5
description: In January 2019, 5 collections appeared on a popular hacker forum, representing a combination of data from many other leaks. The fifth collection contains 16 thousand files with a total size of 42 gigabytes. The files contained 1.25 billion pairs of emails and passwords, but there were only 600 million unique strings. Unlike other collections, there was often information about which site the data was leaked from.

title: HoweLand
