description: In August 2022, the database of the minecraft griefer server HoweLand, consisting of two files relating to July and August, became publicly available. The database contained 80 thousand players, as well as data about their IP, linked social networks and passwords in the form of AuthMe hashes.

title: WhitePages
description: In mid-2016, telephone and address directory service Whitepages was among a number of sites that were hacked and their data sold in early 2019. The data includes more than 11 million unique email addresses, as well as names and passwords stored as SHA-1 or bcrypt hashes.

title: Uteka.ua
description: This is a Ukrainian online library on the topics of accounting, taxes and law. In 2021, more than 250 thousand records containing names, company names, telephone numbers, emails and other data were stolen from it.

title: SoulSplit.com
description: In 2014, a data leak occurred on one of the largest private servers for the popular MMORPG game SoulSplit 2. It affected about 225 thousand records, including nicknames and passwords in the form of SHA1 hashes.

title: Dibi.ru
description: In November 2024, the Russian board of ads dibi.ru was subjected to Parsing.1.7 million ads were collected, although the number of unique users is several times lower.Data contains names, phones, mail and information from ads.

title: Dev.Socolor.ru
description: This is a Russian cosmetics website. On August 13, 2024, a database leak occurred on it. The database contains emails, phone numbers, names, addresses, passwords in the form of MD5 hashes and other information. A total of 325 thousand records.

title: GloriaJeans
description: On June 6, 2023, the hacker group NLB made the customer database of the clothing store Gloria Jeans publicly available. The database contains 3.1 million records and includes emails, phone numbers, names, dates of birth and bonus card numbers. The leak occurred on May 11, 2023.

title: AGEnergy
description: In March 2022, Australian solar energy company AG Energy suffered a data breach. The leak revealed full names, email addresses, home phone numbers, cell phone numbers and physical addresses. In total, 138 thousand customers were affected.

title: CdekShopping
description: In August 2022, Ukrainian hackers posted a continuation of the sensational leaks of SDEKA, a Russian delivery service. They published data from the CDEK.Shopping and CDEK.Market services, containing names, phone numbers, dates of birth and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt. The leaked CDEK.Market contains 87 thousand users, and CDEK.Shopping - 20 thousand.

title: CoinMarketCap
description: In October 2021, it was discovered that 3.1 million email addresses were being traded on hacker forums. This data was likely leaked by cryptocurrency market capitalization website CoinMarketCap, although they denied this. The leak did not contain any data other than emails.

title: RenRen
description: In December 2011, a data leak occurred on the Chinese social network RenRen. The breach included email addresses and passwords stored without encryption. In total, 4.7 million users were affected.

title: Forbes
description: In February 2014, the Forbes website was attacked, resulting in the leakage of more than 1 million user accounts. The attack was likely carried out by the Syrian Electronic Army as retaliation for its supposed "hate of Syria." The attack also led to the posting of fake news on forbes.com. The emails, passwords, nicknames and other data of one million users were compromised.

title: BookChor
description: In January 2021, Indian bookselling website Bookchor suffered a data breach that exposed half a million customer records. The exposed data included email and IP addresses, names, gender, dates of birth, phone numbers and passwords, stored as unsalted MD5 hashes.

title: MTicket
description: At the beginning of October 2022, the Ukrainian ticket sales service “Maestro Ticket System” was hacked. The leak contains 1.7 million users and 3 million orders. The data includes names, phone numbers, emails, dates of birth, addresses and hashed passwords.

title: CouponMom
description: In 2014, a file was created allegedly containing data from the website www.couponmom.com. It contained 11 million email addresses and passwords in plain text. Upon further investigation, data was also found in the file indicating that it was obtained from the Armor Games website. When disclosed to both organizations, each discovered that the data did not represent their entire customer base and possibly included records from other sources.

title: Securepe.in
description: This is an Indian financial website. It was hacked in the spring of 2023, as a result of which names, phone numbers, emails, company names, addresses and other data about users were made publicly available. In total there are more than 200 thousand records.

title: JoyGames 2019
description: Around December 2019, a data breach occurred on the forums of the popular gaming site JoyGames, affecting 4.6 million members. The breach included usernames, email addresses, IP addresses and passwords as salted MD5 hashes. Due to the fact that JoyGames does not use captcha, there are many bots among users.

title: VK 2019
description: In April 2022, a leak of VK users appeared in telegram channels. Data refers to 2019. The published database included names, phone numbers, addresses, dates of birth, educational and relationship information, and other data. There are 9.6 million users in total.

title: BlackMarketReloaded
description: In October 2013, data leaked from the underground online market BlackMarketReloaded, which specialized in the sale of illegal goods and services. The database contained about 330 thousand entries, including nicknames and crypto wallet numbers.

title: FreeGame 2017
description: In December 2019, gaming website FreeGame2017 suffered a data breach that affected 1.8 million users. The attack exposed email addresses, usernames and passwords as salted MD5 hashes.

title: GetContact 12.2020
description: GetContact is a caller identification application that collects data from its users' phone books. At the end of 2020, using parsing, a lot of data was pumped out of it, mainly about Russian users. The leak contains almost 20 million phone numbers and 44 million names under which they were recorded in contacts.

title: Antarestr.ru
description: Antares Trade is a distributor of household goods. In September 2022, it suffered a hack that affected 9 thousand user records and 116 thousand orders. The data contains phone numbers, names, passwords and order information.

title: Parkmobile
description: In March 2021, a leak occurred in the ParkMobile parking service, which exposed the data of 21 million customers. They included emails, names, phone numbers, car numbers and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes.

title: 212300.com
description: The city portal 212300.com, which brings together residents of the Chinese Danyang to discuss education, real estate and employment, was hacked in 2012. The attackers took over the confidential data of 700 thousand forum participants, gaining access to emails, nicknames, IP addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: Greece
description: Database of Greek citizens launched in 2023. Contains phone numbers, names, emails, addresses, jobs and relationship status. Presumably it was obtained by scraping a dating service. There are 300 thousand records in the database.

title: DanceSport.ru
description: In January 2021, a leak occurred from a Russian website dedicated to dance. The published data contains emails, nicknames, IPs, dates of birth, passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt and other information. In total there are just over 17 thousand users.

title: Lifebox
description: In June 2022, the French security company Lifebox suffered a data leak that affected 74.6 thousand clients. The leak exposed full names, email addresses, dates of birth, IP addresses, physical addresses and passwords as unsalted MD5 hashes.

title: Darxe 500k Indonesia ComboList
description: Combolist containing 500,000 lines of emails and passwords in clear text. Data from Indonesia.

title: Animal Jam
description: In October 2020, the online children's game Animal Jam suffered a data leak. It contained 46 million user accounts and more than 7 million unique email addresses. The data also included usernames, IP addresses, dates of birth, physical addresses, parent names, and passwords in the form of PBKDF2 hashes.

title: KinoKassa.ru
description: In February 2023, it became known that the Russian ticket sales service KinoKassa.ru had been hacked. The database contains emails, phone numbers and ticket prices. In total there are 88.5 thousand users.

title: Econrj.ru
description: In 2023, data from the online solar panel store Econrj was made public, including records of 24 thousand users containing names, emails and phone numbers, as well as tables of orders and reviews.

title: InfoTecs
description: On May 20, 2023, the hacker group NLB reported the hacking of the Russian company InfoTeKS. It's ironic that this company is in the business of protecting information. 60 thousand records were published containing emails, names, phone numbers, addresses, passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt and other user data.

title: WorldClass.ru
description: Data leak from the World Class fitness club network that occurred in 2018. As a result, personal data of clients, including famous people, was disclosed. The database contains full name, date of birth, phone number, email, passport details and addresses.

title: FaceSittingForum.com
description: In November 2019, the erotic forum FaceSitting, dedicated to facesitting, suffered from a hack. 48 thousand users were affected, the hack compromised IP addresses and email addresses, usernames and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: DataCamp
description: In December 2018, data science website DataCamp leaked data dating back to January 2017. As a result, 760 thousand unique email addresses, IP addresses, names and passwords were exposed in the form of bcrypt hashes. In 2019, the data was put up for sale on a darknet marketplace and subsequently began to circulate widely.

title: Storagefront
description: Around April 2020, Storagefront suffered a data breach that affected 136,000 customers. The hack included email addresses, full names and passwords stored as PBKDF2 hashes.

title: Mmgp.ru
description: In 2020, there was a hack on the Russian earnings and investment forum Mmgp.ru. The leak contains 350 thousand users and includes posts, nicknames, IPs, passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt and other data.

title: SpiceMC
description: In January 2021, users of the SpiceMC minecraft server were leaked. The leak contains 460 thousand records with nicknames, IP addresses and passwords in the form of AuthMe hashes.

title: Raruk.ru
description: Raruk is a Russian online store for handicrafts. In July 2022, it suffered a hack that resulted in the publication of 15 thousand records of its clients. The data contains emails, nicknames, bcrypt passwords and names that were very often randomly generated.

title: Metropolis
description: In February 2022, an SQL dump containing data from registered users of the Moscow Metropolis shopping center application (metropolis-center.ru) was posted publicly on a shadow forum. The dump contains information on 86 thousand shopping center clients: phone numbers, emails, names, links to social networks and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes.

title: Kaneva
description: In July 2016, the virtual world game Kaneva suffered a leak that affected 3.9 million players. The breach included usernames, email addresses, dates of birth and passwords in the form of salted MD5 hashes. The site used the formula strtoupper(md5(md5($pass.strtolower($username)).$salt))). After being hacked, the game was closed in 2017 and the domain now redirects to the game publisher's website.

title: Azamat Ushanov Subscribers
description: Quite an old leak containing a list of Azamat Ushanov’s subscribers for 2014. The database was obtained from the Smart Responder automatic mailing service and contains names, emails, phone numbers and cities. There are about 400 thousand records in total.

title: LinuxMint
description: In February 2016, the website of a Linux distribution called Linux Mint was hacked and the ISO was infected with a backdoor. The site also operated a phpBB forum, which was subsequently put up for sale along with nearly 145,000 email addresses, passwords and other personal information about subscribers.

title: Baza RF 2021
description: This database contains information about a million Russian citizens. It appeared in the public domain in 2021, but its source is unknown. The file contains emails, phone numbers and full names.

title: AmartFurniture
description: In May 2022, Australian retailer Amart Furniture reported that their warranty claims database was the target of a cyber attack. More than 100,000 records containing email address, physical address, names, phone numbers and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes were exposed and published online by the attacker.

title: Russian Railways Staff
description: In June 2019, a resident of the Krasnodar Territory downloaded the personal data of 700 thousand Russian Railways employees and in August made them freely available on the resource infach.me. And after a while, in June 2022, another version of this leak, containing 690 thousand lines, became publicly available. The database contains names, positions, emails and telephone numbers. However, not all phones actually belong to these employees.

title: Ukrtelecom.ua
description: On September 3, 2023, the customer base of the Ukrainian provider Ukrtelecom became publicly available. The database contains 170 thousand records, including names, addresses, telephone numbers and names of connected services. The leak occurred in August 2023.

title: Black-Energy.ru
description: Black-Energy is a now defunct programming forum. In 2010, it suffered from a data breach that affected 2,000 users. The data includes emails, nicknames, IPs and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: Planzala.ru
description: On June 28, 2023, the Planzala.ru website, which provides ticket purchasing services, became a victim of a data leak. The compromised database contains more than 950 thousand entries, including full names, phone numbers, emails, IP addresses, as well as passwords in the form of a bcrypt hash.

title: Belkurtki.ru
description: In September 2022, there was a leak from the Belkurtki.ru clothing store. The data contains about 30 thousand records with users and their orders. The database includes phones, names, emails, IPs, physical addresses, purchase data and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: DonJuji
description: On February 7, 2023, a hacker under the pseudonym DonJuji made publicly available all the databases he had ever hacked. He said that this was due to the fact that he was changing his field of activity. In total, he published more than 2,000 databases with a total size of 105 gigabytes, mainly in the form of SQL dumps. The data contained more than 150 million emails and related information.

title: Zomato
description: In May 2017, restaurant guide website Zomato was hacked, exposing nearly 17 million accounts. The data contains email addresses, usernames, and salted MD5 password hashes.

title: Mgnl.ru
description: In June 2024, text files containing a dump of several tables from the database of the website shop.mgnl.ru, an online store of the Magnolia supermarket chain, were made publicly available. The files contain names, emails, addresses, phone numbers, hashed passwords and order information. In total there are about 250 thousand unique users.

title: Toonbook
description: In November 2015, Toonbook, a “cartoon version of Facebook,” suffered a data breach that affected 32.1 thousand members. The leak exposed usernames, email addresses and IP addresses. Please note that due to poor database format, some strings may be mixed up. The data was originally published by CallJmpMov on RaidForums.

title: VNG
description: In April 2018, news broke of a data breach at Vietnamese company VNG after data was discovered to be traded on a popular hacker forum where it was widely shared. The leak occurred in May 2015 and included more than 163 million records. The data contained names, dates of birth, gender, home addresses, unsalted MD5 hashes, and 25 million unique email addresses.

title: Lozhka.pl.ua
description: This Ukrainian food delivery site was hacked in 2023. The leak contains 1,300 users with phone numbers, names, addresses and hashed passwords.

title: LeagueSpy
description: In December 2020, the sports website LeagueSpy suffered a data leak that affected 159 thousand members. The breach resulted in the disclosure of data including email addresses, IP addresses, usernames and passwords stored as hashes by phpBB.

title: ArmorGames
description: In January 2019, the website of the gaming portal Armor Games suffered a data leak. A total of 10.6 million email addresses were affected. Usernames, IPs, birthdays and passwords in SHA-1 hashes with salt were also revealed.

title: Klerk.ru
description: "Clerk" is a Russian website for helping accountants. It was hacked in March 2014. The leak contains 750 thousand records and includes emails, nicknames, cities of residence, IP addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: Dropbox
description: In mid-2012, Dropbox suffered a data leak. The credentials of tens of millions of customers were exposed. The passwords of the affected users were only reset in August 2016. The database contained over 68 million entries and included email addresses and salted password hashes (half of them SHA1 and half bcrypt).

title: RozakHutor
description: On June 9, 2023, the NLB hacker group published data from the Rosa Khutor mountain resort. The leak contains 520 thousand records and includes emails, phone numbers, names, dates of birth and passwords, mostly in the form of salted MD5 hashes. The database also contains residential addresses and work information.

title: Technic
description: In November 2018, Technic, a platform specializing in modpacks for Minecraft, suffered a data leak. Technic immediately reported the breach and said that the affected data included email and IP addresses of more than 265 thousand unique users, as well as chat logs, private messages and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes with an operating factor of 13.

title: Philharmonia.spb.ru
description: In April 2023, the website of the St. Petersburg Philharmonic was hacked. The leak contains 220 thousand records and includes emails, names and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: XponentialFitness
description: In March 2022, “the largest boutique fitness franchise group,” Xponential Fitness, experienced a data breach that affected 179,000 customers. The attack resulted in the disclosure of data including email addresses, full names and locations. The database leak occurred because Xponential left a backup copy unprotected.

title: Dota2Hentai
description: Around January 2021, the Dota 2 Hentai porn site suffered a data leak. The attack exposed usernames, email addresses and passwords stored as MD5 hashes. In total, 40.7 thousand users were affected.

title: TheCrims.com
description: As a result of a hacker attack on the website of the criminal-themed online game TheCrims, about 160 thousand player records were obtained, including emails, residential addresses, IP addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt. The hack occurred in September 2016.

title: GSMHosting
description: In August 2016, there was a data leak on the GSMHosting forum that affected 2.6 million user posts. The breach included email addresses, usernames and passwords stored as MD5 hashes.

title: Last.fm
description: In March 2012, music site Last.fm was hacked and 43 million MD5 emails and passwords were exposed. The site learned about the incident immediately, but hid it and the extent of the leak was not known until September 2016.

title: SrimuruGantrading.com.sg
description: At the end of 2019, the website representing the large supermarket chain SRI MURUGAN suffered a data leak. About 18 thousand records of orders and 20 thousand records of users were leaked into the network. Emails, names, phone numbers, addresses, IP addresses, as well as payment and shipping information were exposed.

title: GeckoSuperVpn
description: In February 2021, a number of free VPN services were hacked including SuperVPN, GeckoVPN and FlashVPN. As a result, more than 20 million records were exposed. Most likely, all three brands used the same platform. The data also included emails, users' login country, date and time of each login, and device information including make, model, IMSI, and serial number.

title: FSSP Vladivostok
description: In 2009, the database of the Federal Bailiff Service of Vladivostok appeared on the Internet. The file contained information about 682 thousand people, including full names, addresses, and business information.

title: DiskUnion
description: Around June 2022, Japanese record store chain and music distributor DiskUnion suffered a data breach that affected 702,000 customers. The breach included email addresses, full names, home addresses, phone numbers and plain text passwords.

title: Banorte
description: In August 2022, records from the Mexican bank Banorte were posted on a hacker forum. They contained 2.1 million emails, physical addresses, names, phone numbers, RFCs and bank accounts.

title: Ge.tt
description: In May 2017, file sharing platform Ge.tt suffered a data breach. The data was subsequently put up for sale on the dark web marketplace in February 2019, along with numerous other breaches. The breach included names, social media profile IDs, SHA256 password hashes and nearly 2.5 million unique email addresses.

title: Alllossless.net
description: In March 2020, a SQL dump of the pirated music file distribution site Alllossless.net occurred. About 1.15 million user records were leaked online. Data such as logins, emails, IP addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes were leaked.

title: Acko.ru
description: In September 2023, the hacker group UHG hacked the ASKO insurance company and gained access to a database containing information about more than 3 million users. The compromised data included full names, phone numbers, emails, residential addresses, and vehicle information.

title: Capital Economics
description: In December 2020, there was a data leak from Capital Economics, an economic consulting company. A database containing information about more than 419 thousand users, including full names, phone numbers, emails and addresses, was leaked online.

title: Rulyou.ru
description: On September 3, 2023, the database of drivers of the Russian freight transportation service “Rulyu.ru” became publicly available. The database contains emails, phone numbers, names, dates of birth, document numbers and bank card numbers. Please note that in the leak the bank card numbers are listed in their entirety! They were partially hidden by us, but they are posted in the public domain without censorship.

title: CallCenter Ukraine
description: At the end of 2023, an download from the CRM system of one of the Ukrainian fraudulent call centers, which call victims in Russia and scam them out of money according to one scheme or another, became publicly available. The upload, dating back to 02/2023, contains 6.9 million rows containing personal data of potential victims, as well as some internal information of the call center itself. The database contains names, phone numbers, addresses, dates of birth and text comments from scammers, usually containing the method of divorce used and the nickname.

title: PropTiger
description: In January 2018, Indian real estate website PropTiger suffered a data leak. A database file of 346 GB in size was made publicly available. Two years later it was published on a hacker forum. The leak contained user records and login histories. There are over 2 million unique email addresses in total. The data also included names, dates of birth, gender, IP addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes.

title: EscortreViews.com
description: In January 2021, the database of the escort website EscortreViews.com became publicly available. The data of more than 400 thousand users was leaked into the network. The leak contains emails, nicknames, dates of birth and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: SpbTeatr.ru
description: A small leak from the website of the theater in St. Petersburg. The original SQL dump weighed more than 100MB, but it contained only 57 records with emails, nicknames, IP addresses and user reviews.

title: Numpass 31kk+
description: At the beginning of 2019, a Numpass file appeared on the network containing 31 million phones and passwords that the owners of these phones used on various services. Most likely, this file was compiled from many other leaks.

title: MyloOpt
description: Soap-opt.com.ua is a Ukrainian website selling soap and other cosmetics. In May 2021, it suffered due to a hack. The database became publicly available in 2024 and contained about 60 thousand orders, including phone number, mail and name of the buyer, as well as delivery address.

title: AbbyWinters
description: In March 2016, a data leak occurred on the porn site Abby Winters, which affected 435 thousand users. The breach included email addresses (encrypted with an unknown algorithm), usernames and passwords in the form of Haval-256 hashes.

title: CallFilter.app
description: CallFilter is an application for identifying spam and blocking unwanted calls. At the end of August 2024, a list of all fraudulent calls published on the site was collected using scraping. The resulting database contains 520 thousand telephone numbers and 1.2 million anonymous reviews of calls from these telephones. The data also contains phone categories, their operators and regions.

title: Truth Finder
description: In 2019, the public records search service TruthFinder suffered a data breach that was later reported in early 2023. The data included more than 8 million unique customer email addresses, as well as their names, phone numbers and passwords in the form of scrypt hashes.

title: UCAR
description: Around October 2020, the French car rental service UCAR suffered a data leak that affected 134 thousand users. The attack exposed email addresses, home phone numbers, mobile phone numbers, physical addresses and full names.

title: Lekfarm.ua
description: In April 2021, the website selling medical products Lekfarm.ua suffered from a leak. Information about 157 thousand users was exposed, including phone numbers, full names, emails and salted SHA1 hashed passwords.

title: TheMarket.io
description: On June 12, 2023, the Russian marketplace TheMarket.io became a victim of a leak. Despite the slogan “a secure transaction for a secure purchase,” hackers were able to steal and publish a database containing 73 thousand orders and 260 thousand users. The data contains full names, emails, telephones, addresses and partial bank card numbers.

title: Altenens.is
description: Altenens is a forum dedicated to income on the Internet, various earning schemes, IT issues and much more. In June 2022, it was hacked. More than a million records were affected, nicknames, emails, forum statistics and Bitcoin wallets of service users were published.

title: Auchan
description: On June 6, 2023, the hacker group NLB published a database of clients of the Auchan retail chain. The data contains 4.7 million emails, 7.7 million phone numbers, as well as names, delivery addresses and other technical details. Judging by the data, the hack itself occurred on May 18, 2023.

title: Yavp.pl
description: On June 6, 2022, a Russian hacker group published a leak of the Yavp.pl website, which helps Ukrainian refugees in Poland find work. The leak contains 63 thousand users and information about their names, emails, Facebook, VK, IP addresses and passwords in the form of hashes.

title: Maksavit.ru
description: In October 2024, a large Russian pharmacy chain was hacked, and customer data was put up for sale on one of the shadow forums for $950. However, within a few days the database was made available to the public. Its source was the Maksavit pharmacy, from which the data of 1.2 million users was leaked, including names, phone numbers, emails, dates of birth and order details, including lists of purchased medications.

title: TeraBase64
description: A huge collection of files published in February 2020 by a person with the handle @HTTSMVKCOM. It contained 3.2 billion lines of plain text emails and passwords, but only 1.28 billion unique lines. All this data was most likely obtained from many other leaks.

title: Yell.ru
description: In 2020, the Yell.ru yellow pages site was subjected to Parsing.A base containing 1.6 million records was collected.Jeanne included phones, companies, addresses, descriptions, and in some cases the names of the owners of the company.

title: NaijaLoaded.com
description: Naijaloaded.com, an entertainment portal with music, video and news content, was the victim of a data breach in late 2011. Information about 240 thousand users was published, including emails, phone numbers, full names, nicknames, passwords and addresses.

title: FarmaDelivery.com
description: This leak of a Brazilian pharmaceutical company occurred at the end of 2021. More than a million records containing emails, names, addresses, dates of birth and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt have become publicly available.

title: SF Express
description: In September 2020, one of China's largest courier companies known as SF Express (ShunFeng) allegedly suffered a data breach that affected 65.9 million users. The breach exposed full names, phone numbers and physical addresses.

title: Rusnod.ru
description: In 2016, the Russian political association rusnod.ru was hacked. It contains 60 thousand lines with names, emails, phone numbers, addresses, dates of birth and passwords in plain text. This is not the last hack of this site; it was also hacked in 2021 and 2022.

title: Extremekids
description: This is a Russian network of sports clubs for children. In October 2023, it was leaked, affecting 285 thousand users. The database contains phone numbers, emails and names. There were only 1.5 thousand emails in the file.

title: MandarinBank
description: In February 2023, the NLB hacker team published a leak of the MandarinBank payment system. It included data from 16 thousand users, including emails, passwords and data on all sessions (2.7 million).

title: ItalonCeramica.ru
description: Leak from a store selling ceramics. Contains 7000 records with mails, phone numbers, names and addresses of clients. The leak occurred in October 2022.

title: PetFlow
description: In December 2017, pet supply delivery service PetFlow suffered a data breach that subsequently appeared for sale on the darknet market. About 1 million accounts were affected. Email addresses and passwords were exposed in the form of unsalted MD5 hashes.

title: Meyson.fr
description: On November 18, 2022, the French website Meyson, which sells goods, suffered a data leak of approximately 150 thousand users. The compromised database contains emails, names and purchase amounts.

title: GameSprit
description: In December 2019, the popular gaming platform GameSprite was hacked. The website was hacked via the admin panel “discuz! Forum" along with several other gaming websites. The hack affected more than 7 million users and exposed email addresses, usernames and salted MD5 passwords.

title: ClubHouse
description: In April 2021, a user base of the social network ClubHouse, designed for voice communication, appeared on the hacker forum. The data was obtained by parsing the site via API. In this way, 1.3 million records were collected with names, nicknames and Instagram IDs, which were used for authorization.

title: Pilkinail
description: In November 2022, it became known about an unprotected server belonging to the large manicure and pedicure network Pilkinail. Later, a file containing about 800 thousand lines with user data was posted on the forum. They include names, phone numbers, emails, dates of birth and order information.

title: JoinPiggy.com
description: JoinPiggy - cashback service. It was hacked in September 2020, affecting 1.5 million people. The data contains emails, phone numbers, names, social networks and other information about users.

title: Vmmo.ru
description: In April 2023, the gaming site Vmmo probably suffered from a hack. The data contains 2917 thousand records with ticks, telephones and emails. However, such a small set of data may indicate that the data was collected by scraping, and therefore the exact origin of the database is unknown.

title: ClubeDoIngresso
description: In August 2019, the Brazilian event platform Clube do Ingresso suffered a data leak that affected 85.3 thousand users. The breach exposed full names, gender, dates of birth, email addresses, CPF numbers, locations and passwords as MD5 hashes.

title: Rozetka.ua
description: In 2019, the Ukrainian website Rozetka, which sells electronics, clothing and household goods, suffered from a hack. The leak contains 163 thousand lines, including phone numbers, names, emails, addresses and dates of birth of clients.

title: Jamtangan
description: Around July 2021, "Indonesia's No. 1 Online Watch Store" Jamtangan (also known as Machtwatch) experienced a data breach. The breach included email addresses, IP addresses, full names, phone numbers and passwords stored as MD5 hashes. In total, 434 thousand users were affected.

title: Unigame
description: In December 2019, the now-defunct gaming site Unigame suffered a data leak that affected 851,000 users. The leak exposed email addresses and passwords as salted MD5 hashes.

title: Instagram 962k
description: As a result of parsing the social network Instagram, a database containing information about 960 thousand accounts appeared on the Internet. The data included emails, full names, phone numbers, and usernames.

title: PasswordIndex
description: This is an inverse index created in March 2023. It allows you to search for all emails associated with a particular password. This index contains 1.3 billion unique passwords and 3.2 billion emails for which they were used. Enter the received emails into the search to get more information.

title: Vertex-Club.ru
description: In early June 2024, the Russian news site Vertex-Club suffered from a hack. The database, published soon, included 117 thousand lines with names, emails, phone numbers, addresses, hashed passwords and other data about users.

title: AiType
description: In December 2017, the ai.type virtual keyboard application was compromised. A huge amount of data was exposed to the public on an unsecured MongoDB instance. The 577 GB dataset contained extensive personal information, including more than 20 million unique email addresses, as well as social media profiles and address book contacts.

title: Combook.ru
description: Combook is a Russian book site. At the end of 2023, a database of its users appeared, containing names, emails, phone numbers and addresses. A total of 116,000 records.

title: MMO-trick.com
description: The now defunct MMO-trick website was selling cheats and bots for the game World Of Warcraft. In May 2020, it was hacked and 94 thousand user records became publicly available. The data contains emails, names, dates of birth, IP, passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt and other information.

title: IIMJobs
description: Indian job portal IIMJobs suffered a data leak in December 2018? which exposed 4.1 million unique email addresses. The data also included names, phone numbers, geographic locations, dates of birth, job titles, job applications and cover letters, and unsalted MD5 hashes of passwords.

title: OpenBonus24.ru
description: In 2022, the OpenBonus24.ru business management and customer acquisition system suffered a data leak. Several tables were leaked online, including 243 thousand records of orders and about 12 thousand records with user data. Phone numbers, addresses and full names, as well as shipping addresses, were revealed.

title: RbxRocks
description: In August 2018, a data leak occurred on the Rbx.Rocks trading platform dedicated to the Roblox game. The data included names, email addresses and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes, totaling 25 thousand lines. In July 2019, another 125 thousand entries appeared. The website has since gone offline with a message stating that "Rbx.Rocks v2.0 is currently under construction."

title: Wildberries
description: It is alleged that on June 23, 2022, the Wildberries online store was hacked. The published leak contained about a million records, including emails, full names, addresses and phone numbers of users. Representatives of Wildberries denied the presence of a leak from their services. It is quite possible that the leak is a compilation from other databases.

title: Stratfor
description: In December 2011, Anonymous attacked the global intelligence company known as Stratfor, exposing hundreds of gigabytes of email and tens of thousands of credit card data. The hack also affected 860,000 user accounts with email address, time zone, and unsalted MD5 password.

title: CannabisForum
description: In February 2014, the marijuana website Cannabis.com's forum was hacked and became public. The leaked data included more than 227 thousand accounts and almost 10 thousand private messages between forum users. The leak also contains usernames, dates of birth, email addresses, geolocation, IP addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: OneClickMoney.ru
description: In February 2024, a leak occurred from a Russian microfinance organization, claiming to be OneClickMoney. The hacker was able to obtain an SQL dump of a site containing almost 10 million users. The data includes names, dates of birth, passport data, work data and up to 6 different phone numbers of the client and his contact persons, as well as other information.

title: EuropaJobs
description: In August 2019, the now-defunct European job website europa.jobs suffered a data breach. The incident exposed 226,000 unique email addresses as well as extensive personal information including names, dates of birth, job applications and passwords. The data was subsequently distributed on a popular hacker forum.

title: Underworld Empire
description: In April 2017, a forum dedicated to the game Underworld Empire suffered a data leak that exposed 429,000 accounts. The data was then published on a hacker forum in mid-February 2018. The leak contained IP addresses, email addresses, usernames and salted MD5 hashes.

title: Telegram Chats
description: In 2022, using parsing public Telegram channels, 63 million records about their participants were collected. These records contain their IDs, names, phone numbers and channels in which these users are members. There are also descriptions of these channels and information about whether the user has a fraud mark.

title: D3Scene 2019
description: Around July 2019, gaming website D3Scene experienced a data breach. The attack exposed email addresses, usernames, IP addresses, dates of birth and passwords stored as vBulletin hashes. In total, 963 thousand users were affected. The site was previously hacked in 2016.

title: ShinyMigom.ru
description: In November 2022, a leak occurred from the Russian tire store shiny-migom.ru. The published database contains the names of clients and the text of their reviews. There are 6000 entries in total.

title: Sencha.com
description: Web development software company. Suffered from a hack on September 16, 2020, the published leak contains almost 850 thousand records. The data contains names, emails, dates of birth, IP addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: 138gsm.ru
description: 138gsm is a Russian store of spare parts for phones. On February 18, 2019, a leak occurred on it. 162 thousand orders and 30 thousand user records were published. The data contains emails, phone numbers, names, addresses and order amounts, as well as passwords in plain text. However, most of the passwords were generated automatically.

title: RFCont.ru
description: It is alleged that at the end of 2022, the database of RefStroyServis, a company for the sale and rental of refrigerators, became publicly available. The leak contains 4.2 million records with emails, phone numbers and customer names. The contents of the database overlap with many other leaks, and therefore it is likely that it is fake.

title: Ata-k.com
description: Ata-k is a Spanish forum with leaked erotic photos and videos. In November 2019, it suffered from a leak that affected 34 thousand users. IP addresses, email addresses, usernames and passwords were published as salted MD5 hashes.

title: Synevo.ua
description: On April 27, 2023, it became known about an attack by a Russian hacker group on a Ukrainian network of medical laboratories. The published data from them contains information about approximately 5 million Ukrainians. The data contains names, emails, telephone numbers, dates of birth, IP addresses and other information.

title: Sovamed.ru
description: In February 2024, it became known that hackers gained access to information from the appointment form on the website of the SOVA medical center. The published data contains names, telephone numbers, emails, cities of residence and texts of comments. A total of 126 thousand records.

title: Autozs.ru
description: Autozs.ru is a Russian store specializing in automotive parts. The company’s server, where information about clients and orders was located, was publicly available. In August 2022, attackers took advantage of this and dumped the database. 480 thousand records were made publicly available. They included mail, phone numbers, names, addresses and payment information of customers.

title: GsmForum.ru
description: This is a forum for repairing cell phones and electronic gadgets. The leak occurred in April 2018 and affected 1.2 million users. The database contains nicknames, emails, IP addresses and passwords in plain text.

title: MySmsBox.ru
description: Mysmsbox is a platform for viewing information by phone number. In October 2024, about 20 thousand records containing phone numbers, emails, company names, user comments and other information were collected from it using parsing.

title: DayZ.com
description: In April 2016, data was leaked from the MMO action game DayZ. The leak affected information about 200 thousand accounts with names, emails, IP addresses, dates of birth and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: Tuned Global
description: In January 2021, data from a number of hacked services including Tuned Global was published on a public hacker forum. The leak dates back to 2016 and includes 985 thousand records containing email addresses, names, physical addresses, passwords and phone numbers. Passwords were stored in plain text.

title: Ontecnia.com
description: In January 2020, the Spanish website Ontecnia, which provides business services, suffered a leak. 64 thousand user records were published, including emails, names, passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt and Facebook account IDs.

title: 4dk.ru
description: In September 2022, the Russian website “What to do Consult” (4dk.ru), which provides products for business development, suffered from a leak. As a result, a SQL dump was published containing very dirty data. The database contains 150 thousand users and information about their phones, emails, names, IP addresses and company names. Many of these fields were rarely filled out.

title: Hexui
description: Around May 2016, a data leak occurred on the CS:GO cheat forum Hexui, affecting 13.6 thousand participants. The breach exposed email addresses, geographic locations, IP addresses, names, nicknames, website activity and passwords as MyBB hashes. Although there was no official statement about the leak, site administrators reset user passwords.

title: Gemotest
description: In April 2022, a leak occurred in the Russian laboratory Gemotest. She revealed the names, dates of birth, gender, telephone numbers, mails, physical addresses, insurance and passport numbers of 30.4 million people.

title: MarketsMojo
description: In March 2021, Indian investment platform MarketsMojo suffered a data breach that affected 496 thousand members. The breach included email addresses, phone numbers, full names and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes. The initial attack vector was a misconfigured aws s3 bucket.

title: MalindoAir
description: In March 2019, the Malaysian airline Malindo Air suffered a data breach. The leak resulted in the disclosure of email addresses, dates of birth, physical addresses, passport numbers and phone numbers. In total, 45 million customers were affected.

title: Avito 2018
description: Avito is a Russian service for posting advertisements. It has been hacked and leaked countless times, but one of the biggest happened in 2018. It contains 55 million records of products for sale. Entries include phone numbers, full names, regions, as well as prices, product names and descriptions.

title: ClearVoice Surveys
description: In April 2021, market research company ClearVoice Surveys accidentally made and distributed a public backup of its 2015 database. The data included 15 million unique email addresses, as well as names, physical and IP addresses, gender, dates of birth and plain text passwords.

title: Fast-anime.ru
description: Fast-anime is a Russian website that sells anime-related items. At the beginning of 2021, a user database containing 155 thousand records was downloaded from it. The leak includes names, phone numbers, emails, residential addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes.

title: TheFappening.so
description: In December 2015, a celebrity nude photo discussion forum known as "The Fappening" was compromised and 179,000 accounts were exposed. Exposed participant data included usernames, email addresses, and salted password hashes.

title: NanoCad.ru
description: In January 2024, the NanoCad website, which provides software for solving engineering problems, suffered a data leak. As a result, a SQL database dump of more than 30 gigabytes in size was published, which included hundreds of tables with a variety of data, including tables of users, orders and suppliers, forum data, product reviews and mailing lists. The user table contains about a million rows with emails, names, phone numbers, cities of residence and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt. In the remaining tables you can find residential addresses, INN, places of work, comments on products, company data and many other data.

title: MinecraftWorldmap
description: Around January 2016, the Minecraft World Map site, created for sharing maps of the game, was hacked. About 71 thousand email addresses, IP addresses, and hashed passwords with salt were exposed.

title: Zimnie.com
description: In June 2024, a leak occurred in the online sports store Zimnie. The published data contains 43 thousand user records and 47 thousand of their orders. Including names, emails, phone numbers, passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes, as well as information about purchases.

title: PandaBuy.com
description: In March 2024, 1.3 million unique email addresses of an online store for purchasing goods from China, PandaBuy, were posted on a popular hacker forum. The data also included IP and physical addresses, names, phone numbers and order requests. The leak is believed to have originated from Sanggiero and IntelBroker.

title: Elanic
description: In January 2020, there was a leak in the Indian fashion market Elanic. The hacker forum had 2.8 million posts with 2.3 million unique email addresses. The data also included user names and geographic locations. The site confirmed that the data was retrieved from one of their servers. Data refer to 2016–2018.

title: Bitly
description: In May 2014, link shortening and monetization company Bitly announced that it had suffered a data breach. The published data contained 9.3 million unique email addresses, as well as usernames and SHA1 hashed passwords. In rare cases, the bcrypt algorithm was used.

title: Neteller
description: In May 2010, the Neteller e-wallet service suffered from a data leak that affected more than 3.6 million customers. The leak was not discovered until October 2015 and involved names, email addresses, home addresses and account balances.

title: ForceOnline
description: In May 2016, online gaming site Army Force Online suffered a data breach that exposed 1.5 million accounts. The data includes usernames, email addresses, IP addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes.

title: Perekrestok.ru
description: In 2014, the loyalty program of the Russian supermarket Perekrestok suffered from a leak. About 800 thousand records were published containing phone numbers, as well as in some cases emails, names and patronymics of clients. The data also included bonus card numbers and their balance. Please note that there were no names in the leak; they were added to the database based on data from other leaks.

title: HLTV
description: In June 2016, HLTV's Counter Strike website was hacked. 611 thousand accounts were made publicly available. The leak revealed names, nicknames, email addresses and password hashes. The site used the formula MD5(MD5(pass)+MD5(pass)+MD5(pass)+MD5(pass)+SALT) and the static salt GoRainbowThisFuckingdweeb.

title: Indianathletics.in
description: In February 2022, an SQL dump of the Indian Athletics Federation was published. The leak contains 235 thousand records. The data includes emails, names, telephone numbers, automatically generated passwords (or hashes of an unknown format), as well as residential addresses, dates of birth, parents' names and blood type.

title: Smeni-Auto.ru
description: In October 2023, the message board for the sale of Smeni-Auto cars was scraped. 64 thousand advertisements were collected with emails, phone numbers and names of the authors, as well as data on the cars being sold.

title: THCtalk
description: Around November 2017, the THCtalk "Marijuana Discussion Forum" suffered a data breach. The hack included usernames, email addresses, IP addresses, dates of birth and passwords stored as vBulletin hashes. In total, 82 thousand users were affected.

title: Uiggy
description: In June 2016, the Facebook app known as “Uiggy” was hacked. The leaked accounts also revealed the emails, names, gender and Facebook ID of the owners. A total of 2.7 million users.

title: Regme
description: In August 2022, a data leak occurred in the Russian tax assistance service Regme.online. This resulted in the disclosure of data that included email addresses, phone numbers, full names and passwords in the form of SHA-1 hashes. In total, 269 thousand users were affected.

title: PayHere
description: At the end of March 2022, Sri Lanka's payment gateway PayHere suffered a data breach. As a result, more than 65 GB of payment data were exposed. The records included more than 15 million unique email addresses. The leak also contained IP addresses, physical addresses, names, phone numbers, purchase history and partially private credit card information.

title: Grastin.ru
description: In 2022, the Russian courier service Grastin suffered from a data leak. The file, published later, contained 1.5 million records, including names, phone numbers, addresses, mail and other information.

title: Kolyan.net
description: On January 13, 2021, a data leak occurred on a Thai online platform specializing in slot games for making money. The leak affected approximately 360 thousand users. The database contained full names, emails, logins, IP addresses and other information about users.

title: BookMate
description: In mid-2018, the e-book subscription service Bookmate was hacked. The data included nearly 4 million emails as well as names, genders, dates of birth and passwords in the form of salted SHA-512 hashes.

title: MixZip.ru
description: At the beginning of May 2024, a sale was discovered on the closed BreachForums forum, and then a data leak occurred from the online store of spare parts for household appliances mixzip.ru. The database contained information about more than 266 thousand users and over 200 thousand orders. The compromised data included full names, phone numbers, postal codes, addresses, banking information and Base64 hashed passwords.

title: Tnote
description: Around January 2021, the Korean travel notes app (tnote.kr) experienced a data leak that affected 170 thousand users. The attack exposed usernames, email addresses, phone numbers, dates of birth, device names, full names and passwords stored in an unknown format.

title: Tokopedia
description: In April 2020, Indonesia's largest online store was hacked. The hacker forum posted 90 million lines of data, including emails, names, gender, dates of birth and passwords in the form of SHA2-384 hashes.

title: CombatCraft
description: In 2019, users of the Minecraft server CombatCraft were leaked; nicknames, emails, IP addresses and user passwords were published in the form of AuthMe hashes. Always 880 thousand records.

title: Webtretho.com
description: This is a forum and community for parents and women. The site suffered a leak in 2021, affecting nearly 2 million users. The data contains names, emails and telephone numbers, as well as information about Facebook accounts.

title: Jivo.ru
description: In 2020, open access to the server of the business manager Jivo.ru was discovered. This led to data leakage of 230 thousand users. The leak contained emails, phone numbers, full names and addresses of sites with the Jivo module installed.

title: IntelligenceX
description: Around August 2021, Intelligence X (intelx.io) was targeted by an attacker who scraped the Embeds section of the website. The released archive contained more than 80,000 pastes extracted from pastebin.com, pastie.org and skidpaste.org or IntelX. In total, the archive contained 46 million emails, many of which were accompanied by passwords.

title: Rune Village
description: In October 2011, the now-defunct Runescape forum Rune Village suffered a data leak that affected 45.8 thousand users. The attack exposed usernames, email addresses, IP addresses, dates of birth and passwords stored as hashes by phpBB.

title: Oruzhiye59
description: In 2022, there was a leak in a Russian weapons store. 19.6 thousand lines containing names, phone numbers, emails and addresses of clients were made publicly available.

title: SberSpasibo
description: On March 9, 2023, the NLB hacker group published a leak from the SberSpasibo service, the Sberbank bonus program. The published database includes emails, telephone numbers, dates of birth and information about the availability of credit cards. A total of 48.3 million records.

title: Insanelyi.com
description: In July 2014, the website for purchasing airline tickets Insanelyi.com was hacked. Data about 103 thousand users was publicly available, including nicknames, emails and passwords in the form of an MD5 hash with salt.

title: Rjb.ru
description: In August 2022, the Russian job search site RJB was hacked. The leak contained 965 thousand records and included emails, names, dates of birth, telephone numbers, addresses, passport data, information about specialty and other information.

title: Short-Edition.com
description: In June 2021, French short fiction publishing house Short Édition suffered a data breach that exposed 505,000 records. Affected data included email and physical addresses, names, phone numbers, dates of birth, gender, and passwords stored as salted SHA-1 hashes or salted SHA-512 hashes.

title: PeopleDataLabs
description: In October 2019, a server was discovered with 12 billion personal data records. They belonged to the data enrichment company PeopleDataLabs. 622 million mail, telephones and places of work were affected.

title: AlltvRemote.in
description: TV management service website AlltvRemote.in has suffered a data breach. As a result, information about 257 thousand users was exposed, including emails, nicknames, registration dates and hashed passwords.

title: PKMN
description: In August 2019, a data leak occurred in the Pokemon fan community PKMN.NET, which affected 53.6 thousand users. The leak exposed usernames, email addresses and passwords stored as SMF hashes.

title: Armeec
description: Armeets is a Russian insurance company. It was hacked in 2023 and about a million records about its clients were made public. The data includes names, phone numbers, emails and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes, as well as information about purchased insurance, its period and paid amounts.

title: Tie.com.ua
description: In April 2023, the Ukrainian website Tie.com.ua, which sells accessories, became a victim of black hat hackers. As a result, a database containing information about 47 thousand orders was leaked online. Phone numbers, full names, emails, IP addresses, and shipping addresses were compromised.

title: Reincubate
description: In October 2020, application data company Reincubate suffered a data breach. The leak was discovered as a backup from November 2017. The data included more than 616 thousand unique email addresses, names and passwords in the form of PBKDF2 hashes.

title: CCAA
description: In August 2021, the Brazilian training platform CCAA suffered a data breach that affected 979 thousand participants. The attack exposed email addresses and passwords stored as Wordpress hashes.

title: FlashFlashRevolution 2019
description: In July 2019, the music rhythm game Flash Flash Revolution suffered a data leak. It contained almost 1.9 million users in addition to the same service's data leak in 2016. The leak includes emails, IP addresses, usernames, dates of birth, and salted MD5 hashes.

title: KuchenLand.ru
description: In April 2024, the online home goods store KuchenLand suffered from a hack. More than half a million records were published with emails, phone numbers, addresses and payment information of clients.

title: DengiSrazy v2
description: In 2024, a huge number of leaks received from various microfinance organizations were published in telegram channels. One of the largest such databases appeared as the database of the MFO “Money at once,” although most likely it was obtained from the credit history bureau nbki.ru. However, “Money Immediately” also suffered from hacking, and therefore a real leak of this particular service soon appeared. It is not so large and contains only 370 thousand records, but there is a lot of data in them: the names of the borrower and his contact persons, up to 7 phone numbers, passport details, addresses, information about income and place of work and other information.

title: RespectShoes.ru
description: Respect-shoes is a Russian clothing store. On March 11, 2022, data from their website was stolen. The resulting database contains 350 thousand users. The data contains emails, names, phone numbers, dates of birth and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: OTP Bank
description: In 2023, one of the largest Russian banks, OTP Bank, was hacked. As a result, a database containing information about almost 90 thousand clients was leaked online. Data such as telephone numbers, full names and residential addresses were compromised.

title: ClashOfClansBuilder.com
description: This now defunct site contained diagrams for placing bulls in the game ClashOfClans. In 2021, it was hacked and 880 thousand user records were made public. These contain emails, nicknames, IP addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes.

title: RedMart
description: In October 2020, news emerged of a Lazada RedMart data breach containing records dating back to July 2020 and being sold through the online marketplace. In total, the data included 1.1 million customer email addresses, as well as names, phone numbers, physical addresses, partial credit card numbers and SHA-1 hashed passwords.

title: ForumDate.ru
description: In November 2019, there was a leak from the Russian forum for meeting foreigners ForumDate. 32 thousand users were affected, the hack compromised IP addresses and email addresses, usernames and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: HeatGames
description: Around June 2021, online gaming site HeatGames experienced a data breach that affected 1.1 million users. The breach included email addresses, IP addresses, countries and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes. The website was hacked by @donjuji.

title: RosReestr
description: In 2013, there was a leak from RosReestr, the Russian cadastral service. Information about 10 million real estate properties was published, including their addresses, names of owners, their passport details and legal codes, as well as the history of the transfer of real estate objects.

title: Barahla.net
description: Barahla.net is a Russian bulletin board. On August 20, 2023, all data from it was collected using parsing. It received over 5 million users and approximately 27 million listings. The data contains names, emails, telephone numbers and displayed products.

title: Katapult.com
description: In September 2020, rental planning website Katapult suffered a data breach that affected 2.2 million users. The attack exposed email addresses, full names, usernames and passwords in the form of PBKDF2 hashes.

title: MosCovid
description: There is a file online with information about people who were sick with coronavirus in the city of Moscow. It contains data on 113 thousand people, including full names, dates of birth and other disease information. The exact date and source of the leak are unknown.

title: Experian
description: In September 2015, the US Credit Bureau and the Experian consumer data broker suffered from data leakage, which affected about millions of customers who have applied for financing from T-Mobile.In total, there are 150 million records in the database, the number of unique user is one.The leak contains personal data, including mail, phones, names, physical addresses, date of birth and various other personal characteristics.

title: iMesh
description: In September 2013, the iMesh media sharing client was hacked. About 50 million accounts have been exposed. In mid-2016, the data leaked online and included emails, IPs, names, and salted MD5 hashes.

title: Podrygka
description: On August 1, 2023, it became known that the Podruzhka online store, which sells cosmetics and perfumes, was hacked. The data contains names, phone numbers, emails and passwords in the form of hashes. At first, only a partial leak containing 200 thousand lines was published, but later a complete leak appeared, containing 2 million lines.

title: DisserCat.com
description: Data from the website of the scientific electronic library of dissertations and abstracts DisserCat was collected using parsing in September 2024. Information about 54 thousand users was obtained, including their names and data on scientific works.

title: PaddyPower
description: In October 2010, Irish bookmaker Paddy Power suffered a data breach. The records of 750,000 customers were exposed. The leak was not reported until July 2014. The data contained extensive personal information including names, addresses, phone numbers, passwords, as well as security questions and answers.

title: VkusVill
description: In December 2022, the Russian online grocery store VkusVill reported a data leak. The data contained phone numbers, emails, dates and amounts of orders, and the last 4 digits of a bank card. 240 thousand users were affected.

title: TheLastDoor
description: In January 2020, the database of the official website of the horror video game “The Last Door” was leaked, as a result of which the data of approximately 130 thousand players became available. The database contains full names, emails, IP addresses and hashed passwords.

title: Sberbank 2023
description: In 2023, a database allegedly containing Sberbank users appeared in the public domain. The database contained almost 10 million users and included phone numbers, emails, full names and dates of birth. In fact, it was compiled from several leaks from 2022 using enrichment.

title: Netlog
description: In July 2018, the Belgian social network Netlog discovered a data breach of their systems that occurred in November 2012. The leak affected 49 million subscribers, whose emails and passwords were revealed.

title: Kassa.mts.ru
description: At the end of 2022, a Ukrainian hacker group published a complete list of the MTS Business website. The leak, several hundred gigabytes in size, included, among other things, the database of the MTS cash register service. The data contains two emails (personal and automatically generated), names, phone numbers, cities of residence and passwords in plain text, a total of 600 records. The data also contains logs of requests for technical support, containing 57 thousand calls with names, phone numbers and descriptions of the request.

title: uTorrent
description: In early 2016, the uTorrent client BitTorrent forum suffered a data breach that came to light later that year. The IP.Board-based forum database contained 395 thousand accounts including usernames, email addresses and unsalted MD5 password hashes.

title: AmiHome.by
description: In February 2023, a leak occurred from the Belarusian online furniture store “AmiHome”. 300 thousand user records were made publicly available. The data includes names, phone numbers, emails, dates of birth and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: Dom.ru
description: In November 2022, it became known about a data leak from the website of the Russian Internet provider Dom.ru. The leak contains more than 3 million records, including usernames, phone numbers, dates of birth, tax identification numbers and comments on applications.

title: BlackDiamondsCasino
description: BlackDiamondsCasino is a mobile casino application that was hacked in November 2022. 128 thousand user records were made publicly available. The data included only emails and dates of registration at the casino.

title: AlbionOnline
description: In October 2020, a data leak occurred on the forum of the fantasy MMORPG game Albion Online, which affected 292 thousand users. The breach involved usernames, email addresses and passwords stored as Double Bcrypt hashes (bcrypt rehashed to bcrypt again).

title: XKCD
description: In July 2019, a leak occurred on the webcomic forum XKCD, affecting 562,000 subscribers. It contained usernames, email addresses, IPs and passwords in MD5 phpBB3 format.

title: Snapchat
description: In January 2014, a week after Gibson Security described vulnerabilities in the Snapchat service, 4.6 million usernames and phone numbers were stolen from it. The attack involved brute-forcing a large number of phone numbers through the Snapchat API, in response to Snapchat's claim that the attack was "theoretical." In the published file, the phones did not contain the last two digits.

title: SilabGarza
description: Around July 2012, Runescape's private server forum, SilabGarza (aka SG-Forum.info), suffered a data breach. The stolen data included more than 105 thousand emails, as well as usernames, IP addresses and passwords stored as salted MD5 hashes.

title: MyCube.ru
description: The Russian MineCraft server MyCube.ru was hacked. The exact date of the leak is unknown, although it happened before 2018. 200,000 emails and passwords to them in plain text were made publicly available.

title: Hookers
description: In October 2019, a data breach occurred on the Dutch prostitution forum Hookers.nl, exposing the personal information of sex workers and their clients. Hackers gained access to the forum through an unpatched vulnerability in vBulletin software. IP addresses, email addresses, usernames and bcrypt password hashes were published. A total of 291,000 participants were affected.

title: CryptoArchiveNoPublik
description: A large collection of emails and passwords for them, collected in 2022 from leaks related to cryptocurrencies. Contains 71 million rows. Presumably used to hack accounts on crypto exchanges.

title: Apolyton
description: In May 2020, a data leak occurred on the gaming forum Apolyton Civilization Site, which affected 123 thousand users. The breach exposed email addresses, usernames and passwords in the form of VBulletin/BcryptMD5 hashes.

title: Seat.es
description: In 2021, there was a leak from the official website of the Spanish automaker SEAT. Approximately 703 thousand user data was published, including names, emails, phone numbers and passwords.

title: Igis.ru
description: The Izhevsk geographic information system Igis was hacked in September 2024 by hackers who published about 80 thousand records. The compromised information included emails, names, phone numbers, IP addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes.

title: BlackHatWorld
description: In June 2014, 750 thousand accounts were hacked from the Black Hat World search engine optimization forum system. The breach included dates of birth, email addresses, personal messenger data, IP addresses, passwords, usernames and website activity.

title: APKTW
description: Around September 2022, the Taiwanese website APK.TW suffered a data breach that affected 3.7 million users. The leak exposed usernames, email addresses, IP addresses and passwords as salted MD5 hashes (type 2611).

title: Vird.ru
description: This is a virtual dispatcher for cargo transportation in Russia. It was hacked in Argust 2020, affecting 92 thousand users. The data contains full names, registration dates and one or two telephone numbers of each client.

title: VitaExpress
description: On June 8, 2023, a partial leak from the Russian online pharmacy VitaExpress.ru was made publicly available. The published data contains 666 thousand records and includes emails, names, phone numbers and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: Wishbone 2020
description: In January 2020, the “anything comparison” mobile app Wishbone was affected. This is the second app data leak, the first was in 2016. The published data included nearly 10 million unique email addresses, passwords, names, phone numbers, geographic locations and other personal user attributes. Passwords were stored as MD5 hashes without salt.

title: Residents St.Petersburg
description: In May 2021, a database of residents of St. Petersburg became publicly available. It contained about 700 thousand records containing names and information about them, including passports, telephone numbers and other data recorded in one field.

title: Avtoto
description: AvtoTO.ru is a Russian auto parts store. On August 14, 2022, Ukrainian hackers released a store database containing names, phone numbers, addresses, emails and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes. In total, 510 thousand store customers were affected.

title: Bitrix vacancies
description: In October 2022, hackers made the database of the job search service “Bitrix Jobs” publicly available. The database contained 1 million rows. The records included full name, desired positions, resume processing status and other data.

title: USALife
description: USA.Life is a self-proclaimed alternative to Facebook dedicated to free speech. In 2020, the service’s database was hacked and posted on a hacker forum. The leak contains 144,637 usernames, email addresses and passwords with various first and last names. Passwords are a mixture of SHA-1 and bcrypt.

title: InfoFlot
description: In July 2024, the database of Russia's largest center, Infoflot, specializing in river and sea cruises, became publicly available. The leak contains information from 2 million of the company's clients. The data contains names, passports, telephones, mails and other data.

title: Click.org
description: In April 2021, click tracking software Click.org suffered a data breach. The leak included email addresses, IP addresses, physical addresses, names, phone numbers. In total, 542 thousand users were affected.

title: BlackStarWear.ru
description: In February 2021, a Russian branded clothing store created by the music group BlackStar suffered from a data leak. 180 thousand user posts and the same number of their orders were published. The data contains emails, phone numbers, names, IP addresses, passwords in the form of SHA1 hashes with salt, as well as addresses for delivery of goods.

title: Kora.ru
description: On August 17, 2023, from the online cosmetics store Kora.ru, data from 2.5 million records, including emails, phone numbers and customer names, became publicly available.

title: Espiya.net
description: Espiya is a forum dedicated to discussing the topic of espionage and surveillance. In 2021, there was a leak on it, revealing almost 200 thousand users of the site. The data contains names, emails, IPs, regions of residence and passwords in the form of SHA1 hashes with salt.

title: BolshayaPeremena
description: On July 10, 2023, the hacker group NLB published a leak from the Russian website “Big Change,” which organizes events. The leak contains the names, phone numbers, emails, addresses and places of education of five million people, including schoolchildren, students and teachers.

title: Job.sy
description: In March 2020, there was a data leak from an online job search platform in Syria. It contained about 80 thousand entries, including full names in Arabic and English, passwords in the form of MD5 hashes, phone numbers and email.

title: MuMaYi
description: In May 2011, a data leak occurred on the Chinese Android site MuMaYi, which affected 132 thousand subscribers. The breach included email addresses, IP addresses, usernames, dates of birth and passwords stored as MD5 hashes.

title: LeadHunters (fake)
description: In March 2020, a huge collection of data was discovered on a public server. But now it is not publicly available and only a fake database with the same name is available, containing the names, emails, telephone numbers, dates of birth and addresses of almost 9 million people. The source of this database is unknown.

title: Sgtas.ua
description: This is a Ukrainian insurance company hacked in 2021. The leaked data became publicly available only at the beginning of 2024 and includes two tables - car insurance data (3 million records) and data of people traveling abroad (500 thousand records). The leak contains Taxpayer Identification Number (TIN), car license plates, VIN, car models, cities of residence, as well as dates and amounts of insurance. There are no names or phone numbers in the database.

title: Rus-buket.ru
description: An online store delivering flower arrangements suffered a hacker attack in March 2020. As a result, a database containing about 16 thousand records was published. Among the stolen information were names, addresses, emails, phone numbers and some order information.

title: DLH.net
description: In July 2016, gaming news site DLH.net suffered a data breach. As a result, the identities of 3.3 million subscribers were revealed. The leak led to the disclosure of emails, dates of birth and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes. hashes.

title: SexClub.ru
description: In December 2021, a dump of the adult dating site SexClub containing 320 thousand entries was made publicly available. The data contains emails, nicknames, IP addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes.

title: Ongab.ru
description: In 2019, a leak occurred on the Russian gaming site Ongab.ru. 92 thousand users were affected. Emails, names, IDs of Facebook and Contact accounts, as well as passwords in the form of MD5 hashes were made publicly available.

title: Intime.ua
description: In 2018, the Ukrainian postal service InTime was hacked. 250 thousand records containing information about the senders and recipients of parcels, including names, phone numbers and addresses, have become publicly available.

title: Gravatar scrape 2023
description: The Gravatar service allows users to use one avatar on multiple services. In January 2023, the data of 61 million users was collected from it using scraping. They included mails, nicknames and avatars.

title: Zakupka
description: In September 2016, the Ukrainian marketplace zakupka.com was hacked. As a result of this, hackers managed to download a database larger than 25GB. It contained 840 thousand telephone numbers and 1.2 million emails, as well as other information about users: IP addresses, dates of birth, addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: Alora
description: At the beginning of 2018, a data leak occurred on the private server RuneScape Alora, which affected 207 thousand users. The breach included usernames, email addresses, IP addresses and passwords stored as IPB hashes. Alora denied that any data was accessed in their ad.

title: Bikerep.dk
description: BikeRep is a Danish bicycle repair site. It was hacked in July 2023. The leak contains 35 thousand records and includes emails, phone numbers, addresses, Facebook accounts and passwords in the form of unknown hashes.

title: France Covid
description: France's database of COVID-19 vaccine recipients suffered a leak in 2019. It contained 440 thousand records including full names, emails, phone numbers and addresses.

title: Tula.ru
description: On August 7, 2023, a partial database of the official portal of the city of Tula (in Russia) became publicly available. The data contains 6900 records with names, emails and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: SweClockers
description: In early 2015, the Swedish news site “SweClockers” was hacked. 255 thousand accounts were exposed. The attack exposed usernames, email addresses and salted password hashes encrypted using a combination of MD5 and SHA512.

title: Business Molodost
description: Business Youth is a now defunct entrepreneurial training company. It was hacked in 2015, but the database became publicly available only in the summer of 2024. The data contains only the name and one or two emails of each client. A total of 850 thousand records. Given this data set, it is likely that the database was obtained through scraping rather than hacking.

title: Dodonew
description: At the end of 2011, the base from the Chinese web site Dodonew.com got into open access.They contained 8.7 million accounts.The data in the violation contain email addresses, user names and passwords in the form of simple text.

title: Cerebriti
description: Around January 2020, the Spanish learning games and knowledge portal Cerebriti experienced a data breach. The breach exposed full names, email addresses, gender, dates of birth, IP addresses and passwords stored as SHA1 hashes. In total, 126 thousand users were affected.

title: Confael.ru
description: The Russian online chocolate and gift store Confael.ru suffered a data leak in 2015. About 13 thousand records containing full names, cities, phone numbers and emails of clients were leaked into the network.

title: Yappy
