description: On November 8, 2022, it became known about a leak in the Russian video hosting “Yappy”. The published database contained 2.1 million phone numbers, 400 thousand names, 300 thousand emails and only a few dozen hashed passwords.

title: Borealis
description: Sometime in 2018, a data leak occurred on the Russian Minecraft Borealis server, which affected 351 thousand users. The breach exposed usernames, email addresses and passwords in clear text.

title: NomerIO
description: In July 2021, the nomer.io service and all its mirrors suffered from a hack. This service provided a search for personal data by phone number. The leak contains 4.5 million emails with passwords without hashing. There is also data on status and total spending. The database was obtained as follows: the source code of the site was found, which contained the administrator’s email, the password for this email was found in other databases and was suitable.

title: JoyGames 2022
description: In September 2022, a leak occurred on the gaming website JoyGames. She exposed names, email addresses, IPs and passwords as salted MD5 hashes. Due to the fact that JoyGames does not use captcha, there are many bots among users. A total of 4.8 million users. The site had already been hacked earlier in 2019.

title: Carding Mafia
description: The Carding Mafia forum was designed to steal and trade stolen credit cards. In March 2021, a leak occurred on the forum, which exposed emails, usernames, IP addresses and passwords in the form of salted MD5 hashes. In total, almost 300 thousand participants were affected. The forum was later hacked again in December 2021, just 9 months later, but this leak is not publicly available.

title: Infiniton.es
description: This database of the Spanish company Infiniton, which sells household appliances, became publicly available in March 2023. The leak contained data from 280 thousand users, such as names, emails and purchase amounts.

title: Clf09
description: Around July 2022, the Chinese adult forum 草榴社區 (clf09) suffered a data breach that affected 3.2 million users. The breach included usernames, email addresses and passwords stored as MD5 hashes.

title: Quickdns.xyz
description: A database of an unknown service that became publicly available in June 2023. Contains 9.5 million mails and the dates they were added to the system.

title: FNS 2019
description: In 2019, data from the Russian tax service became publicly available. They consisted of more than 6,000 documents in xml format containing data about campaigns and their owners. The data included full names, tax identification numbers, legal codes, and company areas of activity. A total of 3.6 million records.

title: Tumblr
description: In early 2013, Tumblr suffered a leak that exposed over 65 million accounts. The data was later put up for sale and included emails and passwords as SHA1 hashes with a salt.

title: Anilibria
description: Around August 2018, the Russian anime site AniLibria suffered a data leak that affected 149 thousand users. The attack exposed usernames, email addresses and passwords stored as statically salted MD5 hashes.

title: Akb.ru
description: In November 2024, there was a large-scale compromise of information on the AKB.ru website. On a specialized forum, a user with the nickname B1sko posted an information array of the leading Russian platform selling car batteries and components. More than 1.2 million consumer records, including nicknames, email addresses, and mobile numbers, were leaked into the network.

title: Go Games
description: Around October 2015, the manga website gogames.me suffered a data breach. The exposed data included records of 3.4 million customers, including email, IP addresses, usernames and passwords in the form of salted MD5 hashes. Go Games did not respond to reports of the incident.

title: Tacomart.com
description: Tacomart is a Taiwanese e-commerce service. At the end of 2012, it suffered a leak that affected more than one million people. The data includes emails, phone numbers, names, addresses, educational backgrounds and other information.

title: AlfaBank 2023
description: In October 2023, it became known that Alfabank was hacked by the NLB hacker team. They said they had 21 million bank customer records. The database consisted of three tables - with names, emails and telephone numbers. At the same time, the bank knew up to ten telephone numbers for each client, and therefore the total number of telephones exceeded 60 million, of which 46 million were unique. The data also included names, dates of birth, credit card and account numbers, and card expiration dates.

title: GamerSoul
description: Around May 2020, there was a data leak on the gaming forum GamerSoul. The attack resulted in the disclosure of data including email addresses and passwords stored as VBulletin and Bcrypt hashes. In total, 152 thousand users were affected. The site does not currently exist.

title: CleverMarkets.com
description: The CleverMarkets trading forum was hacked in November 2019. 20 thousand users were affected. IP addresses, email addresses, usernames and passwords were published as salted MD5 hashes.

title: GlavKniga.ru
description: The Russian website, publishing house Main Book, was hacked on December 6, 2019. A database containing more than 23 thousand records, including emails, phone numbers and usernames, was compromised.

title: Evony
description: In June 2016, the online multiplayer game Evony was hacked and over 29 million unique accounts were exposed. The attack exposed usernames, email addresses and IP addresses, as well as unsalted MD5 password hashes.

title: F4club.ru
description: In March 2024, a database appeared in telegram channels containing 57 thousand emails and no other data. It was alleged that it was obtained from the erotic site F4club.ru, but the recovery form on the site shows that the users from the leak are not registered there, and therefore the reliability of the data remains questionable.

title: AstraMetall.ru
description: Somewhere between 2017 and 2019, Astra Metal, a Russian company that sells health insurance, experienced a data breach. 320 thousand records about clients were published, including their telephone numbers, names, mails, residential addresses, dates of birth and medical policy numbers.

title: PPCGeeks.com
description: In August 2016, a data leak occurred on the website PPCGeeks, a forum for fans of pocket PCs, which affected 492 thousand users. The attack resulted in the disclosure of data including usernames, email addresses, IP addresses, dates of birth and passwords stored as salted MD5 hashes.

title: AntiPublic
description: In December 2016, a huge leak containing 458 million unique emails and passwords appeared in the public domain. It was used to hack accounts in which the owner reused his password. Similar leaks are also used to assess the novelty of data in other databases.

title: VivaDengi.ru
description: This is a Russian website for issuing microloans. Was hacked in 2022. The published database contains name, phone number, mail, date and place of birth. There are 372 thousand lines in total, but there were duplicates among them.

title: URentBike
description: At the end of 2020, the Russian scooter and bicycle rental service Urent.ru suffered from a data leak. About 380 thousand user records with phone numbers, emails and device data were published. The database also contained a lot of service tables, payment data and other information.

title: LabQuest.ru
description: In December 2023, a file containing data from clients of the LabQuest medical laboratory was made publicly available. The data contains 466 thousand lines with names, phone numbers, emails, date of birth and passport details. Dumps of employee emails were also published.

title: Ural-Toys.ru
description: On May 17, 2022, the database of the Ural Toys store, which specializes in the wholesale sale of toys, became publicly available. The data of 50 thousand users was exposed, including names, emails and telephone numbers. However, at the moment there are only 10 thousand records from the leak in the public domain.

title: Zakupis-ekb.ru
description: A website specializing in online shopping, Zakupis-ekb.ru, experienced a data leak. A database with information about 70 thousand users has leaked online. Emails, phone numbers and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes were compromised.

title: Void.to
description: In June 2019, the hacker website Void.to suffered a data leak. 95 thousand unique email addresses were published, as well as IP addresses, names, personal messages and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt or bcrypt. A rival hacking website claimed responsibility for the hack.

title: ReverbNation
description: In January 2014, ReverbNation, an online service designed to help musicians build their careers, suffered a leak. The data contained over 7 million accounts with unique email addresses and salted SHA1 passwords.

title: StreamCraft 2020
description: In June 2020, the Russian minecraft server StreamCraft suffered from a data leak. The published database included nicknames, emails, IP addresses and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes. In total, 1.8 million players were affected.

title: UtilityPayments Uzbekistan
description: This database contains data on utility payments obtained from the website egaz.uz. This is one of the government services of Uzbekistan. The data contains telephone numbers, names, passports, dates of birth, balance data and so-called PINFL codes. A total of 3.5 million records. The leak occurred on 06/08/2024.

title: Tricolor.ru
description: In 2021, the Russian television service Tricolor suffered from a data leak. The full version of the leak contained 3.8 million records, but only 300 thousand of them were made publicly available. The database contains full names, phone numbers, emails, addresses and dates of request for services.

title: Smida.gov.ua
description: At the beginning of June 2022, hackers hacked the Ukrainian state portal “Agency for Development of Stock Market Infrastructure of Ukraine” (smida.gov.ua) and published user data. The database contains 330 thousand records with emails, names, nicknames, phone numbers and passwords in the form of Argon or MD5 hashes without salt.

title: MyFitnessPal
description: In February 2018, diet and exercise service MyFitnessPal suffered a data breach. The incident exposed 144 million unique emails along with names, IPs and passwords in the form of SHA-1 and bcrypt hashes. All data, except for bcrypt hashes, was later made publicly available.

title: Residents RF 2019
description: In 2019, a database with data on Russian citizens was published. It contains 25 million records. The file contains names, phone numbers, addresses, passport details, Snils and INN numbers and dates of birth. The origin of the base is unknown.

title: Rendez-Vous
description: In January 2024, scans of passports and resumes of people who responded to vacancies for the online shoe and clothing store “Rendez-Vous” were posted on one of the forums. In addition to these documents, the hacker also leaked some tables from the database, including users, orders, reviews, resumes and other data. The information contained names, emails, telephone numbers, dates of birth, addresses, order costs and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt. There are about 9 million records in total.

title: Northwestern Federal District
description: This is a database of residents of the northwestern federal district of the Russian Federation, published in the fall of 2024. The origin of the data is unknown, but it is believed to have been scraped or hacked into one of the government websites. The database contains telephone numbers, names, dates of birth, passport details and residential addresses. A total of 1.8 million records.

title: Frostland.pro
description: Frostland is a Russian server for the game MineCraft. It is unknown when the leak occurred, but it affected 204 thousand accounts. Nicknames, emails and passwords were published in the form of MD5 hashes without salt.

title: AntiAgent.ru
description: At the end of September 2020, a database containing 50 thousand records related to the AntiAgent.ru platform, which deals with the rental and sale of real estate, became publicly available. The data contains emails and passwords in plain text.

title: Tailieu.vn
description: In November 2019, Vietnamese education website TaiLieu suffered a data breach that exposed 7.3 million customer records. The published data included usernames, email addresses, dates of birth and passwords stored as unsalted MD5 hashes.

title: AlfaStrah
description: On April 27, 2023, hackers from NLB made publicly available the database of the Russian insurance company Alfastrakhovanie, owned by Alfabank. The file contains 1 million records with names, dates of birth, emails, phone numbers and passwords in the form of hashes. Hackers claim that there are 14 million records in the complete leak.

title: TAPAirPortugal
description: In August 2022, the Portuguese airline TAP Air Portugal (FlyTap) was the target of a ransomware attack carried out by Ragnar Locker's gang. The hackers later leaked the compromised data through a public darknet site. More than 5 million unique email addresses were exposed, along with other personal data including names, gender, date of birth, phone numbers and physical addresses.

title: TikTok
description: Since the beginning of 2022, a huge database obtained from TikTok using parsing has been distributed in Telegram channels. The database, several hundred gigabytes in size, contains information about 300 million videos, but the number of unique authors is only about 200 thousand. The data contains nicknames and logins, statistics of views and comments, as well as links to avatars and video descriptions.

title: Samolet.ru
description: Samolet is a Russian company that sells apartments in new buildings in Moscow. In January 2023, it suffered a leak that affected 20,000 users and 3,000 employees. The data contains names, telephone numbers, emails, tax identification numbers and company names.

title: SportMarafon
description: Sport-marafon.ru is a Russian tourist and ski store. In 2022, it suffered a leak that affected 287 thousand users. Phone numbers, emails, names, dates of birth and residential addresses were made publicly available.

title: Jack Vosmyorkin
description: This database, published in September 2024 under the name "Jack Vosmerkin", contains 650 million records about Americans. The data contains connections between citizens at their place of residence. Has fields with names, addresses, associated people and SNN (US Social Security Number). The data in the database was taken from the previously sensational National Public Data leak and enriched with data from another lesser-known leak.

title: 1000dosok.ru
description: In May 2024, the free classifieds site 1000dosok was hacked. As a result, about a million entries were published with emails, phone numbers, nicknames, IP addresses, cities of residence and information about advertisements.

title: Minecraft-Monitor.ru
description: This is a Russian site that monitors activity on various Minecraft servers and stores lists of players on them. The date of the hack is unknown. The database contains almost 1.5 million entries, including nickname, server and the number of player logins to it.

title: Bureau van Dijk
description: Around July 2021, business information publisher specializing in “private company data,” Bureau van Dijk, suffered a data breach. The violation included full names, email addresses, phone numbers, physical addresses, dates of birth, job titles, European VAT numbers, tax numbers, patent numbers, patents. names, company names and other data. A total of 484 million rows of data.

title: Vk Parsing 2021
description: In 2021, the data of many users of the VKontakte social network was collected using parsing. Unlike most other parsers, this database contains connections between links to profiles and phone numbers. There are only 235 million records, but there is no data in the database except phone numbers and links.

title: Zoosk 2020
description: In January 2020, the online dating service Zoosk suffered a data leak that subsequently spread widely among online hacker communities. The hack contained 24 million unique email addresses and extensive personal information, including gender, dates of birth, height, weight, religion, ethnicity and political views. In hacker circles, some of the data, including passwords, was missing.

title: Doska.ykt
description: This is a news feed for the city of Yakutsk. In October 2024, all advertisements from this site were collected using parsing. The result was about 100 thousand records with phone numbers, names, ad descriptions and other information from user profiles.

title: Defineyolu.club
description: The now defunct website Defineyolu.club was hacked in November 2019. 37 thousand users were affected. IP addresses, email addresses, usernames and passwords were published as salted MD5 hashes.

title: Apt-Mebel.ru
description: This is a Russian furniture store.In October 2024, he suffered from a leak, which affected 870 thousand customers.The user table contained names, phones, mail, addresses and passwords in the form of Hash MD5 with salt or BCRYPT.SQL Dampus also contained somewhat smaller tables with other data.

title: Danto
description: This is a company specializing in e-commerce. At the end of 2023, a database containing the data of its users and their orders began to be distributed. The exact date of the leak is unknown, but the database contains more than 2 million people, as well as information about their emails, telephone numbers, addresses and cities of residence, as well as other information.

title: ToonDoo
description: In August 2019, comic book creation site ToonDoo suffered a data breach. The data was subsequently shared on a hacker forum, where a database containing more than 6 million entries was published. The data included email addresses, IP addresses, usernames, gender location and salted password hashes.

title: Renaissance Strah
description: In June 2023, it became known about a leak from the Russian insurance company Renaissance Insurance. Hackers hacked the eOSAGO service and compromised the login page for their personal account, which allowed them to collect data from approximately 2% of users. This is 632 thousand people. The data contains emails, full names and telephone numbers.

title: RoatPkz
description: Around July 2022, a private RuneScape server known as Roat Pkz suffered a data breach. The leak exposed usernames, email addresses and IP addresses. In total, 876 thousand users were affected. There are only about 40 thousand email addresses in the data.

title: Elevrus.com
description: Elevrus is a now defunct marketing community. His website was hacked in January 2016. The leak included names, emails, phones, regions, IPs and passwords in plain text. There are about 200 thousand records in total.

title: SandMc.ru
description: In December 2020, the databases of the MineCraft server SandPex (sandmc.ru) became publicly available. The dump, dating back to early 2020, contained nicknames, IP addresses and passwords in the form of AuthMe hashes. A total of 240 thousand users. The server was later hacked again in early 2021.

title: RussianTax 2022
description: Around 2022, there was a major leak from the Russian tax system. The exact cause of the leak is unknown, but the subsequently published file contained 55 million records. The leak includes names, phone numbers, emails, dates of birth, SNILS data and INN.

title: Instant Checkmate
description: In 2019, public records search service Instant Checkmate suffered a data breach that was later reported in early 2023. The data included nearly 12 million unique customer email addresses, names, phone numbers and passwords stored as scrypt hashes.

title: PremiumBonus.ru
description: Premium Bonus is a Russian service with marketing tools to increase customer loyalty. Their website states that they are trusted by over 800 companies. As it turned out, they were trusted in vain, since at the beginning of 2021, information about all the site’s clients became publicly available. Data includes phone numbers, emails, names, dates of birth and gender. API keys were also stolen, which led to leaks from many other companies.

title: SellyVN
description: In February 2022, Vietnamese e-commerce platform selly.vn suffered a data leak. The breach exposed full names, email addresses and phone numbers. In total, 331 thousand users were affected.

title: Erolaif.ru
description: "Erolife" is a Russian online store of intimate goods. Was hacked on 02/19/2024. 35 thousand users and 49 thousand of their orders were made publicly available. The data contains emails, names, ip, passwords, addresses and a list of ordered goods.

title: Canva
description: In May 2019, the graphic design tool Canva's website suffered a data breach. This leak affected 137 million subscribers. The exposed data included email, names, cities of residence and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes.

title: Covid19
description: In 2020, during quarantine, all people traveling anywhere were entered into a certain register designed to prevent the spread of coronavirus. This register contained full names, passport details, mails, telephone numbers, places of work, travel routes and reasons for obtaining such a certificate. Later, this registry was hacked and 12.8 million records were made public.

title: CityBee
description: CityBee is a Lithuanian car sharing service that provides car, motorcycle and bicycle rental services. In February 2021, it suffered a data leak. The data of more than 110 thousand users was published, including names, email addresses, passwords in the form of SHA1 hashes and driver's license numbers. No credit card information was compromised.

title: Zhenai
description: In December 2011, Chinese dating site Zhenai.com suffered a data breach that affected 5 million subscribers. The leaked data contained email addresses and passwords in plain text.

title: Sirena 2016
description: Sirena Travel is the largest air ticket booking system. In 2016, it suffered a leak of passenger and flight data. The published database included 58.5 million passenger flight records. These records included the passengers' names, passport details and dates of birth, as well as information about the route and flight number.

title: DomConect.ru
description: In August 2022, the Russian Internet provider DomConect was hacked. The leak included technical support data, customer history and call data. The total number of telephones exceeds 2 million, but there is almost no data on customer names.

title: Parking.mos.ru
description: In December 2018 and January 2019, two leaks occurred from the Moscow parking service. These leaks contain phone numbers, license plates and parking information. The first leak contains 6.76 million users, and the second leak contains 5.7 million. This is not the first leak of this service. In 2016, their clients’ bank cards were also leaked.

title: LK.vodo-kanal.ru
description: In February 2023, the database of the Cheboksary water utility became publicly available. The leak contains emails, names, phone numbers and addresses. A total of 40 thousand records.

title: GamingUnity
description: Around May 2017, the gaming website GamingUnity experienced a data breach. The attack exposed email addresses, usernames and passwords as salted MD5 hashes. In total, 11.4 thousand users were affected. The website has since been renamed and is now something else.

title: Deezer
description: At the end of 2022, music streaming service Deezer reported a data breach that affected more than 240 million customers. The breach occurred due to a backup published in mid-2019 by a third-party partner. The affected data included 229 million emails, as well as IP addresses, usernames, gender, dates of birth and geographic locations of customers.

title: HabboSt
description: Around February 2017, the gaming website habbo.st experienced a data breach. As a result of the incident, more than 888 thousand strings were exposed, including more than 590 thousand unique email addresses, IP addresses, usernames and passwords. Passwords are stored as md5($pass.$salt) hashes with a static salt xCg532%@%gdvf^5DGaa6&*rFTfg^FD4$OIFThrR_gh(ugf*/

title: USA phones database
description: A huge database of US residents containing 183 million rows. It was published in April 2022 and included full names, phone numbers, emails, gender and career details. There were very few emails - approximately 9.2 million.

title: Fractal
description: Around May 2021, international artificial intelligence and analytics service Fractal suffered a data breach. The hack exposed email addresses, job titles, full names and phone numbers. In total, 12.2 million users were affected.

title: 100realt.ru
description: At the end of 2021, data from the Russian real estate website 100realt.ru was collected using scraping. The leak contains names, phone numbers, addresses and information about the products being sold. A total of 4.7 million records.

title: EstanteVirtual
description: In February 2019, EstanteVirtual, the largest book portal in Brazil, suffered a data leak. The attack exposed full names, usernames, email addresses, physical addresses and passwords in the form of SHA-1 hashes. A total of 5.4 million users were affected. The website was hacked by "Gnosticplayers".

title: Fotostrana.ru (parsing)
description: Fotostrana is a Russian dating site. In 2022, all user data was collected from it using parsing, resulting in a database of 80 million rows. After removing duplicates and blank pages, 36 million records remained. The data includes names, dates of birth, cities of residence, gender, description and link to the user's avatar and profile.

title: Drizly
description: Around July 2020, the American online alcohol delivery service Drizly suffered a data breach. The data was sold online and then widely distributed. The leak contained 2.5 million unique email addresses, as well as names, physical and IP addresses, phone numbers, dates of birth and passwords in bcrypt hashes.

title: Caorle
description: In April 2022, the Italian travel website Caorle suffered a data breach that affected 20.3 thousand users. The breach exposed full names, email addresses, phone numbers, physical addresses and nationalities.

title: Belarus.unn
description: There is a database on the Internet with information about 488 thousand residents of Belarus, containing TIN and full names. The source was probably the scraping of one of the government websites.

title: EGRIP
description: In Russia there is a “Unified State Register of Individual Entrepreneurs” (USRIP). In 2022, there was a leak in it, as a result of which the data of 16.8 million Russians was published. A huge database of 140Gb included information about all individual entrepreneurs, including names, addresses, mails, businesses, occupations, passport details, dates of issue of certificates and legal codes - INN, OGRN, GRNIP, OGRNIP, SPVZ, OKVED and others.

title: B2B USA Businesses
description: In mid-2017, a spam list of more than 105 million people living in America was discovered on the Internet. The list, called "B2B USA Businesses," categorized email addresses by employer, providing information about individuals' job titles as well as their work phone numbers and physical addresses.

title: Legalizer
description: In August 2021, an unknown hacker hacked and posted data from the legalizer drug trading platform. A complete dump was made publicly available, including products, posts, comments, personal messages, nicknames and emails. The forum contained 45 thousand users and 170 thousand personal messages.

title: SlideTeam
description: In April 2021, SlideTeam, the "world's largest collection of pre-designed presentation slides," had 1.4 million user records hacked. The following year they were published on a popular hacker forum. The data included names, email addresses, and passwords as salted hashes (Magento). A strongpoint from an intermediate server was probably used for the hack.

title: Foreign citizens RF
description: There is a publicly accessible database with information about more than 4 million citizens living in Russia. The data was obtained in 2019 from an unknown source. The file contained full names, passport details, addresses, as well as information about citizenship and documents.

title: CanadaProtein.com
description: CanadaProtein, an online store specializing in the sale of sports nutrition and health and fitness supplements, suffered from a data leak about more than 145 thousand users. The compromised data contains emails, full names, IP addresses and passwords as a salted SHA1 hash.

title: QQ
description: In 2020, the Chinese website QQ suffered a data leak. The attack exposed user IDs and phone numbers associated with them. In total, 719 million people were affected.

title: Dubsmash
description: In December 2018, the video messaging service Dubsmash suffered a leak. The incident revealed 162 million unique emails, as well as PBKDF2 usernames and password hashes. In 2019, everything became open access.

title: Megafon.ru
description: In 2007, the Russian telephone operator Megafon suffered from user leakage. Data from 100 thousand records containing telephone numbers, names, addresses and passport data of clients were made publicly available.

title: Darkhvh.ru
description: The Minecraft gaming platform of the Darkhvh server, on May 24, 2023, suffered from a hacker attack. As a result, 45 thousand player records were made publicly available, including nicknames, IP addresses and passwords in plain text.

title: Okrug
description: In 2022, the Russian special molds store Okrug.ru suffered from a leak. About 200 thousand records were published with telephone numbers, names, dates of birth and, in some cases, residential addresses.

title: Register DrugAddicts
description: This database contains a list of drug addicts in Russia. The data is a combination of various registries of prisoners and those undergoing treatment. The leak contains 128 thousand people with their name, date of birth and residential address. The leak appeared in 2023, but the date of data collection is unknown.

title: Emias
description: In April 2024, it became known that the servers of the Moscow Information Technology Department were hacked. According to the hackers, they managed to steal 40 terabytes of information. Many services were affected, the databases of which subsequently periodically appeared in the public domain. This also affected the Unified Medical Information and Analytical System (UMIAS), the database of which was published at the end of August 2024. The data contains 19 million unique records with names, dates of birth, telephone numbers, mails, document numbers, addresses and other numerous information.

title: CashToYou
description: CashToYou is one of the Russian microfinance organizations. On 12/16/2023 it suffered from a leak that affected almost 13 million users. The published table contains a very large number of columns with information about clients, their places of work, income, loan terms and other data. The database also contains scans of documents and photographs in the form of links, which is rare for leaks.

title: RZD
description: On November 6, 2020, a data leak occurred in the Russian Railways (RZD) company. The Russian Railways bonus program has suffered. The leak contains 1.36 million user emails, their passwords as salted MD5 hashes, and the language used. The database also contained a lot of technical information, such as train schedules and the order of stations. This is the second Russian Railways leak, the first happened in 2019.

title: Ohrana.ua
description: The Ukrainian website Ohrana, which provides security and safety services, became a victim of a data leak on November 24, 2019. A database with information about 76 thousand users was leaked online, containing phone numbers, full names, IP addresses and, in some cases, comments from profiles.

title: HotelPlazaRoma.com
description: In March 2023, an SQL dump of the website of the HotelPlazaRoma hotel, located in Spain, became publicly available. The leak contains 16 thousand customer records with emails, phone numbers, names and other data.

title: ArmA3Life
description: In July 2015, a data leak occurred on the ArmA3-Life gaming forum. The breach exposed usernames, email addresses, dates of birth, IP addresses and passwords stored as IPB hashes. In total, 125 thousand users were affected.

title: Iw-shop.ru
description: In 2017, there was a data leak from the Russian website iw-shop, specializing in the sale of sports nutrition. It affected 12 thousand user records and 18 thousand of their orders. The database included full names, emails, telephone numbers and delivery addresses.

title: ShockGore
description: In August 2020, a website for sharing graphic videos and images of animal cruelty suffered a data breach. The hack exposed 74,000 unique email addresses, as well as usernames, IP addresses, gender, and unsalted SHA-1 password hashes. Personal messages were also disclosed, many of which contained requests for publication of materials.

title: V-Tight Gel
description: Around February 2016, data came out from the V-Tight Gel website. The leak contains 2 million records. The data contained personal information including name, telephone number and physical address. V-Tight Gel did not respond to multiple requests for comment.

title: Omaze
description: In July 2020, online fundraising platform Omaze was hacked. As a result, 2.7 million users suffered from their personal information being leaked. Data included usernames, email addresses, passwords, social media links, geographic locations, first names, last names, and gender of users.

title: VipСhecker
description: VipСhecker is a Russian site for aggregating Minecraft server leaks, which allows you to hack accounts on different servers. In 2020, the complete collection of databases for this checker was leaked. The data includes 26 million records. Each entry contains the server name, the player's nickname, and the password they used in plain text or as an AuthMe hash.

title: BitcoinSecurity
description: In September 2014, a large dump of 5 million usernames and passwords was discovered posted on a Russian Bitcoin forum. Contained mostly Gmail.

title: UFCFightClub
description: In November 2017, a data leak occurred on the forums of the UFC fight club website (forums.ufcfightclub.com), which affected 239 thousand users. The breach included email addresses, IP addresses, usernames and passwords stored as md5 hashes.

title: Eskimi
description: At the end of 2020, the platform at Eskimi suffered a data breach that exposed 2.6 million records with 1.2 million unique email addresses. The data included usernames, dates of birth, gender, and passwords as unsalted MD5 hashes.

title: Royal Enfield
description: In January 2020, motorcycle maker Royal Enfield left its database publicly accessible, resulting in the inadvertent release of data from over 400,000 customers. The leaks included email addresses, physical addresses, names, motorcycle information, social media profiles, encrypted passwords and other personal information.

title: VipHackForums
description: Around December 2014, a data leak occurred on the hacker forum VipHackForums, which affected 35 thousand users. The breach included usernames, IP addresses, email addresses and passwords stored as MD5 hashes.

title: ParfumCity.com.ua
description: In March 2021, the Ukrainian cosmetics store ParfumCity suffered from a hack. The published database contains tables of users, orders, comments and reviews. A total of 40 thousand clients and 500 thousand orders. The data contains phone numbers, emails, names, passwords in the form of MD5 hashes, delivery addresses, IP, order amounts and comments on them.

title: Individual Enterprises RF 2017
description: In Russia there is a register of individual entrepreneurs, the data from which is available to everyone. In 2017, all users were removed from it using parsing. The resulting database contains about 2 million records with full names, TINs and regions.

title: Vk Phone 2021
description: In 2021, using parsing, a database of phone numbers of users of the Russian social network VKontakte was created. It remained private for a long time and began to spread only in the summer of 2023. The database contains phone numbers, names and account IDs. A total of 5.7 million records.

title: XBIZ
description: In June 2017, the “Adult Industry Social Network” XBIZ.net suffered a data leak that affected 28 thousand members. The breach included usernames, email addresses, IP addresses, dates of birth and passwords stored as vBulletin hashes.

title: LocateFamily.com
description: At the beginning of 2018, the LocateFamily website was hacked. This American site was created to search for people, for which it collects their personal data. The published version contains 140 thousand entries, but more than 11 million people were likely affected. Data includes telephone numbers, names and addresses.

title: Zoosk 2011
description: Around 2011, it became known about the alleged hacking of the dating site Zoosk.com. The data consists of 53 million records. They include email addresses and plain text passwords. However, there is no evidence that the data actually came from the Zoosk service. Zoosk later suffered another leak in 2020. It included 24 million users.

title: Getcontact+NumBuster
description: The Getcontact and NumBuster services allow you to determine by looking at a person’s phone number how other people list him in phone books. Data from such services is regularly collected into collections. One of these was published in 2022 and contained 141,000 telephone numbers and 867,000 names from phone books.

title: Rusrek.com
description: Rusrek is an information portal for Russian-speaking residents of the United States. In early 2021, it suffered a hack that exposed 160,000 records of its users. The data contains names, emails, IP addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: GoGames 2020
description: Around January 2020, a data leak occurred on the Go Games manga website. The breach resulted in the disclosure of data of usernames, email addresses and passwords stored as salted MD5 hashes. In total, 6.3 million users were affected. The previous Go Games hack occurred in 2015 and then affected about 3 million users.

title: BigBasket
description: In October 2020, Indian grocery platform bigbasket suffered a data breach. More than 20 million customer records were exposed. The data was initially sold and became public the following April. The data included email, IP, physical addresses, names, phone numbers, dates of birth, and passwords as Django hashes (SHA-1).

title: TridentCryptoFund
description: Around February 2020, cryptocurrency investment platform Trident Crypto Fund suffered a data breach. The hack included email addresses, full names, phone numbers, countries, IP addresses and passwords stored as MD5 hashes. In total, 263 thousand users were affected.

title: Kyrgyzstan FOMS 2019
description: In 2019, the database of the Compulsory Health Insurance Fund of Kyrgyzstan became publicly available. The leak contains 7.6 million records and includes only names, dates of birth and the so-called PIN - a personal number that is used as a tax identification number.

title: ParagonCheats
description: In May 2021, the Paragon Cheats website, dedicated to cheats for GTA Online, suffered a data leak. The hack exposed 188,000 customer records, including usernames, email addresses and IP addresses.

title: OwnedCore
description: Around August 2013, a World of Warcraft exploits forum called "OwnedCore" was hacked. The data of more than 880 thousand accounts was made publicly available. The forum also included IP addresses and passwords stored as salted hashes using a weak implementation that made it possible to quickly crack many of them.

title: IPMart
description: In 2015, iPmart (now known as Mobi NUKE) was hacked and the data of 2.4 million forum members was stolen. Including IP, dates of birth and passwords in the form of illiterately salted hashes.

title: OnlineTkani.ru
description: In February 2023, the Russian website OnlineTkani.ru, specializing in the sale of tools and materials for sewing, encountered an incident as a result of which its user database was leaked online. It contained 15 thousand customer records and 67 thousand order records, which included emails, phone numbers, IP addresses, full names, and salted SHA1 hashed passwords.

title: Willway.ru
description: In March 2023, a hack occurred on the Willway transfer booking website. A database of 7,700 records was published. It contains emails, names, addresses, places of work and 1-3 phone numbers of each client.

title: EduMarket.ru
description: In May 2024, the Russian educational website EduMarket.ru suffered from a hack. As a result, two different versions of its user data were publicly available, each containing about a million records. The data contains phone numbers, emails, names, dates of birth and passwords in plain text.

title: PlanetaObuvi.ru
description: In June 2020, the Russian shoe store PlanetaObuvi suffered from a hack. An SQl dump containing 20 thousand users and 60 thousand of their orders has become publicly available. The data includes names, emails, telephone numbers, IP addresses, passwords in the form of MD5 hashes and addresses for delivery of orders.

title: ProctorU.com
description: “ProctorU” is a service that allows students to take exams remotely. He is known for actually installing spyware on the computers of exam takers that monitors cameras, browsers, files on disks, etc. In July 2020, a dump of this service appeared, containing 444 thousand lines. Including names, emails, telephone numbers, addresses, citizenship and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes.

title: Mspy.com
description: In June 2024, hackers obtained a huge amount of data from spyware manufacturer mSpy and published it online. The archive contained 142 GB of user data and support tickets, as well as 176 GB of more than half a million email attachments. In total, the leak contained 2.4 million unique email addresses, IP names, and photos. These were essentially support tickets asking for help installing spyware on targeted devices, while the attachments contained various data, including screenshots of financial transactions and credit card photos. A mspy leak dating back to 2015 was previously published, but there was no data in it.

title: HDFCbank.com
description: One of the largest private Indian banks suffered a data breach in 2023. 3.2 million records were compromised, including emails, addresses, names and phone numbers of clients.

title: Jobs.ua
description: This is a Ukrainian job search site. In 2021, it suffered from a leak; about 4 million records were uploaded to the public domain, but the number of unique users is lower. The data contains emails, names, phone numbers, IP addresses, dates of birth and information about vacancies and positions - their name, description and desired income.

title: P3dhack.ru
description: At the beginning of July 2023, the P3dhack website, which provides cheats for the game PayDay 2, was hacked, affecting the data of 35 thousand users. The database contained nicknames, emails, IP addresses and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes.

title: Arteza.com
description: Arteza.com is an online store of goods for artists. In March 2023, a leak from this site appeared online, containing the data of 576,000 users. The data included emails, full names, dates of birth, locations and website balances.

title: VKmix.com
description: In 2020, the VKmix.com website, which provides promotion on social networks, was hacked. The published database contains only emails and passwords in plain text, with a total of 1.4 million entries.

title: Jefit
description: In August 2020, the workout tracking app Jefit was hacked. The data was sold to the hacker community and included 9 million emails, IPs, names and passwords in the form of vBulletin or argon2 hashes.

title: Turecarga.com
description: In 2012, the website of the now defunct mobile phone charging company Turecarga in Spain was hacked. The leak, 485 thousand lines in size, contains emails, names, dates of birth and residential addresses of users.

title: FunnyGames
description: In April 2018, online entertainment site Funny Games suffered a data breach that exposed 764,000 emails, as well as IP addresses and salted MD5 hashes of passwords. In July, the incident was reported to Funny Games, which acknowledged the breach and determined that it was caused by outdated code that was no longer in use. The number of entries in the hack represents approximately half of the user base.

title: JustDate
description: The alleged hack of the dating website Justdate.com hit the internet in September 2016. It included more than 24 million records: email addresses, dates of birth and physical location. Most likely, the data was obtained from another source.

title: MyHeritage
description: In October 2017, the genealogy site MyHeritage was leaked. This became known 7 months later. More than 92 million customer records were exposed, including email and password hashes with SHA-1 salt.

title: AutoCentrum.pl
description: In February 2018, a data leak incident occurred on a popular Polish portal dedicated to car reviews and auto services. 164 thousand records containing emails and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes were exposed.

title: Forex 40k
description: A Forex market database has appeared online, containing information about 40 thousand users, including names, phone numbers and emails.

title: QZaem
description: In September 2023, a leak occurred from the microcredit organization Qzaem. In January 2024, the data of its users began to be sold on the darknet. After 5 months, the vulnerability on the site was still not fixed, and therefore other hackers downloaded a new database on 02/03/2024 and made it publicly available. The database contains two files, which contain a total of 7.6 million unique records. The data includes phones, names, emails, addresses, IPs, loan amounts, passport data and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with an unknown static salt.

title: Adapt
description: In November 2018, an unprotected database was discovered hosted on the Adapt data aggregator. More than 9.3 million unique records of individuals were found, including their names, employer names, job titles, contact information, and employer information. including a description of the organization's size and income. There was no response from Adapt.

title: JetAudio
description: In November 2008, audio player company COWON America (JetAudio) suffered a data breach that affected 17.5 thousand members. The hack included usernames, email addresses, dates of birth, IP addresses and passwords stored as vBulletin hashes.

title: Kazakhstan Resident 2021
description: In 2021, a file containing personal information of citizens of Kazakhstan appeared online. The data included full names, tax identification numbers and phone numbers. In total, it contained 633 thousand records.

title: LeslipFrancais.fr
description: In April 2024, a data leak occurred from the French company Le Slip Français, a manufacturer of underwear. As a result, 1.5 million records containing email addresses, physical addresses, names and phone numbers of users were exposed.

title: Play.anicloud.ru
description: In May 2023, the database of the minecraft server complex - Anicloud - became publicly available. Previously, the server was called Forine and was also leaked. The data contains 7 thousand records about players and includes nicknames, IP addresses and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes.

title: FMS Moscow 2017
description: In 2017, there was a data leak from the server of the Federal Migration Service of Moscow. 40 thousand records were publicly available, including names, passport details and residential addresses.

title: Legendas
description: In October 2017, Spanish subtitle site Legendas suffered a data breach that affected 3.8 million subscribers. The breach included usernames, email addresses, IP addresses, full names and unencrypted passwords.

title: FerretCheck
description: In the fall of 2020, the FerretCheck checker database was published. This service searched for users in hacked databases for the game MineCraft and returned lists of their passwords. This was used to hack their accounts on game servers. The database included leaks from approximately 80 game servers, totaling 19 million lines. They contained nicknames, passwords in the form of AuthMe hashes, IP addresses and a total of 447 thousand emails.

title: CaterinaLeman.ru
description: Caterina Leman is a luxury fashion brand and an online store specializing in the sale of high-quality clothing and accessories focused on fashionable buyers in Russia and neighboring countries.In October 2024, the database from this site got into open access.The leak contains 12 thousand records with names, phones, posts and dates of the birth of customers of the store.

title: Ducks Unlimited
description: In mid-2021, Ducks Unlimited, an American wetland conservation organization, reported a data breach. The data dates back to January 2021 and contains 1.3 million email addresses of website users. The affected data included names, phone numbers, physical addresses, dates of birth, and passwords in the form of unsalted MD5 hashes.

title: Turkey citizen
description: In 2016, a data dump was published containing information about 49.6 million Turkish citizens. The database contains full names, places of residence, names of parents, dates of birth and other information.

title: Tutu.ru
description: Tutu.ru company specializes in the sale of train tickets, air tickets and hotel reservations. In March 2020, hackers gained access to the site's database and published all data from it. They included emails, phone numbers and other personal information. The data of 36 million users of the Tutu.ru mobile application was also compromised.

title: Opel-club.com.ua
description: This is a Ukrainian automobile website dedicated to the Opel brand. There is a publicly accessible database containing 71 thousand user records of this site. The data contains nicknames, emails and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: Zurich.com
description: In January 2023, the Japanese division of Zurich Insurance suffered a data breach that exposed the records of 2.6 million customers with more than 756 thousand unique email addresses. The data was subsequently posted on a hacker forum. The leak included names, gender, dates of birth and details of insured vehicles.

title: Traffic Police Krasnodar 2007
description: Leak from the Krasnodar traffic police dating back to 2007. Contains 300 thousand records, including telephone numbers, names, addresses, dates of birth, passport data and car data.

title: Ukraine 53M Citizenship
description: On September 13, 2021, it became known that a database of Ukrainian citizens had been leaked. The database, containing 53 million records, most likely came from government agencies. It contained home telephone numbers, full names and residential addresses.

title: Beeline Kazakhstan
description: In 2018, there was a leak of Beeline subscribers in Kazakhstan. The database contains 7.5 million records and includes names, phone numbers and addresses of clients.

title: Utah Gun Exchange
description: In July 2020, online gun message board Utah Gun Exchange suffered a data breach that affected several other related sites. A total of 235,000 unique email addresses were exposed and then sold online along with names, usernames, genders, IP addresses and password hashes.

title: MosParking
description: This is a database of Moscow parking lots containing data on their use from 2014 to 2019. The database contains 160 million records, but there are only 3.5 million unique users. The data contains phone number, date and time of parking, as well as information about the car.

title: GiveSendGo
description: In February 2022, Christian fundraising service GiveSendGo suffered a data breach. The personal details of 90,000 donors were released to protest vaccination mandates. The hack exposed names, email addresses, zip codes, donation amounts and comments made during the donation.

title: 14m Twitter Combo
description: A combination of emails and passwords for Twitter accounts obtained from various leaks. The database was published in August 2022 on a hacker forum.

title: VimeMC
description: At the beginning of 2018, the VimeMC minecraft server suffered from a hack. The leak contained half a million records with nicknames, IP addresses and passwords in the form of SHA1 hashes with salt.

title: Pinup
description: At the end of 2021, a hacker put up for sale the database of the Russian bookmaker PinUp. He sold 10 million records for 10 thousand dollars, but at the moment there are only about 900 thousand records in the public domain. The data contains emails, phone numbers, names and balance information.

title: Lumin PDF
description: In April 2019, the PDF management service suffered a data breach. This was not publicly reported until September, when data from 15.5 million users appeared on a popular hacker forum. The leak also included names, email addresses, gender, spoken language, and either a bcrypt password hash or a Google authentication token.

title: Travelio
description: In November 2021, Indonesian real estate website Travelio suffered a data breach that exposed more than 470,000 customer accounts. The data included email addresses, names, password hashes, phone numbers, dates of birth, and physical address.

title: Sirena 2023
description: Another leak of Sirena - a system for managing plane tickets. This service has been hacked almost every year since the 20th century. In 2023, the leak affected 3 million customers and information about their names, passports, phone numbers and flight routes.

title: GateHub
description: In October 2019, 1.4 million accounts from the cryptocurrency wallet service GateHub were posted on a popular hacker forum. The service previously acknowledged a data breach in June, although with fewer accounts affected. The hack data included email addresses, mnemonic phrases, encrypted master keys, encrypted recovery keys, and bcrypt hashed passwords.

title: Hyundai
description: This leak contains data from all Russians who bought Hyundai cars between 2019 and 2020. The data contains telephone numbers, names, residential addresses, car models and their VIN codes. The database was compiled from several other leaks.

title: Olx.ua
description: In June 2020, the Ukrainian classifieds website Olx.ua was cleared using scraping. It collected 4.5 million ads. The subsequently published database included the phone numbers and names of sellers, the products they sold, and links to these advertisements. This site has previously suffered a major leak.

title: AlloInternet.ru
description: In June 2022, the AlloInternet online hardware store was leaked. The data contains 111 thousand users and 118 thousand orders. Emails, names, phone numbers, addresses and passwords were compromised in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: Orteka.ru
description: In March 2024, it became known that the database of customers and their orders of another online store had been leaked. This time the network of orthopedic salons orteka.ru suffered. Initially, only part of the leak was made public, but just a month later the full database was also made public. This dump contains phone numbers, names, emails, cities, dates of birth and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes. Only 4 million users.

title: GameAwards.ru
description: In the spring of 2024, a database of users of the GameAwards.ru portal dedicated to video games appeared online. It contains about 200 thousand records, including emails, nicknames and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes.

title: Fling
description: In 2011, the adult social network Fling was hacked. 40 million accounts were exposed. The leak included personal data, as well as email addresses and passwords stored in plain text.

title: ClownForum
description: In May 2021, a data leak occurred on a clown forum called "ClownForum". The violation included email addresses and usernames. A total of 6.3 thousand participants were affected. The website has been down for over a year, simply displaying “Sorry, we are currently unavailable while we clean up the mess. Please come back later."

title: MyBusiness.rf
description: In May 2023, a complete SQL dump of the database of the national online portal Moybusiness.rf, which is intended for Russian entrepreneurs, became freely available. The table contains 207 thousand users. The data includes nicknames, names, emails, phones and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: Kyivcity.gov.ua
description: In February 2023, hackers hacked the official Internet portal of Kyiv and downloaded its database containing 127 thousand user records. Records will include names, dates of birth, addresses and document details. At the same time as this site, about 20 more government sites in Ukraine were hacked.

title: Zynga
description: In September 2019, game developer Zynga (creator of Words with Friends) suffered a leak. 173 million unique emails were exposed, as well as usernames and passwords in the form of salted SHA-1 hashes.

title: BoardakShop.ru
description: This is a Russian store for skateboards and related products. In March 2021, it suffered a hack that affected 3,600 users. The published data contains emails, names, phone numbers, IP and passwords in the form of MD5+Salt hashes.

title: Ulyanovsk FOMS 2018
description: In 2018, there was a leak from the compulsory health insurance fund in the Ulyanovsk region. The data contains telephone numbers, names, addresses, passport details and other information. In total there are more than 800 thousand records.

title: Palevo.com
description: In August 2022, a dump obtained from the now defunct erotic forum Palevo.com appeared in the public domain. The dump was released in June 2020 and contains 200 thousand entries with emails, names, IP addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes without salt. The dump also contained information about the user’s preferences and information from his profile on the forum.

title: Apollo
description: In July 2018, startup Apollo left behind a database containing billions of rows. Among them were 126 million unique email addresses, as well as names, places of work, roles of people and their locations.

title: WEBZEN
description: Around January 2022, the forums of the MMORPG Gaming website WEBZEN were hacked, affecting 208 thousand users. The breach included email addresses, IP addresses, usernames, dates of birth and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes.

title: YandexEat Couriers
description: In 2022, the database of all couriers from the Yandex Food delivery service became publicly available. There are about 700 thousand people in total whose phone numbers, names and passwords are known in the form of bcrypt hashes.

title: xHamster
description: In November 2016, it became known that hackers were trading hundreds of thousands of accounts on the erotic site xHamster. In total, the data contained nearly 380,000 unique user records, which included email addresses, usernames, and unsalted MD5 password hashes.

title: NordAvia
description: In 2016, Russian airline NordAvia suffered a data breach that exposed personal information including full names, dates of birth and passport numbers. In total, about 600 thousand customer records were affected.

title: Roll20
description: In December 2018, tabletop role-playing game site Roll20 suffered a data breach. The hack affected nearly 4 million customers. Email addresses, IP addresses, names, bcrypt password hashes, and the last 4 digits of credit cards were published.

title: Sanpid.com
description: The Sanpid.com trading platform, specializing in heating, water supply and plumbing systems, leaked 52 thousand records. The network included data such as phone numbers, full names and emails.

title: 123RF
description: In March 2020, stock photo site 123RF suffered a data breach that affected over 8 million subscribers and was subsequently sold online. The leak included email, IP, physical addresses, names, phone numbers and passwords as MD5 hashes.

title: Kickex.com
description: In July 2023, the database of clients of the KickEX crypto exchange became publicly available. The leak contains 1.3 million records with emails, names, nicknames and other information.

title: Academy.tn.ru
description: On September 9, 2022, the database of the website of the TECHNONICOL Construction Academy became publicly available. The leak affected the data of 76 thousand users, including logins, names, emails, phone numbers and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt and SHA512-Crypt.

title: Vianet
description: In April 2020, Nepalese internet service provider Vianet suffered a data breach. The attack on the Internet provider led to the disclosure of 177 thousand customer records, including 94 thousand unique email addresses. Names, phone numbers and physical addresses were also revealed.

title: WineStyle.ru
description: In October 2024, the database of the largest Russian wine retailer WineStyle.ru became available online. The compromised dataset contains more than 900 thousand records, including full names, phone numbers, emails, delivery data and IP addresses.

title: CopyMeThat
description: Around February 2021, recipe site CopyMeThat suffered a data breach. The breach included usernames, email addresses and passwords stored as PBKDF2 hashes. In total, 607 thousand users were affected.

title: StoryBird
description: In August 2015, the storytelling service StoryBird suffered a data leak. This resulted in the exposure of 4 million records containing 1 million unique email addresses. The data also included usernames and passwords in the form of PBKDF2 hashes.

title: Irk-rabota.ru
description: List of resumes from the site for job search in Irkutsk. It was obtained through scraping in August 2013. 13 thousand lines with names, phone numbers, marital status, education, experience and other data about a person.

title: Ledger
description: In June 2020, crypto hardware wallet manufacturer Ledger suffered from a data leak. More than 1 million email addresses were exposed. The data was originally sold and then published in December 2020 and included names, physical addresses and phone numbers.

title: Lukoil.ru
description: In 2022, customer data of the largest Russian gas station network, Lukoil, became publicly available. The cause of the leak was probably a vulnerability on the site with a bonus program, which made it possible to collect data using parsing. This resulted in nearly 13 million records containing names, phone numbers and rewards card numbers.

title: NticWeb.com
description: NticWeb is a news site from Algeria. In 2022, it suffered a leak that affected 28.5 thousand users. The database includes emails and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: Poryadok.ru
description: "Order" is a Russian store of goods for the home and garden. In June 2022, it was hacked and 150 thousand customer records were made public. The data contains telephone numbers, emails, names, cities of residence and dates of birth.

title: Realcoding
description: In May 2021, the Russian programming website Realcoding suffered a data leak. The leak exposed usernames, email addresses and passwords stored as MD5 hashes. In total, 113 thousand users were affected.

title: Ar.r2games.com
description: In November 2019, the Ar.r2games website, which is a catalog of RPG games, was hacked. 272 thousand entries were published with emails, nicknames, IP addresses and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: Ajarn
description: In September 2021, Thai English teaching website Ajarn discovered that they were the victim of a hack that occurred in December 2018. The database included 266 thousand email addresses, as well as names, phone numbers, hashed passwords and other personal information. information.

title: PonyExpress.ru
description: In 2019, there was a leak, as a result of which the logistics company Pony Express lost the data of 59 thousand clients. The records contained information about full names, phone numbers, nicknames and addresses.

title: Ziwo.ru
description: The Russian website Ziwo, which sells air conditioners and heaters, was hacked on 02/10/2024. A leak containing more than 200 thousand records with names, phone numbers, emails, addresses, delivery data and payment methods, as well as passwords in the form of MD5 hashes has become publicly available.

title: PS3Hax.net
description: Around July 2015, a Sony Playstation hacking and modding forum known as PS3Hax was hacked and over 447 thousand accounts were exposed. On the vBulletin forum, IP addresses and passwords were stored as salted hashes using a weak implementation that allowed many of them to be quickly cracked.

title: 2GIS 2019
description: 2GIS is an online map service for Russia. In 2019, all data from these maps was collected using parsing and later published. The leak includes 215 thousand records containing the names of objects on the map and contact information indicated in their descriptions - mail, phone numbers and names of companies located in them.

title: MajorGeeks
description: In November 2015, almost 270 thousand accounts from the MajorGeeks support forum were hacked. The accounts were actively sold and traded online and included email addresses, salted password hashes and IP addresses.

title: AltaKarter.ru
description: alta-karter - online store of car accessories. In 2023, it suffered from a leak that affected 113 thousand Russian users. The data contains mails, telephones, names and addresses.

title: Eluxair.ru
description: This is a Russian store selling various heaters and dryers. It was hacked in 2020, which led to the publication of the data of 7 thousand users. Records include names, telephone numbers, mailing addresses and residential addresses.

title: Carmod.ru
description: Carmod.ru is a Russian service for car diagnostics. On May 8, 2023, Ukrainian hackers announced that it had been hacked and published a database. It includes three files - users, orders and reviews. A total of 130 thousand unique records. The data contains names, emails, telephones, IP, residential addresses and data on services provided and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes.

title: Ovh
description: In mid-2015, the forum of the hosting provider Ovh.com suffered a data leak. The forum contained 453 thousand accounts, including usernames, email addresses, IP addresses and passwords x in the form of salted MD5 hashes.

title: debt.reestri.gov.ge
description: This is a Georgian register of debtors, which allows you to obtain information about him by a person’s name. It was hacked in 2021. Because of this, about a million records containing emails, phone numbers, names and addresses became publicly available.

title: Esia
description: In December 2022, hackers from DumpForums published 2 files from a leak from a Russian government services website, numbered 44 and 97. They claimed that they had more than 100 million records, but only a little more than two million were published. The leak includes full names, dates of birth, SNIs data, addresses, emails, phone numbers and passport details.

title: Customs.gov.ua
description: In 2023, it became known that the official website of the state customs service of Ukraine Customs.gov was attacked by hackers. However, the published database contains information only up to 2019. It contains about 340 thousand entries, but the number of unique users is much lower. The data included car numbers, phone numbers and company names, as well as text comments with a detailed description of the car, full names and passport details of passengers.

title: RapidFlyer
description: In July 2019, the French printing service Rapid Flyer suffered a data leak. The breach exposed full names, company names, email addresses, dates of birth, physical addresses, phone numbers, VAT numbers and passwords stored as unsalted MD5 hashes. In total, 166 thousand users were affected.

title: EatStreet
description: In May 2019, the online food ordering service EatStreet suffered a data breach that affected 6.4 million customers. A large amount of personal data was obtained, including names, phone numbers, addresses, partial credit card data and passwords stored as bcrypt hashes.

title: FitoMarket.ru
description: The user database of the Russian pharmaceutical company Fitomarket, owned by Evalar, was leaked online in August 2023. The data contains 240 thousand lines, including names, emails, phone numbers, cities and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: LiteCloud.me
description: This hosting provider for MineCraft servers suffered a hack in late 2017. Server names, player nicknames, their IP addresses and passwords were published in plain text. A total of 400 thousand records.

title: Business-Gazeta.ru
description: In December 2020, hackers gained access to the database of a Russian online publication. As a result of the leak, the data of 64 thousand users became available, including emails, phones, full names, nicknames, as well as passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes.

title: 3delectronics.ru
description: On June 23, 2023, it became known that a Russian online store of spare parts for repairing laptops and phones had been hacked. The leak contains names, emails, phone numbers, shipping addresses and passwords as SHA1 hashes with salt. The database contains 133 thousand users and 239 thousand orders.

title: LolZTeam.net
description: In May 2018, a leak occurred in the Russian hacker community Lolzteam. The attack resulted in the disclosure of data including names, email addresses and gender. In total, 405 thousand users were affected.

title: Onona.ru
description: In June 2021, the database of the Russian sex shop “He and She” became publicly available. The database contains 270 thousand rows containing names, emails, dates of birth, addresses, telephone numbers and passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt.

title: Lomonosov-msu.ru
description: This is a Russian service for organizing conferences. In September 2024, profiles of site users were collected using scraping. About 700 thousand records were received with names, education data, interests and regions of residence, as well as links to avatars. Data was also collected on people’s contacts with each other, 70 thousand records.

title: Ucraft.ru
description: From the website creation platform Ucraft, data about 217 thousand users was leaked onto the network, including emails, full names, nicknames, IP addresses, and passwords in the form of a bcrypt hash.

title: SwingManiacs
description: In January 2021, the Swing Maniacs Spanish dance class website suffered a data breach, affecting 43.3 thousand members. The attack exposed email addresses, phone numbers, physical addresses, full names and passwords as MD5 hashes.

title: Letovo.ru
description: letovo.ru - Private school for high school in New Moscow. Located in the settlement of Sosenskoye. In 2022, hackers hacked it and made a dump of the school’s clients publicly available. The database contains mainly parents of students, about 220 thousand records in total. The leak includes names, phone numbers, emails, selected languages, and passwords in the form of salted MD5 hashes or, in rare cases, md5crypt.

title: ClixSense
description: In September 2016, pay-per-click website ClixSense suffered a data breach that exposed the data of 2.4 million subscribers. The attackers claimed that this was part of a larger data breach involving 6.6 million records. The leaked data included names, physical addresses, emails, IP addresses, gender, balances, dates of birth and passwords. Account balances and passwords are stored in plain text.

title: HopponWorks
description: Around April 2021, food delivery service HopponWorks experienced a data breach that affected 49,000 members. The breach exposed full names, email addresses, dates of birth, phone numbers, locations and very few passwords.

title: Chronicle.com
description: In 2020, news website Chronicle.com suffered a data breach. About 3.5 million users were affected; their names, emails, nicknames and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes were made publicly available.

title: Nz-Cars.ru
description: In June 2024, the automotive website Nz-Cars.ru was hacked. A dump of about 8 thousand lines was made publicly available. The data includes names, phone numbers, IP addresses and order data, as well as text reviews.

title: Phone House Espana
description: In April 2021, Spanish retailer Phone House was allegedly hit by a Babuk ransomware attack. Later, part of the data was posted on the Internet and contained 5.2 million email addresses. The database also contained names, nationalities, gender, dates of birth, telephone numbers and physical addresses. The companies were threatened with further publication if they did not pay the ransom.

title: MaxRealt.ru
description: In 2020, data from a Russian real estate forum was collected using parsing. About a million records were obtained containing telephone numbers, names and cities of residence.

title: SecurityShells.com
description: SecurityShells.com and its counterpart CsplSoftWare.com are Indian sites dedicated to developing cybersecurity solutions for companies. In mid-2024, their servers suffered a hack that resulted in the publication of approximately 5 million user posts. The data contains telephone numbers, emails, dates of birth, names, cities of residence and other information.

title: Hjedd
description: In July 2022, the database of Chinese adult content platform hjedd was leaked online. The published data included usernames, email addresses, phone numbers and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes. The incident occurred because hjedd did not properly secure its database, allowing anyone to connect to it.

title: Havenly
description: In June 2020, interior design website Havenly suffered a data breach that affected nearly 1.4 million of the service's users. The exposed data included email addresses, names, phone numbers, geographic locations and passwords in the form of SHA-1 hashes. The data was subsequently widely distributed among online hacking communities.

title: Artessa.ru
description: Artessa is a Russian women's clothing store. In November 2021, their website suffered a leak that affected 18 thousand users. The data contains emails, names, phone numbers, IP addresses and places of work.

title: Ntws.pro
description: In July 2023, the online platform for insurance agents and brokers “Ntws.pro” was hacked. The published leak contains 200 thousand records with names, emails, telephone numbers, addresses, passport data and information about cars used by the client.

title: CPokemon
description: In November 2020, a data leak occurred on the Centro Pokémon forums, affecting 71.8 thousand users. The attack exposed usernames, email addresses, IP addresses, dates of birth and passwords stored as vBulletin or bcrypt hashes.

title: RussianNames
description: At the end of 2020, a list of names appeared in the public domain. It included 25.5 million full names of Russians and, in some cases, their dates of birth. Most likely, this list is related to coronavirus vaccinations, but there is no exact information about its origin.

title: Live.com
description: In February 2023, a leak from the Live.com service appeared on a hacker forum. It includes 33 million user emails and no other data. The source of this database is unknown.

title: Ngv.ru
description: In September 2022, an SQL dump of the Russian news site Ngv.ru, which publishes news about the oil market, was published. The dump contained about 9 thousand user records and the same number of records from the feedback form on the site. The data contains emails, names, phone numbers, passwords in the form of MD5 hashes with salt and other data.

title: Edmodo
description: In May 2017, the educational platform Edmodo was hacked, exposing 77 million records containing 43 million emails. Usernames and bcrypt password hashes were also published.

title: LaPosteMobile
description: In July 2022, French telecommunications company La Poste Mobile was the target of a LockBit ransomware attack. As a result, the company's data was posted online. The leak included 533,000 unique email addresses, as well as names, physical addresses, phone numbers, dates of birth, gender and banking information. The La Poste Mobile website was down for 10 days after the attack.

title: Daxy.com
description: One of the main players in corporate intelligence in Bulgaria, DAXY.com, was hacked in May 2021. The dump contains 137 thousand entries with emails, names, passwords and other data.

title: 21-vek.spb.ru
description: In October 2023, the insurance company Twenty-First Century was hacked. The leak contains emails, names and phone numbers. A total of 165 thousand lines.

title: GalacticGames
description: Around March 2021, Galactic Games' New and Used Games website suffered a data breach that affected 50.1k users. The leak exposed full names, email addresses, IP addresses, phone numbers and passwords as OpenCart hashes.

title: FOP 01.2022
description: In Ukraine there is a register of individual entrepreneurs (FOP). In January 2022, it suffered a leak that affected more than 7 million people. The database contains names, telephone numbers, emails and OKVED codes that describe the type of business activity.

title: BinWeevils 2014
description: In September 2014, there was a data leak in the online game Bin Weevils. While it was initially stated that only usernames and passwords were exposed, it was later revealed that a wider range of personal attributes were affected. The data included nearly 1.3 million unique email addresses, as well as gender, age and text passwords.

title: StarNet
description: In February 2015, the Moldovan Internet provider StarNet suffered from a hack. The published database contained about 140 thousand email addresses. Personal data was also posted - contact information, Internet provider usage patterns, and even passport numbers.

title: Amigas
description: Around October 2022, the Brazilian marketing company Amigas (maisamigas.com.br) experienced a data breach that affected 603 thousand users (93 thousand unique emails). The attack revealed gender, email addresses, full names, physical addresses and dates of birth.

title: Book24
description: On June 7, 2023, the hacker group NLB made the database of the Russian bookstore Book24.ru publicly available. The published file contained about 4 million lines with emails, phone numbers, names and other customer data. The leak occurred on May 29, 2023.

title: SmartVoting
description: In July 2021, the Smart Voting website, created by Alexei Navalny to campaign against United Russia - the “party of swindlers and thieves”, suffered from a data leak.
