As a result of the leak, emails belonging to 190 thousand people who registered on this site were made publicly available. No data other than mail was published.

title: Telegram Users 520k
description: In 2021, a database collected as a result of Telegram parsing appeared on the Internet. It contains information of 520 thousand lines with names, phone numbers, nicknames and first names.

title: Mate1
description: In February 2016, a leak occurred on the dating site mate1.com. 27 million subscribers were affected. The data included drug and alcohol addictions, relationships, income levels, and passwords without hashes.

title: Majestic-rp
description: This is a game server of the Majestic Role Play project for GTA 5 RP25. In April 2024, it suffered a data breach. The records contained information about logins, emails, IP addresses and nicknames of players. In total, the leak affected approximately 87 thousand records.

title: CafeMumu
description: Cafe "MU-MU" is a chain of fast food cafes in Moscow. In April 2020, they had a leak that affected 57 thousand users. Data includes phone numbers, names, emails, addresses and dates of birth of clients.

title: Roblox
description: At the end of 2023, a list of nicknames and passwords related to the Roblox game appeared in the public domain. It contained 37 million records, of which 11 million were unique. The data was collected from stealer logs.

title: Individual Enterprises RF 2020
description: In Russia there is a register of individual entrepreneurs, the data from which is available to everyone. In 2020, all users were removed from it using parsing. The resulting database contains more than 20 million records with names, emails and TIN.

title: KiwiTaxi.ru
description: In 2020, a database dump of the KiwiTaxi transportation system became publicly available. The database contains 336 thousand clients and includes their names, emails, phone numbers, positions and passwords in the form of SHA1 and SHA256 hashes with salt.

title: CoinTracker
description: In December 2022, Crypto & NFT tax service CoinTracker reported a data breach that affected over 1.5 million of their customers. The leak occurred due to the SendGrid platform as a result of an attack targeting several clients of the email provider. The breach revealed email addresses and partially redacted phone numbers.

title: VK Parsing 2023
description: At the beginning of 2023, information about all users of the Russian social network VKontakte was collected using parsing. The resulting database contains more than 770 million users. The data includes names, locations, educational backgrounds and other information.

title: Persianinoz.com
description: The Persianinoz forum, a community of Iranians in Australia, was hacked in November 2019. 18 thousand users were affected. IP addresses, email addresses, usernames and passwords were published as salted MD5 hashes.

title: MonaShop.ru
description: In February 2024, the MonaShop.ru website, which sells souvenirs, suffered a data leak. Two tables with data on 3.6 thousand customers and 13 thousand orders were disclosed. Emails, phone numbers, nicknames, IP addresses, delivery addresses and passwords in the form of a SHA1 hash with salt were publicly available.

title: Vakinha
description: In June 2020, the Brazilian fundraising service Vakinha suffered a data breach. The incident affected nearly 4.8 million members. The exposed data included email addresses, names, phone numbers, geographic locations, and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes.

title: HairPersona.ru
description: HairPersona - online catalog of hair care products. In 2024, the site suffered from a hack and tables of orders (156 thousand records) and users (75 thousand records) were made publicly available. The data contains names, emails, telephone numbers, addresses, information about orders and payment methods, as well as passwords in the form of MD5 hashes.

title: AimJunkies
description: In April 2014, the Gaming Cheats website known as AimJunkies suffered a data breach that affected 166,000 users. The attack exposed email addresses, usernames and IP addresses.

title: Avast
description: In May 2014, the Avast antivirus forum was hacked and 423 thousand user posts were made public. The leak included usernames, email addresses and MD5 password hashes.

title: PCR Belarus
description: In 2021, an unknown medical portal in Belarus, providing PCR diagnostic services for COVID-19, suffered a data leak. The personal information of 36 thousand users, namely their full names, phone numbers and emails, got into the network.

title: Smed.ru
description: "Stolitsa-Medical" is a Russian online pharmacy with delivery. In 2019, it suffered from a hack that affected 57 thousand customers. The published table contains emails, names, phone numbers and dates of birth of users.

title: BioBigBox
description: In February 2022, BioBigBox's "HIPAA Compliant File Transfer and Storage System" suffered a data breach. The breach included email addresses, phone numbers, full names and passwords stored as MySQL5 hashes. In total, 51 thousand users were affected.

title: Pskb.com
description: In June 2023, the website of the large bank PrimSotsBank encountered an incident, as a result of which the data of about 90 thousand users got into the network. Emails, nicknames, full names, logins, as well as passwords in the form of an MD5 hash with salt were revealed.

title: Coachella
description: In February 2017, it was discovered that a database from the Coachella music festival was being sold online. The data was supposedly taken from the main Coachella website and their message board. The published data included nearly 600 thousand usernames, IP addresses, email addresses, and salted password hashes (MD5 in the case of the message board).

title: Bases-Brothers.ru
description: There is a file on the network containing 8.4 million phones, as well as the names and regions of residence of their owners. Some sources claim that it was collected from Avito using parsing, while others claim that the source is the site bases-brothers.ru, which provided breakdowns by phone numbers. Thus, the exact origin of the leak remains unknown. The parsing dates back to approximately 2017.
